\n[[Category:American political writers]]\n[[Category:American social commentators]]\n[[Category:American tax resisters]]\n[[Category:Anarcha-feminists]]\n[[Category:Anti-fascists]]\n[[Category:Anti-capitalists]]\n[[Category:Boston University faculty]]\n[[Category:Columbia University alumni]]\n[[Category:Drug policy reform activists]]\n[[Category:Feminist historians]]\n[[Category:G7 Welcoming Committee Records artists]]\n[[Category:Harvard University staff]]\n[[Category:Spelman College faculty]]\n[[Category:Historians of anarchism]]\n[[Category:Historians of communism]]\n[[Category:Historians of the United States]]\n[[Category:Jewish American dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Jewish American historians]]\n[[Category:Jewish American social scientists]]\n[[Category:Jewish anarchists]]\n[[Category:Jewish feminists]]\n[[Category:Jewish socialists]]\n[[Category:Male feminists]]\n[[Category:New York University alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:People from Middlesex County, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Socialist feminists]]\n[[Category:Anarchism in the United States]]\n[[Category:United States Army Air Forces officers]]\n[[Category:Writers from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:21st-century American dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century American dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century American historians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American historians]]\n[[Category:American male dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Thomas Jefferson High School (Brooklyn) alumni]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American people of Austrian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Hungarian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n", "name_user": "Outriggr", "label": "safe", "comment": "short description: \"American historian and socialist thinker\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Howard_Zinn"}
{"title_page": "Lohana", "text_new": "{{Distinguish | Lohani}}{{Infobox ethnic group\n| image            = \n| group            = Lohanas\n| poptime          = \n| region1          = India\n| popplace         = \u2022 India\n| langs            = Primarily [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]], [[Kutchi language|Kutchi]], [[Sindhi language|Sindhi]], Punjabi and [[Hindi]]. Also local languages in diaspora countries.\n| rels             = Primarily [[Hinduism]]\n| related          = \u2022 [[Gujarati people]]  \u2022 [[Sindhi people]]  \u2022 [[Khoja]]  \u2022 [[Memon people|Memon]]\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n}}\n\nLohana, also referred to as Loharana and Lohrana, are an Indian caste, traditionally largely occupied as warriors{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}. The word Lohana is a shortened form of Loha Rana. Lohanas are the descendants of the Luva, Son of Lord Rama{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}. Lohanas belong to [[Raghuvanshi]] Dynasty. Lohanas are also Known as [https://books.google.co.ke/books?id=iuURFTHTU0EC&pg=PT38&dq=lohana+lohara+dynasty&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj44eb77bPoAhU0UhUIHdB0BfIQ6AEIJjAA#v=onepage&q=lohana%20lohara%20dynasty&f=false Lohara] \u0932\u094b\u0939\u0930\u093e [[Lohara]] Dynasty \n\nThe Lohanas are divided into three separate cultural groups as a result of centuries apart in different regions. Thus there are significant differences between the culture, language, professions and societies of [[Gujarati languages|Gujarati]] Lohanas, [[Sindhi languages|Sindhi]] Lohanas, [[Kutchi language|Kutchi]] Lohanas.\n\n==History==\nLohanas are [[Kshatriya]] according to the Hindu Ritual Ranking System\n[[File:Saurashtra region within Gujarat India relief map.jpg|right|thumb|Gujarati lohanas trace their origin to Saurashtra region in present-day state of Gujarat, India.]]\n{{multiple image\n| align     = right\n| direction = vertical\n| image1    = Lowana Women (9938634413).jpg\n| width1    = 200\n| caption1  = Lohana women in western India (c. 1855&ndash;1862).\n| image2    = Lohannas (9805958365).jpg\n| width2    = 200\n| caption2  =Lohana men in western India (c. 1855&ndash;1862).\n}}\nIn the 7th century, there was a [[Buddhism|Buddhist]] ruler named [[Agham Lohana]] <ref>https://www.rarebooksocietyofindia.org/book_archive/196174216674_10151577540891675.pdf</ref> ruled a part of Sindh and was Governor of [[Mansura (Brahmanabad)|Brahmanabad]] and contemporary of [[Chach of Alor]]. Agham Lohana is referred to in ''[[Chach Nama]]'' and the city of [[Agham Kot]] is said to be named after him. Even the sea around was known as Lohana Darya (''Darya'' means Sea). Chach of Alor killed Agham Lohana in battle of Brahmanand and married his widow and also married his niece to Agham's son Sirhind.{{citation needed|date=March 2013}} Further, Chach is said to have laid restrictions of Lohana and [[Jat]] tribes from wearing headgear and carrying weapons. He further placed upon the Jat and Lohana restrictions such as:<ref name=cn>The Chach-nama. English translation by Mirza Kalichbeg Fredunbeg. Delhi Reprint, 1979.</ref>\n\n*Forbidding them riding horses with saddles\n*Forbidding them from wearing silk or velvet\n*Forbidding them from wearing headgear or footwear\n*Forcing them to wear black or red scarves\n\n===Gujarati and Kutchi Lohanas===\n[[Gujarati languages|Gujarati]] Lohanas are those having ancestry in [[Saurashtra (region)|Saurashtra]] and speak Gujarati as their mother-tongue. Kutchi Lohanas speak [[Kutchi language|Kutchi]] as their mother-tongue and are native to [[Kutch district|Kutch]].{{cn|date=February 2019}}\n\n===Sindhi Lohanas===\n\nSindh fell under the Muslim rule of [[Muhammad bin Qasim]] after defeat of [[Dahir (Raja)|Dahir]]. Its Hindus were increasingly pressured to convert to Islam. It was around this time that Uderolal - a Sindhi Hindu Lohana also known as [[Jhulelal (Hinduism)|Jhulelal]], [[Dariyalal]] and Jinda Pir - assumed the mantle of Lohana and Hindu leadership. Today Uderolal is revered by both Sindhis and [[Sufi]]s, thus both Hindus and Muslims visit the site of his tomb. For two centuries after him, Lohanas d lived without fear until they found themselves being increasingly threatened and persecuted in Sindh due to their Hindu identity. It was then that they began to migrate mainly towards [[Kutch]] and Saurashtra.<ref name=p/><ref name=\"engineer\"/>\n\nSindhi Lohanas have since been divided into several groups, among which are:<ref>{{cite book|title=Cosmopolitan connections: the Sindhi diaspora, 1860-2000|first=Mark-Anthony |last=Falzon|pages=34, 35|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ljbS-I5Y8WMC&pg=PA34|isbn=978-9004140080 |year=2004 }}</ref>\n* [[Amils]]: generally involved in clerical jobs in government offices, as working in posts of revenue collectors and other senior positions\n* [[Bhaiband]]s: mainly involved in trade and commerce and so mostly merchants.The community was involved in international and trade in interior of Sindh even before the arrival of the British. They also played an important part in the development of the city of [[Karachi]]<ref>{{cite book|last=Askari|first=Sabiah|title=Studies on Karachi: Papers Presented at the Karachi Conference 2013|year=2013|publisher=Cambridge Scholars Publishing|isbn=978-1-44387-744-2|pages=55, 65\u201366|url=https://books.google.com/?id=mSbXCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA58}}</ref>\n* [[Sahitis]]: placed somewhere between Amils and Bhaibands, they could be either in government service or traders\n*Many Sindhi Lohanas are Still Found in Sindh,Pakistan. They Follow Hindu Religion and Workship Lord Rama , Jhulelal and Goddess Hinglaj Mata\n\n==Ruling Area==\n\nLohanas ruled over , from Kabul to Kashmir. It included Today's- Whole Pakistan ([[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]], [[Sindh]], [[Balochistan]],  Khyber [[Pakhtunkhwa]]), It also included The Gandhar Desh (Kandahar in Afghanistan) and Kekay Desh( Iran).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.asian-voice.com/Opinion/Columnists/Lohana-Kings-of-Kashmir-and-Kabul|title=Lohana Kings of Kashmir and Kabul|last=ABPL|website=www.asian-voice.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\n==Society and culture==\nLohanas largely follow Hindu rituals and worship [[Hindu deities]] such as [[Krishna]]. They worship avatars of [[Vishnu]] such as [[Rama]] with his consort [[Sita]] and [[Krishna]] in the form of [[Shrinathji]]. They worship [[Shakti]] in the form of Ravirandal Mataji, and [[Parvati|Ambika]]. The 19th century saints [[Jalaram Bapa]], and [[Yogi ji Maharaj]], also attract many Lohana devotees. Their main [[Kuladevata|clan deities]]  are [[Rana Jashraj|Veer Dada Jashraj]], [[Harkor|Harkor Ba]], Sindhvi Shree Sikotar Mata and [[Dariyalal]]. The Sun is also worshipped by the community.<ref name=p>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=j-xSUpZrzgMC&pg=PA70&dq=lohana+jasraj#v=onepage&q=lohana%20jasraj&f=false |title=Firmes et entreprises en Inde: la firme lignag\u00e8re dans ses r\u00e9seaux |first= Pierre |last=Lachaier| pages= 70\u201373|language=French|isbn=9782865379279 |date=1999-01-01 }}</ref>\n\nLohana celebrate all festivals like other Gujarati Hindu community such as  [[Diwali]], [[Navratri]] and [[Holi]]. They also celebrate the birthday of 19th-century saint [[Jalaram]].{{cn|date=July 2017}}\n\n===Formation of Khoja and Memon Islamic communities===\nThe community's oral history says that the decline of their kingdom began after the death of Veer Dada Jashraj. It also says that their name derives from the city of [[Lahore|Lohargadh]] (/Lohanpur/Lohkot) in [[Multan]], from which they migrated in the 13th century after the establishment of Muslim rule there.<ref name=p/>\n\n[[Pir Sadardin]] converted some Lohanas to the [[Shia]] [[Ismaili]] [[Nizari]] sect of [[Islam]] in the 15th century. As Lohanas were worshippers of [[Shakti]], the emergence of a devotional Ismaili oral tradition that incorporated indigenous conceptions of religion, known as [[ginans]], played a role in the forming of a new ethnic caste-like grouping.<ref name=\"asani\">{{Cite journal|last=Asani|first=Ali S.|date=2001-07-01|title=The Khojahs of South Asia: Defining a Space of their Own|journal=Cultural Dynamics|language=en|volume=13|issue=2|pages=155\u2013168|doi=10.1177/092137400101300202|issn=0921-3740}}</ref> This group came to be known as [[Khoja]]s (from [[Khawaja]]), a title given by Sadardin,<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Nizari Ismaili Tradition in the Indo-Pakistan Subcontinent|last=Nanji|first=Azim|date=April 1979|publisher=Caravan Books|isbn=9780882060200|location=Delmar, NY}}</ref> that would predominantly merge into what is now understood as the Nizari Ismaili branch of Shia Islam.<ref name=\"asani\" />\n\nIn 1422, Jam Rai Dan was tribal leader in [[Sindh]] during the [[Samma Dynasty]]; he was converted to Islam by Sayad Eusuf-ud-Din and he adopted a new name Makrab Khan. At that time a person named Mankeji was head of 84 [[surname|nukhs]] of Lohanas, who were in favour in court of that Samma king. He was persuaded by ruler and the Qadri to convert to Islam. However, not all Lohanas were ready to convert from [[Hinduism]].<ref name=\"engineer\"/> But 700 Lohana families comprising some 6,178 persons converted in [[Thatta District|Thatta]], Sindh.  These are now known as [[Memon people|Memons]] (from [[Momin (disambiguation)|Momin]]s).<ref name=\"engineer\">{{cite book|title=The Muslim communities of Gujarat: an exploratory study of Bohras, Khojas, and Memons|first=Asgharali |last=Engineer|pages=42\u201344|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hY5AAAAAMAAJ|publisher=Ajanta Publications|year=1989}}</ref>{{dubious|reason=unknown author, unknown publisher|date=July 2017}}\n\n==Diaspora==\nThousands of Hindu [[Gujarati people|Gujaratis]] left India between 1880 - 1920 and migrated to [[British colonies]] in the [[African Great Lakes]] region of [[Uganda]], [[Kenya]] and [[Tanganyika]].A significant number of these came from the [[Patidar]] and Lohana communities.<ref>{{cite book |last=Herbert |first=J. |year=2004 |title=Contested terrains: negotiating ethnic boundaries in the city of Leicester since 1950 (Doctoral dissertation, History)|pages=25|url=https://lra.le.ac.uk/handle/2381/31063}}</ref> At that time,however, there was already a bustling merchant class diaspora of [[Gujarati Muslims]] in these countries.<ref>{{Cite journal |url=http://www.asiansinafrica.com/bestanden/Changing_Culture.pdf |last=Oonk |first=G.. |title=The Changing Culture of Hindu Lohanas in East Africa |journal=Contemporary Asians Studies |volume=13 |year=2004 |pages=83\u201397 |access-date=2011-10-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425085509/http://www.asiansinafrica.com/bestanden/Changing_Culture.pdf |archive-date=2012-04-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref> \n\nThe Lohana migrants to East Africa, of which there were 40,000 in 1970,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Gregory|first1=Robert G.|title=The rise and fall of philanthropy in East Africa : the Asian contribution|date=1992|publisher=Transaction Publishers|location=New Brunswick, U.S.A.|isbn=978-1-56000-007-5|page=[https://archive.org/details/risefallofphil00greg/page/28 28]|url=https://archive.org/details/risefallofphil00greg|url-access=registration}}</ref> came mainly from the Saurashtran cities of [[Jamnagar]] and [[Rajkot]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Kalka |first=I. |year=1986 |title=A case study of urban ethnicity: Harrow Gujaratis (Doctoral dissertation, London School of Economics and Political Science (United Kingdom) |page=74 |url=http://etheses.lse.ac.uk/1588/1/U144910.pdf}}</ref> Many Lohanas set up businesses in those countries, two of the most successful being those set up by [[Nanji Kalidas Mehta]] and [[Muljibhai Madhvani]].<ref>{{cite book|title=The Rise and Fall of Philanthropy in East Africa: The Asian's Contribution |first=Robert |last=Gregory |year=1992 |page=53 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=juZ5q6bttEoC&pg=PA53|isbn=9781412833356 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Persistence Amid Adversity:The Growth and Spatial Distribution of the Asian Population of Kenya, 1902-1963|first=Charles Joseph |last=Bennett|publisher=Syracuse University |year=1976 |pages=182|quote=Probably the success of the most prominent Lohana families in Uganda, Nanji Kalidas Mehta and Sons, M. P. Madhvani and D. K. Hindocha had much influence on Lohana migration from Porbandar and Jamnagar}}</ref>\n\nIn the later part of 20th century, following the independence of British colonies, and particularly after [[Idi Amin]]'s [[Expulsion of Asians from Uganda|expulsion order for South Asians in 1972]], most Lohanas moved to the [[United Kingdom]], and to a lesser extent to [[United States]] and [[Canada]].<ref name=gb>{{cit book|url=https://books.google.com/books?.id=nUsOAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA34 |title=Hinduism in Great Britain: the perpetuation of religion in an alien cultural|first= Richard |last=Burghart}}</ref> In the UK, the highest concentration of Lohanas and other Gujarati Hindu communities is around the [[West London]] suburbs of [[Wembley]] and [[Harrow, London|Harrow]], and the city of [[Leicester]] in the [[East Midlands]] region of England.<ref>{{cite book|last=Thompson|first=Linda|title=Young bilingual children in nursery schools|date=2000|publisher=Multilingual Matters|location=Clevedon, England|isbn=978-1853594540|pages=10\u201311|url=https://books.google.com/?id=3hvHeG77s1oC&pg=PA1}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Firth|first1=Shirley|title=Dying, death and bereavement in a British Hindu community|date=1997|publisher=Peeters|location=Leuven|isbn=978-90-6831-976-7|page=21|url=https://books.google.com/?id=pYNXC-HK1u0C&pg=PR8&dq=rameshbhai+mehta++leicester#v=onepage&q=lohana&f=false}}</ref> In 1979, there were 30,000 Lohanas in Britain.<ref>{{cite book |last=Kalka |first=I. |year=1986 |title=A case study of urban ethnicity: Harrow Gujaratis (Doctoral dissertation, London School of Economics and Political Science (United Kingdom) |page=79 |url=http://etheses.lse.ac.uk/1588/1/U144910.pdf}}</ref>\n\n==See Also==\n*[[Khasas]]\n*[[Kingdoms of Ancient India]]\n*[[Lahore]]\n*[[Mehta Kalu]], [[Guru Nanak|Guru Nanak's]] father, a Chandarana Lohana<ref>{{Google books|fleka3YEE8sC|Faith & Philosophy of Sikhism|page=60|text=Kalidas Chandarana}}\n\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{commonscatinline}}\n\n[[Category:Lohana]]\n[[Category:Sindhi tribes in India]]\n[[Category:Gujarati people]]\n[[Category:Hindu communities of Pakistan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish | Lohani}}{{Infobox ethnic group\n| image            = \n| group            = Lohanas\n| poptime          = \n| region1          = India\n| popplace         = \u2022 India\n| langs            = Primarily [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]], [[Kutchi language|Kutchi]], [[Sindhi language|Sindhi]], Punjabi and [[Hindi]]. Also local languages in diaspora countries.\n| rels             = Primarily [[Hinduism]]\n| related          = \u2022 [[Gujarati people]]  \u2022 [[Sindhi people]]  \u2022 [[Khoja]]  \u2022 [[Memon people|Memon]]\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n}}\n\nLohana, also referred to as Loharana and Lohrana, are an Indian caste, traditionally largely occupied as warriors{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}. The word Lohana is a shortened form of Loha Rana. Lohanas are the descendants of the Luva, Son of Lord Rama{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}. Lohanas belong to [[Raghuvanshi]] Dynasty. Lohanas are also Known as [https://books.google.co.ke/books?id=iuURFTHTU0EC&pg=PT38&dq=lohana+lohara+dynasty&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj44eb77bPoAhU0UhUIHdB0BfIQ6AEIJjAA#v=onepage&q=lohana%20lohara%20dynasty&f=false Lohara] \u0932\u094b\u0939\u0930\u093e [[Lohara]] Dynasty \n\nThe Lohanas are divided into three separate cultural groups as a result of centuries apart in different regions. Thus there are significant differences between the culture, language, professions and societies of [[Gujarati languages|Gujarati]] Lohanas, [[Sindhi languages|Sindhi]] Lohanas, [[Kutchi language|Kutchi]] Lohanas.\n\n==History==\nLohanas are [[Kshatriya]] according to the Hindu Ritual Ranking System\n[[File:Saurashtra region within Gujarat India relief map.jpg|right|thumb|Gujarati lohanas trace their origin to Saurashtra region in present-day state of Gujarat, India.]]\n{{multiple image\n| align     = right\n| direction = vertical\n| image1    = Lowana Women (9938634413).jpg\n| width1    = 200\n| caption1  = Lohana women in western India (c. 1855&ndash;1862).\n| image2    = Lohannas (9805958365).jpg\n| width2    = 200\n| caption2  =Lohana men in western India (c. 1855&ndash;1862).\n}}\nIn the 7th century, there was a [[Buddhism|Buddhist]] ruler named [[Agham Lohana]]<ref name=\"Chintaman Vinayak Vaidya\">{{cite book|last=Vinayak Vaidya|first=Chintaman|title=History of mediaeval Hindu India, Volume 1|year=1979|publisher=Cosmo Publications|pages=161\u2013163|url=https://books.google.com/books?eYYBAAAAMAAJ}}</ref>{{Dead link|date=March 2020}} ruled a part of Sindh and was Governor of [[Mansura (Brahmanabad)|Brahmanabad]] and contemporary of [[Chach of Alor]]. Agham Lohana is referred to in ''[[Chach Nama]]'' and the city of [[Agham Kot]] is said to be named after him. Even the sea around was known as Lohana Darya (''Darya'' means Sea). Chach of Alor killed Agham Lohana in battle of Brahmanand and married his widow and also married his niece to Agham's son Sirhind.{{citation needed|date=March 2013}} Further, Chach is said to have laid restrictions of Lohana and [[Jat]] tribes from wearing headgear and carrying weapons. He further placed upon the Jat and Lohana restrictions such as:<ref name=cn>The Chach-nama. English translation by Mirza Kalichbeg Fredunbeg. Delhi Reprint, 1979.</ref>\n\n*Forbidding them riding horses with saddles\n*Forbidding them from wearing silk or velvet\n*Forbidding them from wearing headgear or footwear\n*Forcing them to wear black or red scarves\n\n===Gujarati and Kutchi Lohanas===\n[[Gujarati languages|Gujarati]] Lohanas are those having ancestry in [[Saurashtra (region)|Saurashtra]] and speak Gujarati as their mother-tongue. Kutchi Lohanas speak [[Kutchi language|Kutchi]] as their mother-tongue and are native to [[Kutch district|Kutch]].{{cn|date=February 2019}}\n\n===Sindhi Lohanas===\n\nSindh fell under the Muslim rule of [[Muhammad bin Qasim]] after defeat of [[Dahir (Raja)|Dahir]]. Its Hindus were increasingly pressured to convert to Islam. It was around this time that Uderolal - a Sindhi Hindu Lohana also known as [[Jhulelal (Hinduism)|Jhulelal]], [[Dariyalal]] and Jinda Pir - assumed the mantle of Lohana and Hindu leadership. Today Uderolal is revered by both Sindhis and [[Sufi]]s, thus both Hindus and Muslims visit the site of his tomb. For two centuries after him, Lohanas d lived without fear until they found themselves being increasingly threatened and persecuted in Sindh due to their Hindu identity. It was then that they began to migrate mainly towards [[Kutch]] and Saurashtra.<ref name=p/><ref name=\"engineer\"/>\n\nSindhi Lohanas have since been divided into several groups, among which are:<ref>{{cite book|title=Cosmopolitan connections: the Sindhi diaspora, 1860-2000|first=Mark-Anthony |last=Falzon|pages=34, 35|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ljbS-I5Y8WMC&pg=PA34|isbn=978-9004140080 |year=2004 }}</ref>\n* [[Amils]]: generally involved in clerical jobs in government offices, as working in posts of revenue collectors and other senior positions\n* [[Bhaiband]]s: mainly involved in trade and commerce and so mostly merchants.The community was involved in international and trade in interior of Sindh even before the arrival of the British. They also played an important part in the development of the city of [[Karachi]]<ref>{{cite book|last=Askari|first=Sabiah|title=Studies on Karachi: Papers Presented at the Karachi Conference 2013|year=2013|publisher=Cambridge Scholars Publishing|isbn=978-1-44387-744-2|pages=55, 65\u201366|url=https://books.google.com/?id=mSbXCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA58}}</ref>\n* [[Sahitis]]: placed somewhere between Amils and Bhaibands, they could be either in government service or traders\n*Many Sindhi Lohanas are Still Found in Sindh,Pakistan. They Follow Hindu Religion and Workship Lord Rama , Jhulelal and Goddess Hinglaj Mata\n\n==Ruling Area==\n\nLohanas ruled over , from Kabul to Kashmir. It included Today's- Whole Pakistan ([[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]], [[Sindh]], [[Balochistan]],  Khyber [[Pakhtunkhwa]]), It also included The Gandhar Desh (Kandahar in Afghanistan) and Kekay Desh( Iran).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.asian-voice.com/Opinion/Columnists/Lohana-Kings-of-Kashmir-and-Kabul|title=Lohana Kings of Kashmir and Kabul|last=ABPL|website=www.asian-voice.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\n==Society and culture==\nLohanas largely follow Hindu rituals and worship [[Hindu deities]] such as [[Krishna]]. They worship avatars of [[Vishnu]] such as [[Rama]] with his consort [[Sita]] and [[Krishna]] in the form of [[Shrinathji]]. They worship [[Shakti]] in the form of Ravirandal Mataji, and [[Parvati|Ambika]]. The 19th century saints [[Jalaram Bapa]], and [[Yogi ji Maharaj]], also attract many Lohana devotees. Their main [[Kuladevata|clan deities]]  are [[Rana Jashraj|Veer Dada Jashraj]], [[Harkor|Harkor Ba]], Sindhvi Shree Sikotar Mata and [[Dariyalal]]. The Sun is also worshipped by the community.<ref name=p>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=j-xSUpZrzgMC&pg=PA70&dq=lohana+jasraj#v=onepage&q=lohana%20jasraj&f=false |title=Firmes et entreprises en Inde: la firme lignag\u00e8re dans ses r\u00e9seaux |first= Pierre |last=Lachaier| pages= 70\u201373|language=French|isbn=9782865379279 |date=1999-01-01 }}</ref>\n\nLohana celebrate all festivals like other Gujarati Hindu community such as  [[Diwali]], [[Navratri]] and [[Holi]]. They also celebrate the birthday of 19th-century saint [[Jalaram]].{{cn|date=July 2017}}\n\n===Formation of Khoja and Memon Islamic communities===\nThe community's oral history says that the decline of their kingdom began after the death of Veer Dada Jashraj. It also says that their name derives from the city of [[Lahore|Lohargadh]] (/Lohanpur/Lohkot) in [[Multan]], from which they migrated in the 13th century after the establishment of Muslim rule there.<ref name=p/>\n\n[[Pir Sadardin]] converted some Lohanas to the [[Shia]] [[Ismaili]] [[Nizari]] sect of [[Islam]] in the 15th century. As Lohanas were worshippers of [[Shakti]], the emergence of a devotional Ismaili oral tradition that incorporated indigenous conceptions of religion, known as [[ginans]], played a role in the forming of a new ethnic caste-like grouping.<ref name=\"asani\">{{Cite journal|last=Asani|first=Ali S.|date=2001-07-01|title=The Khojahs of South Asia: Defining a Space of their Own|journal=Cultural Dynamics|language=en|volume=13|issue=2|pages=155\u2013168|doi=10.1177/092137400101300202|issn=0921-3740}}</ref> This group came to be known as [[Khoja]]s (from [[Khawaja]]), a title given by Sadardin,<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Nizari Ismaili Tradition in the Indo-Pakistan Subcontinent|last=Nanji|first=Azim|date=April 1979|publisher=Caravan Books|isbn=9780882060200|location=Delmar, NY}}</ref> that would predominantly merge into what is now understood as the Nizari Ismaili branch of Shia Islam.<ref name=\"asani\" />\n\nIn 1422, Jam Rai Dan was tribal leader in [[Sindh]] during the [[Samma Dynasty]]; he was converted to Islam by Sayad Eusuf-ud-Din and he adopted a new name Makrab Khan. At that time a person named Mankeji was head of 84 [[surname|nukhs]] of Lohanas, who were in favour in court of that Samma king. He was persuaded by ruler and the Qadri to convert to Islam. However, not all Lohanas were ready to convert from [[Hinduism]].<ref name=\"engineer\"/> But 700 Lohana families comprising some 6,178 persons converted in [[Thatta District|Thatta]], Sindh.  These are now known as [[Memon people|Memons]] (from [[Momin (disambiguation)|Momin]]s).<ref name=\"engineer\">{{cite book|title=The Muslim communities of Gujarat: an exploratory study of Bohras, Khojas, and Memons|first=Asgharali |last=Engineer|pages=42\u201344|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hY5AAAAAMAAJ|publisher=Ajanta Publications|year=1989}}</ref>{{dubious|reason=unknown author, unknown publisher|date=July 2017}}\n\n==Diaspora==\nThousands of Hindu [[Gujarati people|Gujaratis]] left India between 1880 - 1920 and migrated to [[British colonies]] in the [[African Great Lakes]] region of [[Uganda]], [[Kenya]] and [[Tanganyika]].A significant number of these came from the [[Patidar]] and Lohana communities.<ref>{{cite book |last=Herbert |first=J. |year=2004 |title=Contested terrains: negotiating ethnic boundaries in the city of Leicester since 1950 (Doctoral dissertation, History)|pages=25|url=https://lra.le.ac.uk/handle/2381/31063}}</ref> At that time,however, there was already a bustling merchant class diaspora of [[Gujarati Muslims]] in these countries.<ref>{{Cite journal |url=http://www.asiansinafrica.com/bestanden/Changing_Culture.pdf |last=Oonk |first=G.. |title=The Changing Culture of Hindu Lohanas in East Africa |journal=Contemporary Asians Studies |volume=13 |year=2004 |pages=83\u201397 |access-date=2011-10-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425085509/http://www.asiansinafrica.com/bestanden/Changing_Culture.pdf |archive-date=2012-04-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref> \n\nThe Lohana migrants to East Africa, of which there were 40,000 in 1970,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Gregory|first1=Robert G.|title=The rise and fall of philanthropy in East Africa : the Asian contribution|date=1992|publisher=Transaction Publishers|location=New Brunswick, U.S.A.|isbn=978-1-56000-007-5|page=[https://archive.org/details/risefallofphil00greg/page/28 28]|url=https://archive.org/details/risefallofphil00greg|url-access=registration}}</ref> came mainly from the Saurashtran cities of [[Jamnagar]] and [[Rajkot]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Kalka |first=I. |year=1986 |title=A case study of urban ethnicity: Harrow Gujaratis (Doctoral dissertation, London School of Economics and Political Science (United Kingdom) |page=74 |url=http://etheses.lse.ac.uk/1588/1/U144910.pdf}}</ref> Many Lohanas set up businesses in those countries, two of the most successful being those set up by [[Nanji Kalidas Mehta]] and [[Muljibhai Madhvani]].<ref>{{cite book|title=The Rise and Fall of Philanthropy in East Africa: The Asian's Contribution |first=Robert |last=Gregory |year=1992 |page=53 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=juZ5q6bttEoC&pg=PA53|isbn=9781412833356 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Persistence Amid Adversity:The Growth and Spatial Distribution of the Asian Population of Kenya, 1902-1963|first=Charles Joseph |last=Bennett|publisher=Syracuse University |year=1976 |pages=182|quote=Probably the success of the most prominent Lohana families in Uganda, Nanji Kalidas Mehta and Sons, M. P. Madhvani and D. K. Hindocha had much influence on Lohana migration from Porbandar and Jamnagar}}</ref>\n\nIn the later part of 20th century, following the independence of British colonies, and particularly after [[Idi Amin]]'s [[Expulsion of Asians from Uganda|expulsion order for South Asians in 1972]], most Lohanas moved to the [[United Kingdom]], and to a lesser extent to [[United States]] and [[Canada]].<ref name=gb>{{cit book|url=https://books.google.com/books?.id=nUsOAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA34 |title=Hinduism in Great Britain: the perpetuation of religion in an alien cultural|first= Richard |last=Burghart}}</ref> In the UK, the highest concentration of Lohanas and other Gujarati Hindu communities is around the [[West London]] suburbs of [[Wembley]] and [[Harrow, London|Harrow]], and the city of [[Leicester]] in the [[East Midlands]] region of England.<ref>{{cite book|last=Thompson|first=Linda|title=Young bilingual children in nursery schools|date=2000|publisher=Multilingual Matters|location=Clevedon, England|isbn=978-1853594540|pages=10\u201311|url=https://books.google.com/?id=3hvHeG77s1oC&pg=PA1}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Firth|first1=Shirley|title=Dying, death and bereavement in a British Hindu community|date=1997|publisher=Peeters|location=Leuven|isbn=978-90-6831-976-7|page=21|url=https://books.google.com/?id=pYNXC-HK1u0C&pg=PR8&dq=rameshbhai+mehta++leicester#v=onepage&q=lohana&f=false}}</ref> In 1979, there were 30,000 Lohanas in Britain.<ref>{{cite book |last=Kalka |first=I. |year=1986 |title=A case study of urban ethnicity: Harrow Gujaratis (Doctoral dissertation, London School of Economics and Political Science (United Kingdom) |page=79 |url=http://etheses.lse.ac.uk/1588/1/U144910.pdf}}</ref>\n\n==See Also==\n*[[Khasas]]\n*[[Kingdoms of Ancient India]]\n*[[Lahore]]\n*[[Mehta Kalu]], [[Guru Nanak|Guru Nanak's]] father, a Chandarana Lohana<ref>{{Google books|fleka3YEE8sC|Faith & Philosophy of Sikhism|page=60|text=Kalidas Chandarana}}\n\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{commonscatinline}}\n\n[[Category:Lohana]]\n[[Category:Sindhi tribes in India]]\n[[Category:Gujarati people]]\n[[Category:Hindu communities of Pakistan]]\n", "name_user": "41.80.64.195", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lohana"}
{"title_page": "People Power Revolution", "text_new": "{{hatnote|\"EDSA Revolution\" redirects here. For other uses, see [[EDSA Revolution (disambiguation)]]. For other uses of \"People Power\", see [[People Power (disambiguation)]].}}\n{{short description|Series of popular demonstrations in the Philippines in 1986}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox civil conflict\n|title=People Power Revolution\n|partof=\n|image= EDSA Revolution pic1.jpg\n|caption=Hundreds of thousands of people filling up [[Epifanio delos Santos Avenue]] (EDSA), facing northbound towards the Boni Serrano Avenue-EDSA intersection.<br />(February 1986)\n|date=  February 22\u201325, 1986 ({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|year1=1986|month1=2|day1=22|year2=1986|month2=2|day2=25}})\n|place=Philippines, primarily [[EDSA (road)|Epifanio de los Santos Avenue]], [[Metro Manila]]\n|causes= \n*[[Assassination of Benigno Aquino Jr.|Assassination]] of [[Benigno Aquino Jr.]] in 1983\n*Fraud during the [[1986 Philippine presidential election|1986 snap presidential election]]\n*Decades of [[Martial law in the Philippines|oppressive and totalitarian rule]]\n|goals=Removal of [[Ferdinand Marcos]] and installation of [[Corazon Aquino]] as President\n|status=\n|result= Revolutionary victory\n*Removal of [[Ferdinand Marcos]] from office\n*End of the [[History of the Philippines (1965\u201386)|Marcos era]]\n*Marcos fled to Hawaii\n*Start of the [[Fifth Philippine Republic]]\n*[[Corazon Aquino]] becomes President of the Philippines \n|side1='''People Power revolutionaries'''<br/>Political groups:<br/>\n*[[United Nationalist Democratic Organization|UNIDO]]\n*[[PDP\u2013Laban]]\n*[[Liberal Party (Philippines)|Liberal Party]]\nMilitary defectors:\n*[[Reform the Armed Forces Movement]]\n*[[Philippine Constabulary|Defected soldiers]]\nOthers:\n*Anti-Marcos civilian protesters\nReligious groups:\n*[[Archdiocese of Manila]]\n*[[Catholic Bishops' Conference of the Philippines|CBCP]]<ref name=convergence>{{cite news|last1=Sison|first1=Jose Maria|title=It was a convergence of various forces|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2479&dat=20060224&id=FFg1AAAAIBAJ&sjid=jiUMAAAAIBAJ&pg=1930,4044246|accessdate=August 4, 2014|work=Philippine Daily Inquirer|date=February 24, 2006}}</ref>\n*[[Protestantism in the Philippines|Protestant churches of the Philippines]]\nMilitant groups:\n*[[Bagong Alyansang Makabayan]]<ref name=convergence /><ref>{{cite news|last1=Araullo|first1=Carolina|title=Left was at Edsa and long before|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=4FU1AAAAIBAJ&sjid=aiUMAAAAIBAJ&pg=1015%2C30844986|accessdate=August 4, 2014|work=Philippine Daily Inquirer|date=March 2, 2000}}</ref>\n**[[Kilusang Mayo Uno]]\n**League of Filipino Students\n**Christians for National Liberation\n|side2=[[History of the Philippines (1965\u20131986)|'''Marcos Administration''']]<br />\n* [[Armed Forces of the Philippines]]\n**Forces loyal to Marcos\n* [[Presidential Security Group]]<ref name=lastdays>{{cite news|last1=Suarez|first1=Miguel|title=Marcos' last days filled with errors and humiliation|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=csNaAAAAIBAJ&sjid=blkDAAAAIBAJ&pg=7096%2C2434617|accessdate=August 4, 2014|work=The Evening Independent|agency=Associated Press|date=February 26, 1986|quote=She (Imelda) did not tell the crowd by that time all but a few thousand soldiers and officers, mostly those in the presidential guard, had by then turn against Marcos to join Mrs. Aquino's \"people power\" revolution}}</ref>\nGovernment parties:\n*[[Kilusang Bagong Lipunan]]\n|leadfigures1=[[Corazon Aquino]]<br/>[[Salvador Laurel]]<br/>[[Juan Ponce Enrile]]<br/>[[Fidel Ramos]]<br/>[[Gregorio Honasan|Gringo Honasan]] <br/>[[Jaime Sin|Jaime Cardinal Sin]]\n|leadfigures2=[[Ferdinand Marcos]]<br/>[[Imelda Marcos]]<br/>[[Fabian Ver]]\n|howmany1=2,000,000+ protestors\n|howmany2= No figures available\n|casualties1= \n|casualties2= \n|fatalities=\n|arrests=\n|detentions=\n|fined=\n|casualties_label=\n|notes=\n}}\n{{History of the Philippines}}\n{{RegchangePH}}\n\nThe '''People Power Revolution''' (also known as the '''EDSA Revolution''', the '''Philippine Revolution of 1986''', '''EDSA 1986''', '''EDSA I''' (pronounced as ''EDSA One'' or ''EDSA Uno'') and '''EDSA People Power''') was a series of popular [[Demonstration (people)|demonstration]]s in the [[Philippines]], mostly in [[Metro Manila]], from February 22\u201325, 1986. There was a sustained campaign of [[civil resistance]] against regime violence and alleged electoral fraud. The [[nonviolent revolution]] led to the departure of [[Ferdinand Marcos]], the end of his 20-year presidential rule, and the restoration of [[democracy]] in the Philippines.\n\nIt is also referred to as the '''Yellow Revolution''' due to the presence of yellow ribbons during demonstrations (in reference to the Tony Orlando [[Tie a Yellow Ribbon Round the Ole Oak Tree|song]])  following the [[Assassination of Benigno Aquino Jr.|assassination of Filipino senator Benigno \"Ninoy\" Aquino, Jr.]]<ref name=\"QUARTET p. 77\">{{cite web|url=http://www.stuartxchange.org/DayFour.html|title=The Original People Power Revolution|publisher=QUARTET p. 77|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080215175737/http://www.stuartxchange.org/DayFour.html|archivedate=February 15, 2008|accessdate=February 28, 2008|df=mdy-all}}</ref> in August 1983 upon his return to the Philippines from exile. It was widely seen as a victory of the people against two decades of presidential rule by President Marcos, and made news headlines as \"the revolution that surprised the world\".<ref name=\"Gandhi\">{{Citation |last=Kumar |first=Ravindra |publication-date=|title=Mahatma Gandhi at the Close of Twentieth Century|location= |publisher=Anmol Publications PVT. LTD. |isbn=978-81-261-1736-9 |page=168 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=lTNpstqGlAMC&pg=PA168&dq=EDSA+Revolution |accessdate= December 2, 2007 |year=2004}}.</ref>\n\nThe majority of the demonstrations took place on a long stretch of [[EDSA (road)|Epifanio de los Santos Avenue]], more commonly known by its acronym ''EDSA'', in [[Metro Manila]] from February 22\u201325, 1986. They involved over two million Filipino civilians, as well as several political and military groups, and religious groups led by [[Cardinal (Catholicism)|Cardinal]] [[Jaime Sin]], the [[Archbishop of Manila]], along with [[Catholic Bishops' Conference of the Philippines]] President Cardinal [[Ricardo Vidal]], the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Cebu|Archbishop of Cebu]]. The protests, fueled by the resistance and opposition from years of governance by President Marcos and his cronies, culminated with the absolute ruler and his family fleeing [[Malaca\u00f1ang Palace]] to exile in [[Hawaii]]. Ninoy Aquino's widow, [[Corazon Aquino]], was immediately installed as the [[List of Presidents of the Philippines|eleventh]] President as a result of the revolution.<ref>\n{{cite web| url = http://www.stuartxchange.com/EdsaIntro.html| title = Edsa people Power 1 Philippines| accessdate = December 3, 2007| publisher = Angela Stuart-Santiago| url-status = live| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071213180847/http://www.stuartxchange.com/EdsaIntro.html| archivedate = December 13, 2007| df = mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Events==\n{{Revolution sidebar}}\n\n===Aborted military coup===\nAppalled by the bold and apparent election irregularities, the [[Reform the Armed Forces Movement]] set into motion a coup attempt against Marcos. The initial plan was for a team to assault Malaca\u00f1an Palace and arrest Ferdinand Marcos. Other military units would take over key strategic facilities, such as the [[Ninoy Aquino International Airport|airport]], military bases,  the GHQAFP in [[Camp Aguinaldo]], and major highway junctions to restrict counteroffensive by Marcos-loyal troops.\n\nHowever, after Marcos learned about the plot, he ordered their leaders' arrest,<ref>{{Citation |last=West |first=Lois A. |publication-date=1997\n|title=Militant Labor in the Philippines |location= |publisher=Temple University Press |isbn=978-1-56639-491-8 |pages=19\u201320 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=KcaOhzm8gAQC&pg=PA20&dq=Philippine+People+power+revolution |accessdate= December 3, 2007 |year=1997}}.</ref> and presented to the international and local press some of the captured plotters, Maj. Saulito Aromin and Maj. Edgardo Doromal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stuartxchange.org/DayOne.html|title=Day One (EDSA: The Original People Power Revolution by Angela Stuart-Santiago)|accessdate=March 15, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150807094913/http://www.stuartxchange.org/DayOne.html|archivedate=August 7, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThreatened with their impending imprisonment, Defense Minister Juan Ponce Enrile and his fellow coup plotters decided to ask for help from then-AFP Vice Chief of Staff Lt. Gen [[Fidel Ramos]], who was also the chief of the [[Philippine Constabulary]] (now the Philippine National Police). Ramos agreed to resign from his position and support the plotters. Enrile also contacted the highly influential Cardinal Archbishop of Manila [[Jaime Sin]] for his support.\n\nAt about 6:30&nbsp;p.m. on February 22, Enrile and Ramos held a press conference at the Ministry of National Defense building in Camp Aguinaldo, where they announced that they had resigned from their positions in Marcos' cabinet and were withdrawing support from his government. Marcos himself later conducted a news conference calling on Enrile and Ramos to surrender, urging them to \"stop this stupidity\".<ref name=\"peoplepower_eyewitness\">{{Citation |last=Paul Sagmayao |first=Mercado |authorlink= |first2=Francisco S.|last2=Tatad |title=People Power: The Philippine Revolution of 1986: An Eyewitness History |publisher=The James B. Reuter, S.J., Foundation |year=1986 |location=[[Manila]], [[Philippines]] |pages= |url= |oclc=16874890}}</ref>\n\n===Sin's appeal===\nAfter Cardinal Vidal's condemnation of the snap election's fraudulent result, a message was aired over [[Radio Veritas]] at around 9 p.m., Cardinal Sin exhorted Filipinos in the capital to aid rebel leaders by going to the section of EDSA between [[Camp Crame]] and [[Camp Aguinaldo|Aguinaldo]] and giving emotional support, food and other supplies. For many, this seemed an unwise decision since civilians would not stand a chance against a dispersal by government troops. Many people, especially priests and nuns, still trooped to EDSA.<ref name=\"peoplepower_eyewitness\" />\n\nRadio Veritas played a critical role during the mass uprising. Former [[University of the Philippines]] president Francisco Nemenzo stated that: \"''Without Radio Veritas, it would have been difficult, if not impossible, to mobilize millions of people in a matter of hours.''\" Similarly, a certain account in the event said that: \"''Radio Veritas, in fact, was our umbilical cord to whatever else was going on''.\"<ref name=\"McCargo\">{{Citation |last=McCargo |first=Duncan |publication-date=2003|title=Media and Politics in Pacific Asia |location= |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-0-415-23375-0 |page=20|url=https://books.google.com/?id=CuGJ575iLLAC&pg=PA20&dq=Radio+Veritas+1986+Philippine+revolution |accessdate= December 3, 2007 |year=2003}}</ref>\n\n===Rising mass support===\nAt dawn, Sunday, government troops arrived to knock down the main transmitter of Radio Veritas, cutting off broadcasts to people in the provinces. The station switched to a standby transmitter with a limited range of broadcast.<ref name=\"McCargo\"/> The station was targeted because it had proven to be a valuable communications tool for the people supporting the rebels, keeping them informed of government troop movements and relaying requests for food, medicine, and supplies.<ref name=\"peoplepower_eyewitness\" />\n\nStill, people came to EDSA until it swelled to hundreds of thousands of unarmed civilians. The mood in the street was very festive, with many bringing whole families. Performers entertained the crowds, nuns and priests led prayer vigils, and people set up barricades and makeshift sandbags, trees, and vehicles in several places along EDSA and intersecting streets such as Santolan and Ortigas Avenue. Everywhere, people listened to Radio Veritas on their radios. Several groups sang ''[[Bayan Ko]]'' (My Homeland),<ref>{{Citation |last=Taylor |first=Robert H. |publication-date=2002\n|title=The Idea of Freedom in Asia and Africa |location= |publisher= Stanford University Press |isbn=978-0-8047-4514-7 |page=210 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=RfbSlkGP8TEC&pg=PA210&dq=Bayan+Ko+in+1986+Philippine+revolution |accessdate= December 3, 2007 |year=2002}}.</ref> which, since 1980, had become a patriotic anthem of the opposition. People frequently flashed the 'LABAN' sign,<ref>{{Citation |last=Crisostomo |first=Isabelo T. |publication-date=1987|title=Cory, Profile of a President: The Historic Rise to Power of Corazon |location=|publisher=Branden Books |isbn=978-0-8283-1913-3 |page=217 |url=https://books.google.com/id=iW_ddLowBYkC&pg=PA217&dq=LABAN+signs+during+EDSA+I |accessdate= December 3, 2007 |year=1987}}.</ref> which is an \"L\" formed with their thumb and index finger. 'laban' is the Filipino word for 'fight', but also the abbreviation of [[Lakas ng Bayan]], Ninoy Aquino's party.\n\nAfter lunch on February 23, Enrile and Ramos decided to consolidate their positions. Enrile crossed EDSA from [[Camp Aguinaldo]] to [[Camp Crame]] amidst cheers from the crowd.<ref name=\"peoplepower_eyewitness\" />\n\nIn the mid-afternoon, [[Radio Veritas]] relayed reports of [[Philippine Marine Corps|Marines]] massing near the camps in the east and [[LVT-5]] tanks approaching from the north and south. A contingent of Marines with tanks and armored vans, led by Brigadier General Artemio Tadiar, was stopped along Ortigas Avenue, about two kilometers from the camps, by tens of thousands of people.<ref>{{Citation |last=Lizano |first=Lolita |publication-date=1988|title=Flower in a Gun Barrel: The Untold Story of the Edsa Revolution |location= |publisher= L.R. Lizano|isbn= |page=|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Bm0yAAAAIAAJ&dq=EDSA+Revolution&q=EDSA+Revolution |accessdate= December 2, 2007 |year=1988}}.</ref> Nuns holding rosaries knelt in front of the tanks and men and women linked arms together to block the troops.<ref>{{Citation |last=Merkl |first=Peter H. |publication-date=2005|title=The Rift Between America And Old Europe: the distracted eagle |location= |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-0-415-35985-6 |page=144 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=WavpuvE2HA4C&pg=PA144&dq=EDSA+Revolution |accessdate= December 2, 2007 |year=2005}}.</ref> Tadiar asked the crowds to make a clearing for them, but they did not budge. In the end, the troops retreated with no shots fired.<ref name=\"peoplepower_eyewitness\" />\n\nBy evening, the standby transmitter of Radio Veritas failed. Shortly after midnight, the staff was able to go to another station to begin broadcasting from a secret location under the moniker [[DZRJ-AM|\"Radyo Bandido\"]] (Outlaw Radio, which is now known as [[DZRJ-AM]]). June Keithley, with her husband [[Angelo Castro, Jr.]], was the radio broadcaster who continued Radio Veritas' program throughout the night and in the remaining days.<ref name=\"peoplepower_eyewitness\"/>\n\n===More military defections===\nAt dawn on Monday, February 24, the first serious encounter with government troops occurred. Marines marching from Libis, in the east, lobbed tear gas at the demonstrators, who quickly dispersed. Some 3,000 Marines then entered and held the east side of Camp Aguinaldo.<ref name=\"peoplepower_eyewitness\" />\n\nLater, helicopters manned by the 15th Strike Wing of the [[Philippine Air Force]], led by Colonel Antonio Sotelo, were ordered from Sangley Point in Cavite (South of Manila) to head to Camp Crame.<ref name=\"Crisostomo\">{{Citation |last=Crisostomo |first=Isabelo T. |publication-date=1987\n|title=Cory, Profile of a President: The Historic Rise to Power of Corazon |location= |publisher= Branden Books|isbn= 978-0-8283-1913-3|page=226 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=iW_ddLowBYkC&pg=PA226&dq=Col.+Antonio+Sotelo+to+camp+crame |accessdate= December 3, 2007 |date=April 1, 1987}}.</ref> Secretly, the squadron had already defected and instead of attacking Camp Crame, landed in it, with the crowds cheering and hugging the pilots and crew members.<ref name=\"peoplepower_eyewitness\" />\n\nA [[Bell 214]] helicopter piloted by Major Deo Cruz of the 205th Helicopter Wing and [[Sikorsky S-76]] gunships piloted by Colonel Charles Hotchkiss of the 20th Air Commando Squadron joined the rebel squadron earlier in the air. The presence of the helicopters boosted the morale of Enrile and Ramos who had been continually encouraging their fellow soldiers to join the opposition movement.<ref name=\"peoplepower_eyewitness\" /> In the afternoon, Aquino arrived at the base where Enrile, Ramos, RAM officers and a throng were waiting.<ref name=\"Crisostomo\"/>\n\n===The capture of MBS-4===\nAt around that time, [[June Keithley]] received reports that Marcos had left Malaca\u00f1ang Palace and broadcast this to the people at EDSA. The crowd celebrated and even Ramos and Enrile came out from Crame to appear to the crowds. The jubilation was however short-lived as Marcos later appeared on television on the government-controlled [[People's Television Network|MBS-4]],<ref>{{Citation |last=Maramba |first=Asuncion David |publication-date=1987\n|title=On the Scene: The Philippine Press Coverage of the 1986 Revolution |location= |publisher=Solar publishing Corp. |isbn= 978-971-17-0628-9|page=27 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=2QAeAAAAMAAJ&dq=Channel+9+tower+in+1986+revolution&q=Channel+4 |accessdate= December 3, 2007 |year=1987}}.</ref> (using the foreclosed [[ABS-CBN (television network)|ABS-CBN]] facilities, transmitter, and compound in [[ABS-CBN Broadcasting Center|Broadcast Plaza]]) declaring that he would not step down. It was thereafter speculated that the false report was a calculated move against Marcos to encourage more defections.<ref name=\"peoplepower_eyewitness\" />\n\nDuring this broadcast, MBS-4 suddenly went off the air. A contingent of rebels, under Colonel Mariano Santiago, had captured the station.  MBS-4 was put back on the air shortly after noon, with [[Orly Punzalan]] announcing on live television, \"Channel 4 is on the air again to serve the people.\" By this time, the crowds at EDSA had swollen to over a million. (Some estimates placed them at two million.)<ref name=\"peoplepower_eyewitness\" />\n\nThis broadcast was considered the \"return\" of [[ABS-CBN (television network)|ABS-CBN]] on air because this was the time when former employees of the network were inside the complex after 14 years of closure since Marcos took it over during the Martial Law of 1972. [[DZRJ-AM|\"Radyo Bandido\"]] ended broadcasting that afternoon, while Radio Veritas resumed transmissions, this time from the [[ABS-CBN Broadcasting Center|Broadcast Plaza]]'s radio studios.\n\nIn the late afternoon, rebel helicopters attacked [[Villamor Airbase]], destroying presidential air assets. Another helicopter went to [[Malaca\u00f1an Palace|Malaca\u00f1ang]], fired a rocket, and caused minor damage. Later, most of the officers who had graduated from the [[Philippine Military Academy]] (PMA) defected. The majority of the Armed Forces had already changed sides.<ref name=\"peoplepower_eyewitness\" />\n\n===Marcos orders not to shoot===\n{{listen| filename=Marcos_-_ver.ogg|title=\"My order is not to attack\" | description=[[President of the Philippines|President]] [[Ferdinand Marcos]] and General [[Fabian Ver]] during a press conference in Malaca\u00f1an Palace. | format= [[Ogg]]}}\n\nPrior dialogues to stop the revolution had not succeeded with the Armed Forces of the Philippines, which was led by General Fabian Ver. AFP was ready to mount an airstrike on the day but Marcos ordered them to halt.\n\nThe actual dialogue on TV between Marcos and then AFP Chief of Staff General Fabian Ver went as follows:\n\n{{quote|Fabian Ver: The Ambush there is aiming to mount there in the top. Very quickly, you must immediately leave to conquer them, immediately, Mr. President.<br /> \nFerdinand Marcos: Just wait, come here.<br />\nVer: Please, Your Honor, so we can immediately strike them. We have to immobilize the helicopters that they've got. We have two fighter planes flying now to strike at any time, sir.<br />\nMarcos: My order is not to attack. No, no, no! Hold on. My order is not to attack.<br />\nVer: They are massing civilians near our troops and we cannot keep on withdrawing. You asked me to withdraw yesterday\u2013<br />\nMarcos (interrupting): Uh yes, but ah... My order is to disperse without shooting them.<br />\nVer: We cannot withdraw all the time...<br /> \nMarcos: No! No! No! Hold on! You disperse the crowd without shooting them.}}\n\n===Two inaugurations===\n[[File:Corazon Aquino inauguration.jpg|thumb|300px|Corazon Aquino was inaugurated as the 11th president of the Philippines on February 25, 1986 at Sampaguita Hall (Now Kalayaan Hall).]]\nOn the morning of Tuesday, February 25, at around 7 a.m., a minor clash occurred between loyal government troops and the reformists. Snipers stationed atop the crony-owned [[Radio Philippines Network|RPN-9]] transmitter in Panay Avenue, near MBS-4, began shooting at the reformists. Many rebel soldiers surged to the station,<ref name=\"peoplepower_eyewitness\" /> and a rebel S-76 helicopter later shot the snipers at the broadcast tower. The troops later left after a V-150 was blocked by the crowd assembled.\n\nLater in the morning, [[Corazon Aquino]] was inaugurated as President of the Philippines in a simple ceremony at [[Club Filipino]]<ref>{{Citation |last=Crisostomo |first=Isabelo T. |publication-date=|title=Cory, Profile of a President: The Historic Rise to Power of Corazon |location= |publisher= Branden Books|isbn= 978-0-8283-1913-3|page=257 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=iW_ddLowBYkC&pg=PA257&dq=Cory+Aquino+in+Club+Filipino |accessdate= December 3, 2007 |date=April 1, 1987}}.</ref> in Greenhills, about a kilometer from Camp Crame. She was sworn in as President by Senior Associate Justice [[Claudio Teehankee]], and Laurel as Vice-President by Justice Vicente Abad Santos. The Bible on which Aquino swore her oath was held by her mother-in-law Aurora Aquino, the mother of [[Benigno Aquino, Jr.|Ninoy Aquino]]. Attending the ceremonies were Ramos, who was then promoted to General, Enrile, and many politicians.<ref name=\"peoplepower_eyewitness\" />\n\nOutside Club Filipino, all the way to EDSA, hundreds of people cheered and celebrated. ''[[Bayan Ko]]'' (''My Country'', a popular folk song and the unofficial National Anthem of protest) was sung after Aquino's oath-taking. Many people wore yellow, the color of Aquino's presidential campaign.\n\nAn hour later, Marcos held the inauguration at [[Malaca\u00f1ang Palace]]. Loyalist civilians attended the ceremony, shouting \"''Marcos, Marcos, Marcos pa rin!'' (Marcos, Marcos, still Marcos!)\". On the Palace balcony, Marcos took the Oath of Office, aired on [[Intercontinental Broadcasting Corporation|IBC-13]] and [[Radio Philippines Network|RPN-9]] (RPN-9 was going off-the-air during the broadcast of the inauguration, as its transmitter was captured by reformist soldiers).<ref name=\"peoplepower_eyewitness\" /> None of the invited foreign dignitaries attended the ceremony, for security reasons. The couple finally emerged on the balcony of the Palace before 3,000 KBL loyalists who were shouting, \"Capture the snakes!\"<ref name=\"Ellison\">{{Citation |last=Ellison |first=Katherine |publication-date=2005|title=Imelda: Steel Butterfly of the Philippines |location= |publisher=iUniverse |isbn=978-0-595-34922-7 |page=244 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=Dfl53AtDM0oC&pg=RA1-PA244&dq=Dahil+Sa+sang+by+Imelda+Marcos |accessdate= December 3, 2007 |year=2005}}.</ref> Rather tearfully,<ref name=\"Ellison\"/> First Lady Imelda Marcos gave a farewell rendition of the couple's theme song \u2013 the 1938 ''[[kundiman]]'' ''\"[[Dahil Sa Iyo]]\"'' (Because of You) \u2013 chanting the song's entreaties in [[Tagalog language|Tagalog]]:\n\n<blockquote>\nBecause of you, I became happy<br />\nLoving I shall offer you<br />\nIf it is true I shall be enslaved by you<br />\nAll of this because of you.<ref name=\"Ellison\"/>\n</blockquote>\n\nThe broadcast of the event was interrupted as rebel troops successfully captured the other stations.<ref name=\"peoplepower_eyewitness\" />\n\nBy this time, hundreds of people had amassed at the barricades along [[Mendiola]], only a hundred meters away from Malaca\u00f1ang. They were prevented from storming the Palace by loyal government troops securing the area. The angry demonstrators were pacified by priests who warned them not to be violent.<ref name=\"peoplepower_eyewitness\" />\n\n===Marcos' departure===\nAt 3:00&nbsp;p.m. ([[Eastern Time Zone|EST]]) on Monday, President Marcos phoned [[United States Senate|United States Senator]] [[Paul Laxalt]],<ref name=\"Ellison\"/> asking for advice from the [[White House]]. Laxalt advised him to \"cut and cut clean\",<ref>{{Cite book|title = Reagan: the life|last = Brands|first = H W|publisher = Doubleday|year = 2015|isbn = 9780385536400|location = New York|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=wHd5BAAAQBAJ&lpg=PT617&vq=laxalt%20marcos%20cut%20and%20cut%20clean&dq=laxalt%20marcos%20cut%20and%20cut%20clean&pg=PT617#v=onepage&q=laxalt%20marcos%20cut%20and%20cut%20clean&f=false|url-status = live|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160105160957/https://books.google.com/books?id=wHd5BAAAQBAJ&lpg=PT617&vq=laxalt%20marcos%20cut%20and%20cut%20clean&dq=laxalt%20marcos%20cut%20and%20cut%20clean&pg=PT617#v=onepage&q=laxalt%20marcos%20cut%20and%20cut%20clean&f=false|archivedate = January 5, 2016|df = mdy-all}}</ref> to which Marcos expressed his disappointment after a short pause. In the afternoon, Marcos talked to Minister Enrile, asking for safe passage for him, his family, and close allies such as General Ver.\n\nAt midnight [[Philippine Standard Time|PHT]], the Marcos family boarded a [[United States Air Force]] HH-3E Rescue [[helicopter]]<ref name=\"Halperin\">{{Citation|last=Halperin|first=Jonathan J.|title=The Other Side: How Soviets and Americans Perceive Each Other|url=https://books.google.com/?id=H1so7Od--csC&pg=PA63&dq=Marcos+departure|page=63|publication-date=1987|year=1987|location=|publisher=Transaction Publishers|isbn=978-0-88738-687-9|accessdate=December 3, 2007}}.</ref> and flew to [[Clark Air Base]] in [[Angeles City]] 83 kilometers north of Manila.\n\nAt Clark Air Base, Marcos asked to spend a couple of days with his family in Ilocos Norte, his native province. Aquino vetoed the request. President Reagan privately derided Cory Aquino for denying Marcos a last look at his home province.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/03/19/magazine/reagan-and-the-philippines-setting-marcos-adrift.html?pagewanted=all |title=REAGAN AND THE PHILIPPINES: Setting Marcos Adrift |accessdate=February 11, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170111001104/http://www.nytimes.com/1989/03/19/magazine/reagan-and-the-philippines-setting-marcos-adrift.html?pagewanted=all |archivedate=January 11, 2017  |newspaper=The New York Times |date=March 19, 1989 |last1=Karnow |first1=Stanley }}</ref>\n\nThe deposed First Family and their servants then rode US Air Force [[DC9|DC-9 Medivac]] and [[C-141 Starlifter|C-141B]] planes to [[Andersen Air Force Base]] in the north of the United States territory of [[Guam]], then flying to Hickam Air Force Base in [[Hawaii]] where Marcos finally arrived on February 26. The United States Government documented that they entered the United States with millions of dollars in jewelry, gold, stocks, and cash.<ref name=\"Gandhi\"/><ref name=\"peoplepower_eyewitness\"/>\n\nWhen news of the Marcos family's departure reached civilians, many rejoiced and danced in the streets. Over at [[Mendiola]], the demonstrators stormed the Palace, which was closed to ordinary people for around a decade. Despite looting by some angry protesters, the majority wandered about inside through rooms where national history was shaped, looking at objects extravagant and mundane that the Marcos clan and its court had abandoned in their flight.{{Citation needed|date=February 2011}}\n\nIn other countries, people also rejoiced and congratulated Filipinos they knew. [[CBS]] anchorman [[Bob Simon]] reported: \"We Americans like to think we taught the Filipinos democracy. Well, tonight they are teaching the world.\" <ref name=\"peoplepower_eyewitness\"/>\n\nSome authors say that Marcos prevented civil war similar to the [[Syrian Civil War]] by refusing to use guns notwithstanding the insistence of his top general, and by agreeing to step down during the EDSA revolution.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.manilatimes.net/level-duterte-drop-scourge-syrian-civil-war/291350/ |title=Level up on Duterte or drop into the scourge of the Syrian civil war |accessdate=January 10, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170112181957/http://www.manilatimes.net/level-duterte-drop-scourge-syrian-civil-war/291350/ |archivedate=January 12, 2017  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://thestandard.com.ph/opinion/columns/hail-to-the-chair-by-victor-avecilla/226306/why-the-reds-hate-marcos-20170110.html |title=Why the Reds hate Marcos - Manila Standard |accessdate=February 24, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170112181419/http://thestandard.com.ph/opinion/columns/hail-to-the-chair-by-victor-avecilla/226306/why-the-reds-hate-marcos-20170110.html |archivedate=January 12, 2017  }}</ref> The White House said, \"By leaving the Philippines at a critical juncture in his nation's history, Mr. Marcos permitted the peaceful transition to popular, democratic rule.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/09/29/obituaries/ferdinand-marcos-ousted-leader-of-philippines-dies-at-72-in-exile.html |title=Ferdinand Marcos, Ousted Leader of Philippines, Dies at 72 in Exile |accessdate=February 11, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170112181330/http://www.nytimes.com/1989/09/29/obituaries/ferdinand-marcos-ousted-leader-of-philippines-dies-at-72-in-exile.html |archivedate=January 12, 2017  |newspaper=The New York Times |date=September 29, 1989 |last1=Gross |first1=Jane }}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\n{{main|Presidency of Corazon Aquino}}\n{{wikisource|Provisional Constitution of the Philippines (1986)|Proclamation \u2116 3: Provisional Constitution of the Philippines (1986)}}\n\nImmediately after her accession, Aquino issued Proclamation No. 3, a [[provisional constitution]] which established a [[Revolutionary government in the Philippines|revolutionary government]]. The edict promulgated the 1986 Freedom Constitution, which retained or superseded various provisions of the 1973 Constitution that were in force up to that point. This allowed Aquino to wield both executive and legislative powers; among her first acts was to unilaterally abolish the [[Batasang Pambansa]] (the unicameral legislature [[1984 Philippine parliamentary election|duly elected in 1984]]), pending a plebiscite for a more permanent Constitution and the establishment of a new Congress by 1987.<ref>{{cite book |author=Joaquin G. Bernas |title=The Intent of the 1986 Constitution Writers|publisher=Rex Book Store|location=Manila, Philippines|year=1995|pages=2\u20134 |author-link=Joaquin G. Bernas}}</ref>\n\nThe revolution had an effect on [[democratization]] movements in such countries as [[Taiwan]] and [[South Korea]]; other effects include the restoration of the freedom of the press, abolition of repressive laws enforced by the previous regime, the adoption of the [[1987 Constitution]], and the subordination of the military to civilian rule, despite several coup attempts during Aquino's rule.<ref name=\"aftermath\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-pacific-12567320 |title=People Power at 25: Long road to Philippine democracy |first=Kate |last=McGeown |work=BBC.co.uk |date=February 25, 2011 |accessdate=February 25, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110226073508/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-pacific-12567320 |archivedate=February 26, 2011  }}</ref>\n\nThe revolution provided for the restoration of democratic institutions after thirteen years of totalitarian rule and these institutions has been used by various groups to challenge the entrenched [[Political family|political families]] and to strengthen Philippine democracy.<ref>{{Citation |last=Putzel |first=James |date=Spring 1999 |title=Survival of an imperfect democracy in the Philippines |journal=Democratization |volume=6 |issue=1 |pages=198\u2013223 |doi=10.1080/13510349908403603 |postscript=.  }}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:VisitorViewingBantayogEDSATimeline.jpg|thumb|A visitor to the [[Bantayog ng mga Bayani]] Museum browses through a timeline of the EDSA Revolution, one of the last sequences in the Museum's coverage of protest movements against the Marcos dictatorship.]]The People Power Revolution has inspired a call for a change of government through peaceful protests rather than bloodshed.  Many similar revolutions have followed since then, taking the Philippine example of nonviolent regime change, such as that in [[Fall of the Berlin Wall|East Germany]] and many other former Soviet Bloc countries.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sbs.com.au/news/article/2014/02/24/comment-remembering-philippines-people-power-revolution |title=Archived copy |accessdate=May 16, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161221214001/http://www.sbs.com.au/news/article/2014/02/24/comment-remembering-philippines-people-power-revolution |archivedate=December 21, 2016  }}</ref> It also helped inspire the [[Arab Spring]] in 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.lse.ac.uk/ideas/2011/03/exporting-%e2%80%9cpeople-power%e2%80%9d-the-philippine-revolution-25-years-later/|title=Exporting \"People Power\"? The Philippine Revolution 25 Years Later|date=March 15, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe EDSA Revolution Anniversary is a special [[public holiday in the Philippines]].  Since 2002, the holiday has been a special non-working holiday.<ref name=\"pn295\">[http://www.gov.ph/2011/11/24/proclamation-no-295-s-2011/ Proclamation No. 295: Declaring 2012 National Holidays] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130117171806/http://www.gov.ph/2011/11/24/proclamation-no-295-s-2011/ |date=January 17, 2013 }}, December 12, 2011, Official Gazette of the Philippines</ref><ref name=\"p1841\">{{cite web |url=http://www.laborlaw.usc-law.org/download/pdf/2010_Holidays.pdf |title=Proclamation No. 1841 |date=July 21, 2009 |website=Philippine Labor Laws |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171010145524/http://www.laborlaw.usc-law.org/download/pdf/2010_Holidays.pdf |archivedate=October 10, 2017  }}</ref>\n[[File:People Power Revolution commemorative 10-peso coin obverse and reverse.png|right|thumbnail|10-peso coin commemorating the People Power Revolution]]\n\nRampant corruption during the term of President [[Joseph Estrada]] led to the similar [[2001 EDSA Revolution]] leading to his resignation from the presidency.\n\nIn 2003, the ''Radio Broadcast of the Philippine People Power Revolution'' was inscribed in the [[UNESCO]] [[Memory of the World Register]], the official documentary heritage list of the [[United Nations]]' educational and scientific body.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.unesco.org/new/en/communication-and-information/flagship-project-activities/memory-of-the-world/register/full-list-of-registered-heritage/registered-heritage-page-7/radio-broadcast-of-the-philippine-people-power-revolution/#c188230|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150824190648/http://www.unesco.org/new/en/communication-and-information/flagship-project-activities/memory-of-the-world/register/full-list-of-registered-heritage/registered-heritage-page-7/radio-broadcast-of-the-philippine-people-power-revolution/|url-status=dead|title=Radio Broadcast of the Philippine People Power Revolution &#124; United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization|archivedate=August 24, 2015|website=www.unesco.org}}</ref>\n\nOn September 12, 2007, [[Trial of Joseph Estrada|Estrada was found guilty of plunder]] beyond reasonable doubt by the [[Sandiganbayan|Philippine anti-graft court]] and sentenced to life imprisonment.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=http://globalnation.inquirer.net/84269/estradas-plunder-conviction-remembered|title=Estrada's plunder conviction remembered|last=Rodis|first=Rodel|date=August 28, 2013|work=Inquirer|access-date=April 27, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/60117/erap-guilty-of-plunder-sentenced-to-reclusion-perpetua/story/|title=Erap guilty of plunder, sentenced to reclusion perpetua|last=|first=|date=September 12, 2007|work=GMA News Online|access-date=April 27, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\"Sturcke\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2007/sep/12/philippines|title=Estrada given life sentence for corruption|last=Sturcke|first=James|date=September 12, 2007|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=April 27, 2018}}</ref> He was pardoned by President Gloria Macapagal-Arroyo on October 25, 2007.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-philippines-estrada-idUKMNB0007120071025|title=Former Philippine president Estrada pardoned|last=Mogato|first=Manny|date=October 25, 2007|work=Reuters|access-date=April 27, 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==Timeline==\n{{main|Timeline of the People Power Revolution}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[EDSA (road)|Epifanio de los Santos Avenue]], for more information about the road\n*\"[[Handog ng Pilipino sa Mundo]]\"\n*\"[[Magkaisa]]\"\n*\"[[Bayan Ko]]\"\n*[[EDSA Shrine]]\n*[[People Power Monument]]\n\n'''General:'''\n* [[Timeline of the Marcos Dictatorship]]\n\n'''Similar events:'''\n*[[EDSA II]]\n*[[EDSA III]]\n* [[Gda\u0144sk Agreement]] of 1980 and [[Polish Round Table Agreement|Round Table Agreement]] of 1989, both induced by peaceful protests in Poland by [[Solidarity (Polish trade union)|Solidarity]]\n*[[Tiananmen Square protests of 1989]] \n*[[Romanian Revolution]]\n*[[Velvet Revolution]], in Czechoslovakia\n*[[8888 Uprising]], in Burma (now Myanmar)\n*[[May 1998 riots of Indonesia]]\n*[[Iranian Revolution]]\n*[[Tunisian Revolution]]\n*[[Egyptian Revolution of 2011]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n{{Commons category}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*Baron, Cynthia S. and Suazo, Melba M. ''Nine Letters: The Story of the 1986 Filipino Revolution.'' Quezon City, Philippines. Gerardo P. Baron Books. 1986.\n*Johnson, Brian. ''The Four Days of Courage: The Untold Story of the People Who Brought Marcos Down.'' Toronto, Canada. McClelland and Stewart, 1987.\n* {{Cite book|last= Lacsamana |first= Leodivico Cruz |title=Philippine History and Government |edition= Second |year=1990 |isbn= 971-06-1894-6 |publisher=Phoenix Publishing House, Inc.|ref=harv}}\n*Mendoza, Amado, '\"People Power\" in the Philippines, 1983\u201386', in [[Adam Roberts (scholar)|Adam Roberts]] and [[Timothy Garton Ash]] (eds.), [http://web.archive.bibalex.org/web/20111208132001/http://ukcatalogue.oup.com/product/9780199552016.do ''Civil Resistance and Power Politics: The Experience of Non-violent Action from Gandhi to the Present''], Oxford: Oxford University Press, 2009. {{ISBN|978-0-19-955201-6}}.  [https://web.archive.org/web/20110629175120/http://www.oup.com/us/catalog/general/subject/Politics/ComparativePolitics/?view=usa&ci=9780199552016 ''US edition'']. [https://books.google.com/books?id=BxOQKrCe7UUC&dq=Civil+resistance+and+power+politics&source=gbs_navlinks_s ''On Google''].\n*Mercado, Paul Sagmayao, and Tatad, Francisco S. ''People Power: The Philippine Revolution of 1986: An eyewitness history.'' Manila, Philippines. The James B. Reuter, S.J., Foundation. 1986.\n*Schock, Kurt. ''Unarmed Insurrections: People Power Movements in Nondemocracies.'' Minneapolis, USA. University of Minnesota Press. 2005.\n{{Martial EDSA  |state=expanded}}\n{{Fall of Communism}}\n{{Cold War}}\n{{Corazon Aquino}}\n{{PhilippinePresElections}}\n{{Philippines topics}}\n{{Philippine national holidays}}\n\n[[Category:People Power Revolution| ]]\n[[Category:1986 in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:1980s coups d'\u00e9tat and coup attempts]]\n[[Category:20th-century revolutions]]\n[[Category:Armed Forces of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Battles and conflicts without fatalities]]\n[[Category:Colour revolutions]]\n[[Category:Presidency of Ferdinand Marcos]]\n[[Category:History of the Philippines (1965\u201386)]]\n[[Category:History of Metro Manila]]\n[[Category:Imelda Marcos]]\n[[Category:Military history of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Nonviolent revolutions]]\n[[Category:Protests in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Presidential elections in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Rebellions in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:February 1986 events in Asia]]\n", "text_old": "{{hatnote|\"EDSA Revolution\" redirects here. For other uses, see [[EDSA Revolution (disambiguation)]]. For other uses of \"People Power\", see [[People Power (disambiguation)]].}}\n{{short description|Series of popular demonstrations in the Philippines in 1986}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox civil conflict\n|title=People Power Revolution\n|partof=\n|image= EDSA Revolution pic1.jpg\n|caption=Hundreds of thousands of people filling up [[Epifanio delos Santos Avenue]] (EDSA), facing northbound towards the Boni Serrano Avenue-EDSA intersection.<br />(February 1986)\n|date=  February 22\u201325, 1986 ({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|year1=1986|month1=2|day1=22|year2=1986|month2=2|day2=25}})\n|place=Philippines, primarily [[EDSA (road)|Epifanio de los Santos Avenue]], [[Metro Manila]]\n|causes= \n*[[Assassination of Benigno Aquino Jr.|Assassination]] of [[Benigno Aquino Jr.]] in 1983\n*Fraud during the [[1986 Philippine presidential election|1986 snap presidential election]]\n*Decades of [[Martial law in the Philippines|oppressive and totalitarian rule]]\n|goals=Removal of [[Ferdinand Marcos]] and installation of [[Corazon Aquino]] as President\n|status=\n|result= Revolutionary victory\n*Removal of [[Ferdinand Marcos]] from office\n*End of the [[History of the Philippines (1965\u201386)|Marcos era]]\n*Marcos fled to Hawaii\n*Start of the [[Fifth Philippine Republic]]\n*[[Corazon Aquino]] becomes President of the Philippines \n|side1='''People Power revolutionaries'''<br/>Political groups:<br/>\n*[[United Nationalist Democratic Organization|UNIDO]]\n*[[PDP\u2013Laban]]\n*[[Liberal Party (Philippines)|Liberal Party]]\nMilitary defectors:\n*[[Reform the Armed Forces Movement]]\n*[[Philippine Constabulary|Defected soldiers]]\nOthers:\n*Anti-Marcos civilian protesters\nReligious groups:\n*[[Archdiocese of Manila]]\n*[[Catholic Bishops' Conference of the Philippines|CBCP]]<ref name=convergence>{{cite news|last1=Sison|first1=Jose Maria|title=It was a convergence of various forces|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2479&dat=20060224&id=FFg1AAAAIBAJ&sjid=jiUMAAAAIBAJ&pg=1930,4044246|accessdate=August 4, 2014|work=Philippine Daily Inquirer|date=February 24, 2006}}</ref>\n*[[Protestantism in the Philippines|Protestant churches of the Philippines]]\nMilitant groups:\n*[[Bagong Alyansang Makabayan]]<ref name=convergence /><ref>{{cite news|last1=Araullo|first1=Carolina|title=Left was at Edsa and long before|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=4FU1AAAAIBAJ&sjid=aiUMAAAAIBAJ&pg=1015%2C30844986|accessdate=August 4, 2014|work=Philippine Daily Inquirer|date=March 2, 2000}}</ref>\n**[[Kilusang Mayo Uno]]\n**League of Filipino Students\n**Christians for National Liberation\n|side2=[[History of the Philippines (1965\u20131986)|'''Marcos Administration''']]<br />\n* [[Armed Forces of the Philippines]]\n**Forces loyal to Marcos\n* [[Presidential Security Group]]<ref name=lastdays>{{cite news|last1=Suarez|first1=Miguel|title=Marcos' last days filled with errors and humiliation|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=csNaAAAAIBAJ&sjid=blkDAAAAIBAJ&pg=7096%2C2434617|accessdate=August 4, 2014|work=The Evening Independent|agency=Associated Press|date=February 26, 1986|quote=She (Imelda) did not tell the crowd by that time all but a few thousand soldiers and officers, mostly those in the presidential guard, had by then turn against Marcos to join Mrs. Aquino's \"people power\" revolution}}</ref>\nGovernment parties:\n*[[Kilusang Bagong Lipunan]]\n|leadfigures1=[[Corazon Aquino]]<br/>[[Salvador Laurel]]<br/>[[Juan Ponce Enrile]]<br/>[[Fidel Ramos]]<br/>[[Gregorio Honasan|Gringo Honasan]] <br/>[[Jaime Sin|Jaime Cardinal Sin]]\n|leadfigures2=[[Ferdinand Marcos]]<br/>[[Imelda Marcos]]<br/>[[Fabian Ver]]\n|howmany1=2,000,000+ protestors\n|howmany2= No figures available\n|casualties1= \n|casualties2= \n|fatalities=\n|arrests=\n|detentions=\n|fined=\n|casualties_label=\n|notes=\n}}\n{{History of the Philippines}}\n{{RegchangePH}}\n\nThe '''People Power Revolution''' (also known as the '''EDSA Revolution''', the '''Philippine Revolution of 1986''', '''EDSA 1986''', '''EDSA I''' (pronounced as ''EDSA One'' or ''EDSA Uno'') and '''EDSA People Power''') was a series of popular [[Demonstration (people)|demonstration]]s in the [[Philippines]], mostly in [[Metro Manila]], from February 22\u201325, 1986. There was a sustained campaign of [[civil resistance]] against regime violence and alleged electoral fraud. The [[nonviolent revolution]] led to the departure of [[Ferdinand Marcos]], the end of his 20-year presidential rule, and the restoration of [[democracy]] in the Philippines.\n\nIt is also referred to as the '''Yellow Revolution''' due to the presence of yellow ribbons during demonstrations (in reference to the Tony Orlando [[Tie a Yellow Ribbon Round the Ole Oak Tree|song]])  following the [[Assassination of Benigno Aquino Jr.|assassination of Filipino senator Benigno \"Ninoy\" Aquino, Jr.]]<ref name=\"QUARTET p. 77\">{{cite web|url=http://www.stuartxchange.org/DayFour.html|title=The Original People Power Revolution|publisher=QUARTET p. 77|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080215175737/http://www.stuartxchange.org/DayFour.html|archivedate=February 15, 2008|accessdate=February 28, 2008|df=mdy-all}}</ref> in August 1983 upon his return to the Philippines from exile. It was widely seen as a victory of the people against two decades of presidential rule by President Marcos, and made news headlines as \"the revolution that surprised the world\".<ref name=\"Gandhi\">{{Citation |last=Kumar |first=Ravindra |publication-date=|title=Mahatma Gandhi at the Close of Twentieth Century|location= |publisher=Anmol Publications PVT. LTD. |isbn=978-81-261-1736-9 |page=168 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=lTNpstqGlAMC&pg=PA168&dq=EDSA+Revolution |accessdate= December 2, 2007 |year=2004}}.</ref>\n\nThe majority of the demonstrations took place on a long stretch of [[EDSA (road)|Epifanio de los Santos Avenue]], more commonly known by its acronym ''EDSA'', in [[Metro Manila]] from February 22\u201325, 1986. They involved over two million Filipino civilians, as well as several political and military groups, and religious groups led by [[Cardinal (Catholicism)|Cardinal]] [[Jaime Sin]], the [[Archbishop of Manila]], along with [[Catholic Bishops' Conference of the Philippines]] President Cardinal [[Ricardo Vidal]], the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Cebu|Archbishop of Cebu]]. The protests, fueled by the resistance and opposition from years of governance by President Marcos and his cronies, culminated with the absolute ruler and his family fleeing [[Malaca\u00f1ang Palace]] to exile in [[Hawaii]]. Ninoy Aquino's widow, [[Corazon Aquino]], was immediately installed as the [[List of Presidents of the Philippines|eleventh]] President as a result of the revolution.<ref>\n{{cite web| url = http://www.stuartxchange.com/EdsaIntro.html| title = Edsa people Power 1 Philippines| accessdate = December 3, 2007| publisher = Angela Stuart-Santiago| url-status = live| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071213180847/http://www.stuartxchange.com/EdsaIntro.html| archivedate = December 13, 2007| df = mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Background and history==\n{{Main|Ferdinand Marcos}}\n[[Image:Ferdinand Marcos.JPEG|thumb|President [[Ferdinand Marcos]] served for 20 years, the longest tenure in Philippine history.]]\nPresident Ferdinand E. Marcos was [[1965 Philippine presidential election|elected president in 1965]], defeating incumbent [[Diosdado Macapagal|President Diosdado Macapagal]] by a margin of 52 to 43 percent. During this time, Marcos was very active in the initiation of public works projects and the intensification of tax collections. Marcos and his government claimed that they \"built more roads than all his predecessors combined and more schools than any previous administration\".<ref>{{Harvnb|Lacsamana|1990|p=187}}</ref> Amidst charges from the opposition party of vote-buying and a fraudulent election, President Marcos was reelected in the [[1969 Philippine presidential election]], this time defeating [[Sergio Osme\u00f1a Jr.|Sergio Osme\u00f1a, Jr.]] by 61 to 39 percent.\n\nPresident Marcos' second term for the presidency was marred by allegations by the opposition [[Liberal Party (Philippines)|Liberal Party]] of widespread graft and corruption. According to [[leftists]] who rioted during the [[First Quarter Storm]], the increasing disparity of wealth between the very wealthy and the very poor that made up the majority of the Philippines' population led to a rise in crime and civil unrest around the country. These factors, including the formation of the [[New People's Army]] and a bloody Muslim separatist movement in the southern island of Mindanao led by the [[Moro National Liberation Front]], contributed to the rapid rise of civil discontent and unrest in the country.{{citation needed|date = February 2014}}\n\n=== Proclamation of Martial Law ===\n{{Main|Martial law under Ferdinand Marcos}}\nBarred from running for a third term as president in 1973, Marcos announced [[Proclamation No. 1081]] on September 23, 1972, declaring [[Martial law under Ferdinand Marcos|martial law]] with rising civil disobedience as a justification. Through this decree and after obtaining voters consent through the plebiscite, President Marcos seized emergency powers giving him full control of the Philippines' military and the authority to suppress and abolish the [[freedom of speech]], the [[freedom of the press]], and many other [[civil liberties]]. President Marcos also dissolved the [[Philippine Congress]] and shut down media establishments critical of the Marcos Administration.<ref name=\"Celoza\"/>\n\nPresident Marcos also ordered the immediate arrest of his political opponents and critics. Among those arrested were Senate President [[Jovito Salonga]], Senator [[Jose Diokno]], and Senator [[Benigno Aquino Jr.]], whom Marcos linked with the [[Communists]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Ninoy linked up with the Left to aid presidential ambition|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/198820/news/specialreports/ninoy-networked-with-everyone-reds-included|newspaper=GMA News|date=August 18, 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150207014355/http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/198820/news/specialreports/ninoy-networked-with-everyone-reds-included|archivedate=February 7, 2015}}</ref> and the man who was groomed by the opposition to succeed President Marcos after the 1973 elections.<ref name=\"Celoza\"/> On November 25, 1977, the Military Commission charged Aquino along with his two co-accused, [[New People's Army|NPA]] leaders [[Bernabe Buscayno]] (Commander Dante) and Lt. Victor Corpuz, guilty of all charges and sentenced them to death by firing squad.<ref>{{cite news|title=Max Soliven recalls Ninoy Aquino: Unbroken|url=http://asianjournalusa.com/max-soliven-recalls-ninoy-aquino-unbroken-p5828-87.htm|accessdate=August 30, 2013|newspaper=Philippines Star|date=October 10, 2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131016015855/http://asianjournalusa.com/max-soliven-recalls-ninoy-aquino-unbroken-p5828-87.htm|archivedate=October 16, 2013}}</ref>\n\nA [[Constitutional convention (political meeting)|constitutional convention]], which had been called for in 1970 to replace the Commonwealth era [[1935 Constitution of the Philippines|1935 Constitution]], continued the work of framing a new constitution after the declaration of martial law. The new constitution went into effect in early 1973, changing the form of government from presidential to [[parliamentary system|parliamentary]] and allowing President Marcos to stay in power beyond 1973. The constitution was approved by 95% of the voters in the [[1973 Philippine constitutional plebiscite|Philippine constitutional plebiscite]].\n\nIn 1978, while still in prison, Aquino founded his [[political party]], ''[[Lakas ng Bayan]]'' (abbreviated \"LABAN\"; English: ''People's Power'') to run for office in the [[Interim Batasang Pambansa]] (Parliament). All LABAN candidates lost, including Ninoy himself.\n\nWith practically all of his political opponents were arrested and in exile, President Marcos' pre-emptive declaration of martial law in 1972 and the [[1973 Philippine constitutional plebiscite|ratification]] of his new constitution by more than 95% of voters enabled Marcos to effectively legitimize his government and hold on to power for another 14 years beyond his first two terms as president. In a [[Cold War]] context, Marcos retained the support of the United States through Marcos' promise to stamp out communism in the Philippines and by assuring the United States of its continued use of military and naval bases in the Philippines.<ref name=\"Celoza\">{{Citation|title=Ferdinand Marcos and the Philippines: the political economy of authoritarianism |first=Albert |last=Celoza |publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group |year=1997}}</ref>\n\n===Assassination of Ninoy Aquino===\n{{main|Assassination of Benigno Aquino, Jr.}}\nDespite warnings from the military and other First Lady Imelda R. Marcos, Ninoy Aquino was determined to return to the Philippines. Asked what he thought of the death threats, Ninoy Aquino responded, \"The Filipino is worth dying for.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Aquino, Corazon Cojuangco \u2022 The Ramon Magsaysay Award Foundation \u2022 Honoring greatness of spirit and transformative leadership in Asia|url=http://rmaward.asia/awardees/aquino-corazon-cojuangco/|website=rmaward.asia|url-status=dead |\narchiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170804175243/http://rmaward.asia/awardees/aquino-corazon-cojuangco/|archivedate=August 4, 2017|accessdate=January 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAt that time, Ninoy's passport had expired and the renewal had been denied. Ninoy, therefore, acquired a plan to acquire a fake passport with the help of [[Rashid Lucman]],<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Philippine Star|title=A look back at Ninoy Aquino's murder|date=August 20, 2014|url=http://www.philstar.com/news-feature/2014/08/20/1359731/look-back-ninoy-aquinos-murder|accessdate=March 30, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160828054443/http://www.philstar.com/news-feature/2014/08/20/1359731/look-back-ninoy-aquinos-murder|archivedate=August 28, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Philippine Star\">{{cite journal|journal=Philippine Star|title=Will Noynoy Aquino be the hero of Muslims in Mindanao?|url=http://www.philstar.com/letters-editor/604043/will-noynoy-aquino-be-hero-muslims-mindanao|date=August 20, 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161010224659/http://www.philstar.com/letters-editor/604043/will-noynoy-aquino-be-hero-muslims-mindanao|archivedate=October 10, 2016}}</ref> The passport carried the alias ''Marcial Bonifacio'' (Marcial for martial law and Bonifacio for Fort Bonifacio, his erstwhile prison).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.inq7.net/nat/2003/aug/21/nat_4-1.htm |title=Services \u2013 INQUIRER.net |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060516180338/http://www.inq7.net/nat/2003/aug/21/nat_4-1.htm |archivedate=May 16, 2006 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\nOn August 21, 1983, after a three-year exile in the [[United States]], Aquino was [[assassination|assassinated]] by [[Rolando Galman]] as he disembarked from a [[Taiwan]]ese commercial flight at the [[Ninoy Aquino International Airport|Manila International Airport]] (which was later renamed in Aquino's honor).<ref>{{Citation |editor-last1=Javate-De Dios |editor-first1=Aurora |editor-first2=Petronilo |editor-last2=Bn Daroy |editor-first3=Lorna |editor-last3=Kalaw-Tirol |title=Dictatorship and Revolution: Roots of People's Power |publisher=Conspectus Foundation Incorporated |date=1988 |oclc=19609244 |page=132 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=Nz1yAAAAMAAJ&dq=Dictatorship+and+Revolution%3A+Roots+of+People%27s+Power |asin=B0000EEE8J |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151017232007/https://books.google.com/books?ei=_6RFU_T8JYrIyAHwhIDgBA&id=Nz1yAAAAMAAJ&dq=Dictatorship+and+Revolution%3A+Roots+of+People%27s+Power |archivedate=October 17, 2015  }}.</ref> His assassination shocked and outraged many Filipinos, most of whom had lost confidence in the Marcos administration. The event led to more suspicions about the government, triggering non-cooperation among Filipinos that eventually led to outright [[civil disobedience]].<ref>{{Citation |last=Schock |first=Kurt |authorlink= |editor= |title=Unarmed Insurrections: People Power Movements in Nondemocracies |origyear= |chapter-url= |chapter-format= |accessdate= |edition= |series= |year=2005 |publisher= University of Minnesota Press|location= |language= |isbn=978-0-8166-4192-5 |oclc= |doi= |id= |pages=56 |chapter=People Power Unleashed: South Africa and the Philippines |chapterurl= |quote= }}</ref> It also shook the Marcos Administration, which was by then deteriorating due in part to Marcos' worsening health and ultimately fatal illness ([[lupus erythematosus]]).{{citation needed|date = February 2014}}\n\nThe assassination of Ninoy Aquino caused the Philippines economy to deteriorate even further, and the government plunged further into debt. By the end of 1983, the Philippines was in an economic recession, with the economy contracting by 6.8%.<ref>\n{{cite web| url = https://www.ualberta.ca/~vmitchel/fw9.html| title = Lakas Ng Bayan: The People's Power/EDSA Revolution 1986| accessdate = December 10, 2007| publisher = [[University of Alberta]], [[Canada]]| url-status = live| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070808142736/http://www.ualberta.ca/~vmitchel/fw9.html| archivedate = August 8, 2007| df = mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 1984, Marcos appointed a commission, led by Chief Justice [[Enrique Fernando]], to launch an investigation into Aquino's assassination. Despite the commission's conclusions, Cardinal [[Jaime Sin]], the Archbishop of Manila, declined an offer to join the commission and rejected the government's views on the assassination.\n\n===Calls for election===\n{{main|1986 Philippine presidential election}}\nOn November 3, 1985, after pressure from the US government,<ref>\n{{cite news| url = http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1079/is_v86/ai_4188363| title = Election developments in the Philippines \u2013 President Reagan's statement \u2013 transcript| accessdate = December 3, 2007| publisher = US Department of State Bulletin, April 1986| year=1986}}</ref> Marcos suddenly announced that a snap presidential election would take place the following year, one year ahead of the regular presidential election schedule, to legitimize his control over the country.<ref name=\"NSM\">{{Citation |last=Zunes |first=Stephen |publication-date=1999|title=Nonviolent Social Movements: A Geographical Perspective |location= |publisher=Blackwell Publishing |isbn=978-1-57718-076-0 |page=129 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=rlIH-NQbFQgC&pg=PA129&dq=Philippine+People+power+revolution |accessdate= December 3, 2007 |year=1999 |display-authors=1 |author2=<Please add first missing authors to populate metadata.>}}</ref>  The snap election was legalized with the passage of Batas Pambansa Blg. 883 (National Law No. 883) by the Marcos-controlled unicameral congress called the [[Regular Batasang Pambansa]].<ref name=\"Steinberg 2000 144\">{{Citation |first=David Joel |last=Steinberg |publisher=Basic Books |year=2000 |page=144 |title=The Philippines: Colonialism, collaboration, and resistance}}</ref>\n\nThe growing opposition movement encouraged Ninoy Aquino's widow, Corazon Aquino, to run for the presidency. United Opposition (UNIDO) leader, [[Salvador Laurel]], who earlier filed his candidacy as an official UNIDO candidate for the presidency, gave way to Cory after a political deal which was later reneged by Cory after the election. [[Salvador Laurel]] eventually ran as Cory Aquino's running mate for vice-president under the United Opposition (UNIDO) party. Marcos ran for re-election, with [[Arturo Tolentino]] as his running mate under the Kilusang Bagong Lipunan (KBL) party.<ref name=\"Steinberg 2000 144\"/>\n\n===1986 election===\n{{main|1986 Philippine presidential election}}\nThe election was held on February 7, 1986.<ref name=\"NSM\"/> The official election canvasser, the [[Commission on Elections]] (COMELEC), declared that Marcos was the winner. The final tally of the COMELEC had Marcos winning with 10,807,197 votes against Aquino's 9,291,761 votes. On the other hand, based on returns of 70% of the precincts<ref>{{Cite book | url=https://books.google.com/?id=-1TMCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA384&lpg=PA384&dq=namfrel+7,835,070+aquino#v=onepage&q=namfrel%207%2C835%2C070%20aquino&f=false | title=A Force More Powerful: A Century of Non-Violent Conflict| isbn=9780312240509| last1=Ackerman| first1=Peter| last2=Duvall| first2=Jack| date=October 5, 2001}}</ref> of the [[National Movement for Free Elections]] (NAMFREL), an accredited poll watcher, had Aquino winning with 7,835,070 votes against Marcos' 7,053,068 votes.<ref>{{Citation|title=A Force More Powerful: A Century of Nonviolent Conflict|author1=Peter Ackerman|author2=Jack DuVall|publisher=Macmillan|year=2001|isbn=978-0-312-24050-9|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=OVtKS9DCN0kC&pg=PA384 384]|url=https://books.google.com/?id=OVtKS9DCN0kC|authorlink1=Peter Ackerman|authorlink2=Jack DuVall}};<br />^ {{Citation|author=Isabelo T. Crisostomo|title=Cory\u2014profile of a president|publisher=Branden Books|year=1987|isbn=978-0-8283-1913-3|page=[https://archive.org/details/coryprofileofpre00cris/page/193 193]|url=https://books.google.com/?id=iW_ddLowBYkC}} (showing a reproduction of NAMFREL's announcement of the results).</ref>\n\nThis electoral exercise was marred by widespread reports of violence and tampering of election results, culminating in the walkout of 30 COMELEC computer technicians to protest the deliberate manipulation of the official election results to favor Ferdinand Marcos.  The walkout was considered as one of the early \"sparks\" of the People Power Revolution. The walkout also served as an affirmation to allegations of vote-buying, fraud, and tampering of election results by the KBL.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.pcij.org/i-report/edsa20/william-torres.html| title = iReport EDSA 20th Anniversary Special Issue &#124; Dr. William Castro| accessdate = January 16, 2008| publisher = Philippine Center for Investigative Journalism, February 2006| url-status = live| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080120161749/http://pcij.org/i-report/edsa20/william-torres.html| archivedate = January 20, 2008| df = mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.rappler.com/nation/politics/elections-2013/22582-1986-comelec-walkout-not-about-cory-or-marcos | title = 1986 Comelec walkout not about Cory or Marcos | accessdate = January 12, 2016 | publisher = Rappler | first = Reynaldo | last = Santos, Jr. | date = February 26, 2013 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160228042402/http://www.rappler.com/nation/politics/elections-2013/22582-1986-comelec-walkout-not-about-cory-or-marcos | archivedate = February 28, 2016 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nBecause of reports of alleged fraud, the [[Catholic Bishops' Conference of the Philippines]] (CBCP) through Cardinal [[Ricardo Vidal]] issued a statement condemning the elections. The United States Senate also passed a resolution stating the same condemnation.<ref name=\"NSM\"/> [[US president]] [[Ronald Reagan]] issued a statement calling the fraud reports as \"disturbing\" but he said that there was fraud \"on both sides\" of the Philippine election.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1986/02/26/in-crucial-call-laxalt-told-marcos-cut-cleanly/9329b85d-f7b0-4021-884d-5e5e659a4cb0/|title=In Crucial Call, Laxalt Told Marcos: 'Cut Cleanly'|last1=Hoffman|first1=David|last2=Cannon|first2=Lou|last3=Coleman|first3=Milton|last4=Dewar|first4=Helen|last5=Goshko|first5=John M.|last6=Oberdorfer|first6=Don|last7=W|first7=George C.|work=The Washington Post|date=February 26, 1986|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822084009/https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1986/02/26/in-crucial-call-laxalt-told-marcos-cut-cleanly/9329b85d-f7b0-4021-884d-5e5e659a4cb0/|archivedate=August 22, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url = http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1079/is_v86/ai_4188363| title = PRESIDENT'S STATEMENT, FEB. 11, 1986| accessdate = December 3, 2007| publisher = US Department of State Bulletin, April 1986| year=1986}}</ref> In response to the protests, COMELEC claimed that Marcos with 53 percent won over Aquino. However, NAMFREL countered that the latter won over Marcos with 52 percent of votes.<ref>{{Citation |last=Schock |first=Kurt |publication-date=|title=Unarmed Insurrections: People Power Movements in Nondemocracies |location= |publisher= U of Minnesota Press|isbn= 978-0-8166-4193-2|page=77 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=RRVk5qJpOH8C&pg=PA77&dq=Cory+Aquino+1986+inauguration |accessdate= December 3, 2007 |year=2005}}.</ref>\n\nOn February 15, Marcos was proclaimed by COMELEC and Batasang Pambansa as the winner amidst the controversy. All 50 opposition members of the Parliament walked out in protest.  The Filipino people repudiated the results, asserting that Aquino was the real victor. Both \"winners\" took their oath of office in two different places, with Aquino gaining greater mass support. Aquino also called for coordinated strikes and mass boycott of the media and businesses owned by Marcos' cronies. As a result, the crony banks, corporations, and media were hit hard, and their shares in the stock market plummeted to record levels.{{citation needed|date = February 2014}}\n\n===Vidal's declaration===\nCardinal Vidal, after the result of the snap election, issued a declaration in lieu of the Philippine Church hierarchy stating that when \"a government does not of itself freely correct the evil it has inflicted on the people then it is our serious moral obligation as a people to make it do so.\" The declaration also asked \"every loyal member of the Church, every community of the faithful, to form their judgment about the February 7 polls\" and told all the Filipinos, \"Now is the time to speak up.  Now is the time to repair the wrong.  The wrong was systematically organized.  So must its correction be.  But as in the election itself, that depends fully on the people; on what they are willing and ready to do.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbcponline.net/documents/1980s/1986-post_election.html|title=POST-ELECTION STATEMENT|accessdate=March 15, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923201056/http://www.cbcponline.net/documents/1980s/1986-post_election.html|archivedate=September 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Events==\n{{Revolution sidebar}}\n\n===Aborted military coup===\nAppalled by the bold and apparent election irregularities, the [[Reform the Armed Forces Movement]] set into motion a coup attempt against Marcos. The initial plan was for a team to assault Malaca\u00f1an Palace and arrest Ferdinand Marcos. Other military units would take over key strategic facilities, such as the [[Ninoy Aquino International Airport|airport]], military bases,  the GHQAFP in [[Camp Aguinaldo]], and major highway junctions to restrict counteroffensive by Marcos-loyal troops.\n\nHowever, after Marcos learned about the plot, he ordered their leaders' arrest,<ref>{{Citation |last=West |first=Lois A. |publication-date=1997\n|title=Militant Labor in the Philippines |location= |publisher=Temple University Press |isbn=978-1-56639-491-8 |pages=19\u201320 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=KcaOhzm8gAQC&pg=PA20&dq=Philippine+People+power+revolution |accessdate= December 3, 2007 |year=1997}}.</ref> and presented to the international and local press some of the captured plotters, Maj. Saulito Aromin and Maj. Edgardo Doromal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stuartxchange.org/DayOne.html|title=Day One (EDSA: The Original People Power Revolution by Angela Stuart-Santiago)|accessdate=March 15, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150807094913/http://www.stuartxchange.org/DayOne.html|archivedate=August 7, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThreatened with their impending imprisonment, Defense Minister Juan Ponce Enrile and his fellow coup plotters decided to ask for help from then-AFP Vice Chief of Staff Lt. Gen [[Fidel Ramos]], who was also the chief of the [[Philippine Constabulary]] (now the Philippine National Police). Ramos agreed to resign from his position and support the plotters. Enrile also contacted the highly influential Cardinal Archbishop of Manila [[Jaime Sin]] for his support.\n\nAt about 6:30&nbsp;p.m. on February 22, Enrile and Ramos held a press conference at the Ministry of National Defense building in Camp Aguinaldo, where they announced that they had resigned from their positions in Marcos' cabinet and were withdrawing support from his government. Marcos himself later conducted a news conference calling on Enrile and Ramos to surrender, urging them to \"stop this stupidity\".<ref name=\"peoplepower_eyewitness\">{{Citation |last=Paul Sagmayao |first=Mercado |authorlink= |first2=Francisco S.|last2=Tatad |title=People Power: The Philippine Revolution of 1986: An Eyewitness History |publisher=The James B. Reuter, S.J., Foundation |year=1986 |location=[[Manila]], [[Philippines]] |pages= |url= |oclc=16874890}}</ref>\n\n===Sin's appeal===\nAfter Cardinal Vidal's condemnation of the snap election's fraudulent result, a message was aired over [[Radio Veritas]] at around 9 p.m., Cardinal Sin exhorted Filipinos in the capital to aid rebel leaders by going to the section of EDSA between [[Camp Crame]] and [[Camp Aguinaldo|Aguinaldo]] and giving emotional support, food and other supplies. For many, this seemed an unwise decision since civilians would not stand a chance against a dispersal by government troops. Many people, especially priests and nuns, still trooped to EDSA.<ref name=\"peoplepower_eyewitness\" />\n\nRadio Veritas played a critical role during the mass uprising. Former [[University of the Philippines]] president Francisco Nemenzo stated that: \"''Without Radio Veritas, it would have been difficult, if not impossible, to mobilize millions of people in a matter of hours.''\" Similarly, a certain account in the event said that: \"''Radio Veritas, in fact, was our umbilical cord to whatever else was going on''.\"<ref name=\"McCargo\">{{Citation |last=McCargo |first=Duncan |publication-date=2003|title=Media and Politics in Pacific Asia |location= |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-0-415-23375-0 |page=20|url=https://books.google.com/?id=CuGJ575iLLAC&pg=PA20&dq=Radio+Veritas+1986+Philippine+revolution |accessdate= December 3, 2007 |year=2003}}</ref>\n\n===Rising mass support===\nAt dawn, Sunday, government troops arrived to knock down the main transmitter of Radio Veritas, cutting off broadcasts to people in the provinces. The station switched to a standby transmitter with a limited range of broadcast.<ref name=\"McCargo\"/> The station was targeted because it had proven to be a valuable communications tool for the people supporting the rebels, keeping them informed of government troop movements and relaying requests for food, medicine, and supplies.<ref name=\"peoplepower_eyewitness\" />\n\nStill, people came to EDSA until it swelled to hundreds of thousands of unarmed civilians. The mood in the street was very festive, with many bringing whole families. Performers entertained the crowds, nuns and priests led prayer vigils, and people set up barricades and makeshift sandbags, trees, and vehicles in several places along EDSA and intersecting streets such as Santolan and Ortigas Avenue. Everywhere, people listened to Radio Veritas on their radios. Several groups sang ''[[Bayan Ko]]'' (My Homeland),<ref>{{Citation |last=Taylor |first=Robert H. |publication-date=2002\n|title=The Idea of Freedom in Asia and Africa |location= |publisher= Stanford University Press |isbn=978-0-8047-4514-7 |page=210 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=RfbSlkGP8TEC&pg=PA210&dq=Bayan+Ko+in+1986+Philippine+revolution |accessdate= December 3, 2007 |year=2002}}.</ref> which, since 1980, had become a patriotic anthem of the opposition. People frequently flashed the 'LABAN' sign,<ref>{{Citation |last=Crisostomo |first=Isabelo T. |publication-date=1987|title=Cory, Profile of a President: The Historic Rise to Power of Corazon |location=|publisher=Branden Books |isbn=978-0-8283-1913-3 |page=217 |url=https://books.google.com/id=iW_ddLowBYkC&pg=PA217&dq=LABAN+signs+during+EDSA+I |accessdate= December 3, 2007 |year=1987}}.</ref> which is an \"L\" formed with their thumb and index finger. 'laban' is the Filipino word for 'fight', but also the abbreviation of [[Lakas ng Bayan]], Ninoy Aquino's party.\n\nAfter lunch on February 23, Enrile and Ramos decided to consolidate their positions. Enrile crossed EDSA from [[Camp Aguinaldo]] to [[Camp Crame]] amidst cheers from the crowd.<ref name=\"peoplepower_eyewitness\" />\n\nIn the mid-afternoon, [[Radio Veritas]] relayed reports of [[Philippine Marine Corps|Marines]] massing near the camps in the east and [[LVT-5]] tanks approaching from the north and south. A contingent of Marines with tanks and armored vans, led by Brigadier General Artemio Tadiar, was stopped along Ortigas Avenue, about two kilometers from the camps, by tens of thousands of people.<ref>{{Citation |last=Lizano |first=Lolita |publication-date=1988|title=Flower in a Gun Barrel: The Untold Story of the Edsa Revolution |location= |publisher= L.R. Lizano|isbn= |page=|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Bm0yAAAAIAAJ&dq=EDSA+Revolution&q=EDSA+Revolution |accessdate= December 2, 2007 |year=1988}}.</ref> Nuns holding rosaries knelt in front of the tanks and men and women linked arms together to block the troops.<ref>{{Citation |last=Merkl |first=Peter H. |publication-date=2005|title=The Rift Between America And Old Europe: the distracted eagle |location= |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-0-415-35985-6 |page=144 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=WavpuvE2HA4C&pg=PA144&dq=EDSA+Revolution |accessdate= December 2, 2007 |year=2005}}.</ref> Tadiar asked the crowds to make a clearing for them, but they did not budge. In the end, the troops retreated with no shots fired.<ref name=\"peoplepower_eyewitness\" />\n\nBy evening, the standby transmitter of Radio Veritas failed. Shortly after midnight, the staff was able to go to another station to begin broadcasting from a secret location under the moniker [[DZRJ-AM|\"Radyo Bandido\"]] (Outlaw Radio, which is now known as [[DZRJ-AM]]). June Keithley, with her husband [[Angelo Castro, Jr.]], was the radio broadcaster who continued Radio Veritas' program throughout the night and in the remaining days.<ref name=\"peoplepower_eyewitness\"/>\n\n===More military defections===\nAt dawn on Monday, February 24, the first serious encounter with government troops occurred. Marines marching from Libis, in the east, lobbed tear gas at the demonstrators, who quickly dispersed. Some 3,000 Marines then entered and held the east side of Camp Aguinaldo.<ref name=\"peoplepower_eyewitness\" />\n\nLater, helicopters manned by the 15th Strike Wing of the [[Philippine Air Force]], led by Colonel Antonio Sotelo, were ordered from Sangley Point in Cavite (South of Manila) to head to Camp Crame.<ref name=\"Crisostomo\">{{Citation |last=Crisostomo |first=Isabelo T. |publication-date=1987\n|title=Cory, Profile of a President: The Historic Rise to Power of Corazon |location= |publisher= Branden Books|isbn= 978-0-8283-1913-3|page=226 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=iW_ddLowBYkC&pg=PA226&dq=Col.+Antonio+Sotelo+to+camp+crame |accessdate= December 3, 2007 |date=April 1, 1987}}.</ref> Secretly, the squadron had already defected and instead of attacking Camp Crame, landed in it, with the crowds cheering and hugging the pilots and crew members.<ref name=\"peoplepower_eyewitness\" />\n\nA [[Bell 214]] helicopter piloted by Major Deo Cruz of the 205th Helicopter Wing and [[Sikorsky S-76]] gunships piloted by Colonel Charles Hotchkiss of the 20th Air Commando Squadron joined the rebel squadron earlier in the air. The presence of the helicopters boosted the morale of Enrile and Ramos who had been continually encouraging their fellow soldiers to join the opposition movement.<ref name=\"peoplepower_eyewitness\" /> In the afternoon, Aquino arrived at the base where Enrile, Ramos, RAM officers and a throng were waiting.<ref name=\"Crisostomo\"/>\n\n===The capture of MBS-4===\nAt around that time, [[June Keithley]] received reports that Marcos had left Malaca\u00f1ang Palace and broadcast this to the people at EDSA. The crowd celebrated and even Ramos and Enrile came out from Crame to appear to the crowds. The jubilation was however short-lived as Marcos later appeared on television on the government-controlled [[People's Television Network|MBS-4]],<ref>{{Citation |last=Maramba |first=Asuncion David |publication-date=1987\n|title=On the Scene: The Philippine Press Coverage of the 1986 Revolution |location= |publisher=Solar publishing Corp. |isbn= 978-971-17-0628-9|page=27 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=2QAeAAAAMAAJ&dq=Channel+9+tower+in+1986+revolution&q=Channel+4 |accessdate= December 3, 2007 |year=1987}}.</ref> (using the foreclosed [[ABS-CBN (television network)|ABS-CBN]] facilities, transmitter, and compound in [[ABS-CBN Broadcasting Center|Broadcast Plaza]]) declaring that he would not step down. It was thereafter speculated that the false report was a calculated move against Marcos to encourage more defections.<ref name=\"peoplepower_eyewitness\" />\n\nDuring this broadcast, MBS-4 suddenly went off the air. A contingent of rebels, under Colonel Mariano Santiago, had captured the station.  MBS-4 was put back on the air shortly after noon, with [[Orly Punzalan]] announcing on live television, \"Channel 4 is on the air again to serve the people.\" By this time, the crowds at EDSA had swollen to over a million. (Some estimates placed them at two million.)<ref name=\"peoplepower_eyewitness\" />\n\nThis broadcast was considered the \"return\" of [[ABS-CBN (television network)|ABS-CBN]] on air because this was the time when former employees of the network were inside the complex after 14 years of closure since Marcos took it over during the Martial Law of 1972. [[DZRJ-AM|\"Radyo Bandido\"]] ended broadcasting that afternoon, while Radio Veritas resumed transmissions, this time from the [[ABS-CBN Broadcasting Center|Broadcast Plaza]]'s radio studios.\n\nIn the late afternoon, rebel helicopters attacked [[Villamor Airbase]], destroying presidential air assets. Another helicopter went to [[Malaca\u00f1an Palace|Malaca\u00f1ang]], fired a rocket, and caused minor damage. Later, most of the officers who had graduated from the [[Philippine Military Academy]] (PMA) defected. The majority of the Armed Forces had already changed sides.<ref name=\"peoplepower_eyewitness\" />\n\n===Marcos orders not to shoot===\n{{listen| filename=Marcos_-_ver.ogg|title=\"My order is not to attack\" | description=[[President of the Philippines|President]] [[Ferdinand Marcos]] and General [[Fabian Ver]] during a press conference in Malaca\u00f1an Palace. | format= [[Ogg]]}}\n\nPrior dialogues to stop the revolution had not succeeded with the Armed Forces of the Philippines, which was led by General Fabian Ver. AFP was ready to mount an airstrike on the day but Marcos ordered them to halt.\n\nThe actual dialogue on TV between Marcos and then AFP Chief of Staff General Fabian Ver went as follows:\n\n{{quote|Fabian Ver: The Ambush there is aiming to mount there in the top. Very quickly, you must immediately leave to conquer them, immediately, Mr. President.<br /> \nFerdinand Marcos: Just wait, come here.<br />\nVer: Please, Your Honor, so we can immediately strike them. We have to immobilize the helicopters that they've got. We have two fighter planes flying now to strike at any time, sir.<br />\nMarcos: My order is not to attack. No, no, no! Hold on. My order is not to attack.<br />\nVer: They are massing civilians near our troops and we cannot keep on withdrawing. You asked me to withdraw yesterday\u2013<br />\nMarcos (interrupting): Uh yes, but ah... My order is to disperse without shooting them.<br />\nVer: We cannot withdraw all the time...<br /> \nMarcos: No! No! No! Hold on! You disperse the crowd without shooting them.}}\n\n===Two inaugurations===\n[[File:Corazon Aquino inauguration.jpg|thumb|300px|Corazon Aquino was inaugurated as the 11th president of the Philippines on February 25, 1986 at Sampaguita Hall (Now Kalayaan Hall).]]\nOn the morning of Tuesday, February 25, at around 7 a.m., a minor clash occurred between loyal government troops and the reformists. Snipers stationed atop the crony-owned [[Radio Philippines Network|RPN-9]] transmitter in Panay Avenue, near MBS-4, began shooting at the reformists. Many rebel soldiers surged to the station,<ref name=\"peoplepower_eyewitness\" /> and a rebel S-76 helicopter later shot the snipers at the broadcast tower. The troops later left after a V-150 was blocked by the crowd assembled.\n\nLater in the morning, [[Corazon Aquino]] was inaugurated as President of the Philippines in a simple ceremony at [[Club Filipino]]<ref>{{Citation |last=Crisostomo |first=Isabelo T. |publication-date=|title=Cory, Profile of a President: The Historic Rise to Power of Corazon |location= |publisher= Branden Books|isbn= 978-0-8283-1913-3|page=257 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=iW_ddLowBYkC&pg=PA257&dq=Cory+Aquino+in+Club+Filipino |accessdate= December 3, 2007 |date=April 1, 1987}}.</ref> in Greenhills, about a kilometer from Camp Crame. She was sworn in as President by Senior Associate Justice [[Claudio Teehankee]], and Laurel as Vice-President by Justice Vicente Abad Santos. The Bible on which Aquino swore her oath was held by her mother-in-law Aurora Aquino, the mother of [[Benigno Aquino, Jr.|Ninoy Aquino]]. Attending the ceremonies were Ramos, who was then promoted to General, Enrile, and many politicians.<ref name=\"peoplepower_eyewitness\" />\n\nOutside Club Filipino, all the way to EDSA, hundreds of people cheered and celebrated. ''[[Bayan Ko]]'' (''My Country'', a popular folk song and the unofficial National Anthem of protest) was sung after Aquino's oath-taking. Many people wore yellow, the color of Aquino's presidential campaign.\n\nAn hour later, Marcos held the inauguration at [[Malaca\u00f1ang Palace]]. Loyalist civilians attended the ceremony, shouting \"''Marcos, Marcos, Marcos pa rin!'' (Marcos, Marcos, still Marcos!)\". On the Palace balcony, Marcos took the Oath of Office, aired on [[Intercontinental Broadcasting Corporation|IBC-13]] and [[Radio Philippines Network|RPN-9]] (RPN-9 was going off-the-air during the broadcast of the inauguration, as its transmitter was captured by reformist soldiers).<ref name=\"peoplepower_eyewitness\" /> None of the invited foreign dignitaries attended the ceremony, for security reasons. The couple finally emerged on the balcony of the Palace before 3,000 KBL loyalists who were shouting, \"Capture the snakes!\"<ref name=\"Ellison\">{{Citation |last=Ellison |first=Katherine |publication-date=2005|title=Imelda: Steel Butterfly of the Philippines |location= |publisher=iUniverse |isbn=978-0-595-34922-7 |page=244 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=Dfl53AtDM0oC&pg=RA1-PA244&dq=Dahil+Sa+sang+by+Imelda+Marcos |accessdate= December 3, 2007 |year=2005}}.</ref> Rather tearfully,<ref name=\"Ellison\"/> First Lady Imelda Marcos gave a farewell rendition of the couple's theme song \u2013 the 1938 ''[[kundiman]]'' ''\"[[Dahil Sa Iyo]]\"'' (Because of You) \u2013 chanting the song's entreaties in [[Tagalog language|Tagalog]]:\n\n<blockquote>\nBecause of you, I became happy<br />\nLoving I shall offer you<br />\nIf it is true I shall be enslaved by you<br />\nAll of this because of you.<ref name=\"Ellison\"/>\n</blockquote>\n\nThe broadcast of the event was interrupted as rebel troops successfully captured the other stations.<ref name=\"peoplepower_eyewitness\" />\n\nBy this time, hundreds of people had amassed at the barricades along [[Mendiola]], only a hundred meters away from Malaca\u00f1ang. They were prevented from storming the Palace by loyal government troops securing the area. The angry demonstrators were pacified by priests who warned them not to be violent.<ref name=\"peoplepower_eyewitness\" />\n\n===Marcos' departure===\nAt 3:00&nbsp;p.m. ([[Eastern Time Zone|EST]]) on Monday, President Marcos phoned [[United States Senate|United States Senator]] [[Paul Laxalt]],<ref name=\"Ellison\"/> asking for advice from the [[White House]]. Laxalt advised him to \"cut and cut clean\",<ref>{{Cite book|title = Reagan: the life|last = Brands|first = H W|publisher = Doubleday|year = 2015|isbn = 9780385536400|location = New York|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=wHd5BAAAQBAJ&lpg=PT617&vq=laxalt%20marcos%20cut%20and%20cut%20clean&dq=laxalt%20marcos%20cut%20and%20cut%20clean&pg=PT617#v=onepage&q=laxalt%20marcos%20cut%20and%20cut%20clean&f=false|url-status = live|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160105160957/https://books.google.com/books?id=wHd5BAAAQBAJ&lpg=PT617&vq=laxalt%20marcos%20cut%20and%20cut%20clean&dq=laxalt%20marcos%20cut%20and%20cut%20clean&pg=PT617#v=onepage&q=laxalt%20marcos%20cut%20and%20cut%20clean&f=false|archivedate = January 5, 2016|df = mdy-all}}</ref> to which Marcos expressed his disappointment after a short pause. In the afternoon, Marcos talked to Minister Enrile, asking for safe passage for him, his family, and close allies such as General Ver.\n\nAt midnight [[Philippine Standard Time|PHT]], the Marcos family boarded a [[United States Air Force]] HH-3E Rescue [[helicopter]]<ref name=\"Halperin\">{{Citation|last=Halperin|first=Jonathan J.|title=The Other Side: How Soviets and Americans Perceive Each Other|url=https://books.google.com/?id=H1so7Od--csC&pg=PA63&dq=Marcos+departure|page=63|publication-date=1987|year=1987|location=|publisher=Transaction Publishers|isbn=978-0-88738-687-9|accessdate=December 3, 2007}}.</ref> and flew to [[Clark Air Base]] in [[Angeles City]] 83 kilometers north of Manila.\n\nAt Clark Air Base, Marcos asked to spend a couple of days with his family in Ilocos Norte, his native province. Aquino vetoed the request. President Reagan privately derided Cory Aquino for denying Marcos a last look at his home province.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/03/19/magazine/reagan-and-the-philippines-setting-marcos-adrift.html?pagewanted=all |title=REAGAN AND THE PHILIPPINES: Setting Marcos Adrift |accessdate=February 11, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170111001104/http://www.nytimes.com/1989/03/19/magazine/reagan-and-the-philippines-setting-marcos-adrift.html?pagewanted=all |archivedate=January 11, 2017  |newspaper=The New York Times |date=March 19, 1989 |last1=Karnow |first1=Stanley }}</ref>\n\nThe deposed First Family and their servants then rode US Air Force [[DC9|DC-9 Medivac]] and [[C-141 Starlifter|C-141B]] planes to [[Andersen Air Force Base]] in the north of the United States territory of [[Guam]], then flying to Hickam Air Force Base in [[Hawaii]] where Marcos finally arrived on February 26. The United States Government documented that they entered the United States with millions of dollars in jewelry, gold, stocks, and cash.<ref name=\"Gandhi\"/><ref name=\"peoplepower_eyewitness\"/>\n\nWhen news of the Marcos family's departure reached civilians, many rejoiced and danced in the streets. Over at [[Mendiola]], the demonstrators stormed the Palace, which was closed to ordinary people for around a decade. Despite looting by some angry protesters, the majority wandered about inside through rooms where national history was shaped, looking at objects extravagant and mundane that the Marcos clan and its court had abandoned in their flight.{{Citation needed|date=February 2011}}\n\nIn other countries, people also rejoiced and congratulated Filipinos they knew. [[CBS]] anchorman [[Bob Simon]] reported: \"We Americans like to think we taught the Filipinos democracy. Well, tonight they are teaching the world.\" <ref name=\"peoplepower_eyewitness\"/>\n\nSome authors say that Marcos prevented civil war similar to the [[Syrian Civil War]] by refusing to use guns notwithstanding the insistence of his top general, and by agreeing to step down during the EDSA revolution.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.manilatimes.net/level-duterte-drop-scourge-syrian-civil-war/291350/ |title=Level up on Duterte or drop into the scourge of the Syrian civil war |accessdate=January 10, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170112181957/http://www.manilatimes.net/level-duterte-drop-scourge-syrian-civil-war/291350/ |archivedate=January 12, 2017  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://thestandard.com.ph/opinion/columns/hail-to-the-chair-by-victor-avecilla/226306/why-the-reds-hate-marcos-20170110.html |title=Why the Reds hate Marcos - Manila Standard |accessdate=February 24, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170112181419/http://thestandard.com.ph/opinion/columns/hail-to-the-chair-by-victor-avecilla/226306/why-the-reds-hate-marcos-20170110.html |archivedate=January 12, 2017  }}</ref> The White House said, \"By leaving the Philippines at a critical juncture in his nation's history, Mr. Marcos permitted the peaceful transition to popular, democratic rule.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/09/29/obituaries/ferdinand-marcos-ousted-leader-of-philippines-dies-at-72-in-exile.html |title=Ferdinand Marcos, Ousted Leader of Philippines, Dies at 72 in Exile |accessdate=February 11, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170112181330/http://www.nytimes.com/1989/09/29/obituaries/ferdinand-marcos-ousted-leader-of-philippines-dies-at-72-in-exile.html |archivedate=January 12, 2017  |newspaper=The New York Times |date=September 29, 1989 |last1=Gross |first1=Jane }}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\n{{main|Presidency of Corazon Aquino}}\n{{wikisource|Provisional Constitution of the Philippines (1986)|Proclamation \u2116 3: Provisional Constitution of the Philippines (1986)}}\n\nImmediately after her accession, Aquino issued Proclamation No. 3, a [[provisional constitution]] which established a [[Revolutionary government in the Philippines|revolutionary government]]. The edict promulgated the 1986 Freedom Constitution, which retained or superseded various provisions of the 1973 Constitution that were in force up to that point. This allowed Aquino to wield both executive and legislative powers; among her first acts was to unilaterally abolish the [[Batasang Pambansa]] (the unicameral legislature [[1984 Philippine parliamentary election|duly elected in 1984]]), pending a plebiscite for a more permanent Constitution and the establishment of a new Congress by 1987.<ref>{{cite book |author=Joaquin G. Bernas |title=The Intent of the 1986 Constitution Writers|publisher=Rex Book Store|location=Manila, Philippines|year=1995|pages=2\u20134 |author-link=Joaquin G. Bernas}}</ref>\n\nThe revolution had an effect on [[democratization]] movements in such countries as [[Taiwan]] and [[South Korea]]; other effects include the restoration of the freedom of the press, abolition of repressive laws enforced by the previous regime, the adoption of the [[1987 Constitution]], and the subordination of the military to civilian rule, despite several coup attempts during Aquino's rule.<ref name=\"aftermath\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-pacific-12567320 |title=People Power at 25: Long road to Philippine democracy |first=Kate |last=McGeown |work=BBC.co.uk |date=February 25, 2011 |accessdate=February 25, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110226073508/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-pacific-12567320 |archivedate=February 26, 2011  }}</ref>\n\nThe revolution provided for the restoration of democratic institutions after thirteen years of totalitarian rule and these institutions has been used by various groups to challenge the entrenched [[Political family|political families]] and to strengthen Philippine democracy.<ref>{{Citation |last=Putzel |first=James |date=Spring 1999 |title=Survival of an imperfect democracy in the Philippines |journal=Democratization |volume=6 |issue=1 |pages=198\u2013223 |doi=10.1080/13510349908403603 |postscript=.  }}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:VisitorViewingBantayogEDSATimeline.jpg|thumb|A visitor to the [[Bantayog ng mga Bayani]] Museum browses through a timeline of the EDSA Revolution, one of the last sequences in the Museum's coverage of protest movements against the Marcos dictatorship.]]The People Power Revolution has inspired a call for a change of government through peaceful protests rather than bloodshed.  Many similar revolutions have followed since then, taking the Philippine example of nonviolent regime change, such as that in [[Fall of the Berlin Wall|East Germany]] and many other former Soviet Bloc countries.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sbs.com.au/news/article/2014/02/24/comment-remembering-philippines-people-power-revolution |title=Archived copy |accessdate=May 16, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161221214001/http://www.sbs.com.au/news/article/2014/02/24/comment-remembering-philippines-people-power-revolution |archivedate=December 21, 2016  }}</ref> It also helped inspire the [[Arab Spring]] in 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.lse.ac.uk/ideas/2011/03/exporting-%e2%80%9cpeople-power%e2%80%9d-the-philippine-revolution-25-years-later/|title=Exporting \"People Power\"? The Philippine Revolution 25 Years Later|date=March 15, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe EDSA Revolution Anniversary is a special [[public holiday in the Philippines]].  Since 2002, the holiday has been a special non-working holiday.<ref name=\"pn295\">[http://www.gov.ph/2011/11/24/proclamation-no-295-s-2011/ Proclamation No. 295: Declaring 2012 National Holidays] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130117171806/http://www.gov.ph/2011/11/24/proclamation-no-295-s-2011/ |date=January 17, 2013 }}, December 12, 2011, Official Gazette of the Philippines</ref><ref name=\"p1841\">{{cite web |url=http://www.laborlaw.usc-law.org/download/pdf/2010_Holidays.pdf |title=Proclamation No. 1841 |date=July 21, 2009 |website=Philippine Labor Laws |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171010145524/http://www.laborlaw.usc-law.org/download/pdf/2010_Holidays.pdf |archivedate=October 10, 2017  }}</ref>\n[[File:People Power Revolution commemorative 10-peso coin obverse and reverse.png|right|thumbnail|10-peso coin commemorating the People Power Revolution]]\n\nRampant corruption during the term of President [[Joseph Estrada]] led to the similar [[2001 EDSA Revolution]] leading to his resignation from the presidency.\n\nIn 2003, the ''Radio Broadcast of the Philippine People Power Revolution'' was inscribed in the [[UNESCO]] [[Memory of the World Register]], the official documentary heritage list of the [[United Nations]]' educational and scientific body.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.unesco.org/new/en/communication-and-information/flagship-project-activities/memory-of-the-world/register/full-list-of-registered-heritage/registered-heritage-page-7/radio-broadcast-of-the-philippine-people-power-revolution/#c188230|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150824190648/http://www.unesco.org/new/en/communication-and-information/flagship-project-activities/memory-of-the-world/register/full-list-of-registered-heritage/registered-heritage-page-7/radio-broadcast-of-the-philippine-people-power-revolution/|url-status=dead|title=Radio Broadcast of the Philippine People Power Revolution &#124; United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization|archivedate=August 24, 2015|website=www.unesco.org}}</ref>\n\nOn September 12, 2007, [[Trial of Joseph Estrada|Estrada was found guilty of plunder]] beyond reasonable doubt by the [[Sandiganbayan|Philippine anti-graft court]] and sentenced to life imprisonment.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=http://globalnation.inquirer.net/84269/estradas-plunder-conviction-remembered|title=Estrada's plunder conviction remembered|last=Rodis|first=Rodel|date=August 28, 2013|work=Inquirer|access-date=April 27, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/60117/erap-guilty-of-plunder-sentenced-to-reclusion-perpetua/story/|title=Erap guilty of plunder, sentenced to reclusion perpetua|last=|first=|date=September 12, 2007|work=GMA News Online|access-date=April 27, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\"Sturcke\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2007/sep/12/philippines|title=Estrada given life sentence for corruption|last=Sturcke|first=James|date=September 12, 2007|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=April 27, 2018}}</ref> He was pardoned by President Gloria Macapagal-Arroyo on October 25, 2007.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-philippines-estrada-idUKMNB0007120071025|title=Former Philippine president Estrada pardoned|last=Mogato|first=Manny|date=October 25, 2007|work=Reuters|access-date=April 27, 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==Timeline==\n{{main|Timeline of the People Power Revolution}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[EDSA (road)|Epifanio de los Santos Avenue]], for more information about the road\n*\"[[Handog ng Pilipino sa Mundo]]\"\n*\"[[Magkaisa]]\"\n*\"[[Bayan Ko]]\"\n*[[EDSA Shrine]]\n*[[People Power Monument]]\n\n'''General:'''\n* [[Timeline of the Marcos Dictatorship]]\n\n'''Similar events:'''\n*[[EDSA II]]\n*[[EDSA III]]\n* [[Gda\u0144sk Agreement]] of 1980 and [[Polish Round Table Agreement|Round Table Agreement]] of 1989, both induced by peaceful protests in Poland by [[Solidarity (Polish trade union)|Solidarity]]\n*[[Tiananmen Square protests of 1989]] \n*[[Romanian Revolution]]\n*[[Velvet Revolution]], in Czechoslovakia\n*[[8888 Uprising]], in Burma (now Myanmar)\n*[[May 1998 riots of Indonesia]]\n*[[Iranian Revolution]]\n*[[Tunisian Revolution]]\n*[[Egyptian Revolution of 2011]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n{{Commons category}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*Baron, Cynthia S. and Suazo, Melba M. ''Nine Letters: The Story of the 1986 Filipino Revolution.'' Quezon City, Philippines. Gerardo P. Baron Books. 1986.\n*Johnson, Brian. ''The Four Days of Courage: The Untold Story of the People Who Brought Marcos Down.'' Toronto, Canada. McClelland and Stewart, 1987.\n* {{Cite book|last= Lacsamana |first= Leodivico Cruz |title=Philippine History and Government |edition= Second |year=1990 |isbn= 971-06-1894-6 |publisher=Phoenix Publishing House, Inc.|ref=harv}}\n*Mendoza, Amado, '\"People Power\" in the Philippines, 1983\u201386', in [[Adam Roberts (scholar)|Adam Roberts]] and [[Timothy Garton Ash]] (eds.), [http://web.archive.bibalex.org/web/20111208132001/http://ukcatalogue.oup.com/product/9780199552016.do ''Civil Resistance and Power Politics: The Experience of Non-violent Action from Gandhi to the Present''], Oxford: Oxford University Press, 2009. {{ISBN|978-0-19-955201-6}}.  [https://web.archive.org/web/20110629175120/http://www.oup.com/us/catalog/general/subject/Politics/ComparativePolitics/?view=usa&ci=9780199552016 ''US edition'']. [https://books.google.com/books?id=BxOQKrCe7UUC&dq=Civil+resistance+and+power+politics&source=gbs_navlinks_s ''On Google''].\n*Mercado, Paul Sagmayao, and Tatad, Francisco S. ''People Power: The Philippine Revolution of 1986: An eyewitness history.'' Manila, Philippines. The James B. Reuter, S.J., Foundation. 1986.\n*Schock, Kurt. ''Unarmed Insurrections: People Power Movements in Nondemocracies.'' Minneapolis, USA. University of Minnesota Press. 2005.\n{{Martial EDSA  |state=expanded}}\n{{Fall of Communism}}\n{{Cold War}}\n{{Corazon Aquino}}\n{{PhilippinePresElections}}\n{{Philippines topics}}\n{{Philippine national holidays}}\n\n[[Category:People Power Revolution| ]]\n[[Category:1986 in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:1980s coups d'\u00e9tat and coup attempts]]\n[[Category:20th-century revolutions]]\n[[Category:Armed Forces of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Battles and conflicts without fatalities]]\n[[Category:Colour revolutions]]\n[[Category:Presidency of Ferdinand Marcos]]\n[[Category:History of the Philippines (1965\u201386)]]\n[[Category:History of Metro Manila]]\n[[Category:Imelda Marcos]]\n[[Category:Military history of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Nonviolent revolutions]]\n[[Category:Protests in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Presidential elections in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Rebellions in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:February 1986 events in Asia]]\n", "name_user": "103.72.189.5", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eBackground and history)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/People_Power_Revolution"}
{"title_page": "Sia (musician)", "text_new": "{{About|the musician|other uses|Sia (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|Australian singer and songwriter}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}} \n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name            = Sia<!--DO NOT CHANGE THIS WITHOUT FURTHER DISCUSSION-->\n| image           = Sia Seattle (cropped).jpg\n| caption         = Sia performing in Seattle, Washington in August 2011\n| birth_name      = Sia Kate Isobelle Furler\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1975|12|18}}\n| birth_place     = [[Adelaide]], [[South Australia]], Australia\n| occupation      = {{hlist|Singer|songwriter|voice actress|music video director}}\n| years_active    = 1990\u2013present\n| signature       = File:Sia Furler signature.svg\n| module          = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background      = solo_singer\n| genre           = {{hlist|[[Pop music|Pop]]|[[electropop]]|[[indie pop]]|[[acid jazz]]}}\n| label           = {{hlist|[[Dance Pool]]|[[Go! Discs|Go! Beat]]|Inertia|[[RCA Records|RCA]]|Monkey Puzzle|[[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]}}\n| associated_acts = {{hlist|[[Zero 7]]|[[LSD (group)|LSD]]|[[Maddie Ziegler]]}}\n| website         = {{URL|siamusic.net}}\n}}\n}}\n'''Sia Kate Isobelle Furler''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|s|i\u02d0|\u0259|}} {{respell|SEE|\u0259}}; born 18 December 1975) is an Australian singer, songwriter, voice actress and music video director.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/us-music-charts-sia-idUKKBN0FL2SM20140716 |title=Singer-songwriter Sia snags first No. 1 on U.S. Billboard chart |date=16 July 2014 |work=Reuters |access-date=26 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170927155837/http://uk.reuters.com/article/us-music-charts-sia-idUKKBN0FL2SM20140716 |archive-date=27 September 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> She started her career as a singer in the [[acid jazz]] band Crisp in the mid-1990s in [[Adelaide]]. In 1997, when Crisp disbanded, she released her debut [[studio album]] titled ''OnlySee'' in Australia. She moved to London, England, and provided lead vocals for the British duo [[Zero 7]]. In 2000, Sia released her second studio album, ''[[Healing Is Difficult]]'', and her third studio album, ''[[Colour the Small One]]'', in 2004, but all of these struggled to connect with a mainstream audience.\n\nSia relocated to New York City in 2005 and toured in the United States. Her fourth and fifth studio albums, ''[[Some People Have Real Problems]]'' and ''[[We Are Born]]'', were released in 2008 and 2010, respectively. Each was certified gold by the [[Australian Recording Industry Association]] and attracted wider notice than her earlier albums. Uncomfortable with her growing fame, Sia took a hiatus from performing, during which she focused on songwriting for other artists, producing successful collaborations \"[[Titanium (song)|Titanium]]\" (with [[David Guetta]]), \"[[Diamonds (Rihanna song)|Diamonds]]\" (with [[Rihanna]]) and \"[[Wild Ones (song)|Wild Ones]]\" (with [[Flo Rida]]).\n\nIn 2014, Sia broke through as a solo recording artist when her sixth studio album, ''[[1000 Forms of Fear]]'', debuted at No 1 in the U.S. [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and generated the top-ten single \"[[Chandelier (song)|Chandelier]]\" and a trilogy of music videos starring child dancer [[Maddie Ziegler]]. Since then, Sia has usually worn a wig that obscures her face to protect her privacy.<ref name=Age/> Her seventh studio album ''[[This Is Acting]]'' (2016), spawned her first [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] number one single, \"[[Cheap Thrills (song)|Cheap Thrills]]\". The same year, Sia gave her [[Nostalgic for the Present Tour]], which incorporated dancing by Ziegler and others and other performance art elements. Her eighth studio album, ''[[Everyday Is Christmas (album)|Everyday Is Christmas]]'', was released in 2017 and [[reissue]]d in 2018 with three bonus tracks. In 2018 and 2019 she collaborated with [[Labrinth]] and [[Diplo]] in the group [[LSD (group)|LSD]], and they released their [[LSD (album)|self-titled debut album]] in April 2019. Among the [[List of awards and nominations received by Sia|accolades]] received by Sia are nearly a dozen [[ARIA Awards]], 9 [[Grammy Award]] nominations, and an [[MTV Video Music Award]].<ref name=ARIA2014>{{cite web| url=http://www.fasterlouder.com.au/news/40788/Chet-Faker-and-Violent-Soho-lead-20sheeran14-ARIA-nominations|title=Chet Faker and Violent Soholead 2014 ARIA nominations|publisher=fasterlouder|accessdate=5 November 2014}}{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\n===1975\u20131997: Early life and career beginnings===\nSia Kate Isobelle Furler was born on 18 December 1975 in [[Adelaide]], South Australia. Her father, Phil Colson, is a musician, and her mother, Loene Furler, is an art lecturer.<ref name=\"Harry\"/> Sia is the niece of actor-singer [[Kevin Colson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/theatre/kevin-colson-confesses-all-of-his-career-in-starry-firmament-20140926-10meub.html|title=Kevin Colson confesses all of his career in starry firmament|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|last=Craven|first=Peter|date=26 September 2014|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924162821/http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/theatre/kevin-colson-confesses-all-of-his-career-in-starry-firmament-20140926-10meub.html|archive-date=24 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Sia said that as a child she imitated the performing style of [[Aretha Franklin]], [[Stevie Wonder]] and [[Sting (musician)|Sting]], whom she cites as early influences.<ref name=\"NPR\">{{cite interview|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=19075503|title=Sia Learns to Sound Like Herself|first=Alex|last=Cohen|authorlink=Alex Cohen|publisher=[[NPR Music]]|date=15 February 2008|access-date=28 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228100728/https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=19075503|archive-date=28 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> She attended [[Adelaide High School]].<ref name=\"Harry\">{{cite journal|url=http://www.mjmharry.com/docs/Sia-Furler.pdf| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101105010101/http://www.mjmharry.com/docs/Sia-Furler.pdf|title=Sia Sensation|first=Michael|last=Harry|journal=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Adelaide Advertiser]]|pages=24\u201326|format=PDF|archivedate=5 November 2010}}</ref> In the mid-1990s, Sia started a career as a singer in the local [[acid jazz]] band Crisp.<ref name=\"Harry\"/> Sia collaborated with the band and contributed vocals to their album ''Word and the Deal'' (1995) and EP ''Delirium'' (1997).<ref>''Word and the Deal'' and ''Delirium'':\n\n* {{cite web|url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/15875159?selectedversion=NBD12798813|title=Word and the deal / Crisp. [sound recording]|publisher=[[National Library of Australia]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150114223832/http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/15875159?selectedversion=NBD12798813|archivedate=14 January 2015|url-status=dead}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/24518036?q&versionId=29594043|title=Delirium / Crisp. [sound recording]|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=National Library of Australia|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150115020959/http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/24518036?q&versionId=29594043|archivedate=15 January 2015|url-status=dead|access-date=}}</ref>\nIn 1997 Crisp disbanded,<ref name=\"SMHSia\">{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/sia-furler-fame-does-not-become-her-20100617-yjdr.html|title=Sia Furler: Fame does not become her|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|first=Andrew|date=18 June 2010|last=Murfett|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150212030150/http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/sia-furler-fame-does-not-become-her-20100617-yjdr.html|archive-date=12 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> and Sia released her debut [[studio album]], ''OnlySee'', on Flavoured Records, in Australia, on 23 December.<ref name=\"nloa\">{{cite web| url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/7556295?selectedversion=NBD13682423|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131225133718/http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/7556295?selectedversion=NBD13682423| title=Onlysee / Sia Furler. [sound recording]|publisher=National Library of Australia|archivedate=25 December 2013}}</ref> The album sold about 1,200 copies.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Leon |title=Sia's first album onlysee |url=http://boyprincess.com/why-it-bothers-people-that-sia-hides-her-face/d13b98750d6a-original/ |website=Boy Princess |accessdate=28 August 2015 |date=1 March 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160106063531/http://boyprincess.com/why-it-bothers-people-that-sia-hides-her-face/d13b98750d6a-original/ |archivedate=6 January 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title=Sia| url=http://www.discogs.com/artist/21991-Sia| website=Discogs| accessdate=28 August 2015| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150927082613/http://www.discogs.com/artist/21991-Sia| archive-date=27 September 2015| url-status=live}}</ref> Unlike her later albums, ''OnlySee'' was marketed under her full name, \"Sia Furler\". It was produced by Jesse Flavell.<ref>[https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/7556295?selectedversion=NBD13682423 \"Onlysee (sound recording) / Sia Furler\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180108233421/https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/7556295?selectedversion=NBD13682423 |date=8 January 2018 }}, Flavoured Records, 1997, Trove.nla.gov.au, accessed 8 January 2018</ref>\n\n===1997\u20132006: Zero 7, ''Healing Is Difficult'' and ''Colour the Small One''===\n[[File:Sia Furler in concert.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Sia in concert in 2006]]\nAfter Crisp disbanded in 1997, Sia moved to London,<ref name=\"SMHSia\"/> where she performed as a background vocalist for British band [[Jamiroquai]].<ref name=AllMusic>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/sia-mn0000753742/biography |title=Sia Biography |website=[[AllMusic]] |first=Andrew |last=Leahey |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150211225955/http://www.allmusic.com/artist/sia-mn0000753742/biography |archivedate=11 February 2015 |url-status=dead}}</ref> She also provided lead vocals for English downtempo group [[Zero 7]] on their first three studio albums and toured with the group.<ref name=\"Verrico\"/> On Zero 7's 2001 album ''[[Simple Things (Zero 7 album)|Simple Things]]'', Sia contributed vocals to two tracks<ref name=allmusicsimple>{{cite web|title=Simple Things \u2013 Zero 7|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/simple-things-mw0000017246|website=AllMusic|accessdate=19 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131201122541/http://www.allmusic.com/album/simple-things-mw0000017246|archive-date=1 December 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> including the single  \"[[Destiny (Zero 7 song)|Destiny]]\", which peaked at No. 30 on the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref name=\"SiaUK\">{{cite web|url=http://officialcharts.com|title=Sia: Artist|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150217061412/http://www.officialcharts.com/|archive-date=17 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2004, she provided vocals for Zero 7 on \"Somersault\" and \"Speed Dial No. 2\" (from the album ''[[When It Falls]]'').<ref name=allmusicwhen>{{cite web|last1=Bush|first1=John|title=When It Falls \u2013 Zero 7|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/when-it-falls-mw0000328826|website=AllMusic|accessdate=19 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121205013320/http://www.allmusic.com/album/when-it-falls-mw0000328826|archive-date=5 December 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2006, Sia again collaborated with Zero 7 for the group's third album, ''[[The Garden (Zero 7 album)|The Garden]]'' and hence she is regarded as the \"unofficial\" lead singer of Zero 7.<ref name=allmusicgarden>{{cite web|last1=Brown|first1=Marisa|title=The Garden \u2013 Zero 7|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/the-garden-mw0000542394|website=AllMusic|accessdate=19 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150326054553/http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-garden-mw0000542394|archive-date=26 March 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"BB09\">{{cite journal |last=Mason |first=Kerri |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EX4yD1pJCxUC&pg=PA56 |title=Albums: Zero 7 \u2013 Yeah Ghost |page=56 |journal=Billboard |date=3 October 2009 |volume=121 |number=39 |access-date=21 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160404070213/https://books.google.com/books?id=EX4yD1pJCxUC&pg=PA56 |archive-date=4 April 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, Sia signed a recording contract with [[Sony Music]]'s sub-label [[Dance Pool]] and released her first [[single (music)|single]], \"[[Taken for Granted]]\", which peaked at No. 10 on the UK Singles Chart.<ref name=AllMusic/> In 2001, she released her second solo album, ''[[Healing Is Difficult]]'', which blends retro [[jazz]] and [[soul music|soul]] music and lyrically discusses Sia's dealing with the death of her first love affair.<ref name=\"SMHSia\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/healing-is-difficult-mw0000464188|title=Healing Is Difficult \u2013 Sia|website=AllMusic|first=Jon|last=O'Brien|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150208212645/http://www.allmusic.com/album/healing-is-difficult-mw0000464188|archive-date=8 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Displeased with the promotion of the album, Sia fired her manager, left Sony Music and signed with [[Go! Beat Records|Go! Beat]], a subsidiary of [[Universal Music Group]] (UMG).<ref name=\"Verrico\"/> At the [[APRA Awards of 2002]], Sia won the Breakthrough Songwriter category alongside Brisbane pop duo [[Aneiki]]'s Jennifer Waite and Grant Wallis.<ref name=\"APRAWin2002\">{{cite web | url = http://www.apra-amcos.com.au/APRAAwards/MusicAwards/History/2002Winners.aspx |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110308004321/http://www.apra-amcos.com.au/APRAAwards/MusicAwards/History/2002Winners.aspx| title = 2002 Winners \u2013 APRA Music Awards | publisher = [[Australasian Performing Right Association]] | archivedate=8 March 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, Sia released her third studio album, ''[[Colour the Small One]]''.<ref name=\"Ott\">{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/7735-colour-the-small-one/ |title=Sia \u2013 Colour the Small One |last1=Ott |first1=Chris |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=2 March 2004 |accessdate=9 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150816072120/http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/7735-colour-the-small-one/ |archivedate=16 August 2015 }}</ref> The album employs a mixture of [[acoustic music|acoustic instruments]] and [[electronic music|electronic]] backing to her material.<ref name=\"Ott\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2004/jan/02/popandrock.shopping|title=CD: Sia, Colour the Small One|work=[[The Guardian]]|first=Caroline|last=Sullivan|date=2 January 2004|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150216150842/http://www.theguardian.com/music/2004/jan/02/popandrock.shopping|archive-date=16 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The album spawned four singles, including \"[[Don't Bring Me Down (Sia song)|Don't Bring Me Down]]\" and \"[[Breathe Me]]\", the latter of which charted in the United Kingdom,<ref name=\"SiaUK\"/> Denmark and France.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.danishcharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=Breathe+Me&cat=s|title=Breathe Me \u2013 Sia|publisher=[[Tracklisten]]|language=Danish|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150131134906/http://www.danishcharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=Breathe+Me&cat=s|archive-date=31 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDissatisfied with ''Colour the Small One''{{'}}s poor marketing and the album's struggle to connect with a mainstream audience, Sia relocated to New York City in 2005.<ref name=\"SMHSia\"/> During that time, \"Breathe Me\" appeared in the final scene of the U.S. [[HBO]] television series ''[[Six Feet Under (TV series)|Six Feet Under]]'', which helped increase Sia's fame in the United States. Consequently, Sia's manager, David Enthoven, set up a tour across the country to maintain her career.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/20/magazine/sia-furler-the-socially-phobic-pop-star.html?_r=1|title=Sia Furler, the Socially Phobic Pop Star|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=20 April 2014|first=Steve|last=Knopper|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150214121101/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/20/magazine/sia-furler-the-socially-phobic-pop-star.html?_r=1|archive-date=14 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===2007\u20132010: ''Some People Have Real Problems'' and ''We Are Born''===\n[[File:Sia performing photograph by Kris Krug.jpg|thumb|right|Sia performing at [[South by Southwest]] in 2008]]\nIn 2007, Sia released a [[live album]] titled ''[[Lady Croissant]]'', which included eight live songs from her April 2006 performance at the [[Bowery Ballroom]] in New York and one new studio recording\u2014\"Pictures\".<ref name=\"Brown\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/lady-croissant-mw0000557699|title=Sia \u2013 Lady Croissant|website=AllMusic|first=Marisa|last=Brown|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160829134946/http://www.allmusic.com/album/lady-croissant-mw0000557699|archive-date=29 August 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> A year later, she left Zero 7 on friendly terms, replaced by [[ESKA|Eska Mtungwazi]] as the band's frontwoman.<ref name=\"BB09\"/> Sia released her fourth studio album, ''[[Some People Have Real Problems]]'' on 8 January 2008. The album peaked at No. 41 in Australia and was [[List of music recording certifications|certified gold]] by the [[Australian Recording Industry Association]].<ref name=\"Australia\">Australian chart position and certification:\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.australian-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Sia |title=Discography Sia |publisher=ARIA Charts |accessdate=16 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150227104853/http://www.australian-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Sia |archivedate=27 February 2015}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.aria.com.au/pages/httpwww.aria.com.aupageshttpwww.aria.com.aupageshttpwww.aria.com.aualbumaccreds2011.htm |title=Accreditations \u2013 2011 Albums |publisher=Australian Recording Industry Association |accessdate=16 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/64wvlBwg5?url=http://www.aria.com.au/pages/httpwww.aria.com.aupageshttpwww.aria.com.aupageshttpwww.aria.com.auALBUMaccreds2011.htm |archivedate=25 January 2012}}</ref>\nIt charted at No. 26 on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], becoming Sia's first album to chart in the United States.<ref name=\"BB200\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/279248/sia/chart?f=305|title=Sia \u2013 Chart history: Billboard 200|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141214082755/http://www.billboard.com/artist/279248/Sia/chart?f=305|archive-date=14 December 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Some People Have Real Problems'' yielded four singles, including \"[[The Girl You Lost to Cocaine]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nl-be.7digital.com/artist/sia/release/the-girl-you-lost-to-cocaine-3/|title=The Girl You Lost To Cocaine|publisher=[[7digital]]|location=Belgium|language=Dutch|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150110073119/https://nl-be.7digital.com/artist/sia/release/the-girl-you-lost-to-cocaine-3/|archivedate=10 January 2015}}</ref> It peaked at No. 11 in the Netherlands and No. 12 in Spain;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=The+Girl+You+Lost+To+Cocaine&cat=s|title=Sia \u2013 The Girl You Lost to Cocaine|publisher=[[Single Top 100]]|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150113023803/http://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=The+Girl+You+Lost+To+Cocaine&cat=s|archive-date=13 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> it additionally reached No. 8 on the US [[Hot Dance Club Songs]].<ref name=\"DanceClubSongs\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/279248/sia/chart?f=359|title=Sia \u2013 Chart history: Dance Club Songs|work=Billboard|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150620102739/http://www.billboard.com/artist/279248/Sia/chart?f=359|archive-date=20 June 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Another single from the album was \"[[Soon We'll Be Found]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/soon-well-be-found-single/id705846139 |title=iTunes \u2013 Music \u2013 Soon We'll Be Found |publisher=iTunes Store |location=United Kingdom |archivedate=24 February 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150224202640/https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/soon-well-be-found-single/id705846139 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2009, Sia released ''[[TV Is My Parent]]'' on [[DVD]], which includes a live concert at New York's Hiro Ballroom, four music videos and behind-the-scene footage.<ref name=\"MusicNews\">{{cite web|url=http://www.musicnewsnet.com/2009/03/tv-is-my-parent-new-dvd-from-sia.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006160804/http://www.musicnewsnet.com/2009/03/tv-is-my-parent-new-dvd-from-sia.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=6 October 2011|title=TV is My Parent, New DVD from Sia|publisher=Music News Net|date=9 March 2009}}</ref> At the [[ARIA Music Awards of 2009]], Sia won the Best Music DVD category for ''TV Is My Parent''.<ref name=\"ARIAAward2009\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ariaawards.com.au/history-by-year.php?year=2009 |title=ARIA Awards History|publisher=ARIA Awards|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100128034837/http://www.ariaawards.com.au/history-by-year.php|archivedate=28 January 2010}}</ref> She also received a nomination for Best Breakthrough Artist Album for ''Some People Have Real Problems''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Parker |first=Tappan |url=http://dailycollegian.com/2010/05/03/sia-brings-song-to-pearl-street/ |title=Sia brings song to Pearl Street |work=[[The Massachusetts Daily Collegian]] |date=3 May 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141205015846/http://dailycollegian.com/2010/05/03/sia-brings-song-to-pearl-street/ |archivedate=5 December 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, American singer [[Christina Aguilera]] approached Sia about writing [[ballad]]s for Aguilera's then-upcoming sixth studio album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/now-you-sia/story-e6frf7jo-1111119107653|title=Sia Furler is enjoying attentions of Christina Aguilera|work=[[Herald Sun]]|first=Cameron|last=Adams|date=12 March 2009|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130907143511/http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/now-you-sia/story-e6frf7jo-1111119107653|archive-date=7 September 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> The final product, ''[[Bionic (Christina Aguilera album)|Bionic]]'', includes three songs co-written by Sia.<ref>{{cite AV media notes|title=[[Bionic (Christina Aguilera album)|Bionic]]|others=[[Christina Aguilera]]|year=2010|type=liner notes|publisher=[[RCA Records]], a division of [[Sony Music Entertainment]]}}</ref> Later in 2010, Sia also co-wrote \"Bound to You\" for [[Burlesque: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|the soundtrack]] of the American film ''[[Burlesque (2010 American film)|Burlesque]]'', which starred Aguilera and American singer [[Cher]].<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120112044802/http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/content_display/magazine/reviews/albums/e3ibde532c77149bc3146237ecd8761e87d|url=http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/content_display/magazine/reviews/albums/e3ibde532c77149bc3146237ecd8761e87d|title=Burlesque: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|work=Billboard|first=Kerri|last=Mason|date=11 December 2010|archivedate=12 January 2012}}</ref> The song was nominated for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]] at the [[68th Golden Globe Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/ipad/jackie-weaver-nicole-kidman-geoffrey-rush-and-toni-collette-nominated-in-68th-golden-globe-awards/story-fn6bqphm-1225971265572|title=Jackie Weaver, Nicole Kidman, Geoffrey Rush and Toni Collette nominated in 68th Golden Globe Awards|work=The Adelaide Advertiser|date=15 December 2010|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120903005627/http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/ipad/jackie-weaver-nicole-kidman-geoffrey-rush-and-toni-collette-nominated-in-68th-golden-globe-awards/story-fn6bqphm-1225971265572|archive-date=3 September 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> In May 2011, Sia appeared on the [[The Voice (American season 1)|inaugural season]] of the U.S. version of ''[[The Voice (American TV series)|The Voice]]'' as an adviser for Aguilera, who served as a vocal coach and judge.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/music_blog/2011/04/nbcs-the-voice-enlists-monica-reba-mcentire-sia-and-adam-blackstone-as-advisors.html|title=NBC's 'The Voice' enlists Monica, Reba McEntire, Sia and Adam Blackstone as advisors|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141104234733/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/music_blog/2011/04/nbcs-the-voice-enlists-monica-reba-mcentire-sia-and-adam-blackstone-as-advisors.html|date=29 April 2011|archivedate=4 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2010, Sia released her fifth studio album, ''[[We Are Born]]''.<ref name=\"SiaWeAreBorn\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B003SP3WM2|title=We Are Born by Sia|publisher=Amazon.co.uk|accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref> The release peaked at No. 2 on the [[ARIA Charts|ARIA Albums Chart]] and was certified gold by the Australian Recording Industry Association.<ref name=\"Australia\"/> The release of the album was preceded by three singles: the lead single, \"[[You've Changed (Sia song)|You've Changed]]\", was released in December 2009 and charted at No. 31 in Australia.<ref>\"You've Changed\" single release and chart position:\n*{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/nz/album/youve-changed-single/id348315733 |title=iTunes \u2013 Music \u2013 You've Changed |publisher=iTunes Store |location=New Zealand |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6WPE28MJO?url=https://itunes.apple.com/nz/album/youve-changed-single/id348315733 |archivedate=17 February 2015 |url-status=dead }}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=You%27ve+Changed&cat=s |title=You've Changed \u2013 Sia |publisher=ARIA Charts |accessdate=17 February 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150201235222/http://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=You%27ve+Changed&cat=s |archive-date=1 February 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> The follow-up single, \"[[Clap Your Hands (Sia song)|Clap Your Hands]]\", peaked at No. 17 in Australia, No. 10 in the Netherlands and No. 27 in Switzerland.<ref>\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.bandit.fm/album/2688296?cc=AU|title=Clap Your Hands: Sia|publisher=bandit.fm|accessdate=17 February 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150217121806/http://www.bandit.fm/album/2688296?cc=AU|archivedate=17 February 2015}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=Clap+Your+Hands&cat=s|title=Sia \u2013 Clap Your Hands|publisher=[[Single Top 100]]|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150321054914/http://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=Clap+Your+Hands&cat=s|archive-date=21 March 2015|url-status=live}}\n</ref> At the [[ARIA Music Awards of 2010]], ''We Are Born'' earned Sia two categories won: Best Independent Release and Best Pop Release.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ariaawards.com.au/history/year/2010|title=ARIA Awards History: 2010|publisher=ARIA Awards|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140228203958/http://www.ariaawards.com.au/history/year/2010|archivedate=28 February 2014}}</ref> Meanwhile, at the 2011 [[APRA Awards (Australia)|APRA Music Awards]], Sia received a nomination for Song of the Year for \"Clap Your Hands\".<ref name=\"Collins\">{{Cite news | url = http://au.news.yahoo.com/thewest/entertainment/a/-/music/9653365/the-man-behind-the-songs/ | title = The Man Behind the Songs | last1 = Collins | first1 = Simon | work = [[The West Australian]]| date = 16 June 2011 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120928111952/http://au.news.yahoo.com/thewest/entertainment/a/-/music/9653365/the-man-behind-the-songs/|archivedate=28 September 2012 }}</ref> To promote ''We Are Born'', Sia embarked on the [[We Meaning You Tour]], which visited North America and Europe in April\u2013May 2010.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2010/02/sia-announces-the-we-meaning-you-tour-dates|title=Sia Announces 'The We Meaning You Tour' Dates|magazine=[[Consequence of Sound]]|date=3 February 2010|first=Derek|last=Staples|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140831234421/http://consequenceofsound.net/2010/02/sia-announces-the-we-meaning-you-tour-dates/|archivedate=31 August 2014}}</ref> She followed this with the [[We Are Born Tour]], which visited Australia in February 2011 and North America in July\u2013August 2011.<ref>We Are Born Tour:\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.theaureview.com/the-goss/sia-announces-february-2011-australian-tour |title=Sia announces February 2011 Australian Tour |publisher=The AU Review |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140816133240/http://www.theaureview.com/the-goss/sia-announces-february-2011-australian-tour |archivedate=16 August 2014 |url-status=dead }}\n*{{cite web|url=http://siamusic.net/tour |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715020744/http://siamusic.net/tour |title=Tour: Sia |publisher=Sia Music |archivedate=15 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In March 2012, Sia released the greatest hits album ''[[Best Of... (Sia album)|Best Of...]]'' in Australia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.creammagazine.com/2012/03/hello-to-the-first-greatest-hits-set-from-sia/|title=Say hi to Sia's first greatest hits set|work=Cream|date=10 March 2012|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150217132010/http://www.creammagazine.com/2012/03/hello-to-the-first-greatest-hits-set-from-sia/|archive-date=17 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===2010\u20132013: Songwriting career and mainstream recognition===\n[[File:Sia (5423995397) (Cropped).jpg.png|thumb|upright|right|Sia performing in 2011]]\nFollowing the success of ''We Are Born'', Sia became uncomfortable with her growing fame. She later told ''[[The New York Times]]'': \"I just wanted to have a private life. Once, as my friend was telling me they had cancer, someone came up and asked, in the middle of the conversation, if they could take a photograph with me. You get me? That's enough, right?\"<ref name=Knopper>Knopper, Steve. [https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/20/magazine/sia-furler-the-socially-phobic-pop-star.html \"Sia Furler, the Socially Phobic Pop Star\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170413151146/https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/20/magazine/sia-furler-the-socially-phobic-pop-star.html |date=13 April 2017 }}, ''The New York Times'', 18 April 2014, accessed 26 October 2016</ref> She refused to do promos for her tours, began to wear a mask on stage and became increasingly dependent on drugs and alcohol on the road; she considered suicide.<ref name=\"Knopper\" /> Sia fired Enthoven and hired Jonathan Daniel, who suggested that she write songs for other artists.<ref name=Knopper/>\n\nSia retired as a recording artist and began a career as a songwriter. She soon penned \"[[Titanium (song)|Titanium]]\" for American singer [[Alicia Keys]], but it was later sent to [[David Guetta]], who included Sia's original [[demo (music)|demo]] vocals on the song and released it as a single in 2011.<ref name=\"NPRMusic\"/> \"Titanium\" peaked within the top ten of record charts in the United States, Australia and numerous European regions.<ref>\nChart positions for \"Titanium\":\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=David+Guetta+feat.+Sia&titel=Titanium&cat=s|title=David Guetta feat. Sia \u2013 Titanium|publisher=ARIA Charts|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150201233616/http://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=David+Guetta+feat%2E+Sia&titel=Titanium&cat=s|archive-date=1 February 2015|url-status=live}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/300445/David+Guetta/chart?f=379|title=David Guetta \u2013 Chart history: Hot 100|work=Billboard|accessdate=18 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150614031257/http://www.billboard.com/artist/300445/David+Guetta/chart?f=379|archive-date=14 June 2015|url-status=live}}\n</ref> However, Sia was not pleased with the success of the single: \"[...] I never even knew it was gonna happen, and I was really upset. Because I had just retired, I was trying to be a pop songwriter, not an artist.\"<ref name=\"NPRMusic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2014/07/08/329500971/a-reluctant-star-sia-deals-with-fame-on-her-own-terms|title=A Reluctant Star, Sia Deals With Fame on Her Own|publisher=[[NPR Music]]|date=8 July 2014|first=Sam|last=Sanders|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150215153550/http://www.npr.org/2014/07/08/329500971/a-reluctant-star-sia-deals-with-fame-on-her-own-terms|archive-date=15 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> From 2011 to 2013, Sia also co-wrote songs for many recording artists, including [[Beyonc\u00e9]], [[Kylie Minogue]], [[Flo Rida]] and [[Rihanna]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://6thfloor.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/04/21/how-a-song-written-by-sia-furler-becomes-a-hit/?_php=true&_type=blogs&_r=0|title=How a Song Written by Sia Furler Became a Hit|work=The New York Times|date=21 April 2014|first=Steve|last=Knopper|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141205003032/http://6thfloor.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/04/21/how-a-song-written-by-sia-furler-becomes-a-hit/?_php=true&_type=blogs&_r=0|archivedate=5 December 2014}}</ref> Her collaboration with Flo Rida, \"[[Wild Ones (song)|Wild Ones]]\", peaked at No. 5 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 and was the tenth best-selling song of 2012 globally.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ifpi.org/downloads/dmr2013-full-report_english.pdf | title=IFPI Digital Music Report 2013 | work=IFPI | accessdate=3 October 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180529150621/http://www.ifpi.org/downloads/dmr2013-full-report_english.pdf | archive-date=29 May 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===2013\u20132014: Breakthrough with ''1000 Forms of Fear''===\nIn October 2013, Sia released \"[[Elastic Heart]]\" featuring [[The Weeknd]] and [[Diplo]] for [[The Hunger Games: Catching Fire \u2013 Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|the soundtrack]] of the American film ''[[The Hunger Games: Catching Fire]]'' (2013).<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921055615/http://www.allaccess.com/top40-rhythmic/future-releases |url=http://www.allaccess.com/top40-rhythmic/future-releases |title=Top 40/R Future Releases |publisher=All Access Music Group |archivedate=21 September 2013 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Sia executive-produced [[Brooke Candy]]'s debut EP, ''[[Opulence (EP)|Opulence]]'', released in May 2014, and co-wrote 3 songs on the EP.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.factmag.com/2014/04/28/brooke-candy-preps-debut-ep-does-sex-and-violence-in-opulence-video|title=Brooke Candy preps debut EP, does sex-and-violence in ''Opulence'' video|work=[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact]]|date=28 April 2014|access-date=20 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170320052522/http://www.factmag.com/2014/04/28/brooke-candy-preps-debut-ep-does-sex-and-violence-in-opulence-video/|archive-date=20 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In July 2014, Sia released her own sixth studio album, ''[[1000 Forms of Fear]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/1000-forms-of-fear-mw0002680594|title=1000 Forms of Fear \u2013 Sia|website=AllMusic|first=Heather|last=Phares|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210072510/http://www.allmusic.com/album/1000-forms-of-fear-mw0002680594|archive-date=10 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> She again collaborated with Greg Kurstin.<ref name=KurstinCollab>\n*{{cite journal|last1=Leight|first1=Elias|title=Sia Announces New Christmas Album, Directorial Debut|journal=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=1 August 2017|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/sia-announces-new-christmas-album-directorial-debut-w495289|accessdate=2 August 2017|publisher=Wenner Media LLC|issn=0035-791X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801205328/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/sia-announces-new-christmas-album-directorial-debut-w495289|archive-date=1 August 2017|url-status=live}}\n*{{cite news|last1=McNeilage|first1=Ross|title=Sia Has Signed a New Record Deal and Is Releasing a Christmas Album|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/sia/news/sia-is-recording-a-christmas-album|accessdate=2 August 2017|work=[[MTV News]]|publisher=[[MTV]]|date=1 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801210319/http://www.mtv.co.uk/sia/news/sia-is-recording-a-christmas-album|archive-date=1 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The album debuted at No. 1 in the US ''Billboard'' 200 with first-week sales of 52,000 copies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/australia-culture-blog/2014/jul/17/sia-1000-forms-of-fear-no-1-us-album|title=Sia's 1000 Forms of Fear debuts at No 1 in US album charts|first=Clem|last=Bastow|date=17 July 2014|work=The Guardian|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150217170434/http://www.theguardian.com/music/australia-culture-blog/2014/jul/17/sia-1000-forms-of-fear-no-1-us-album|archive-date=17 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> By October 2015, it was certified gold by the [[RIAA]] denoting 500,000 equivalent-album units sold in the United States.<ref>{{cite magazine|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151218061812/http://hitsdailydouble.com/new_album_releases |archivedate= 18 December 2015 |url=http://hitsdailydouble.com/new_album_releases |title=Upcoming Releases |magazine=Hits Daily Double |publisher=HITS Digital Ventures }}</ref> The record peaked at No. 1 in Australia and reached the top ten of charts in numerous European regions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=1000+Forms+Of+Fear&cat=a|title=Sia \u2013 1000 Forms of Fear|publisher=ARIA Charts|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210000509/http://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=1000+Forms+Of+Fear&cat=a|archive-date=10 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> It was certified silver by the [[British Phonographic Industry]] and gold by the Australian Recording Industry Association.<ref>\"Chandelier\" certifications:\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/certified-awards.aspx |title=Certified Awards |format=''Enter the keyword \"Sia\" into the search parameter'' |publisher=[[British Phonographic Industry]] |accessdate=17 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6EEYfYVwc?url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/certified-awards.aspx |archivedate=6 February 2013 |df= }}\n*{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140906185517/http://www.ariacharts.com.au/chart/albums |url=http://www.ariacharts.com.au/chart/albums |title=ARIA Australian Top 50 Albums |publisher=ARIA Charts |archivedate=6 September 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\nBy early 2016, the album had sold 1 million copies worldwide.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/music/sia-reclaims-the-songs-adele-rihanna-and-beyonce-rejected-to-rewrite-the-pop-blueprint/news-story/08460609cb95cfa5464a978b0682a215 | title=Sia reclaims the songs Adele, Rihanna and Beyonce rejected to rewrite the pop blueprint | work=News Corp Australia Network | date=29 January 2016 | accessdate=1 October 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161006120531/http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/music/sia-reclaims-the-songs-adele-rihanna-and-beyonce-rejected-to-rewrite-the-pop-blueprint/news-story/08460609cb95cfa5464a978b0682a215 | archive-date=6 October 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n''1000 Forms of Fear''{{'}}s lead single, \"[[Chandelier (song)|Chandelier]]\" was released in March 2014. The song peaked at No. 8 on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], becoming Sia's first entry on that chart as a lead artist.<ref name=\"Billboardhot100\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/279248/Sia/chart?f=379|title=Sia \u2013 Chart history: Hot 100|work=Billboard|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150322040223/http://www.billboard.com/artist/279248/Sia/chart?f=379|archive-date=22 March 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Elsewhere, the song experienced similar commercial success, ranking in the top ten of the [[record chart]]s in Australia and numerous European regions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=Chandelier&cat=s|title=Sia \u2013 Chandelier|publisher=ARIA Charts|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150223151251/http://www.australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=Chandelier&cat=s|archive-date=23 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> As of January 2015, the single had sold 2 million copies in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/music/nick-jonass-jealous-hits-a-new-peak-108110758051.html|title=Nick Jonas's 'Jealous' Hits a New Peak|first=Paul|last=Grein|publisher=[[Yahoo! Music]]|date=15 January 2015|accessdate=15 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150115011236/https://www.yahoo.com/music/nick-jonass-jealous-hits-a-new-peak-108110758051.html|archive-date=15 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> \"[[Eye of the Needle (song)|Eye of the Needle]]\" and \"[[Big Girls Cry]]\" were released as the second and third singles from the album, respectively, in June 2014.<ref>\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.bandit.fm/album/7804041?cc=AU |title=Eye of the Needle |publisher=bandit.fm |accessdate=17 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150227052707/http://www.bandit.fm/album/7804041?cc=AU |archivedate=27 February 2015}}\n*{{cite web |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6VQMICp5g?url=https://nl-be.7digital.com/artist/sia/release/big-girls-cry/ |url=https://nl-be.7digital.com/artist/sia/release/big-girls-cry |title=Big Girls Cry (2014) |publisher=7digital |location=Belgium |archivedate=8 January 2015 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\nIn January 2015, Sia released a solo version of \"[[Elastic Heart#Sia solo version|Elastic Heart]]\" as the fourth single from ''1000 Forms of Fear''; it eventually reached the top 20 on the Hot 100.<ref name=\"ElasticHeart\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6443523/hot-100-chart-moves-sia-video-controversy|title=Hot 100 Chart Moves: Video Controversy Sends Sia's 'Elastic Heart' to No. 17 Debut|first=Gary|last=Trust|date=16 January 2015|work=Billboard|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120012212/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6443523/hot-100-chart-moves-sia-video-controversy|archive-date=20 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> At the [[57th Annual Grammy Awards]] (2015), Sia received four nominations for \"Chandelier\": [[Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]], [[Grammy Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]], [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Solo Performance|Best Pop Solo Performance]] and [[Grammy Award for Best Music Video|Best Music Video]].<ref name=GrammyNoms2015>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/zackomalleygreenburg/2014/12/05/grammy-nominees-2015-the-full-list/|title=Grammy Nominees 2015: The Full List|first=Zack|last=O'Malley Greenburg|work=[[Forbes]]|date=5 December 2014|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141205233150/http://www.forbes.com/sites/zackomalleygreenburg/2014/12/05/grammy-nominees-2015-the-full-list/|archive-date=5 December 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFor live performances of songs from ''1000 Forms of Fear'', Sia chose not to show her face, either facing away from audiences or hiding it behind oversized platinum blonde wigs. In videos for the singles \"Chandelier\", \"Elastic Heart\" and \"Big Girls Cry\", choreographed by [[Ryan Heffington]] and co-directed by Sia and [[Daniel Askill]], and in many of the promotional live performances, child dancer [[Maddie Ziegler]] performed as a proxy for Sia in bobbed blonde wigs similar to Sia's familiar hairstyle.<ref>Schumann, Rebecka. [http://www.ibtimes.com/dance-moms-star-maddie-ziegler-responds-snl-sia-chandelier-spoof-video-1713850 \"''Dance Moms'' Star Maddie Ziegler Responds to ''SNL'' Sia 'Chandelier' Spoof\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170226091440/http://www.ibtimes.com/dance-moms-star-maddie-ziegler-responds-snl-sia-chandelier-spoof-video-1713850 |date=26 February 2017 }}, ''International Business Times'', 27 October 2014, accessed 2 December 2015; Geslani, Michelle. [http://consequenceofsound.net/2015/12/sia-and-dance-prodigy-maddie-ziegler-deliver-gripping-performance-on-ellen-watch \"Sia and dance prodigy Maddie Ziegler deliver gripping performance on Ellen \u2013 watch\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161005142912/http://consequenceofsound.net/2015/12/sia-and-dance-prodigy-maddie-ziegler-deliver-gripping-performance-on-ellen-watch/ |date=5 October 2016 }}, ConsequenceofSound.net, 1 December 2015; Bailey, Alyssa. [http://www.elle.com/culture/celebrities/news/a32257/sia-maddie-ziegler-ellen-degeneres-show \"Watch Sia and Maddie Ziegler's Chilling Live Performance of 'Alive'\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160610105719/http://www.elle.com/culture/celebrities/news/a32257/sia-maddie-ziegler-ellen-degeneres-show/ |date=10 June 2016 }}, ''Elle'' magazine, 1 December 2015; and Swift, Andy. [http://tvline.com/2015/02/08/sia-kristen-wiig-grammy-performance-2015-grammys-chandelier \"Sia Enlists Kristen Wiig for 'Chandelier' Performance at 2015 Grammy Awards\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160926150710/http://tvline.com/2015/02/08/sia-kristen-wiig-grammy-performance-2015-grammys-chandelier/ |date=26 September 2016 }}, Tvline.com, 8 February 2015</ref> The three videos have received a total of more than 3&nbsp;billion views on [[Vevo]].<ref>Furler, Sia. [https://www.youtube.com/user/SiaVEVO/videos?sort=p&view=0&flow=grid SiaVEVO: Most popular videos] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423182936/https://www.youtube.com/user/SiaVEVO/videos?sort=p&view=0&flow=grid |date=23 April 2016 }}, YouTube, accessed 11 October 2018</ref> Sia explained to [[Kristen Wiig]] in an interview in ''[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]]'' magazine that she decided to conceal her face to avoid a celebrity lifestyle and maintain some privacy: \"I'm trying to have some control over my image. And I'm allowed to maintain some modicum of privacy. But also I would like not to be picked apart or for people to observe when I put on ten pounds or take off ten pounds or I have a hair extension out of place or my fake tan is botched. Most people don't have to be under that pressure, and I'd like to be one of them.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.interviewmagazine.com/music/sia|title=Sia|date=April 2015|work=[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]]|accessdate=30 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150529124817/http://www.interviewmagazine.com/music/sia/|archive-date=29 May 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The video for ''Elastic Heart'' \"courted controversy and plaudits in equal measure\", with some commentators perceiving it to have [[pedophilia|pedophilic]] undertones due to the relative ages of the dancers.<ref>Norton, Siobhan. [https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/health-and-families/features/ballet-fitness-why-growing-numbers-are-using-plis-and-pirouettes-to-work-out-10386434.html \"Ballet fitness: Why growing numbers are using pli\u00e9s and pirouettes to work out\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150926034903/http://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/health-and-families/features/ballet-fitness-why-growing-numbers-are-using-plis-and-pirouettes-to-work-out-10386434.html |date=26 September 2015 }}, ''The Independent'', 14 July 2015</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/jan/11/sia-video-pop-music-not-paedophilia?CMP=soc_567 \"Sia's video: let's be wary of seeing paedophilia everywhere\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170828233629/https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/jan/11/sia-video-pop-music-not-paedophilia?CMP=soc_567 |date=28 August 2017 }}, ''[[Guardian Australia]]'', 11 January 2015</ref> Sia explained that the two dancers represented \"warring 'Sia' self states\", but she nevertheless apologized on Twitter to anyone who was \"[[Trauma trigger|triggered]]\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://gma.yahoo.com/sia-apologizes-pedophilia-perception-music-video-133650931--abc-news-music.html |title=Sia Apologizes for \u2018Pedophilia\u2019 Perception in Music Video |publisher=Yahoo! |date=9 January 2015 |accessdate=8 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150110024135/https://gma.yahoo.com/sia-apologizes-pedophilia-perception-music-video-133650931--abc-news-music.html |archive-date=10 January 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=ElasticCont>Ranscombe, Si\u00e2n. [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/rockandpopfeatures/11585580/The-10-most-controversial-music-videos.html \"The 10 most controversial music videos\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180408070841/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/rockandpopfeatures/11585580/The-10-most-controversial-music-videos.html |date=8 April 2018 }}, ''The Telegraph'', 10 May 2015</ref> Gia Kourlas wrote in ''The New York Times'' in 2016 that Sia's collaborations with Heffington have \"done more to raise the standards of dance in pop music than nearly any current artist integrating the forms\".<ref>Kourlas, Gia. [https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/24/arts/dance/for-sia-dance-is-where-the-human-and-the-weird-intersect.html?smid=tw-nytimesarts&smtyp=cur&_r=1 \"For Sia, Dance Is Where the Human and the Weird Intersect\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170813055653/https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/24/arts/dance/for-sia-dance-is-where-the-human-and-the-weird-intersect.html?smid=tw-nytimesarts&smtyp=cur&_r=1 |date=13 August 2017 }}, ''[[The New York Times]]'', 19 July 2016, accessed 31 October 2016</ref> The \"Chandelier\" video was ranked as the 10th \"greatest music video\" of the 2010s by ''Billboard''.<ref>[https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/list/8544596/best-music-videos-2010s-top-100 \"The 100 Greatest Music Videos of the 2010s: Staff Picks\"], ''Billboard'', November 26, 2019</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Sia contributed to the [[Annie (2014 film soundtrack)|soundtrack]] to the [[Annie (2014 film)|2014 film adaptation]] of the Broadway musical [[Annie (musical)|''Annie'']]. Sia, along with producer Greg Kurstin, wrote three new songs for the film as well as re-working songs from the musical.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rigby|first1=Sam|title=Sia and Beck Join Stars on Annie Movie Soundtrack|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/music/news/a605383/sia-and-beck-join-stars-on-annie-movie-soundtrack.html#~oUASLyfKso2baF|website=[[Digital Spy]]|publisher=Digital Spy|accessdate=3 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141104005343/http://www.digitalspy.com/music/news/a605383/sia-and-beck-join-stars-on-annie-movie-soundtrack.html#~oUASLyfKso2baF|archive-date=4 November 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Sia, Kurstin and ''Annie'' director [[Will Gluck]] were nominated at the [[72nd Golden Globe Awards]] for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]] for one of the film's original songs, \"Opportunity\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/birdman-grand-budapest-pace-noms-for-critics-choice-awards-1201379383/ |title='Birdman,' 'Grand Budapest' Top Critics Choice Awards Nominations |work=Variety |date=15 December 2014 |first=Tim |last=Gray |accessdate=15 December 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141216035611/http://variety.com/2014/film/news/birdman-grand-budapest-pace-noms-for-critics-choice-awards-1201379383/ |archivedate=16 December 2014 |df= }}</ref>\n\n===2015\u20132017: ''This Is Acting''===\n[[File:SIaFurler Boston2016live.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Sia in 2016; since 2014, she has covered most of her face at concerts and on TV]]\nIn an interview with ''[[NME]]'' in February 2015, Sia revealed that she had completed the follow-up to ''1000 Forms of Fear'', entitled ''[[This Is Acting]]''. The album was another collaboration with producer and co-writer Greg Kurstin.<ref name=KurstinCollab/> Furler said that she released ''1000 Forms of Fear'' to free herself from her record deal and had planned simply to write for other artists, but the album's success spurred her to continue writing her own music.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/various-artists/82961|title=Sia reveals early details of brand new album ''This Is Acting''|date=17 February 2015|work=[[NME]]|accessdate=19 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150218161220/http://www.nme.com/news/various-artists/82961|archive-date=18 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> In May 2015, Sia's cover of [[The Mamas & the Papas]]' \"[[California Dreamin']]\" was released on the soundtrack of the movie ''[[San Andreas (film)|San Andreas]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine| last1=Strecker| first1=Erin| title=Sia Releases Haunting 'California Dreamin'' Cover for 'San Andreas' Movie| url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6561316/sia-california-dreamin-cover-san-andreas-movie-mamas-papas| accessdate=18 September 2015| magazine=Billboard| date=2 May 2015| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150917234259/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6561316/sia-california-dreamin-cover-san-andreas-movie-mamas-papas| archive-date=17 September 2015| url-status=live}}</ref> The same month, alongside the digital deluxe release of ''1000 Forms of Fear'', she released a mobile game, ''Bob Job''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McCown|first1=Alex|title=Sia releases a new game, still won't show herself|url=https://www.avclub.com/article/sia-releases-new-game-still-wont-show-herself-219026|accessdate=18 September 2015|newspaper=A.V. Club|date=6 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150913042827/http://www.avclub.com/article/sia-releases-new-game-still-wont-show-herself-219026|archive-date=13 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> \"[[Alive (Sia song)|Alive]]\" from ''This Is Acting'' was co-written by [[Adele]] and had originally been intended for Adele's third album.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lee|first1=Christina|title=Sia Details Next Single, Which Was Originally Written for Adele|url=http://www.idolator.com/7607168/sia-2015-album-this-is-acting-single-adele|website=Idolator|publisher=Time Inc.|date=7 September 2015|accessdate=8 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150908185348/http://www.idolator.com/7607168/sia-2015-album-this-is-acting-single-adele|archive-date=8 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn November, Sia collaborated with composer [[J. Ralph]] on the soundtrack of the environmental documentary ''[[Racing Extinction]]'', co-writing and singing the song \"One Candle\".<ref>Spanos, Brittany. [https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-sias-epic-new-song-one-candle-from-racing-extinction-trailer-20151105 \"Hear Sia, J. Ralph's Epic New Song From ''Racing Extinction'' Trailer\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107031319/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-sias-epic-new-song-one-candle-from-racing-extinction-trailer-20151105 |date=7 November 2017 }}, ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', 5 November 2015. Retrieved 28 September 2016</ref> She also released two more songs from the album, \"[[Bird Set Free]]\"<ref>{{Citation|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KrT_0J6m6y8|accessdate = 29 November 2015|title = Bird Set Free|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151126233141/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KrT_0J6m6y8|archive-date = 26 November 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> and \"One Million Bullets\".<ref>{{Cite web|title = Sia Shares New Track \"One Million Bullets\"|url = https://pitchfork.com/news/62289-sia-shares-new-track-one-million-bullets|website = Pitchfork|accessdate = 29 November 2015|language = en-US|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151130015805/http://pitchfork.com/news/62289-sia-shares-new-track-one-million-bullets/|archive-date = 30 November 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> \"[[Cheap Thrills (song)|Cheap Thrills]]\" and \"[[Reaper (song)|Reaper]]\" were subsequently released as promotional singles for the album. In January 2016, eight days prior to the release of ''This Is Acting'', she released \"Unstoppable\" as the final pre-release promotion single for the album. Eventually, the single \"Cheap Thrills\", featuring [[Sean Paul]], reached No. 1 on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Trust|first1=Gary|title=Sia's 'Cheap Thrills' Takes No. 1 on Hot 100 From Drake|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7446766/sia-cheap-thrills-sean-paul-no-1-hot-100|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=25 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160726141731/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7446766/sia-cheap-thrills-sean-paul-no-1-hot-100|archive-date=26 July 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Sia released two videos for the song, one of which features Ziegler and two male dancers,<ref>[https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7263981/sia-releases-captivating-cheap-thrills-video-featuring-maddie-ziegler \"Sia Releases Captivating 'Cheap Thrills' Video Featuring Maddie Ziegler\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160910215333/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7263981/sia-releases-captivating-cheap-thrills-video-featuring-maddie-ziegler |date=10 September 2016 }}, ''Billboard'', 21 March 2016; and Briones, Isis. [http://www.teenvogue.com/story/sia-maddie-ziegler-cheap-thrills-music-video \"Sia's Music Video of New Single 'Cheap Thrills' With Maddie Ziegler Will Blow You Away\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160918154550/http://www.teenvogue.com/story/sia-maddie-ziegler-cheap-thrills-music-video |date=18 September 2016 }}, ''Teen Vogue'', 21 March 2016</ref> while the other, featuring Sean Paul, shows a 1950s style teen dance party; it has accumulated more than 1.4 billion views.<ref>Sia. [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nYh-n7EOtMA \"Sia \u2013 'Cheap Thrills' (Lyric Video) ft. Sean Paul\"], YouTube, 10 February 2016, accessed 10 December 2019</ref>\n\nIn April 2016, Sia gave a widely acclaimed performance at the [[Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival]] that went [[viral video|viral]] online.<ref name=\"People Are Still Obsessed\">{{Cite web|url=http://time.com/4299395/sia-coachella-performance/|title=People Are Still Obsessed With Sia's Incredible Coachella Performance|website=Time|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422051544/http://time.com/4299395/sia-coachella-performance/|archive-date=22 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>\nSources for the 2016 Coachella Festival performance:\n*{{Cite web|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/04/coachella-is-losing-its-shit-over-sias-performance/|title=Coachella is losing its shit over Sia's performance|website=Consequence of Sound|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160425033830/http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/04/coachella-is-losing-its-shit-over-sias-performance/|archive-date=25 April 2016|url-status=live}}\n*{{Cite web|url=http://www.fuse.tv/2016/04/sia-2016-festivals|title=IS SIA ALREADY THE MVP OF THE 2016 FESTIVAL SEASON?|website=Fuse|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160502125311/http://www.fuse.tv/2016/04/sia-2016-festivals|archive-date=2 May 2016|url-status=live}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/music-festivals/7334157/sia-coachella-2016|title=Sia Captivates & Confounds During Star-Studded Coachella Set|website=Billboard|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423120358/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/music-festivals/7334157/sia-coachella-2016|archive-date=23 April 2016|url-status=live}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/posts/la-et-ms-coachella-2016-sia-main-stage-star-power-20160419-story.html|title=Coachella 2016: Sia changed the whole concept of star power on the main stage|website=Los Angeles Times|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160424161628/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/posts/la-et-ms-coachella-2016-sia-main-stage-star-power-20160419-story.html|archive-date=24 April 2016|url-status=live}}\n*{{Cite web|url=http://www.pe.com/articles/sia-800269-stage-set.html|title=COACHELLA 2016: Sia turns the festival into a stage for performance art (UPDATE)|website=Press Enterprise|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160427040348/http://www.pe.com/articles/sia-800269-stage-set.html|archive-date=27 April 2016|url-status=live}}\n*{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/la-et-ms-coachella-2016-l-ever-elusive-sia-flips-the-script-on-coachella-cam-1460959067-htmlstory.html|title=Coachella: Surviving members of N.W.A reunite, and artists pay tribute to Prince|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|issn=0458-3035|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423103952/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/la-et-ms-coachella-2016-l-ever-elusive-sia-flips-the-script-on-coachella-cam-1460959067-htmlstory.html|archive-date=23 April 2016|url-status=live}}\n</ref><ref name=\"incredible Coachella set\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.dazeddigital.com/music/article/30811/1/watch-sia-s-incredible-coachella-set-in-full-here|title=Watch Sia's incredible Coachella set in full here|website=Dazed Digital|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422050327/http://www.dazeddigital.com/music/article/30811/1/watch-sia-s-incredible-coachella-set-in-full-here|archive-date=22 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Sia legendary\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nylon.com/articles/sia-coachella-2016-performance|title=Sia's Coachella Set Is Already Legendary|website=Nylon Magazine|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423173314/http://www.nylon.com/articles/sia-coachella-2016-performance|archive-date=23 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Her performance received an effusively positive critical reception<ref name=\"incredible Coachella set\"/><ref name=\"Sia legendary\"/> as \"one of the greatest moments in Coachella's 17-year history\",<ref>{{Cite web| url=https://www.yahoo.com/music/this-is-acting-sia-stuns-with-theatrical-180537878.html| title=This Is Acting: Sia Stuns With Theatrical Coachella Spectacle| website=Yahoo! Music| access-date=25 April 2016| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160427062441/https://www.yahoo.com/music/this-is-acting-sia-stuns-with-theatrical-180537878.html| archive-date=27 April 2016| url-status=live}}</ref> and it was consistently noted as one of the best performances of the 2016 festival.<ref>\nLists of the best 2016 Coachella Festival performances:\n*{{Cite web|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/04/coachella-2016-festival-review-from-worst-to-best/46/|title=Coachella 2016 Festival Review: From Worst to Best|website=Consequence of Sound|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423120741/http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/04/coachella-2016-festival-review-from-worst-to-best/46/|archive-date=23 April 2016|url-status=live}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/30-best-things-we-saw-at-coachella-2016-weekend-one-20160418/best-performance-art-sia-20160418|title=30 Best Things We Saw at Coachella: Best Performance Art- Sia|website=Rolling Stone|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160426162416/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/30-best-things-we-saw-at-coachella-2016-weekend-one-20160418/best-performance-art-sia-20160418|archive-date=26 April 2016|url-status=live}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/music-festivals/7334239/coachella-2016-best-moments-first-weekend|title=11 Best Moments From Coachella 2016|website=Billboard|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422071641/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/music-festivals/7334239/coachella-2016-best-moments-first-weekend|archive-date=22 April 2016|url-status=live}}\n*{{Cite web|url=http://www.fuse.tv/2016/04/coachella-2016-10-best-performances#1|title=TOP 10 BEST PERFORMANCES OF COACHELLA 2016|website=Fuse|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160421055836/http://www.fuse.tv/2016/04/coachella-2016-10-best-performances#1|archive-date=21 April 2016|url-status=live}}\n</ref> The performance was her first full concert since 2011.<ref name=\"People Are Still Obsessed\"/> In May 2016, Sia made a surprise appearance on the finale for ''[[Survivor: Ka\u00f4h R\u014dng]]'' where she donated $50,000 to contestant Tai Trang. She donated another $50,000 to an animal charity of his choice, noting that the two share a mutual love of animals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/sia-gives-survivor-finalist-100k-for-being-an-animal-rights-activist_us_573d2480e4b0646cbeec23d9|title=Sia Gives 'Survivor' Finalist $100K For Being An Animal Rights Activist|website=The Huffington Post|access-date=19 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160519041151/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/sia-gives-survivor-finalist-100k-for-being-an-animal-rights-activist_us_573d2480e4b0646cbeec23d9|archive-date=19 May 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The same month, she contributed vocals to a cover of [[Nat King Cole]]'s \"[[Unforgettable (Nat King Cole song)|Unforgettable]]\" which was featured on the [[Finding Dory (soundtrack)|soundtrack]] of 2016 [[Pixar]] film ''[[Finding Dory]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7378273/sia-finding-dory-unforgettable-ellen-nat-king-cole | title=Watch Sia Cover Nat King Cole's 'Unforgettable' for 'Finding Dory' on 'Ellen' | work=Billboard | date=20 May 2016 | accessdate=9 September 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160910060231/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7378273/sia-finding-dory-unforgettable-ellen-nat-king-cole | archive-date=10 September 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2016, Sia gave a concert at [[Red Rocks Amphitheatre]] in Colorado, featuring Ziegler.<ref>Owens, Dylan. [http://www.heyreverb.com/blog/2016/06/23/welcome-sias-theater-dreams-red-rocks-seriesfest/118235/#16 \"For SeriesFest, Sia welcomes Red Rocks to her theater of dreams\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160924185311/http://www.heyreverb.com/blog/2016/06/23/welcome-sias-theater-dreams-red-rocks-seriesfest/118235/#16 |date=24 September 2016 }}, HeyReverb.com, ''[[The Denver Post]]'', 23 June 2016</ref> From May to August, Sia performed in nearly a dozen festival and other concerts in America and European and Middle Eastern countries, including Portugal, Denmark, Sweden, Finland, Hungary, Romania, Poland, the United Kingdom, Russia, Lebanon and Israel.<ref>Young, Alex. [http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/05/sia-announce-2016-world-tour-miguel-and-alunageorge-to-open ''Sia announce 2016 world tour, Miguel and AlunaGeorge to open''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161002113531/http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/05/sia-announce-2016-world-tour-miguel-and-alunageorge-to-open/ |date=2 October 2016 }}, ''Consequence of Sound'', 16 May 2016, accessed 30 September 2016</ref><ref>[http://www.artistdirect.com/entertainment-news/article/sia-announces-tour-with-openers-miguel-and-alunageorge/11864459 ''Sia Announces Tour With Openers Miguel And AlunaGeorge''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161002141105/http://www.artistdirect.com/entertainment-news/article/sia-announces-tour-with-openers-miguel-and-alunageorge/11864459 |date=2 October 2016 }}, ''[[Artistdirect|Artist Direct]]'', 17 May 2016, accessed 30 September 2016</ref><ref>Pate, Stephen. [http://njnnetwork.com/2016/08/sia-open-worldwide-tour-in-byblos-lebanon ''Sia Excites Crowd As Worldwide Tour Opens in Byblos Lebanon''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161003091531/http://njnnetwork.com/2016/08/sia-open-worldwide-tour-in-byblos-lebanon/ |date=3 October 2016 }}, ''NJN Network'', 10 August 2016, accessed 30 September 2016</ref> In September 2016, she released a single, \"[[The Greatest (Sia song)|The Greatest]]\", with vocals from American hip hop recording artist [[Kendrick Lamar]]. A video was released the same day featuring Ziegler \u2013 the dancer's fifth video collaboration with Sia and Heffington.<ref name=GreatestGlicksman>Glicksman, Josh. [https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8478144/sia-maddie-ziegler-friendship-timeline \"A Timeline of Sia & Maddie Ziegler's Friendship, From 'Chandelier' to a New Car\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004094825/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8478144/sia-maddie-ziegler-friendship-timeline |date=4 October 2018 }}, ''Billboard'', 3 October 2018; and Furler, Sia. [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GKSRyLdjsPA \"Sia \u2013 The Greatest\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160909002001/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GKSRyLdjsPA |date=9 September 2016 }}, SiaVEVO, 5 September 2016</ref> The two performed the song with several other dancers, and also performed \"Chandelier\", live the next day at the [[Apple Inc|Apple]] annual [[Apple media events|fall event]], drawing media attention.<ref>Moss, Rachel. [http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/maddie-ziegler-apple-launch-performance_uk_57d16502e4b0d45ff871392a \"13-Year-Old Dancer Maddie Ziegler Totally Stole The Show At The Apple iPhone 7 Launch\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160913015215/http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/maddie-ziegler-apple-launch-performance_uk_57d16502e4b0d45ff871392a |date=13 September 2016 }}, ''Huffington Post'', 8 September 2016; and Robinson, Melia. [http://www.businessinsider.com/dancing-girl-apple-event-2016-9 \"Meet the 13-year-old dancing sensation who stunned people at the big Apple event\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160911144815/http://www.businessinsider.com/dancing-girl-apple-event-2016-9 |date=11 September 2016 }}, ''[[Business Insider]]'', 7 September 2016</ref> The videos that Sia has posted to her YouTube channel have accumulated a total of more than 8&nbsp;billion views, and the channel has more than 18 million subscribers.<ref>Furler, Sia. [https://www.youtube.com/user/siavideos/featured Sia], YouTube, accessed 10 December 2019</ref>\n\nSia gave her [[Nostalgic for the Present Tour]] in North America from September to November 2016, featuring Ziegler.<ref>Craddock, Lauren. [https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7446785/maddie-ziegler-sia-nostalgic-for-the-present-tour \"Maddie Ziegler to Join Sia's Nostalgic for the Present Tour\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160910061039/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7446785/maddie-ziegler-sia-nostalgic-for-the-present-tour |date=10 September 2016 }}, ''Billboard'', 25 July 2016</ref> As at Coachella and subsequent live performances, Sia appeared at the back of the stage with her familiar wig covering her face, while her dancers performed Heffington's choreography synchronized with prerecorded videos played on big screens.<ref>Klein, Josh. [https://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/music/ct-sia-miguel-review-ent-1018-20161017-story.html \"Sia is a bundle of fascinating contradictions during United Center performance\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161020045201/http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/music/ct-sia-miguel-review-ent-1018-20161017-story.html |date=20 October 2016 }}, ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'', 17 October 2016</ref> The tour received a warm reaction: \"She let her dancers own center stage, carrying out one skit/performance after another as Sia delivered the soundtrack. ... It defied all the regular rules of pop concerts, which are usually designed to focus every ounce of the audience\u2019s attention on the star of the show. Yet, Sia's bold gamble paid off, resulting in one of the most daringly original and wholly satisfying shows of 2016.\"<ref name=\"Harrington, Jim\">{{cite web | url=http://www.mercurynews.com/2016/10/02/review-sia-rocks-with-kristen-wiig-paul-dano-in-oakland | title=Review: Sia delivers performance-art masterpiece in Oakland | work=The Mercury News | date=2 October 2016 | accessdate=2 October 2016 | author=Harrington, Jim | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161004154408/http://www.mercurynews.com/2016/10/02/review-sia-rocks-with-kristen-wiig-paul-dano-in-oakland/ | archive-date=4 October 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> Ed Masley of ''[[The Arizona Republic]]'' described the show as \"part performance art, part interpretive dance. ... [Sia] sounded amazing. ... There's so much raw emotion in her songs. And you can definitely hear that in her voice, but it becomes more visceral when you can also read it in the faces of her dancers, especially Ziegler. ... The entire performance was brilliantly staged, with one song flowing seamlessly into another\".<ref>Masley, Ed. [https://www.azcentral.com/story/entertainment/music/2016/10/05/sia-concert-review-maddie-ziegler/91611028 \"Review: Sia reinvented what it means to give a concert \u2013 part performance art, part Maddie Ziegler\"], ''[[The Arizona Republic]]'', 5 October 2016</ref> Sia released the deluxe edition of ''This Is Acting'' in October 2016, which includes three new tracks, a remix version of \"Move Your Body\" and a solo version of \"The Greatest\".<ref>Raynor, Madeline. [https://www.ew.com/article/2016/10/21/sia-this-acting-deluxe-new-songs \"Sia releases 3 new tracks on ''This is Acting'' deluxe version\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161023035131/http://www.ew.com/article/2016/10/21/sia-this-acting-deluxe-new-songs |date=23 October 2016 }}, ''Entertainment Weekly'', 21 October 2016</ref> She was nominated for three 2017 Grammy Awards.<ref name=GrammyNoms2017>[https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7597556/grammys-nominees-complete-list-2017 \"Here Is the Complete List of Nominees for the 2017 Grammys\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161206151125/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7597556/grammys-nominees-complete-list-2017 |date=6 December 2016 }}, ''Billboard'' magazine, 6 December 2016</ref> Sia contributed to the soundtracks for the films ''[[Lion (2016 film)|Lion]]'' and ''[[Wonder Woman (2017 film)|Wonder Woman]]'' with \"[[Never Give Up (Sia song)|Never Give Up]]\" and \"[[To Be Human]]\", respectively.<ref name=Spanos2>{{Cite news |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-sias-sweeping-new-wonder-woman-anthem-to-be-human-w484209 |title=Hear Sia's Sweeping New Anthem 'To Be Human' from 'Wonder Woman' Soundtrack |last=Spanos |first=Brittany |date=25 May 2017 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=26 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525173923/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-sias-sweeping-new-wonder-woman-anthem-to-be-human-w484209 |archive-date=25 May 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> She also co-wrote and performed on a platinum-selling single, \"[[Dusk Till Dawn (Zayn song)|Dusk Till Dawn]]\" by [[Zayn Malik]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Leight|first=Elias|title=Watch Jemima Kirke in Noir Thriller For Zayn Malik, Sia's New Song|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=7 September 2017|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/see-zayn-malik-in-noir-thriller-dusk-till-dawn-video-w501630|accessdate=20 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170920141652/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/see-zayn-malik-in-noir-thriller-dusk-till-dawn-video-w501630|archive-date=20 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>[https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&ar=ZAYN&ti=DUSK+TILL+DAWN+%28FEAT.+SIA%29 \"Zayn: 'Dusk Till Dawn' (Feat. Sia)\"], RIAA, accessed 24 October 2018</ref>\n\nSia performed in concert at the close of the [[Dubai World Cup]] in March 2017, together with her dancers, led by Ziegler.<ref>Hamad, Marwa. [http://gulfnews.com/life-style/music/sia-dons-her-wig-during-theatrical-dubai-gig-1.2000413 \"Sia dons her wig during theatrical Dubai gig\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170326223344/http://gulfnews.com/life-style/music/sia-dons-her-wig-during-theatrical-dubai-gig-1.2000413 |date=26 March 2017 }}, ''Gulf News'', 26 March 2017</ref> They gave a second leg of the Nostalgic for the Present Tour, her first stadium tour in Australasia, in late 2017.<ref>\n*{{Cite news |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7809643/sia-stadium-tour-australia-new-zealand |title=Sia Plots First Stadium Tour of Australia and New Zealand |last=Brandle |first=Lars |date=29 May 2017 |work=Billboard |access-date=29 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170529081115/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7809643/sia-stadium-tour-australia-new-zealand |archive-date=29 May 2017 |url-status=live }}\n*He, Richard S. [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/dec/01/sia-review-when-she-transcends-spectacle-she-soars \"Sia review \u2013 when she transcends spectacle, she soars\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180101172948/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/dec/01/sia-review-when-she-transcends-spectacle-she-soars |date=1 January 2018 }}, ''[[The Guardian]]'', 30 November 2017, accessed 28 January 2018\n</ref>\n\n===2017\u2013present: ''Everyday Is Christmas'' and ''LSD''===\nIn 2017, Sia moved from RCA to [[Atlantic Records]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7882275/sia-christmas-album-atlantic-records-deal|title=Sia Signs to Atlantic Records, Announces Christmas Album|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Kaufman|first=Gil|date=1 August 2017|accessdate=1 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801183635/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7882275/sia-christmas-album-atlantic-records-deal|archive-date=1 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> She released a new album, ''[[Everyday Is Christmas (album)|Everyday Is Christmas]]'', on Atlantic and Monkey Puzzle in November 2017. The album features original songs co-written and co-produced with Kurstin.<ref>\n*{{cite journal|last1=Kaufman|first1=Gil|title=Sia Signs to Atlantic Records, Announces Christmas Album|journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=1 August 2017|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7882275/sia-christmas-album-atlantic-records-deal|accessdate=2 August 2017|publisher=[[Eldridge Industries]]|issn=0006-2510|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801194617/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7882275/sia-christmas-album-atlantic-records-deal|archive-date=1 August 2017|url-status=live}}\n*{{cite journal|title=Sia Signs with Atlantic Records, Christmas Album Due This Year|journal=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=1 August 2017|url=https://variety.com/2017/music/news/sia-signs-with-atlantic-records-christmas-album-due-this-year-1202512120/|accessdate=2 August 2017|issn=0042-2738|oclc=810134503|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801173836/http://variety.com/2017/music/news/sia-signs-with-atlantic-records-christmas-album-due-this-year-1202512120/|archive-date=1 August 2017|url-status=live}}\n</ref> She promoted it by releasing the single \"Santa's Coming for Us\" and by the track \"Snowman\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-sias-joyous-seasonal-song-santas-coming-for-us-w510478|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=16 April 2018|title=Hear Sia's Joyous Seasonal Song 'Santa's Coming for Us|author=Daniel Kreps|date=30 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180417105614/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-sias-joyous-seasonal-song-santas-coming-for-us-w510478|archive-date=17 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8031327/sia-new-song-snowman-christmas-album-listen|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=16 April 2018|title=Sia Shares New Song, Snowman, Says She Wrote Christmas Album By Accident|date=11 November 2017|author=Mary J. DiMeglio|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180424042351/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8031327/sia-new-song-snowman-christmas-album-listen|archive-date=24 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> which she performed during the finale of the [[The Voice (American season 13)|13th season of ''The Voice'']] and on ''[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show]]'' together with Maddie Ziegler.<ref>Aniftos, Rania. [https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8070501/sia-maddie-ziegler-reunite-perform-snowman-ellen \"Sia & Maddie Ziegler Reunite to Perform 'Snowman' on ''Ellen'': Watch\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180105220316/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8070501/sia-maddie-ziegler-reunite-perform-snowman-ellen |date=5 January 2018 }}, ''Billboard'', 13 December 2017</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/tv/news/e2-80-98the-voice-e2-80-99-finale-recap-the-winner-of-season-13-is-revealed/ar-BBH31du|publisher=[[MSN]]|accessdate=16 April 2018|title=The Voice Finale Recap: The Winner Of Season 13 Is Revealed|author=Alyssa Norwin|date=20 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418031517/https://www.msn.com/en-us/tv/news/e2-80-98the-voice-e2-80-99-finale-recap-the-winner-of-season-13-is-revealed/ar-BBH31du|archive-date=18 April 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> In November 2018, Sia released the deluxe edition of the album, containing three bonus tracks, as a [[Target Corporation|Target]] exclusive.<ref>Lenniger, Shea. [https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8482991/sia-deluxe-christmas-album-stream \"Sia Releases Deluxe Version of Her Christmas Album: Listen\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181103123309/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8482991/sia-deluxe-christmas-album-stream |date=3 November 2018 }}, ''Billboard'', 2 November 2018</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Sia collaborated with English musician [[Labrinth]] and American DJ/record producer [[Diplo]], under the name [[LSD (group)|LSD]], to release four songs,<ref>[https://variety.com/2018/music/news/lsd-sia-diplo-and-labrinth-team-up-for-new-song-genius-listen-1202796730 \"Sia, Diplo and Labrinth Team Up for New Song 'Genius' (Listen)\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616065328/https://variety.com/2018/music/news/lsd-sia-diplo-and-labrinth-team-up-for-new-song-genius-listen-1202796730/ |date=16 June 2018 }}, ''Variety'', 3 May 2018; Rettig, James. [https://www.stereogum.com/1995583/lsd-sia-diplo-labrinth-audio-video/video \"LSD (Sia, Diplo, & Labrinth) \u2013 'Audio' Video\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616153713/https://www.stereogum.com/1995583/lsd-sia-diplo-labrinth-audio-video/video/ |date=16 June 2018 }}, [[Stereogum]], 10 May 2018; and Bein, Kat. [https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/8482791/lsd-mountains-new-song \"LSD Reaches New Heights on 'Mountains'\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181102165506/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/8482791/lsd-mountains-new-song |date=2 November 2018 }}, ''Billboard'', 1 November 2018</ref> which were then released as an EP called ''Mountains'' on Spotify.<ref name=\"Legaspi\">{{cite journal |last1=Legaspi |first1=Althea |title=Hear Diplo, Sia, Labrinth Move \u2018Mountains\u2019 on New Song |journal=Rolling Stone |date=1 November 2018 |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/diplo-sia-labrinth-mountains-new-lsd-song-750952/ |accessdate=3 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181102175747/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/diplo-sia-labrinth-mountains-new-lsd-song-750952/ |archive-date=2 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The group released an album, ''[[LSD (album)|Labrinth, Sia & Diplo Present... LSD]]'', in April 2019,<ref>Daw, Stephen. (11 March 2019). [https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/8501893/diplo-sia-labrinth-announce-debut-lsd-album-release-date \"Diplo, Sia & Labrinth Announce Debut LSD Album Release Date\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190315104320/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/8501893/diplo-sia-labrinth-announce-debut-lsd-album-release-date |date=15 March 2019 }}, ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''. Retrieved 11 March 2019</ref> containing the same four songs, five new songs, and a previously released remix of their track \"[[Genius (LSD song)|Genius]]\" with [[Lil Wayne]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/nz/album/labrinth-sia-diplo-present-lsd/1455271201|title=Labrinth, Sia & Diplo Present... LSD by LSD on iTunes|last=|first=|date=|website=iTunes Store|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328164726/https://itunes.apple.com/nz/album/labrinth-sia-diplo-present-lsd/1455271201|archive-date=28 March 2019|url-status=live|access-date=12 April 2019}}</ref> \n\nAlso in 2018, Sia was one of the narrators of Australian animal rights documentary [[Dominion (documentary)|''Dominion'']],<ref>Webber, Jemima. [https://www.livekindly.co/vegan-celebrity-sia-joins-cast-of-new-animal-rights-documentary-dominion \"Vegan Celebrity Sia Joins Cast of New Animal Rights Documentary Dominion\"], LiveKindly.co, 18 May 2018, accessed 14 February 2020</ref> and shared in a 2018 Award of Excellence from the Hollywood International Independent Documentary Awards.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://hiida.com/july-2018-winners.html|title=Hollywood International Independent Documentary Awards]]</ref> The next year, Sia collaborated with composer [[Hans Zimmer]] on the title song, \"Out There\", for the BBC [[David Attenborough]] documentary series ''[[Seven Worlds, One Planet]]''.<ref>Pearce, Tilly. [https://metro.co.uk/2019/10/28/seven-worlds-one-planet-sia-joined-forces-sir-david-attenborough-hans-zimmer-create-iconic-track-10995575 \"''Seven Worlds One Planet'': How Sia joined forces with Sir David Attenborough and Hans Zimmer to create epic track\"], Metro.co.uk, 28 October 2019</ref> In January 2020, Furler released her song \"[[Original (Sia song)|Original]]\", which featured on the ''[[Dolittle (film)|Dolittle]]'' film soundtrack.<ref>https://pitchfork.com/news/listen-to-sias-new-song-original</ref>\n\n==Artistry, musical style and accolades==\n{{further|List of awards and nominations received by Sia}}\n\nAt the start of her career, with the bands Crisp<ref name=AllmusicHealing>{{cite web|last1=O'Brien|first1=Jon|title=Sia: Healing is Difficult|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/healing-is-difficult-mw0000464188|website=AllMusic|accessdate=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180717024024/https://www.allmusic.com/album/healing-is-difficult-mw0000464188|archive-date=17 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Jamiroquai]], Sia performed \"acid jazz\" in Australia and later in London.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Prato|first1=Greg|title=Jamiroquai Overview|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/jamiroquai-mn0000176358|website=AllMusic|accessdate=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180201041752/https://www.allmusic.com/artist/jamiroquai-mn0000176358|archive-date=1 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> With her first solo single, \"Taken for Granted\", she experimented with [[trip hop]].<ref name=AllmusicHealing/> When she joined Zero 7, she sang [[downtempo]] numbers.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wesolowski|first1=David Peter|title=Zero 7 Overview|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/zero-7-mn0000696668|website=AllMusic|accessdate=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180413190527/https://www.allmusic.com/artist/zero-7-mn0000696668|archive-date=13 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nWith ''[[Colour the Small One]]'' (2004) and ''[[Some People Have Real Problems]]'' (2007) she moved into [[jazz]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sullivan|first1=Caroline|title=Sia, Colour the Small One|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2004/jan/02/popandrock.shopping|accessdate=13 April 2018|work=The Guardian|date=1 January 2004|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180718180149/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2004/jan/02/popandrock.shopping|archive-date=18 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[folktronica]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=O'Brien|first1=Jon|title=Sia: Colour the Small One|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/colour-the-small-one-mw0000463309|website=AllMusic|accessdate=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171104214544/https://www.allmusic.com/album/colour-the-small-one-mw0000463309|archive-date=4 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> although the album's biggest hit, \"[[Breathe Me]]\", is described as [[alternative rock]] and a [[power ballad]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Sia: Breathe Me|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/breathe-me-mw0001977876|website=AllMusic|accessdate=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201044614/https://www.allmusic.com/album/breathe-me-mw0001977876|archive-date=1 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Some People Have Real Problems'' expanded her connection with [[indie pop]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mason|first1=Stewart|title=Some People Have Real Problems|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/some-people-have-real-problems-mw0000492954|website=AllMusic|accessdate=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201131351/https://www.allmusic.com/album/some-people-have-real-problems-mw0000492954|archive-date=1 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Some People Have Real Problems / Sia| url=https://www.billboard.com/bbcom/content_display/reviews/albums/e3i5d4ee6c1f9636327deaa5402a021aa97| website=Billboard|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080925190851/http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/content_display/reviews/albums/e3i5d4ee6c1f9636327deaa5402a021aa97|archivedate=25 September 2008}}</ref> Sia stated, \"''Colour the Small One'' ... couldn't be more derivative of [[Kings of Convenience]] and [[James Taylor]] and the things that Zero 7 were playing on the [tour] bus. I'm very easily influenced.\"<ref name=\"Rolling Stone\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/sias-reject-opus-songwriter-on-reclaiming-adele-rihannas-unwanted-hits-20151203?page=4|title=Sia on Reclaiming Adele, Rihanna's Unwanted Hits|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=3 December 2015|access-date=11 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170913213312/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/sias-reject-opus-songwriter-on-reclaiming-adele-rihannas-unwanted-hits-20151203?page=4|archive-date=13 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, after leaving Zero 7, Sia dedicated herself entirely to her solo career.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Leahey|first1=Andrew|title=Sia Biography|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/sia-mn0000753742/biography|website=AllMusic|accessdate=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180717014836/https://www.allmusic.com/artist/sia-mn0000753742/biography|archive-date=17 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[We Are Born]]'' (2010), incorporated various pop styles, including [[synthpop]] and [[R&B]], with introspective themes accompanied by more insistent and livelier rhythms.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hoffman|first1=K. Ross|title=Sia: We Are Born|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/we-are-born-mw0001988460|website=AllMusic|accessdate=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180413190530/https://www.allmusic.com/album/we-are-born-mw0001988460|archive-date=13 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> ''1000 Forms of Fear'' (2014) consolidated her connection with pop (with traces of [[electropop]], reggae and hip-hop)<ref>{{cite web |last=Zaleski |first=Marah |url=https://www.avclub.com/review/accidental-pop-songwriter-sia-doesnt-quite-reclaim-206353 |title=Accidental pop songwriter Sia doesn't quite reclaim solo career momentum |work=[[The A.V. Club]] |date=8 July 2014 |accessdate=8 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140712061920/http://www.avclub.com/review/accidental-pop-songwriter-sia-doesnt-quite-reclaim-206353 |archive-date=12 July 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Fares|first1=Heather|title=Sia: 1000 Forms of Fear|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/1000-forms-of-fear-mw0002680594|website=AllMusic|accessdate=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627144311/https://www.allmusic.com/album/1000-forms-of-fear-mw0002680594|archive-date=27 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> ''This Is Acting'' is mostly composed of songs written by Sia with other female pop artists in mind, but the artists did not include the songs on their albums.<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite web | url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/jan/31/sia-this-is-acting-review-favourite-rejects-beyonce-rihanna-adele | title=Sia: This Is Acting review \u2013 mass-appeal pop with a manic edge | work=The Guardian | date=31 January 2016 | accessdate=2 October 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161003154023/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/jan/31/sia-this-is-acting-review-favourite-rejects-beyonce-rihanna-adele | archive-date=3 October 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> Sia described songwriting for others as \"play-acting.\"<ref name=\"Rolling Stone\"/> ''[[The Guardian]]''{{'}}s Kitty Empire commented that the latter album \"provides an obvious counterpoint to Sia's more personal album of 2014, ''1000 Forms of Fear'', whose stonking single, \"Chandelier\", tackled her intoxicated past. ''This Is Acting'' makes plain the fact of manufacture \u2013 a process akin to bespoke tailoring.\"<ref name=\"guardian\"/>\n\n''This Is Acting'' (2016) alternates more reggae and electropop with more introspective themes.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Chau|first1=Thomas|title=Sia Reveals that She Originally Wrote Her Next Single for Adele|url=http://popcrush.com/sia-new-single-alive-adele/|website=Popcrush|accessdate=13 April 2018|date=7 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150909205054/http://popcrush.com/sia-new-single-alive-adele/|archive-date=9 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Phares|first1=Heather|title=Sia: This Is Acting|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/this-is-acting-mw0002894912|website=AllMusic|accessdate=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709011409/https://www.allmusic.com/album/this-is-acting-mw0002894912|archive-date=9 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In her 2016 live performances, Sia's music is part of performance-art-like shows that involve dance and theatrical effects.<ref name=\"Harrington, Jim\"/><ref name=\"seattle times\">{{cite web | url=http://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/music/hitmaker-sia-kicks-off-nostalgia-for-the-present-tour-at-keyarena | title=Hitmaker Sia begins 'Nostalgic for the Present' tour at the Key | work=Seattle Times | date=1 October 2016 | accessdate=1 October 2016 | author=De Barros, Paul | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160925170836/http://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/music/hitmaker-sia-kicks-off-nostalgia-for-the-present-tour-at-keyarena/ | archive-date=25 September 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> For an [[MTV News]] writer \"Sia's throaty, slurred vocals are her norm\",<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2741713/rihanna-adele-and-what-happens-when-female-voices-show-their-pain/ | title=Rihanna, Adele, and What Happens When Female Voices Show Their Pain | work=MTV News | date=18 February 2016 | accessdate=2 October 2016 | author=Cills, Hazel | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161003194908/http://www.mtv.com/news/2741713/rihanna-adele-and-what-happens-when-female-voices-show-their-pain/ | archive-date=3 October 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> while a ''[[The Fader]]'' contributor noted \"In the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 landscape, Sia's songwriting voice, which deals with depression and addiction, is singular\u2014her actual voice even more so.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thefader.com/2016/01/21/sia-voice-this-is-acting-rihanna-beyonce | title=How Sia's Polarising Vocals Have Invaded The Pop Mainstream | work=The Fader | date=21 January 2016 | accessdate=2 October 2016 | author=Cliff, Aimee | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921170921/http://www.thefader.com/2016/01/21/sia-voice-this-is-acting-rihanna-beyonce | archive-date=21 September 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> ''Everyday Is Christmas'' (2017), Sia's first release of [[Christmas music]] is a pop album that gives old-fashioned holiday music \"some 21st century pop gloss\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Phares|first1=Heather|title=Sia: Everyday Is Christmas|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/everyday-is-christmas-mw0003118444|website=AllMusic|accessdate=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180717013042/https://www.allmusic.com/album/everyday-is-christmas-mw0003118444|archive-date=17 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> National Public Radio called Sia \"the 21st century's most resilient songwriter\".<ref>St. Asaph, Katherine. [https://wamu.org/story/18/11/06/sia-is-the-21st-centurys-most-resilient-songwriter \"Sia Is The 21st Century's Most Resilient Songwriter\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181107145333/https://wamu.org/story/18/11/06/sia-is-the-21st-centurys-most-resilient-songwriter/ |date=7 November 2018 }}, NPR, 6 November 2018</ref>\n\nSia has received an array of accolades, including [[ARIA Awards]], an [[MTV Video Music Award]]<ref name=ARIA2014/> and nine nominations for [[Grammy Award]]s.<ref name=GrammyNoms2015/><ref name=GrammyNoms2017/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2012/12/05/grammy-nominees-list/1749735|title=55th annual Grammy Awards nominees|work=[[USA Today]]|accessdate=17 March 2014|date=16 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140314035249/http://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2012/12/05/grammy-nominees-list/1749735/|archive-date=14 March 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>\n{{Cite web |url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/sia |title=GRAMMY Awards Results for Sia |work=Grammy.com |accessdate=28 January 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171117112351/https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/sia |archive-date=17 November 2017 |url-status=live }}\n</ref>\n\n==Other ventures==\nSia lent her voice to the show ''[[South Park]]'' in its [[South Park (season 18)|eighteenth season]]. In episode 3 entitled \"[[The Cissy]]\", she portrayed [[Lorde]] in a parody song in the episode entitled \"Push (Feeling Good on a Wednesday)\". The resemblance was so convincing that many viewers thought Lorde had provided the voice in the song.<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Kaye|first1=Ben|title=''South Park'' releases full version of Lorde spoofing \"Push (Feel Good on a Wednesday)\" \u2013 listen|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2014/10/south-park-releases-full-version-of-lorde-spoofing-push-feel-good-on-a-wednesday-listen/|accessdate=18 September 2015|magazine=Consequence of Sound|date=16 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150927093640/http://consequenceofsound.net/2014/10/south-park-releases-full-version-of-lorde-spoofing-push-feel-good-on-a-wednesday-listen/|archive-date=27 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Sia wrote and recorded \"Angel by the Wings\", the title song for the documentary film ''[[The Eagle Huntress]]'', which premiered in 2016 at the [[Sundance Film Festival]].<ref>Brandle, Lars. [https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6844265/sia-angel-by-the-wings-eagle-huntress \"Sia Records 'Angel by the Wings' for New Film ''The Eagle Huntress'': Exclusive\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161024130827/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6844265/sia-angel-by-the-wings-eagle-huntress |date=24 October 2016 }}, ''Billboard'', 20 January 2016, accessed 4 November 2016</ref><ref>Guerrasio, Jason. [http://www.businessinsider.com/the-eagle-huntress-daisy-ridley-sia-2016-9 \"How a movie about eagle hunting nabbed a ''Star Wars'' lead actor and a chart-topping singer\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161105033025/http://www.businessinsider.com/the-eagle-huntress-daisy-ridley-sia-2016-9 |date=5 November 2016 }}, ''[[Business Insider]]'', 24 September 2016, accessed 4 November 2016</ref> In 2016 Sia covered \"[[Blackbird (Beatles song)|Blackbird]]\" by [[The Beatles]] for the [[Netflix]] original series ''[[Beat Bugs]]''.<ref name=\"blackbirdsia\">{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/sia-pink-beat-bugs-beatles-covers_us_57a0d767e4b0693164c2db69|title=Listen To Sia And Pink Cover The Beatles For Netflix's Adorable 'Beat Bugs'|first=Julia|last=Brucculieri|date=2 August 2016|accessdate=11 March 2017|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312064411/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/sia-pink-beat-bugs-beatles-covers_us_57a0d767e4b0693164c2db69|archive-date=12 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> She appeared in the 2017 animated film ''[[My Little Pony: The Movie (2017 film)|My Little Pony: The Movie]]'' as the voice of \"pop star\" character Songbird Serenade. She also contributed an original song, \"[[Rainbow (Sia song)|Rainbow]]\", to [[My Little Pony: The Movie (soundtrack)|the film's soundtrack]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/comic-con-sia-joins-my-little-pony-movie-1201820722/|title=Sia Joins the Voice Cast of 'My Little Pony: The Movie\u2019|work=Variety|date=22 July 2016|accessdate=22 July 2016|first=Dave|last=McNary|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160723163849/http://variety.com/2016/film/news/comic-con-sia-joins-my-little-pony-movie-1201820722/|archive-date=23 July 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSia wrote a screenplay based on a one-page story that she had written in 2007.<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Anderson|first1=Ariston|title=Venice: Sia Explains Why She's Directing Her Maddie Ziegler Screenplay|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/venice-sia-says-film-starring-820853|accessdate=18 September 2015|magazine=The Hollywood Reporter|date=7 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150911054358/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/venice-sia-says-film-starring-820853|archive-date=11 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Maddie Ziegler]] stars in the project, along with [[Kate Hudson]] and [[Leslie Odom Jr.]]. The musical, titled ''[[Music (upcoming film)|Music]]'', is directed by Sia and is expected to feature a soundtrack performed by her. It is set for release in 2020.<ref>Chikhoune, Ryma. [https://wwd.com/fashion-news/fashion-scoops/kate-hudson-chats-happyxnature-sustainability-and-starring-in-sias-anticipated-film-music-1203400388 \"Kate Hudson Chats HappyxNature, Sustainability and Starring in Sia's Anticipated Film ''Music''\"], WWD, 13 December 2019</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/sia-face-songs-chandelier-maddie-ziegler-712691/|title=How Sia Saved Herself|last=Aron|first=Hillel|date=24 August 2018|website=Rolling Stone|access-date=15 February 2020}}</ref> Sia wrote the songs for the [[Vox Lux (soundtrack)|soundtrack]] to the 2018 musical film ''[[Vox Lux]]'', with a score by [[Scott Walker (singer)|Scott Walker]].<ref name=Barfield>{{cite web| url=https://theplaylist.net/sia-scott-walker-vox-lux-20180821| title=Sia & Scott Walker Providing The Music For Natalie Portman Musical Drama ''Vox Lux''| last=Barfield| first=Charles| date=21 August 2018| accessdate=23 August 2018| work=The Playlist| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823210559/https://theplaylist.net/sia-scott-walker-vox-lux-20180821/| archive-date=23 August 2018| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nFollowing the disbandment of Crisp in 1997, Sia decided to move to London to follow her relationship with boyfriend Dan Pontifex.<ref name=\"FT06072014\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fashiontimes.com/articles/8205/20140607/sia-furlers-mystery-fiance-revealed-singer-songwriter-engaged-american-documentary.htm |title=Sia Furler's Mystery Fiance Revealed! Singer Songwriter Is Engaged to American Documentary Maker Erik Anders Lang |date=7 June 2014 |work=Fashion Times |accessdate=24 November 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151125065234/http://www.fashiontimes.com/articles/8205/20140607/sia-furlers-mystery-fiance-revealed-singer-songwriter-engaged-american-documentary.htm |archivedate=25 November 2015 }}</ref> Several weeks later, while on a stopover in Thailand, she received the news that Pontifex had died after being in a car accident in London.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Dan Pontifex Award \u2013 win a scholarship to Australia|url = http://www.jancisrobinson.com/articles/dan-pontifex-award-win-a-scholarship-to-australia|website = www.jancisrobinson.com|accessdate = 24 November 2015|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151125084342/http://www.jancisrobinson.com/articles/dan-pontifex-award-win-a-scholarship-to-australia|archive-date = 25 November 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> She returned to Australia, but soon she received a call from one of Pontifex's former housemates, who invited her to stay in London.<ref name=\"SMHSia\"/> Her 2001 album ''Healing Is Difficult'' lyrically deals with Pontifex's death: \"I was pretty fucked up after Dan died. I couldn't really feel anything. I could intellectualise a lot of stuff; that I had a purpose, that I was loved, but I couldn't actually feel anything.\" Sia recalled the effect of his death in a 2007 interview for ''[[The Sunday Times]]'': \"We were all devastated, so we got shit-faced on drugs and [[Special Brew]]. Unfortunately, that bender lasted six years for me.\"<ref name=Age>{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/music/sia-reveals-hearbreaking-reason-she-wears-wigs-in-james-cordens-carpool-karaoke-20160218-gmxa3r.html|title=Sia reveals reason she wears wigs in James Corden's Carpool Karaoke|work=The Age|date=18 February 2016|access-date=22 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161231161605/http://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/music/sia-reveals-hearbreaking-reason-she-wears-wigs-in-james-cordens-carpool-karaoke-20160218-gmxa3r.html|archive-date=31 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Verrico\">{{Cite news | url = http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/culture/music/article77556.ece | title = A Woman on the Verge | last1 = Verrico | first1 = Lisa | newspaper = [[The Sunday Times]] | date = 30 December 2007 | accessdate = 7 July 2011 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150114174024/http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/culture/music/article77556.ece | archive-date = 14 January 2015 | url-status=live }}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Sia discussed her sexual orientation in interviews<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kregloe|first1=Karman|title=Sia's Coming Out|url=http://www.afterellen.com/people/29001-sias-coming-out|accessdate=18 January 2015|work=[[AfterEllen.com]]|date=10 February 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150118085457/http://www.afterellen.com/people/29001-sias-coming-out|archive-date=18 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> and revealed her relationship with [[JD Samson]];<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nymag.com/guides/summer/2010/66785/|title=Sia, the Power Balladist Who Wants to Party|last=Murphy|first=Tim|date=20 June 2010|website=NYMag.com|publisher=|access-date=22 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170315072214/http://nymag.com/guides/summer/2010/66785/|archive-date=15 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> they broke up in 2011.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jeffs|first1=Lotte|title=Hit girl Sia ... the singer who writes Rihanna and Jessie J's chart-toppers|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/esmagazine/hit-girl-sia--the-singer-who-writes-rihanna-and-jessie-js-charttoppers-8319507.html|accessdate=18 January 2015|work=[[London Evening Standard]]|date=16 November 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150119020133/http://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/esmagazine/hit-girl-sia--the-singer-who-writes-rihanna-and-jessie-js-charttoppers-8319507.html|archive-date=19 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Sia, J.D. Samson Confirm Split|url=http://www.advocate.com/news/daily-news/2011/06/13/sia-jd-samson-split|accessdate=18 January 2015|work=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]|date=13 June 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150104030344/http://www.advocate.com/news/daily-news/2011/06/13/sia-jd-samson-split|archive-date=4 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> When asked about her sexuality in 2009, she said, \"I've always dated boys and girls and anything in between. I don't care what gender you are, it's about people. ... I've always been... well, flexible is the word I would use.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.samesame.com.au/25/2009/SiaFurler |title=Sia Furler: The Same Same 25, the 25 Most Influential Gay and Lesbian Australians |work=samesame.com.au |year=2009 |accessdate=30 September 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170224055513/http://www.samesame.com.au/25/2009/SiaFurler |archivedate=24 February 2017 }}</ref>\n\nSia has suffered from depression, addictions to painkillers and alcohol, and had contemplated suicide, going as far as to write a suicide note.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Knopper|first1=Steve|title=Sia Furler, the Socially Phobic Pop Star|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/20/magazine/sia-furler-the-socially-phobic-pop-star.html?_r=0|accessdate=18 January 2015|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=18 April 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129165206/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/20/magazine/sia-furler-the-socially-phobic-pop-star.html?_r=0|archive-date=29 November 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2010, Sia cancelled various promotional events and shows due to her poor health.<ref name=\"SiaStop\">{{cite web| url=http://www.siamusic.net/news-blogs/important-sia-announcement|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100628081118/http://www.siamusic.net/news-blogs/important-sia-announcement|title=*** important sia announcement ***|archivedate=28 June 2010|work=siamusic.net}}</ref> She cited extreme lethargy and panic attacks and considered retiring permanently from performing and touring. She stated that she had been diagnosed with [[Graves' disease]]&nbsp;\u2013 an [[autoimmune]] disorder characterized by an over-active [[thyroid]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/music/sia-furler-fame-does-not-become-her-20100617-yjdr.html|title=Sia Furler: Fame does not become her|work=[[The Age]]|first=Andrew|last=Murfett|date=18 June 2010|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150108204138/http://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/music/sia-furler-fame-does-not-become-her-20100617-yjdr.html|archive-date=8 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Later that year, in an ARIA Awards interview, Sia said her health was improving after rest and thyroid hormone replacement therapy.<ref name=\"JJJInterview\">{{cite web| url=http://www.inertia-music.com/2010/10/stream-sia-chats-about-aria-awards-recovery-and-pop-stardom|title=Sia Chats About ARIA Awards|publisher=Inertia Music|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110311001119/http://www.inertia-music.com/2010/10/stream-sia-chats-about-aria-awards-recovery-and-pop-stardom/|archivedate=11 March 2011}}</ref> In 2019, Sia revealed that she suffers from [[Ehlers\u2013Danlos syndromes|Ehlers\u2013Danlos syndrome]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.medpagetoday.com/blogs/celebritydiagnosis/82650?eun=g1256810d0r|title=Pop Star Sia Opens Up About Her Chronic Pain|website=[[MedPage Today]]|last1=Berman|first1=Michele R.|last2=Boguski|first2=Mark S.|date=10 October 2019|accessdate=13 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nSia married documentary filmmaker Erik Anders Lang at her home in [[Palm Springs, California]], in August 2014.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sia Furler gets married in US|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/latest-news/sia-furler-gets-married-in-us/story-fn3dxix6-1227012334021|work=The Australian|date=4 August 2014|access-date=4 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150117154220/http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/latest-news/sia-furler-gets-married-in-us/story-fn3dxix6-1227012334021|archive-date=17 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The couple revealed their separation in December 2016.<ref>Mizoguchi, Karen and Jeff Nelson. [http://people.com/music/sia-separates-from-husband-erik-anders-lang \"Sia Separates from Husband Erik Anders Lang: 'We Are Dedicated to Remaining Friends'\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161209132452/http://people.com/music/sia-separates-from-husband-erik-anders-lang/ |date=9 December 2016 }}, ''People'' magazine, 7 December 2016</ref> During a 2014 appearance on ''[[The Howard Stern Show]]'', Sia was asked if she was religious, to which she responded, \"I believe in a [[Higher Power]] and it's called 'Whatever Dude' and he's a [[queer]], surfing [[Santa Claus|Santa]] that's a bit like my grandpa, so yes.\"<ref name=\"10 Things\">{{cite magazine |first=Greg |last=Moskovitch |url=http://musicfeeds.com.au/news/10-things-we-learned-from-sias-howard-stern-interview/ |title=10 Things We Learned From Sia's Howard Stern Interview |date=19 June 2014 |magazine=[[Music Feeds]] |accessdate=5 June 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150316065608/http://musicfeeds.com.au/news/10-things-we-learned-from-sias-howard-stern-interview/ |archive-date=16 March 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the same interview, she stated that she is a feminist and that Whatever Dude [[Divine inspiration|divinely inspired]] the lyrics she wrote for [[Rihanna]]'s song \"[[Diamonds (Rihanna song)|Diamonds]]\".<ref name=\"10 Things\" /> One of Sia's tattoos, on her hand, reads \"Whatever Dude\".<ref>Jung, E. Alex. [https://www.vulture.com/2014/05/maddie-ziegler-sia-chandelier-video-chat.html \"Maddie Ziegler on Sia\u2019s 'Chandelier' Video, ''Dance Moms'', and Drew Barrymore\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160928041025/http://www.vulture.com/2014/05/maddie-ziegler-sia-chandelier-video-chat.html |date=28 September 2016 }}, [[New York (magazine)|Vulture.com]], 21 May 2014, accessed 23 September 2016</ref> Sia is a cousin of Australian [[Christian rock]] musician [[Peter Furler]].<ref>{{cite web |URL=http://m.sunshinecoastdaily.com.au/news/beyonces-rave-review-aussie-songwriter-sia-furler/2119840/ |title=Beyonce's rave review for Aussie songwriter Sia Furler |date=19 December 2013 |publisher=Australian Regional Media |access-date=16 June 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150618174051/http://m.sunshinecoastdaily.com.au/news/beyonces-rave-review-aussie-songwriter-sia-furler/2119840/ |archive-date=18 June 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, Sia told Gabriella Paiella of ''[[GQ]]'' that she had recently adopted a son and has \"decided to be single for the rest of [her] life.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gq.com/story/diplo-profile-february-2020|title=14 Hours Inside the Relentless, Often-Shirtless World of Diplo|last=Paiella|first=Gabriella|website=GQ|language=en|access-date=2020-01-14}}</ref>\n\n==Activism==\nSia, who is [[vegan]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Sia/status/465781323089473536|title=sia on Twitter: '@HectorRochas I will! I'm fully vegan now!'|author=Sia|date=12 May 2014|work=[[Twitter]]|accessdate=21 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401214128/https://twitter.com/Sia/status/465781323089473536|archive-date=1 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> participated in an advertisement for [[People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals|PETA Asia-Pacific]], with her dog, Pantera, to encourage pet [[neutering]].<ref name=\"Baker\">{{cite web|url=http://blog.petaasiapacific.com/companion-animals/sia-wants-you-to-take-a-bite-out-of-animal-overpopulation |title=Sia Wants You to 'Take a Bite Out of Animal Overpopulation' |publisher=PETA |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100618012250/http://blog.petaasiapacific.com/companion-animals/sia-wants-you-to-take-a-bite-out-of-animal-overpopulation |archivedate=18 June 2010 }}</ref> Sia has also joined other publicly known figures for the \"Oscar's Law\" campaign, in protest against large-scale pet breeding. Other advocates include singers [[Jon Stevens]], [[Paul Dempsey]], [[Rachael Leahcar]] and [[Missy Higgins]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Home|url=http://www.oscarslaw.org/|work=Oscar's law|publisher=Oscar's Law|accessdate=13 October 2012|year=2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121031141139/http://www.oscarslaw.org/|archive-date=31 October 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\nShe is also a supporter of the Beagle Freedom Project, performing \"I'm in Here\" live at the Beagle Freedom Project Gala on 9 September 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=Meet the Hollywood Hounds! |url=http://www.beaglefreedomproject.org/meet_the_hollywood_hound |work=Beagle Freedom Project |publisher=Beagle Freedom Project |accessdate=9 February 2015 |year=2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150209135123/http://www.beaglefreedomproject.org/meet_the_hollywood_hound |archivedate=9 February 2015 }}</ref> For her 2016 [[Nostalgic for the Present Tour]], Sia partnered with various rescue organizations to conduct a dog adoption fair at each of her concerts.<ref>[http://www.peta.org.au/news/sia-dog-adoption-concerts/ \"Sia Sets Up Dog-Adoption Fairs at Her Concerts\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161123201629/http://www.peta.org.au/news/sia-dog-adoption-concerts/ |date=23 November 2016 }}, PETA Australia, 11 October 2016, Retrieved 22 November 2016.</ref> Sia was nominated for a 2016 Libby Award for \"Best Voice for Animals\".<ref>[http://features.peta2.com/libby-awards-2016/#voteRegistrationDiv \"11th Annual Libby Awards\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161123201110/http://features.peta2.com/libby-awards-2016/#voteRegistrationDiv |date=23 November 2016 }}, peta2.com. Retrieved 22 November 2016.</ref> The video for her 2016 single [[The Greatest (Sia song)|\"The Greatest\"]] was a pro-[[LGBT]] tribute to the 49 people killed in the [[Orlando nightclub shooting|Pulse Orlando Shooting]].<ref>Havens, Lyndsey. [https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7496119/sia-the-greatest-video-orlando-nightclub-shooting-tribute-49-dancers \"Sia's 'The Greatest' Video Features 49 Dancers in Tribute to Orlando Shooting Victims\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180901003803/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7496119/sia-the-greatest-video-orlando-nightclub-shooting-tribute-49-dancers |date=1 September 2018 }}, ''Billboard'', 6 September 2016, accessed 24 October 2018</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{main|Sia discography}}\n{{see also|LSD (group)#Discography}}\n* ''OnlySee'' (1997)\n* ''[[Healing Is Difficult]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[Colour the Small One]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Some People Have Real Problems]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[We Are Born]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[1000 Forms of Fear]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[This Is Acting]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Everyday Is Christmas (album)|Everyday Is Christmas]]'' (2017)\n\n==Tours==\n* [[We Meaning You Tour]] (2010\u20132011)\n* [[We Are Born Tour]] (2011)\n* [[Nostalgic for the Present Tour]] (2016\u20132017)\n\n==Filmography==\n{{further|Sia discography}}\n\nSia wrote and/or performed songs on the following film soundtracks:\n{{Div col}}\n* ''[[The Twilight Saga: Eclipse]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[Burlesque (2010 American film)|Burlesque]]'' (2010)\n* [[The Great Gatsby (2013 film)|''The Great Gatsby'']] (2013)\n* ''[[The Hunger Games: Catching Fire]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[Annie (2014 film)|Annie]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[Transparent (TV series)|Transparent]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[Racing Extinction]]'' (2015)\n* [[Fifty Shades of Grey (film)|''Fifty Shades of Grey'']] (2015)\n* ''[[Pitch Perfect 2]]'' (2015)\n* [[San Andreas (film)|''San Andreas'']] (2015)\n* ''[[Beat Bugs]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[The Eagle Huntress]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Zootopia]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Finding Dory]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[The Neon Demon]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Star Trek Beyond]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Lion (2016 film)|Lion]]'' (2016)<ref name=\"Spanos2\" />\n* ''[[Fifty Shades Darker (film)|Fifty Shades Darker]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Wonder Woman (2017 film)|Wonder Woman]]'' (2017)<ref name=\"Spanos2\" />\n* [[My Little Pony: The Movie (2017 film)|''My Little Pony: The Movie'']] (2017)\n* ''[[Fifty Shades Freed (film)|Fifty Shades Freed]]'' (2018)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Sia/status/950424054091173888|title=The final chapter is coming & Sia's song 'Deer In Headlights' is on the #FiftyShadesFreed soundtrack, out February 9th! Pre-order the album this Friday. - Team Siapic.twitter.com/enXPnFLNR4|last=sia|first=|date=8 January 2018|website=@Sia|language=en|accessdate=10 January 2018}}</ref>\n* ''[[A Wrinkle in Time (2018 film)|A Wrinkle in Time]]'' (2018)<ref>{{cite news|last=Snetiker|first=Marc|title=A Wrinkle in Time soundtrack taps Sade, Sia, Game of Thrones composer|url=https://ew.com/movies/2018/02/20/a-wrinkle-in-time-soundtrack-sade-game-of-thrones-composer/|accessdate=20 February 2018|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=20 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180220220436/http://ew.com/movies/2018/02/20/a-wrinkle-in-time-soundtrack-sade-game-of-thrones-composer/|archive-date=20 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* ''[[Charming (film)|Charming]]'' (2018)\n* ''[[Dumplin' (film)|Dumplin']]'' (2018)\n* ''[[Vox Lux]]'' (2018)<ref name=Barfield/>\n* ''[[Dolittle (film)|Dolittle]]'' (2020)\n{{Div col end}}\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" |Notes\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[Piccadilly Jim (2004 film)|Piccadilly Jim]]''\n| New York Bar Singer\n| [[Cameo appearance|Cameo]]\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Annie (2014 film)|Annie]]'' \n| Animal Care & Control Volunteer\n| Cameo\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[My Little Pony: The Movie (2017 film)|My Little Pony: The Movie]]'' \n| [[List of My Little Pony: Friendship is Magic characters#Canterlot characters|Songbird Serenade]]\n| [[Voice acting|Voice]]\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Peter Rabbit (film)|Peter Rabbit]]''\n| [[The Tale of Mrs. Tiggy-Winkle|Mrs. Tiggy-Winkle]]\n| Voice\n|-\n|2018\n| ''[[Dominion (documentary)|Dominion]]''\n| Narrator\n| [[Documentary film|Documentary]]\n|-\n|2018\n| ''[[Charming (film)|Charming]]'' \n| Half-Oracle\n| Voice\n|-\n| 2021\n|''[[Peter Rabbit 2: The Runaway]]''\n| Mrs. Tiggy-Winkle\n| Voice\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" |Notes\n|-\n| 1997\n| ''[[Home and Away]]''\n| Herself\n| Cameo<ref>Bond, Nick. [https://www.news.com.au/entertainment/tv/chandelier-singer-sia-furler-was-a-home-and-away-wedding-singer/news-story/e117d8aa40e68c1a3d6d4c496abddd78 \"Chandelier singer Sia Furler was a ''Home and Away'' wedding singer\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180617101455/https://www.news.com.au/entertainment/tv/chandelier-singer-sia-furler-was-a-home-and-away-wedding-singer/news-story/e117d8aa40e68c1a3d6d4c496abddd78 |date=17 June 2018 }}, News.com, 3 June 2014, accessed 17 June 2018</ref>\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[South Park]]''\n| [[Lorde]] (singing voice)\n| Season 18; Episode 3: \"[[The Cissy]]\"\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Transparent (TV series)|Transparent]]''\n| Puppet\n| Season 2; Episode 9: \"Man on the Land\"\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[Nobodies (TV series)|Nobodies]]''\n| Herself\n| Season 2; Episode 9: \"Rob in the Hood\"\n|-\n| 2019\n|''[[Seven Worlds, One Planet]]''\n| Herself\n|\"Out there\" ft. [[Hans Zimmer]]\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[Scooby-Doo and Guess Who?]]''\n| Herself\n|Season 1; Episode 11: \"Now You Sia, Now You Don't!\"\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Music|Australia}}\n* [[List of artists who reached number one in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q181484|n=no|b=no|v=no|voy=no|m=no|mw=no|wikt=no|s=no|c=category:Sia (musician)|display=Sia}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{IMDb name|2397981}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|before = [[One Direction]]|title = ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' [[list of Saturday Night Live guests|musical guest]]|years = 17 January 2015|after = [[Blake Shelton]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Sia (musician)|state=expanded}}\n{{Sia singles}}\n{{Zero 7}}\n{{LSD (group)}}\n{{ARIA Award for Album of the Year}}\n{{ARIA Award for Best Female Artist}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sia}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Acid jazz musicians]]\n[[Category:APRA Award winners]]\n[[Category:ARIA Award winners]]\n[[Category:Australian dance musicians]]\n[[Category:Australian female pop singers]]\n[[Category:Australian feminists]]\n[[Category:Australian indie pop musicians]]\n[[Category:Australian multi-instrumentalists]]\n[[Category:Australian expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:Australian people of English descent]]\n[[Category:Australian women in electronic music]]\n[[Category:Bisexual feminists]]\n[[Category:Bisexual musicians]]\n[[Category:Bisexual women]]\n[[Category:Female music video directors]]\n[[Category:Feminist musicians]]\n[[Category:LGBT musicians from Australia]]\n[[Category:LGBT singers]]\n[[Category:LGBT songwriters]]\n[[Category:People from Melbourne]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Adelaide]]\n[[Category:Sia (musician)| ]]\n[[Category:Trip hop musicians]]\n[[Category:LSD (group) members]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century women singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century women singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the musician|other uses|Sia (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|Australian singer and songwriter}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}} \n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name            = Sia<!--DO NOT CHANGE THIS WITHOUT FURTHER DISCUSSION-->\n| image           = Sia Seattle (cropped).jpg\n| caption         = Sia performing in Seattle, Washington in August 2011\n| birth_name      = Sia Kate Isobelle Furler\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1975|12|18}}\n| birth_place     = [[Adelaide]], [[South Australia]], Australia\n| occupation      = {{hlist|Singer|songwriter|voice actress|music video director}}\n| years_active    = 1990\u2013present\n| signature       = File:Sia Furler signature.svg\n| module          = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background      = solo_singer\n| genre           = {{hlist|[[Pop music|Pop]]|[[electropop]]|[[indie pop]]|[[acid jazz]]}}\n| label           = {{hlist|[[Dance Pool]]|[[Go! Discs|Go! Beat]]|Inertia|[[RCA Records|RCA]]|Monkey Puzzle|[[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]}}\n| associated_acts = {{hlist|[[Zero 7]]|[[LSD (group)|LSD]]|[[Maddie Ziegler]]}}\n| website         = {{URL|siamusic.net}}\n}}\n}}\n'''Sia Kate Isobelle Furler''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|s|i\u02d0|\u0259|}} {{respell|SEE|\u0259}}; born 18 December 1975) is an Australian singer, songwriter, voice actress and music video director.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/us-music-charts-sia-idUKKBN0FL2SM20140716 |title=Singer-songwriter Sia snags first No. 1 on U.S. Billboard chart |date=16 July 2014 |work=Reuters |access-date=26 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170927155837/http://uk.reuters.com/article/us-music-charts-sia-idUKKBN0FL2SM20140716 |archive-date=27 September 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> She started her career as a singer in the [[acid jazz]] band Crisp in the mid-1990s in [[Adelaide]]. In 1997, when Crisp disbanded, she released her debut [[studio album]] titled ''OnlySee'' in Australia. She moved to London, England, and provided lead vocals for the British duo [[Zero 7]]. In 2000, Sia released her second studio album, ''[[Healing Is Difficult]]'', and her third studio album, ''[[Colour the Small One]]'', in 2004, but all of these struggled to connect with a mainstream audience.\n\nSia relocated to New York City in 2005 and toured in the United States. Her fourth and fifth studio albums, ''[[Some People Have Real Problems]]'' and ''[[We Are Born]]'', were released in 2008 and 2010, respectively. Each was certified gold by the [[Australian Recording Industry Association]] and attracted wider notice than her earlier albums. Uncomfortable with her growing fame, Sia took a hiatus from performing, during which she focused on songwriting for other artists, producing successful collaborations \"[[Titanium (song)|Titanium]]\" (with [[David Guetta]]), \"[[Diamonds (Rihanna song)|Diamonds]]\" (with [[Rihanna]]) and \"[[Wild Ones (song)|Wild Ones]]\" (with [[Flo Rida]]).\n\nIn 2014, Sia broke through as a solo recording artist when her sixth studio album, ''[[1000 Forms of Fear]]'', debuted at No 1 in the U.S. [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and generated the top-ten single \"[[Chandelier (song)|Chandelier]]\" and a trilogy of music videos starring child dancer [[Maddie Ziegler]]. Since then, Sia has usually worn a wig that obscures her face to protect her privacy.<ref name=Age/> Her seventh studio album ''[[This Is Acting]]'' (2016), spawned her first [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] number one single, \"[[Cheap Thrills (song)|Cheap Thrills]]\". The same year, Sia gave her [[Nostalgic for the Present Tour]], which incorporated dancing by Ziegler and others and other performance art elements. Her eighth studio album, ''[[Everyday Is Christmas (album)|Everyday Is Christmas]]'', was released in 2017 and [[reissue]]d in 2018 with three bonus tracks. In 2018 and 2019 she collaborated with [[Labrinth]] and [[Diplo]] in the group [[LSD (group)|LSD]], and they released their [[LSD (album)|self-titled debut album]] in April 2019. Among the [[List of awards and nominations received by Sia|accolades]] received by Sia are nearly a dozen [[ARIA Awards]], 9 [[Grammy Award]] nominations, and an [[MTV Video Music Award]].<ref name=ARIA2014>{{cite web| url=http://www.fasterlouder.com.au/news/40788/Chet-Faker-and-Violent-Soho-lead-20sheeran14-ARIA-nominations|title=Chet Faker and Violent Soholead 2014 ARIA nominations|publisher=fasterlouder|accessdate=5 November 2014}}{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\n===1975\u20131997: Early life and career beginnings===\nSia Kate Isobelle Furler was born on 18 December 1975 in [[Adelaide]], South Australia. Her father, Phil Colson, is a musician, and her mother, Loene Furler, is an art lecturer.<ref name=\"Harry\"/> Sia is the niece of actor-singer [[Kevin Colson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/theatre/kevin-colson-confesses-all-of-his-career-in-starry-firmament-20140926-10meub.html|title=Kevin Colson confesses all of his career in starry firmament|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|last=Craven|first=Peter|date=26 September 2014|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924162821/http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/theatre/kevin-colson-confesses-all-of-his-career-in-starry-firmament-20140926-10meub.html|archive-date=24 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Sia said that as a child she imitated the performing style of [[Aretha Franklin]], [[Stevie Wonder]] and [[Sting (musician)|Sting]], whom she cites as early influences.<ref name=\"NPR\">{{cite interview|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=19075503|title=Sia Learns to Sound Like Herself|first=Alex|last=Cohen|authorlink=Alex Cohen|publisher=[[NPR Music]]|date=15 February 2008|access-date=28 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228100728/https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=19075503|archive-date=28 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> She attended [[Adelaide High School]].<ref name=\"Harry\">{{cite journal|url=http://www.mjmharry.com/docs/Sia-Furler.pdf| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101105010101/http://www.mjmharry.com/docs/Sia-Furler.pdf|title=Sia Sensation|first=Michael|last=Harry|journal=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Adelaide Advertiser]]|pages=24\u201326|format=PDF|archivedate=5 November 2010}}</ref> In the mid-1990s, Sia started a career as a singer in the local [[acid jazz]] band Crisp.<ref name=\"Harry\"/> Sia collaborated with the band and contributed vocals to their album ''Word and the Deal'' (1995) and EP ''Delirium'' (1997).<ref>''Word and the Deal'' and ''Delirium'':\n\n* {{cite web|url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/15875159?selectedversion=NBD12798813|title=Word and the deal / Crisp. [sound recording]|publisher=[[National Library of Australia]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150114223832/http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/15875159?selectedversion=NBD12798813|archivedate=14 January 2015|url-status=dead}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/24518036?q&versionId=29594043|title=Delirium / Crisp. [sound recording]|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=National Library of Australia|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150115020959/http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/24518036?q&versionId=29594043|archivedate=15 January 2015|url-status=dead|access-date=}}</ref>\nIn 1997 Crisp disbanded,<ref name=\"SMHSia\">{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/sia-furler-fame-does-not-become-her-20100617-yjdr.html|title=Sia Furler: Fame does not become her|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|first=Andrew|date=18 June 2010|last=Murfett|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150212030150/http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/sia-furler-fame-does-not-become-her-20100617-yjdr.html|archive-date=12 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> and Sia released her debut [[studio album]], ''OnlySee'', on Flavoured Records, in Australia, on 23 December.<ref name=\"nloa\">{{cite web| url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/7556295?selectedversion=NBD13682423|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131225133718/http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/7556295?selectedversion=NBD13682423| title=Onlysee / Sia Furler. [sound recording]|publisher=National Library of Australia|archivedate=25 December 2013}}</ref> The album sold about 1,200 copies.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Leon |title=Sia's first album onlysee |url=http://boyprincess.com/why-it-bothers-people-that-sia-hides-her-face/d13b98750d6a-original/ |website=Boy Princess |accessdate=28 August 2015 |date=1 March 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160106063531/http://boyprincess.com/why-it-bothers-people-that-sia-hides-her-face/d13b98750d6a-original/ |archivedate=6 January 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title=Sia| url=http://www.discogs.com/artist/21991-Sia| website=Discogs| accessdate=28 August 2015| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150927082613/http://www.discogs.com/artist/21991-Sia| archive-date=27 September 2015| url-status=live}}</ref> Unlike her later albums, ''OnlySee'' was marketed under her full name, \"Sia Furler\". It was produced by Jesse Flavell.<ref>[https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/7556295?selectedversion=NBD13682423 \"Onlysee (sound recording) / Sia Furler\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180108233421/https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/7556295?selectedversion=NBD13682423 |date=8 January 2018 }}, Flavoured Records, 1997, Trove.nla.gov.au, accessed 8 January 2018</ref>\n\n===1997\u20132006: Zero 7, ''Healing Is Difficult'' and ''Colour the Small One''===\n[[File:Sia Furler in concert.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Sia in concert in 2006]]\nAfter Crisp disbanded in 1997, Sia moved to London,<ref name=\"SMHSia\"/> where she performed as a background vocalist for British band [[Jamiroquai]].<ref name=AllMusic>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/sia-mn0000753742/biography |title=Sia Biography |website=[[AllMusic]] |first=Andrew |last=Leahey |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150211225955/http://www.allmusic.com/artist/sia-mn0000753742/biography |archivedate=11 February 2015 |url-status=dead}}</ref> She also provided lead vocals for English downtempo group [[Zero 7]] on their first three studio albums and toured with the group.<ref name=\"Verrico\"/> On Zero 7's 2001 album ''[[Simple Things (Zero 7 album)|Simple Things]]'', Sia contributed vocals to two tracks<ref name=allmusicsimple>{{cite web|title=Simple Things \u2013 Zero 7|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/simple-things-mw0000017246|website=AllMusic|accessdate=19 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131201122541/http://www.allmusic.com/album/simple-things-mw0000017246|archive-date=1 December 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> including the single  \"[[Destiny (Zero 7 song)|Destiny]]\", which peaked at No. 30 on the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref name=\"SiaUK\">{{cite web|url=http://officialcharts.com|title=Sia: Artist|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150217061412/http://www.officialcharts.com/|archive-date=17 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2004, she provided vocals for Zero 7 on \"Somersault\" and \"Speed Dial No. 2\" (from the album ''[[When It Falls]]'').<ref name=allmusicwhen>{{cite web|last1=Bush|first1=John|title=When It Falls \u2013 Zero 7|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/when-it-falls-mw0000328826|website=AllMusic|accessdate=19 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121205013320/http://www.allmusic.com/album/when-it-falls-mw0000328826|archive-date=5 December 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2006, Sia again collaborated with Zero 7 for the group's third album, ''[[The Garden (Zero 7 album)|The Garden]]'' and hence she is regarded as the \"unofficial\" lead singer of Zero 7.<ref name=allmusicgarden>{{cite web|last1=Brown|first1=Marisa|title=The Garden \u2013 Zero 7|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/the-garden-mw0000542394|website=AllMusic|accessdate=19 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150326054553/http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-garden-mw0000542394|archive-date=26 March 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"BB09\">{{cite journal |last=Mason |first=Kerri |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EX4yD1pJCxUC&pg=PA56 |title=Albums: Zero 7 \u2013 Yeah Ghost |page=56 |journal=Billboard |date=3 October 2009 |volume=121 |number=39 |access-date=21 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160404070213/https://books.google.com/books?id=EX4yD1pJCxUC&pg=PA56 |archive-date=4 April 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, Sia signed a recording contract with [[Sony Music]]'s sub-label [[Dance Pool]] and released her first [[single (music)|single]], \"[[Taken for Granted]]\", which peaked at No. 10 on the UK Singles Chart.<ref name=AllMusic/> In 2001, she released her second solo album, ''[[Healing Is Difficult]]'', which blends retro [[jazz]] and [[soul music|soul]] music and lyrically discusses Sia's dealing with the death of her first love affair.<ref name=\"SMHSia\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/healing-is-difficult-mw0000464188|title=Healing Is Difficult \u2013 Sia|website=AllMusic|first=Jon|last=O'Brien|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150208212645/http://www.allmusic.com/album/healing-is-difficult-mw0000464188|archive-date=8 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Displeased with the promotion of the album, Sia fired her manager, left Sony Music and signed with [[Go! Beat Records|Go! Beat]], a subsidiary of [[Universal Music Group]] (UMG).<ref name=\"Verrico\"/> At the [[APRA Awards of 2002]], Sia won the Breakthrough Songwriter category alongside Brisbane pop duo [[Aneiki]]'s Jennifer Waite and Grant Wallis.<ref name=\"APRAWin2002\">{{cite web | url = http://www.apra-amcos.com.au/APRAAwards/MusicAwards/History/2002Winners.aspx |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110308004321/http://www.apra-amcos.com.au/APRAAwards/MusicAwards/History/2002Winners.aspx| title = 2002 Winners \u2013 APRA Music Awards | publisher = [[Australasian Performing Right Association]] | archivedate=8 March 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, Sia released her third studio album, ''[[Colour the Small One]]''.<ref name=\"Ott\">{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/7735-colour-the-small-one/ |title=Sia \u2013 Colour the Small One |last1=Ott |first1=Chris |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=2 March 2004 |accessdate=9 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150816072120/http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/7735-colour-the-small-one/ |archivedate=16 August 2015 }}</ref> The album employs a mixture of [[acoustic music|acoustic instruments]] and [[electronic music|electronic]] backing to her material.<ref name=\"Ott\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2004/jan/02/popandrock.shopping|title=CD: Sia, Colour the Small One|work=[[The Guardian]]|first=Caroline|last=Sullivan|date=2 January 2004|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150216150842/http://www.theguardian.com/music/2004/jan/02/popandrock.shopping|archive-date=16 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The album spawned four singles, including \"[[Don't Bring Me Down (Sia song)|Don't Bring Me Down]]\" and \"[[Breathe Me]]\", the latter of which charted in the United Kingdom,<ref name=\"SiaUK\"/> Denmark and France.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.danishcharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=Breathe+Me&cat=s|title=Breathe Me \u2013 Sia|publisher=[[Tracklisten]]|language=Danish|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150131134906/http://www.danishcharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=Breathe+Me&cat=s|archive-date=31 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDissatisfied with ''Colour the Small One''{{'}}s poor marketing and the album's struggle to connect with a mainstream audience, Sia relocated to New York City in 2005.<ref name=\"SMHSia\"/> During that time, \"Breathe Me\" appeared in the final scene of the U.S. [[HBO]] television series ''[[Six Feet Under (TV series)|Six Feet Under]]'', which helped increase Sia's fame in the United States. Consequently, Sia's manager, David Enthoven, set up a tour across the country to maintain her career.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/20/magazine/sia-furler-the-socially-phobic-pop-star.html?_r=1|title=Sia Furler, the Socially Phobic Pop Star|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=20 April 2014|first=Steve|last=Knopper|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150214121101/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/20/magazine/sia-furler-the-socially-phobic-pop-star.html?_r=1|archive-date=14 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===2007\u20132010: ''Some People Have Real Problems'' and ''We Are Born''===\n[[File:Sia performing photograph by Kris Krug.jpg|thumb|right|Sia performing at [[South by Southwest]] in 2008]]\nIn 2007, Sia released a [[live album]] titled ''[[Lady Croissant]]'', which included eight live songs from her April 2006 performance at the [[Bowery Ballroom]] in New York and one new studio recording\u2014\"Pictures\".<ref name=\"Brown\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/lady-croissant-mw0000557699|title=Sia \u2013 Lady Croissant|website=AllMusic|first=Marisa|last=Brown|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160829134946/http://www.allmusic.com/album/lady-croissant-mw0000557699|archive-date=29 August 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> A year later, she left Zero 7 on friendly terms, replaced by [[ESKA|Eska Mtungwazi]] as the band's frontwoman.<ref name=\"BB09\"/> Sia released her fourth studio album, ''[[Some People Have Real Problems]]'' on 8 January 2008. The album peaked at No. 41 in Australia and was [[List of music recording certifications|certified gold]] by the [[Australian Recording Industry Association]].<ref name=\"Australia\">Australian chart position and certification:\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.australian-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Sia |title=Discography Sia |publisher=ARIA Charts |accessdate=16 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150227104853/http://www.australian-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Sia |archivedate=27 February 2015}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.aria.com.au/pages/httpwww.aria.com.aupageshttpwww.aria.com.aupageshttpwww.aria.com.aualbumaccreds2011.htm |title=Accreditations \u2013 2011 Albums |publisher=Australian Recording Industry Association |accessdate=16 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/64wvlBwg5?url=http://www.aria.com.au/pages/httpwww.aria.com.aupageshttpwww.aria.com.aupageshttpwww.aria.com.auALBUMaccreds2011.htm |archivedate=25 January 2012}}</ref>\nIt charted at No. 26 on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], becoming Sia's first album to chart in the United States.<ref name=\"BB200\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/279248/sia/chart?f=305|title=Sia \u2013 Chart history: Billboard 200|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141214082755/http://www.billboard.com/artist/279248/Sia/chart?f=305|archive-date=14 December 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Some People Have Real Problems'' yielded four singles, including \"[[The Girl You Lost to Cocaine]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nl-be.7digital.com/artist/sia/release/the-girl-you-lost-to-cocaine-3/|title=The Girl You Lost To Cocaine|publisher=[[7digital]]|location=Belgium|language=Dutch|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150110073119/https://nl-be.7digital.com/artist/sia/release/the-girl-you-lost-to-cocaine-3/|archivedate=10 January 2015}}</ref> It peaked at No. 11 in the Netherlands and No. 12 in Spain;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=The+Girl+You+Lost+To+Cocaine&cat=s|title=Sia \u2013 The Girl You Lost to Cocaine|publisher=[[Single Top 100]]|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150113023803/http://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=The+Girl+You+Lost+To+Cocaine&cat=s|archive-date=13 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> it additionally reached No. 8 on the US [[Hot Dance Club Songs]].<ref name=\"DanceClubSongs\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/279248/sia/chart?f=359|title=Sia \u2013 Chart history: Dance Club Songs|work=Billboard|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150620102739/http://www.billboard.com/artist/279248/Sia/chart?f=359|archive-date=20 June 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Another single from the album was \"[[Soon We'll Be Found]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/soon-well-be-found-single/id705846139 |title=iTunes \u2013 Music \u2013 Soon We'll Be Found |publisher=iTunes Store |location=United Kingdom |archivedate=24 February 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150224202640/https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/soon-well-be-found-single/id705846139 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2009, Sia released ''[[TV Is My Parent]]'' on [[DVD]], which includes a live concert at New York's Hiro Ballroom, four music videos and behind-the-scene footage.<ref name=\"MusicNews\">{{cite web|url=http://www.musicnewsnet.com/2009/03/tv-is-my-parent-new-dvd-from-sia.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006160804/http://www.musicnewsnet.com/2009/03/tv-is-my-parent-new-dvd-from-sia.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=6 October 2011|title=TV is My Parent, New DVD from Sia|publisher=Music News Net|date=9 March 2009}}</ref> At the [[ARIA Music Awards of 2009]], Sia won the Best Music DVD category for ''TV Is My Parent''.<ref name=\"ARIAAward2009\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ariaawards.com.au/history-by-year.php?year=2009 |title=ARIA Awards History|publisher=ARIA Awards|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100128034837/http://www.ariaawards.com.au/history-by-year.php|archivedate=28 January 2010}}</ref> She also received a nomination for Best Breakthrough Artist Album for ''Some People Have Real Problems''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Parker |first=Tappan |url=http://dailycollegian.com/2010/05/03/sia-brings-song-to-pearl-street/ |title=Sia brings song to Pearl Street |work=[[The Massachusetts Daily Collegian]] |date=3 May 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141205015846/http://dailycollegian.com/2010/05/03/sia-brings-song-to-pearl-street/ |archivedate=5 December 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, American singer [[Christina Aguilera]] approached Sia about writing [[ballad]]s for Aguilera's then-upcoming sixth studio album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/now-you-sia/story-e6frf7jo-1111119107653|title=Sia Furler is enjoying attentions of Christina Aguilera|work=[[Herald Sun]]|first=Cameron|last=Adams|date=12 March 2009|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130907143511/http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/now-you-sia/story-e6frf7jo-1111119107653|archive-date=7 September 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> The final product, ''[[Bionic (Christina Aguilera album)|Bionic]]'', includes three songs co-written by Sia.<ref>{{cite AV media notes|title=[[Bionic (Christina Aguilera album)|Bionic]]|others=[[Christina Aguilera]]|year=2010|type=liner notes|publisher=[[RCA Records]], a division of [[Sony Music Entertainment]]}}</ref> Later in 2010, Sia also co-wrote \"Bound to You\" for [[Burlesque: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|the soundtrack]] of the American film ''[[Burlesque (2010 American film)|Burlesque]]'', which starred Aguilera and American singer [[Cher]].<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120112044802/http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/content_display/magazine/reviews/albums/e3ibde532c77149bc3146237ecd8761e87d|url=http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/content_display/magazine/reviews/albums/e3ibde532c77149bc3146237ecd8761e87d|title=Burlesque: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|work=Billboard|first=Kerri|last=Mason|date=11 December 2010|archivedate=12 January 2012}}</ref> The song was nominated for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]] at the [[68th Golden Globe Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/ipad/jackie-weaver-nicole-kidman-geoffrey-rush-and-toni-collette-nominated-in-68th-golden-globe-awards/story-fn6bqphm-1225971265572|title=Jackie Weaver, Nicole Kidman, Geoffrey Rush and Toni Collette nominated in 68th Golden Globe Awards|work=The Adelaide Advertiser|date=15 December 2010|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120903005627/http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/ipad/jackie-weaver-nicole-kidman-geoffrey-rush-and-toni-collette-nominated-in-68th-golden-globe-awards/story-fn6bqphm-1225971265572|archive-date=3 September 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> In May 2011, Sia appeared on the [[The Voice (American season 1)|inaugural season]] of the U.S. version of ''[[The Voice (American TV series)|The Voice]]'' as an adviser for Aguilera, who served as a vocal coach and judge.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/music_blog/2011/04/nbcs-the-voice-enlists-monica-reba-mcentire-sia-and-adam-blackstone-as-advisors.html|title=NBC's 'The Voice' enlists Monica, Reba McEntire, Sia and Adam Blackstone as advisors|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141104234733/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/music_blog/2011/04/nbcs-the-voice-enlists-monica-reba-mcentire-sia-and-adam-blackstone-as-advisors.html|date=29 April 2011|archivedate=4 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2010, Sia released her fifth studio album, ''[[We Are Born]]''.<ref name=\"SiaWeAreBorn\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B003SP3WM2|title=We Are Born by Sia|publisher=Amazon.co.uk|accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref> The release peaked at No. 2 on the [[ARIA Charts|ARIA Albums Chart]] and was certified gold by the Australian Recording Industry Association.<ref name=\"Australia\"/> The release of the album was preceded by three singles: the lead single, \"[[You've Changed (Sia song)|You've Changed]]\", was released in December 2009 and charted at No. 31 in Australia.<ref>\"You've Changed\" single release and chart position:\n*{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/nz/album/youve-changed-single/id348315733 |title=iTunes \u2013 Music \u2013 You've Changed |publisher=iTunes Store |location=New Zealand |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6WPE28MJO?url=https://itunes.apple.com/nz/album/youve-changed-single/id348315733 |archivedate=17 February 2015 |url-status=dead }}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=You%27ve+Changed&cat=s |title=You've Changed \u2013 Sia |publisher=ARIA Charts |accessdate=17 February 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150201235222/http://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=You%27ve+Changed&cat=s |archive-date=1 February 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> The follow-up single, \"[[Clap Your Hands (Sia song)|Clap Your Hands]]\", peaked at No. 17 in Australia, No. 10 in the Netherlands and No. 27 in Switzerland.<ref>\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.bandit.fm/album/2688296?cc=AU|title=Clap Your Hands: Sia|publisher=bandit.fm|accessdate=17 February 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150217121806/http://www.bandit.fm/album/2688296?cc=AU|archivedate=17 February 2015}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=Clap+Your+Hands&cat=s|title=Sia \u2013 Clap Your Hands|publisher=[[Single Top 100]]|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150321054914/http://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=Clap+Your+Hands&cat=s|archive-date=21 March 2015|url-status=live}}\n</ref> At the [[ARIA Music Awards of 2010]], ''We Are Born'' earned Sia two categories won: Best Independent Release and Best Pop Release.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ariaawards.com.au/history/year/2010|title=ARIA Awards History: 2010|publisher=ARIA Awards|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140228203958/http://www.ariaawards.com.au/history/year/2010|archivedate=28 February 2014}}</ref> Meanwhile, at the 2011 [[APRA Awards (Australia)|APRA Music Awards]], Sia received a nomination for Song of the Year for \"Clap Your Hands\".<ref name=\"Collins\">{{Cite news | url = http://au.news.yahoo.com/thewest/entertainment/a/-/music/9653365/the-man-behind-the-songs/ | title = The Man Behind the Songs | last1 = Collins | first1 = Simon | work = [[The West Australian]]| date = 16 June 2011 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120928111952/http://au.news.yahoo.com/thewest/entertainment/a/-/music/9653365/the-man-behind-the-songs/|archivedate=28 September 2012 }}</ref> To promote ''We Are Born'', Sia embarked on the [[We Meaning You Tour]], which visited North America and Europe in April\u2013May 2010.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2010/02/sia-announces-the-we-meaning-you-tour-dates|title=Sia Announces 'The We Meaning You Tour' Dates|magazine=[[Consequence of Sound]]|date=3 February 2010|first=Derek|last=Staples|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140831234421/http://consequenceofsound.net/2010/02/sia-announces-the-we-meaning-you-tour-dates/|archivedate=31 August 2014}}</ref> She followed this with the [[We Are Born Tour]], which visited Australia in February 2011 and North America in July\u2013August 2011.<ref>We Are Born Tour:\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.theaureview.com/the-goss/sia-announces-february-2011-australian-tour |title=Sia announces February 2011 Australian Tour |publisher=The AU Review |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140816133240/http://www.theaureview.com/the-goss/sia-announces-february-2011-australian-tour |archivedate=16 August 2014 |url-status=dead }}\n*{{cite web|url=http://siamusic.net/tour |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715020744/http://siamusic.net/tour |title=Tour: Sia |publisher=Sia Music |archivedate=15 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In March 2012, Sia released the greatest hits album ''[[Best Of... (Sia album)|Best Of...]]'' in Australia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.creammagazine.com/2012/03/hello-to-the-first-greatest-hits-set-from-sia/|title=Say hi to Sia's first greatest hits set|work=Cream|date=10 March 2012|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150217132010/http://www.creammagazine.com/2012/03/hello-to-the-first-greatest-hits-set-from-sia/|archive-date=17 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===2010\u20132013: Songwriting career and mainstream recognition===\n[[File:Sia (5423995397) (Cropped).jpg.png|thumb|upright|right|Sia performing in 2011]]\nFollowing the success of ''We Are Born'', Sia became uncomfortable with her growing fame. She later told ''[[The New York Times]]'': \"I just wanted to have a private life. Once, as my friend was telling me they had cancer, someone came up and asked, in the middle of the conversation, if they could take a photograph with me. You get me? That's enough, right?\"<ref name=Knopper>Knopper, Steve. [https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/20/magazine/sia-furler-the-socially-phobic-pop-star.html \"Sia Furler, the Socially Phobic Pop Star\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170413151146/https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/20/magazine/sia-furler-the-socially-phobic-pop-star.html |date=13 April 2017 }}, ''The New York Times'', 18 April 2014, accessed 26 October 2016</ref> She refused to do promos for her tours, began to wear a mask on stage and became increasingly dependent on drugs and alcohol on the road; she considered suicide.<ref name=\"Knopper\" /> Sia fired Enthoven and hired Jonathan Daniel, who suggested that she write songs for other artists.<ref name=Knopper/>\n\nSia retired as a recording artist and began a career as a songwriter. She soon penned \"[[Titanium (song)|Titanium]]\" for American singer [[Alicia Keys]], but it was later sent to [[David Guetta]], who included Sia's original [[demo (music)|demo]] vocals on the song and released it as a single in 2011.<ref name=\"NPRMusic\"/> \"Titanium\" peaked within the top ten of record charts in the United States, Australia and numerous European regions.<ref>\nChart positions for \"Titanium\":\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=David+Guetta+feat.+Sia&titel=Titanium&cat=s|title=David Guetta feat. Sia \u2013 Titanium|publisher=ARIA Charts|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150201233616/http://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=David+Guetta+feat%2E+Sia&titel=Titanium&cat=s|archive-date=1 February 2015|url-status=live}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/300445/David+Guetta/chart?f=379|title=David Guetta \u2013 Chart history: Hot 100|work=Billboard|accessdate=18 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150614031257/http://www.billboard.com/artist/300445/David+Guetta/chart?f=379|archive-date=14 June 2015|url-status=live}}\n</ref> However, Sia was not pleased with the success of the single: \"[...] I never even knew it was gonna happen, and I was really upset. Because I had just retired, I was trying to be a pop songwriter, not an artist.\"<ref name=\"NPRMusic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2014/07/08/329500971/a-reluctant-star-sia-deals-with-fame-on-her-own-terms|title=A Reluctant Star, Sia Deals With Fame on Her Own|publisher=[[NPR Music]]|date=8 July 2014|first=Sam|last=Sanders|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150215153550/http://www.npr.org/2014/07/08/329500971/a-reluctant-star-sia-deals-with-fame-on-her-own-terms|archive-date=15 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> From 2011 to 2013, Sia also co-wrote songs for many recording artists, including [[Beyonc\u00e9]], [[Kylie Minogue]], [[Flo Rida]] and [[Rihanna]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://6thfloor.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/04/21/how-a-song-written-by-sia-furler-becomes-a-hit/?_php=true&_type=blogs&_r=0|title=How a Song Written by Sia Furler Became a Hit|work=The New York Times|date=21 April 2014|first=Steve|last=Knopper|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141205003032/http://6thfloor.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/04/21/how-a-song-written-by-sia-furler-becomes-a-hit/?_php=true&_type=blogs&_r=0|archivedate=5 December 2014}}</ref> Her collaboration with Flo Rida, \"[[Wild Ones (song)|Wild Ones]]\", peaked at No. 5 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 and was the tenth best-selling song of 2012 globally.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ifpi.org/downloads/dmr2013-full-report_english.pdf | title=IFPI Digital Music Report 2013 | work=IFPI | accessdate=3 October 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180529150621/http://www.ifpi.org/downloads/dmr2013-full-report_english.pdf | archive-date=29 May 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===2013\u20132014: Breakthrough with ''1000 Forms of Fear''===\nIn October 2013, Sia released \"[[Elastic Heart]]\" featuring [[The Weeknd]] and [[Diplo]] for [[The Hunger Games: Catching Fire \u2013 Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|the soundtrack]] of the American film ''[[The Hunger Games: Catching Fire]]'' (2013).<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921055615/http://www.allaccess.com/top40-rhythmic/future-releases |url=http://www.allaccess.com/top40-rhythmic/future-releases |title=Top 40/R Future Releases |publisher=All Access Music Group |archivedate=21 September 2013 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Sia executive produced [[Brooke Candy]]'s debut EP, ''[[Opulence (EP)|Opulence]]'', released in May 2014, and co-wrote 3 songs on the EP.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.factmag.com/2014/04/28/brooke-candy-preps-debut-ep-does-sex-and-violence-in-opulence-video|title=Brooke Candy preps debut EP, does sex-and-violence in ''Opulence'' video|work=[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact]]|date=28 April 2014|access-date=20 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170320052522/http://www.factmag.com/2014/04/28/brooke-candy-preps-debut-ep-does-sex-and-violence-in-opulence-video/|archive-date=20 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In July 2014, Sia released her own sixth studio album, ''[[1000 Forms of Fear]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/1000-forms-of-fear-mw0002680594|title=1000 Forms of Fear \u2013 Sia|website=AllMusic|first=Heather|last=Phares|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210072510/http://www.allmusic.com/album/1000-forms-of-fear-mw0002680594|archive-date=10 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> She again collaborated with Greg Kurstin.<ref name=KurstinCollab>\n*{{cite journal|last1=Leight|first1=Elias|title=Sia Announces New Christmas Album, Directorial Debut|journal=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=1 August 2017|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/sia-announces-new-christmas-album-directorial-debut-w495289|accessdate=2 August 2017|publisher=Wenner Media LLC|issn=0035-791X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801205328/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/sia-announces-new-christmas-album-directorial-debut-w495289|archive-date=1 August 2017|url-status=live}}\n*{{cite news|last1=McNeilage|first1=Ross|title=Sia Has Signed a New Record Deal and Is Releasing a Christmas Album|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/sia/news/sia-is-recording-a-christmas-album|accessdate=2 August 2017|work=[[MTV News]]|publisher=[[MTV]]|date=1 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801210319/http://www.mtv.co.uk/sia/news/sia-is-recording-a-christmas-album|archive-date=1 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The album debuted at No. 1 in the US ''Billboard'' 200 with first-week sales of 52,000 copies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/australia-culture-blog/2014/jul/17/sia-1000-forms-of-fear-no-1-us-album|title=Sia's 1000 Forms of Fear debuts at No 1 in US album charts|first=Clem|last=Bastow|date=17 July 2014|work=The Guardian|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150217170434/http://www.theguardian.com/music/australia-culture-blog/2014/jul/17/sia-1000-forms-of-fear-no-1-us-album|archive-date=17 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> By October 2015, it was certified gold by the [[RIAA]] denoting 500,000 equivalent-album units sold in the United States.<ref>{{cite magazine|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151218061812/http://hitsdailydouble.com/new_album_releases |archivedate= 18 December 2015 |url=http://hitsdailydouble.com/new_album_releases |title=Upcoming Releases |magazine=Hits Daily Double |publisher=HITS Digital Ventures }}</ref> The record peaked at No. 1 in Australia and reached the top ten of charts in numerous European regions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=1000+Forms+Of+Fear&cat=a|title=Sia \u2013 1000 Forms of Fear|publisher=ARIA Charts|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210000509/http://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=1000+Forms+Of+Fear&cat=a|archive-date=10 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> It was certified silver by the [[British Phonographic Industry]] and gold by the Australian Recording Industry Association.<ref>\"Chandelier\" certifications:\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/certified-awards.aspx |title=Certified Awards |format=''Enter the keyword \"Sia\" into the search parameter'' |publisher=[[British Phonographic Industry]] |accessdate=17 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6EEYfYVwc?url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/certified-awards.aspx |archivedate=6 February 2013 |df= }}\n*{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140906185517/http://www.ariacharts.com.au/chart/albums |url=http://www.ariacharts.com.au/chart/albums |title=ARIA Australian Top 50 Albums |publisher=ARIA Charts |archivedate=6 September 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\nBy early 2016, the album had sold 1 million copies worldwide.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/music/sia-reclaims-the-songs-adele-rihanna-and-beyonce-rejected-to-rewrite-the-pop-blueprint/news-story/08460609cb95cfa5464a978b0682a215 | title=Sia reclaims the songs Adele, Rihanna and Beyonce rejected to rewrite the pop blueprint | work=News Corp Australia Network | date=29 January 2016 | accessdate=1 October 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161006120531/http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/music/sia-reclaims-the-songs-adele-rihanna-and-beyonce-rejected-to-rewrite-the-pop-blueprint/news-story/08460609cb95cfa5464a978b0682a215 | archive-date=6 October 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n''1000 Forms of Fear''{{'}}s lead single, \"[[Chandelier (song)|Chandelier]]\" was released in March 2014. The song peaked at No. 8 on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], becoming Sia's first entry on that chart as a lead artist.<ref name=\"Billboardhot100\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/279248/Sia/chart?f=379|title=Sia \u2013 Chart history: Hot 100|work=Billboard|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150322040223/http://www.billboard.com/artist/279248/Sia/chart?f=379|archive-date=22 March 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Elsewhere, the song experienced similar commercial success, ranking in the top ten of the [[record chart]]s in Australia and numerous European regions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=Chandelier&cat=s|title=Sia \u2013 Chandelier|publisher=ARIA Charts|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150223151251/http://www.australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Sia&titel=Chandelier&cat=s|archive-date=23 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> As of January 2015, the single had sold 2 million copies in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/music/nick-jonass-jealous-hits-a-new-peak-108110758051.html|title=Nick Jonas's 'Jealous' Hits a New Peak|first=Paul|last=Grein|publisher=[[Yahoo! Music]]|date=15 January 2015|accessdate=15 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150115011236/https://www.yahoo.com/music/nick-jonass-jealous-hits-a-new-peak-108110758051.html|archive-date=15 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> \"[[Eye of the Needle (song)|Eye of the Needle]]\" and \"[[Big Girls Cry]]\" were released as the second and third singles from the album, respectively, in June 2014.<ref>\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.bandit.fm/album/7804041?cc=AU |title=Eye of the Needle |publisher=bandit.fm |accessdate=17 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150227052707/http://www.bandit.fm/album/7804041?cc=AU |archivedate=27 February 2015}}\n*{{cite web |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6VQMICp5g?url=https://nl-be.7digital.com/artist/sia/release/big-girls-cry/ |url=https://nl-be.7digital.com/artist/sia/release/big-girls-cry |title=Big Girls Cry (2014) |publisher=7digital |location=Belgium |archivedate=8 January 2015 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\nIn January 2015, Sia released a solo version of \"[[Elastic Heart#Sia solo version|Elastic Heart]]\" as the fourth single from ''1000 Forms of Fear''; it eventually reached the top 20 on the Hot 100.<ref name=\"ElasticHeart\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6443523/hot-100-chart-moves-sia-video-controversy|title=Hot 100 Chart Moves: Video Controversy Sends Sia's 'Elastic Heart' to No. 17 Debut|first=Gary|last=Trust|date=16 January 2015|work=Billboard|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120012212/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6443523/hot-100-chart-moves-sia-video-controversy|archive-date=20 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> At the [[57th Annual Grammy Awards]] (2015), Sia received four nominations for \"Chandelier\": [[Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]], [[Grammy Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]], [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Solo Performance|Best Pop Solo Performance]] and [[Grammy Award for Best Music Video|Best Music Video]].<ref name=GrammyNoms2015>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/zackomalleygreenburg/2014/12/05/grammy-nominees-2015-the-full-list/|title=Grammy Nominees 2015: The Full List|first=Zack|last=O'Malley Greenburg|work=[[Forbes]]|date=5 December 2014|accessdate=17 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141205233150/http://www.forbes.com/sites/zackomalleygreenburg/2014/12/05/grammy-nominees-2015-the-full-list/|archive-date=5 December 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFor live performances of songs from ''1000 Forms of Fear'', Sia chose not to show her face, either facing away from audiences or hiding it behind oversized platinum blonde wigs. In videos for the singles \"Chandelier\", \"Elastic Heart\" and \"Big Girls Cry\", choreographed by [[Ryan Heffington]] and co-directed by Sia and [[Daniel Askill]], and in many of the promotional live performances, child dancer [[Maddie Ziegler]] performed as a proxy for Sia in bobbed blonde wigs similar to Sia's familiar hairstyle.<ref>Schumann, Rebecka. [http://www.ibtimes.com/dance-moms-star-maddie-ziegler-responds-snl-sia-chandelier-spoof-video-1713850 \"''Dance Moms'' Star Maddie Ziegler Responds to ''SNL'' Sia 'Chandelier' Spoof\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170226091440/http://www.ibtimes.com/dance-moms-star-maddie-ziegler-responds-snl-sia-chandelier-spoof-video-1713850 |date=26 February 2017 }}, ''International Business Times'', 27 October 2014, accessed 2 December 2015; Geslani, Michelle. [http://consequenceofsound.net/2015/12/sia-and-dance-prodigy-maddie-ziegler-deliver-gripping-performance-on-ellen-watch \"Sia and dance prodigy Maddie Ziegler deliver gripping performance on Ellen \u2013 watch\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161005142912/http://consequenceofsound.net/2015/12/sia-and-dance-prodigy-maddie-ziegler-deliver-gripping-performance-on-ellen-watch/ |date=5 October 2016 }}, ConsequenceofSound.net, 1 December 2015; Bailey, Alyssa. [http://www.elle.com/culture/celebrities/news/a32257/sia-maddie-ziegler-ellen-degeneres-show \"Watch Sia and Maddie Ziegler's Chilling Live Performance of 'Alive'\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160610105719/http://www.elle.com/culture/celebrities/news/a32257/sia-maddie-ziegler-ellen-degeneres-show/ |date=10 June 2016 }}, ''Elle'' magazine, 1 December 2015; and Swift, Andy. [http://tvline.com/2015/02/08/sia-kristen-wiig-grammy-performance-2015-grammys-chandelier \"Sia Enlists Kristen Wiig for 'Chandelier' Performance at 2015 Grammy Awards\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160926150710/http://tvline.com/2015/02/08/sia-kristen-wiig-grammy-performance-2015-grammys-chandelier/ |date=26 September 2016 }}, Tvline.com, 8 February 2015</ref> The three videos have received a total of more than 3&nbsp;billion views on [[Vevo]].<ref>Furler, Sia. [https://www.youtube.com/user/SiaVEVO/videos?sort=p&view=0&flow=grid SiaVEVO: Most popular videos] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423182936/https://www.youtube.com/user/SiaVEVO/videos?sort=p&view=0&flow=grid |date=23 April 2016 }}, YouTube, accessed 11 October 2018</ref> Sia explained to [[Kristen Wiig]] in an interview in ''[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]]'' magazine that she decided to conceal her face to avoid a celebrity lifestyle and maintain some privacy: \"I'm trying to have some control over my image. And I'm allowed to maintain some modicum of privacy. But also I would like not to be picked apart or for people to observe when I put on ten pounds or take off ten pounds or I have a hair extension out of place or my fake tan is botched. Most people don't have to be under that pressure, and I'd like to be one of them.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.interviewmagazine.com/music/sia|title=Sia|date=April 2015|work=[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]]|accessdate=30 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150529124817/http://www.interviewmagazine.com/music/sia/|archive-date=29 May 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The video for ''Elastic Heart'' \"courted controversy and plaudits in equal measure\", with some commentators perceiving it to have [[pedophilia|pedophilic]] undertones due to the relative ages of the dancers.<ref>Norton, Siobhan. [https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/health-and-families/features/ballet-fitness-why-growing-numbers-are-using-plis-and-pirouettes-to-work-out-10386434.html \"Ballet fitness: Why growing numbers are using pli\u00e9s and pirouettes to work out\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150926034903/http://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/health-and-families/features/ballet-fitness-why-growing-numbers-are-using-plis-and-pirouettes-to-work-out-10386434.html |date=26 September 2015 }}, ''The Independent'', 14 July 2015</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/jan/11/sia-video-pop-music-not-paedophilia?CMP=soc_567 \"Sia's video: let's be wary of seeing paedophilia everywhere\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170828233629/https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/jan/11/sia-video-pop-music-not-paedophilia?CMP=soc_567 |date=28 August 2017 }}, ''[[Guardian Australia]]'', 11 January 2015</ref> Sia explained that the two dancers represented \"warring 'Sia' self states\", but she nevertheless apologized on Twitter to anyone who was \"[[Trauma trigger|triggered]]\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://gma.yahoo.com/sia-apologizes-pedophilia-perception-music-video-133650931--abc-news-music.html |title=Sia Apologizes for \u2018Pedophilia\u2019 Perception in Music Video |publisher=Yahoo! |date=9 January 2015 |accessdate=8 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150110024135/https://gma.yahoo.com/sia-apologizes-pedophilia-perception-music-video-133650931--abc-news-music.html |archive-date=10 January 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=ElasticCont>Ranscombe, Si\u00e2n. [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/rockandpopfeatures/11585580/The-10-most-controversial-music-videos.html \"The 10 most controversial music videos\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180408070841/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/rockandpopfeatures/11585580/The-10-most-controversial-music-videos.html |date=8 April 2018 }}, ''The Telegraph'', 10 May 2015</ref> Gia Kourlas wrote in ''The New York Times'' in 2016 that Sia's collaborations with Heffington have \"done more to raise the standards of dance in pop music than nearly any current artist integrating the forms\".<ref>Kourlas, Gia. [https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/24/arts/dance/for-sia-dance-is-where-the-human-and-the-weird-intersect.html?smid=tw-nytimesarts&smtyp=cur&_r=1 \"For Sia, Dance Is Where the Human and the Weird Intersect\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170813055653/https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/24/arts/dance/for-sia-dance-is-where-the-human-and-the-weird-intersect.html?smid=tw-nytimesarts&smtyp=cur&_r=1 |date=13 August 2017 }}, ''[[The New York Times]]'', 19 July 2016, accessed 31 October 2016</ref> The \"Chandelier\" video was ranked as the 10th \"greatest music video\" of the 2010s by ''Billboard''.<ref>[https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/list/8544596/best-music-videos-2010s-top-100 \"The 100 Greatest Music Videos of the 2010s: Staff Picks\"], ''Billboard'', November 26, 2019</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Sia contributed to the [[Annie (2014 film soundtrack)|soundtrack]] to the [[Annie (2014 film)|2014 film adaptation]] of the Broadway musical [[Annie (musical)|''Annie'']]. Sia, along with producer Greg Kurstin, wrote three new songs for the film as well as re-working songs from the musical.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rigby|first1=Sam|title=Sia and Beck Join Stars on Annie Movie Soundtrack|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/music/news/a605383/sia-and-beck-join-stars-on-annie-movie-soundtrack.html#~oUASLyfKso2baF|website=[[Digital Spy]]|publisher=Digital Spy|accessdate=3 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141104005343/http://www.digitalspy.com/music/news/a605383/sia-and-beck-join-stars-on-annie-movie-soundtrack.html#~oUASLyfKso2baF|archive-date=4 November 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Sia, Kurstin and ''Annie'' director [[Will Gluck]] were nominated at the [[72nd Golden Globe Awards]] for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]] for one of the film's original songs, \"Opportunity\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/birdman-grand-budapest-pace-noms-for-critics-choice-awards-1201379383/ |title='Birdman,' 'Grand Budapest' Top Critics Choice Awards Nominations |work=Variety |date=15 December 2014 |first=Tim |last=Gray |accessdate=15 December 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141216035611/http://variety.com/2014/film/news/birdman-grand-budapest-pace-noms-for-critics-choice-awards-1201379383/ |archivedate=16 December 2014 |df= }}</ref>\n\n===2015\u20132017: ''This Is Acting''===\n[[File:SIaFurler Boston2016live.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Sia in 2016; since 2014, she has covered most of her face at concerts and on TV]]\nIn an interview with ''[[NME]]'' in February 2015, Sia revealed that she had completed the follow-up to ''1000 Forms of Fear'', entitled ''[[This Is Acting]]''. The album was another collaboration with producer and co-writer Greg Kurstin.<ref name=KurstinCollab/> Furler said that she released ''1000 Forms of Fear'' to free herself from her record deal and had planned simply to write for other artists, but the album's success spurred her to continue writing her own music.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/various-artists/82961|title=Sia reveals early details of brand new album ''This Is Acting''|date=17 February 2015|work=[[NME]]|accessdate=19 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150218161220/http://www.nme.com/news/various-artists/82961|archive-date=18 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> In May 2015, Sia's cover of [[The Mamas & the Papas]]' \"[[California Dreamin']]\" was released on the soundtrack of the movie ''[[San Andreas (film)|San Andreas]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine| last1=Strecker| first1=Erin| title=Sia Releases Haunting 'California Dreamin'' Cover for 'San Andreas' Movie| url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6561316/sia-california-dreamin-cover-san-andreas-movie-mamas-papas| accessdate=18 September 2015| magazine=Billboard| date=2 May 2015| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150917234259/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6561316/sia-california-dreamin-cover-san-andreas-movie-mamas-papas| archive-date=17 September 2015| url-status=live}}</ref> The same month, alongside the digital deluxe release of ''1000 Forms of Fear'', she released a mobile game, ''Bob Job''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McCown|first1=Alex|title=Sia releases a new game, still won't show herself|url=https://www.avclub.com/article/sia-releases-new-game-still-wont-show-herself-219026|accessdate=18 September 2015|newspaper=A.V. Club|date=6 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150913042827/http://www.avclub.com/article/sia-releases-new-game-still-wont-show-herself-219026|archive-date=13 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> \"[[Alive (Sia song)|Alive]]\" from ''This Is Acting'' was co-written by [[Adele]] and had originally been intended for Adele's third album.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lee|first1=Christina|title=Sia Details Next Single, Which Was Originally Written for Adele|url=http://www.idolator.com/7607168/sia-2015-album-this-is-acting-single-adele|website=Idolator|publisher=Time Inc.|date=7 September 2015|accessdate=8 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150908185348/http://www.idolator.com/7607168/sia-2015-album-this-is-acting-single-adele|archive-date=8 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn November, Sia collaborated with composer [[J. Ralph]] on the soundtrack of the environmental documentary ''[[Racing Extinction]]'', co-writing and singing the song \"One Candle\".<ref>Spanos, Brittany. [https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-sias-epic-new-song-one-candle-from-racing-extinction-trailer-20151105 \"Hear Sia, J. Ralph's Epic New Song From ''Racing Extinction'' Trailer\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107031319/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-sias-epic-new-song-one-candle-from-racing-extinction-trailer-20151105 |date=7 November 2017 }}, ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', 5 November 2015. Retrieved 28 September 2016</ref> She also released two more songs from the album, \"[[Bird Set Free]]\"<ref>{{Citation|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KrT_0J6m6y8|accessdate = 29 November 2015|title = Bird Set Free|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151126233141/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KrT_0J6m6y8|archive-date = 26 November 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> and \"One Million Bullets\".<ref>{{Cite web|title = Sia Shares New Track \"One Million Bullets\"|url = https://pitchfork.com/news/62289-sia-shares-new-track-one-million-bullets|website = Pitchfork|accessdate = 29 November 2015|language = en-US|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151130015805/http://pitchfork.com/news/62289-sia-shares-new-track-one-million-bullets/|archive-date = 30 November 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> \"[[Cheap Thrills (song)|Cheap Thrills]]\" and \"[[Reaper (song)|Reaper]]\" were subsequently released as promotional singles for the album. In January 2016, eight days prior to the release of ''This Is Acting'', she released \"Unstoppable\" as the final pre-release promotion single for the album. Eventually, the single \"Cheap Thrills\", featuring [[Sean Paul]], reached No. 1 on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Trust|first1=Gary|title=Sia's 'Cheap Thrills' Takes No. 1 on Hot 100 From Drake|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7446766/sia-cheap-thrills-sean-paul-no-1-hot-100|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=25 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160726141731/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7446766/sia-cheap-thrills-sean-paul-no-1-hot-100|archive-date=26 July 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Sia released two videos for the song, one of which features Ziegler and two male dancers,<ref>[https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7263981/sia-releases-captivating-cheap-thrills-video-featuring-maddie-ziegler \"Sia Releases Captivating 'Cheap Thrills' Video Featuring Maddie Ziegler\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160910215333/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7263981/sia-releases-captivating-cheap-thrills-video-featuring-maddie-ziegler |date=10 September 2016 }}, ''Billboard'', 21 March 2016; and Briones, Isis. [http://www.teenvogue.com/story/sia-maddie-ziegler-cheap-thrills-music-video \"Sia's Music Video of New Single 'Cheap Thrills' With Maddie Ziegler Will Blow You Away\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160918154550/http://www.teenvogue.com/story/sia-maddie-ziegler-cheap-thrills-music-video |date=18 September 2016 }}, ''Teen Vogue'', 21 March 2016</ref> while the other, featuring Sean Paul, shows a 1950s style teen dance party; it has accumulated more than 1.4 billion views.<ref>Sia. [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nYh-n7EOtMA \"Sia \u2013 'Cheap Thrills' (Lyric Video) ft. Sean Paul\"], YouTube, 10 February 2016, accessed 10 December 2019</ref>\n\nIn April 2016, Sia gave a widely acclaimed performance at the [[Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival]] that went [[viral video|viral]] online.<ref name=\"People Are Still Obsessed\">{{Cite web|url=http://time.com/4299395/sia-coachella-performance/|title=People Are Still Obsessed With Sia's Incredible Coachella Performance|website=Time|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422051544/http://time.com/4299395/sia-coachella-performance/|archive-date=22 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>\nSources for the 2016 Coachella Festival performance:\n*{{Cite web|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/04/coachella-is-losing-its-shit-over-sias-performance/|title=Coachella is losing its shit over Sia's performance|website=Consequence of Sound|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160425033830/http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/04/coachella-is-losing-its-shit-over-sias-performance/|archive-date=25 April 2016|url-status=live}}\n*{{Cite web|url=http://www.fuse.tv/2016/04/sia-2016-festivals|title=IS SIA ALREADY THE MVP OF THE 2016 FESTIVAL SEASON?|website=Fuse|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160502125311/http://www.fuse.tv/2016/04/sia-2016-festivals|archive-date=2 May 2016|url-status=live}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/music-festivals/7334157/sia-coachella-2016|title=Sia Captivates & Confounds During Star-Studded Coachella Set|website=Billboard|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423120358/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/music-festivals/7334157/sia-coachella-2016|archive-date=23 April 2016|url-status=live}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/posts/la-et-ms-coachella-2016-sia-main-stage-star-power-20160419-story.html|title=Coachella 2016: Sia changed the whole concept of star power on the main stage|website=Los Angeles Times|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160424161628/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/posts/la-et-ms-coachella-2016-sia-main-stage-star-power-20160419-story.html|archive-date=24 April 2016|url-status=live}}\n*{{Cite web|url=http://www.pe.com/articles/sia-800269-stage-set.html|title=COACHELLA 2016: Sia turns the festival into a stage for performance art (UPDATE)|website=Press Enterprise|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160427040348/http://www.pe.com/articles/sia-800269-stage-set.html|archive-date=27 April 2016|url-status=live}}\n*{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/la-et-ms-coachella-2016-l-ever-elusive-sia-flips-the-script-on-coachella-cam-1460959067-htmlstory.html|title=Coachella: Surviving members of N.W.A reunite, and artists pay tribute to Prince|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|issn=0458-3035|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423103952/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/la-et-ms-coachella-2016-l-ever-elusive-sia-flips-the-script-on-coachella-cam-1460959067-htmlstory.html|archive-date=23 April 2016|url-status=live}}\n</ref><ref name=\"incredible Coachella set\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.dazeddigital.com/music/article/30811/1/watch-sia-s-incredible-coachella-set-in-full-here|title=Watch Sia's incredible Coachella set in full here|website=Dazed Digital|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422050327/http://www.dazeddigital.com/music/article/30811/1/watch-sia-s-incredible-coachella-set-in-full-here|archive-date=22 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Sia legendary\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nylon.com/articles/sia-coachella-2016-performance|title=Sia's Coachella Set Is Already Legendary|website=Nylon Magazine|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423173314/http://www.nylon.com/articles/sia-coachella-2016-performance|archive-date=23 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Her performance received an effusively positive critical reception<ref name=\"incredible Coachella set\"/><ref name=\"Sia legendary\"/> as \"one of the greatest moments in Coachella's 17-year history\",<ref>{{Cite web| url=https://www.yahoo.com/music/this-is-acting-sia-stuns-with-theatrical-180537878.html| title=This Is Acting: Sia Stuns With Theatrical Coachella Spectacle| website=Yahoo! Music| access-date=25 April 2016| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160427062441/https://www.yahoo.com/music/this-is-acting-sia-stuns-with-theatrical-180537878.html| archive-date=27 April 2016| url-status=live}}</ref> and it was consistently noted as one of the best performances of the 2016 festival.<ref>\nLists of the best 2016 Coachella Festival performances:\n*{{Cite web|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/04/coachella-2016-festival-review-from-worst-to-best/46/|title=Coachella 2016 Festival Review: From Worst to Best|website=Consequence of Sound|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423120741/http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/04/coachella-2016-festival-review-from-worst-to-best/46/|archive-date=23 April 2016|url-status=live}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/30-best-things-we-saw-at-coachella-2016-weekend-one-20160418/best-performance-art-sia-20160418|title=30 Best Things We Saw at Coachella: Best Performance Art- Sia|website=Rolling Stone|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160426162416/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/30-best-things-we-saw-at-coachella-2016-weekend-one-20160418/best-performance-art-sia-20160418|archive-date=26 April 2016|url-status=live}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/music-festivals/7334239/coachella-2016-best-moments-first-weekend|title=11 Best Moments From Coachella 2016|website=Billboard|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422071641/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/music-festivals/7334239/coachella-2016-best-moments-first-weekend|archive-date=22 April 2016|url-status=live}}\n*{{Cite web|url=http://www.fuse.tv/2016/04/coachella-2016-10-best-performances#1|title=TOP 10 BEST PERFORMANCES OF COACHELLA 2016|website=Fuse|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160421055836/http://www.fuse.tv/2016/04/coachella-2016-10-best-performances#1|archive-date=21 April 2016|url-status=live}}\n</ref> The performance was her first full concert since 2011.<ref name=\"People Are Still Obsessed\"/> In May 2016, Sia made a surprise appearance on the finale for ''[[Survivor: Ka\u00f4h R\u014dng]]'' where she donated $50,000 to contestant Tai Trang. She donated another $50,000 to an animal charity of his choice, noting that the two share a mutual love of animals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/sia-gives-survivor-finalist-100k-for-being-an-animal-rights-activist_us_573d2480e4b0646cbeec23d9|title=Sia Gives 'Survivor' Finalist $100K For Being An Animal Rights Activist|website=The Huffington Post|access-date=19 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160519041151/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/sia-gives-survivor-finalist-100k-for-being-an-animal-rights-activist_us_573d2480e4b0646cbeec23d9|archive-date=19 May 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The same month, she contributed vocals to a cover of [[Nat King Cole]]'s \"[[Unforgettable (Nat King Cole song)|Unforgettable]]\" which was featured on the [[Finding Dory (soundtrack)|soundtrack]] of 2016 [[Pixar]] film ''[[Finding Dory]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7378273/sia-finding-dory-unforgettable-ellen-nat-king-cole | title=Watch Sia Cover Nat King Cole's 'Unforgettable' for 'Finding Dory' on 'Ellen' | work=Billboard | date=20 May 2016 | accessdate=9 September 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160910060231/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7378273/sia-finding-dory-unforgettable-ellen-nat-king-cole | archive-date=10 September 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2016, Sia gave a concert at [[Red Rocks Amphitheatre]] in Colorado, featuring Ziegler.<ref>Owens, Dylan. [http://www.heyreverb.com/blog/2016/06/23/welcome-sias-theater-dreams-red-rocks-seriesfest/118235/#16 \"For SeriesFest, Sia welcomes Red Rocks to her theater of dreams\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160924185311/http://www.heyreverb.com/blog/2016/06/23/welcome-sias-theater-dreams-red-rocks-seriesfest/118235/#16 |date=24 September 2016 }}, HeyReverb.com, ''[[The Denver Post]]'', 23 June 2016</ref> From May to August, Sia performed in nearly a dozen festival and other concerts in America and European and Middle Eastern countries, including Portugal, Denmark, Sweden, Finland, Hungary, Romania, Poland, the United Kingdom, Russia, Lebanon and Israel.<ref>Young, Alex. [http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/05/sia-announce-2016-world-tour-miguel-and-alunageorge-to-open ''Sia announce 2016 world tour, Miguel and AlunaGeorge to open''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161002113531/http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/05/sia-announce-2016-world-tour-miguel-and-alunageorge-to-open/ |date=2 October 2016 }}, ''Consequence of Sound'', 16 May 2016, accessed 30 September 2016</ref><ref>[http://www.artistdirect.com/entertainment-news/article/sia-announces-tour-with-openers-miguel-and-alunageorge/11864459 ''Sia Announces Tour With Openers Miguel And AlunaGeorge''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161002141105/http://www.artistdirect.com/entertainment-news/article/sia-announces-tour-with-openers-miguel-and-alunageorge/11864459 |date=2 October 2016 }}, ''[[Artistdirect|Artist Direct]]'', 17 May 2016, accessed 30 September 2016</ref><ref>Pate, Stephen. [http://njnnetwork.com/2016/08/sia-open-worldwide-tour-in-byblos-lebanon ''Sia Excites Crowd As Worldwide Tour Opens in Byblos Lebanon''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161003091531/http://njnnetwork.com/2016/08/sia-open-worldwide-tour-in-byblos-lebanon/ |date=3 October 2016 }}, ''NJN Network'', 10 August 2016, accessed 30 September 2016</ref> In September 2016, she released a single, \"[[The Greatest (Sia song)|The Greatest]]\", with vocals from American hip hop recording artist [[Kendrick Lamar]]. A video was released the same day featuring Ziegler \u2013 the dancer's fifth video collaboration with Sia and Heffington.<ref name=GreatestGlicksman>Glicksman, Josh. [https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8478144/sia-maddie-ziegler-friendship-timeline \"A Timeline of Sia & Maddie Ziegler's Friendship, From 'Chandelier' to a New Car\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004094825/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8478144/sia-maddie-ziegler-friendship-timeline |date=4 October 2018 }}, ''Billboard'', 3 October 2018; and Furler, Sia. [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GKSRyLdjsPA \"Sia \u2013 The Greatest\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160909002001/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GKSRyLdjsPA |date=9 September 2016 }}, SiaVEVO, 5 September 2016</ref> The two performed the song with several other dancers, and also performed \"Chandelier\", live the next day at the [[Apple Inc|Apple]] annual [[Apple media events|fall event]], drawing media attention.<ref>Moss, Rachel. [http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/maddie-ziegler-apple-launch-performance_uk_57d16502e4b0d45ff871392a \"13-Year-Old Dancer Maddie Ziegler Totally Stole The Show At The Apple iPhone 7 Launch\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160913015215/http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/maddie-ziegler-apple-launch-performance_uk_57d16502e4b0d45ff871392a |date=13 September 2016 }}, ''Huffington Post'', 8 September 2016; and Robinson, Melia. [http://www.businessinsider.com/dancing-girl-apple-event-2016-9 \"Meet the 13-year-old dancing sensation who stunned people at the big Apple event\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160911144815/http://www.businessinsider.com/dancing-girl-apple-event-2016-9 |date=11 September 2016 }}, ''[[Business Insider]]'', 7 September 2016</ref> The videos that Sia has posted to her YouTube channel have accumulated a total of more than 8&nbsp;billion views, and the channel has more than 18 million subscribers.<ref>Furler, Sia. [https://www.youtube.com/user/siavideos/featured Sia], YouTube, accessed 10 December 2019</ref>\n\nSia gave her [[Nostalgic for the Present Tour]] in North America from September to November 2016, featuring Ziegler.<ref>Craddock, Lauren. [https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7446785/maddie-ziegler-sia-nostalgic-for-the-present-tour \"Maddie Ziegler to Join Sia's Nostalgic for the Present Tour\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160910061039/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7446785/maddie-ziegler-sia-nostalgic-for-the-present-tour |date=10 September 2016 }}, ''Billboard'', 25 July 2016</ref> As at Coachella and subsequent live performances, Sia appeared at the back of the stage with her familiar wig covering her face, while her dancers performed Heffington's choreography synchronized with prerecorded videos played on big screens.<ref>Klein, Josh. [https://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/music/ct-sia-miguel-review-ent-1018-20161017-story.html \"Sia is a bundle of fascinating contradictions during United Center performance\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161020045201/http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/music/ct-sia-miguel-review-ent-1018-20161017-story.html |date=20 October 2016 }}, ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'', 17 October 2016</ref> The tour received a warm reaction: \"She let her dancers own center stage, carrying out one skit/performance after another as Sia delivered the soundtrack. ... It defied all the regular rules of pop concerts, which are usually designed to focus every ounce of the audience\u2019s attention on the star of the show. Yet, Sia's bold gamble paid off, resulting in one of the most daringly original and wholly satisfying shows of 2016.\"<ref name=\"Harrington, Jim\">{{cite web | url=http://www.mercurynews.com/2016/10/02/review-sia-rocks-with-kristen-wiig-paul-dano-in-oakland | title=Review: Sia delivers performance-art masterpiece in Oakland | work=The Mercury News | date=2 October 2016 | accessdate=2 October 2016 | author=Harrington, Jim | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161004154408/http://www.mercurynews.com/2016/10/02/review-sia-rocks-with-kristen-wiig-paul-dano-in-oakland/ | archive-date=4 October 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> Ed Masley of ''[[The Arizona Republic]]'' described the show as \"part performance art, part interpretive dance. ... [Sia] sounded amazing. ... There's so much raw emotion in her songs. And you can definitely hear that in her voice, but it becomes more visceral when you can also read it in the faces of her dancers, especially Ziegler. ... The entire performance was brilliantly staged, with one song flowing seamlessly into another\".<ref>Masley, Ed. [https://www.azcentral.com/story/entertainment/music/2016/10/05/sia-concert-review-maddie-ziegler/91611028 \"Review: Sia reinvented what it means to give a concert \u2013 part performance art, part Maddie Ziegler\"], ''[[The Arizona Republic]]'', 5 October 2016</ref> Sia released the deluxe edition of ''This Is Acting'' in October 2016, which includes three new tracks, a remix version of \"Move Your Body\" and a solo version of \"The Greatest\".<ref>Raynor, Madeline. [https://www.ew.com/article/2016/10/21/sia-this-acting-deluxe-new-songs \"Sia releases 3 new tracks on ''This is Acting'' deluxe version\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161023035131/http://www.ew.com/article/2016/10/21/sia-this-acting-deluxe-new-songs |date=23 October 2016 }}, ''Entertainment Weekly'', 21 October 2016</ref> She was nominated for three 2017 Grammy Awards.<ref name=GrammyNoms2017>[https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7597556/grammys-nominees-complete-list-2017 \"Here Is the Complete List of Nominees for the 2017 Grammys\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161206151125/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7597556/grammys-nominees-complete-list-2017 |date=6 December 2016 }}, ''Billboard'' magazine, 6 December 2016</ref> Sia contributed to the soundtracks for the films ''[[Lion (2016 film)|Lion]]'' and ''[[Wonder Woman (2017 film)|Wonder Woman]]'' with \"[[Never Give Up (Sia song)|Never Give Up]]\" and \"[[To Be Human]]\", respectively.<ref name=Spanos2>{{Cite news |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-sias-sweeping-new-wonder-woman-anthem-to-be-human-w484209 |title=Hear Sia's Sweeping New Anthem 'To Be Human' from 'Wonder Woman' Soundtrack |last=Spanos |first=Brittany |date=25 May 2017 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=26 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525173923/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-sias-sweeping-new-wonder-woman-anthem-to-be-human-w484209 |archive-date=25 May 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> She also co-wrote and performed on a platinum-selling single, \"[[Dusk Till Dawn (Zayn song)|Dusk Till Dawn]]\" by [[Zayn Malik]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Leight|first=Elias|title=Watch Jemima Kirke in Noir Thriller For Zayn Malik, Sia's New Song|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=7 September 2017|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/see-zayn-malik-in-noir-thriller-dusk-till-dawn-video-w501630|accessdate=20 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170920141652/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/see-zayn-malik-in-noir-thriller-dusk-till-dawn-video-w501630|archive-date=20 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>[https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&ar=ZAYN&ti=DUSK+TILL+DAWN+%28FEAT.+SIA%29 \"Zayn: 'Dusk Till Dawn' (Feat. Sia)\"], RIAA, accessed 24 October 2018</ref>\n\nSia performed in concert at the close of the [[Dubai World Cup]] in March 2017, together with her dancers, led by Ziegler.<ref>Hamad, Marwa. [http://gulfnews.com/life-style/music/sia-dons-her-wig-during-theatrical-dubai-gig-1.2000413 \"Sia dons her wig during theatrical Dubai gig\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170326223344/http://gulfnews.com/life-style/music/sia-dons-her-wig-during-theatrical-dubai-gig-1.2000413 |date=26 March 2017 }}, ''Gulf News'', 26 March 2017</ref> They gave a second leg of the Nostalgic for the Present Tour, her first stadium tour in Australasia, in late 2017.<ref>\n*{{Cite news |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7809643/sia-stadium-tour-australia-new-zealand |title=Sia Plots First Stadium Tour of Australia and New Zealand |last=Brandle |first=Lars |date=29 May 2017 |work=Billboard |access-date=29 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170529081115/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7809643/sia-stadium-tour-australia-new-zealand |archive-date=29 May 2017 |url-status=live }}\n*He, Richard S. [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/dec/01/sia-review-when-she-transcends-spectacle-she-soars \"Sia review \u2013 when she transcends spectacle, she soars\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180101172948/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/dec/01/sia-review-when-she-transcends-spectacle-she-soars |date=1 January 2018 }}, ''[[The Guardian]]'', 30 November 2017, accessed 28 January 2018\n</ref>\n\n===2017\u2013present: ''Everyday Is Christmas'' and ''LSD''===\nIn 2017, Sia moved from RCA to [[Atlantic Records]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7882275/sia-christmas-album-atlantic-records-deal|title=Sia Signs to Atlantic Records, Announces Christmas Album|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Kaufman|first=Gil|date=1 August 2017|accessdate=1 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801183635/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7882275/sia-christmas-album-atlantic-records-deal|archive-date=1 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> She released a new album, ''[[Everyday Is Christmas (album)|Everyday Is Christmas]]'', on Atlantic and Monkey Puzzle in November 2017. The album features original songs co-written and co-produced with Kurstin.<ref>\n*{{cite journal|last1=Kaufman|first1=Gil|title=Sia Signs to Atlantic Records, Announces Christmas Album|journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=1 August 2017|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7882275/sia-christmas-album-atlantic-records-deal|accessdate=2 August 2017|publisher=[[Eldridge Industries]]|issn=0006-2510|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801194617/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7882275/sia-christmas-album-atlantic-records-deal|archive-date=1 August 2017|url-status=live}}\n*{{cite journal|title=Sia Signs with Atlantic Records, Christmas Album Due This Year|journal=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=1 August 2017|url=https://variety.com/2017/music/news/sia-signs-with-atlantic-records-christmas-album-due-this-year-1202512120/|accessdate=2 August 2017|issn=0042-2738|oclc=810134503|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801173836/http://variety.com/2017/music/news/sia-signs-with-atlantic-records-christmas-album-due-this-year-1202512120/|archive-date=1 August 2017|url-status=live}}\n</ref> She promoted it by releasing the single \"Santa's Coming for Us\" and by the track \"Snowman\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-sias-joyous-seasonal-song-santas-coming-for-us-w510478|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=16 April 2018|title=Hear Sia's Joyous Seasonal Song 'Santa's Coming for Us|author=Daniel Kreps|date=30 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180417105614/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-sias-joyous-seasonal-song-santas-coming-for-us-w510478|archive-date=17 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8031327/sia-new-song-snowman-christmas-album-listen|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=16 April 2018|title=Sia Shares New Song, Snowman, Says She Wrote Christmas Album By Accident|date=11 November 2017|author=Mary J. DiMeglio|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180424042351/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8031327/sia-new-song-snowman-christmas-album-listen|archive-date=24 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> which she performed during the finale of the [[The Voice (American season 13)|13th season of ''The Voice'']] and on ''[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show]]'' together with Maddie Ziegler.<ref>Aniftos, Rania. [https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8070501/sia-maddie-ziegler-reunite-perform-snowman-ellen \"Sia & Maddie Ziegler Reunite to Perform 'Snowman' on ''Ellen'': Watch\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180105220316/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8070501/sia-maddie-ziegler-reunite-perform-snowman-ellen |date=5 January 2018 }}, ''Billboard'', 13 December 2017</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/tv/news/e2-80-98the-voice-e2-80-99-finale-recap-the-winner-of-season-13-is-revealed/ar-BBH31du|publisher=[[MSN]]|accessdate=16 April 2018|title=The Voice Finale Recap: The Winner Of Season 13 Is Revealed|author=Alyssa Norwin|date=20 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418031517/https://www.msn.com/en-us/tv/news/e2-80-98the-voice-e2-80-99-finale-recap-the-winner-of-season-13-is-revealed/ar-BBH31du|archive-date=18 April 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> In November 2018, Sia released the deluxe edition of the album, containing three bonus tracks, as a [[Target Corporation|Target]] exclusive.<ref>Lenniger, Shea. [https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8482991/sia-deluxe-christmas-album-stream \"Sia Releases Deluxe Version of Her Christmas Album: Listen\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181103123309/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8482991/sia-deluxe-christmas-album-stream |date=3 November 2018 }}, ''Billboard'', 2 November 2018</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Sia collaborated with English musician [[Labrinth]] and American DJ/record producer [[Diplo]], under the name [[LSD (group)|LSD]], to release four songs,<ref>[https://variety.com/2018/music/news/lsd-sia-diplo-and-labrinth-team-up-for-new-song-genius-listen-1202796730 \"Sia, Diplo and Labrinth Team Up for New Song 'Genius' (Listen)\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616065328/https://variety.com/2018/music/news/lsd-sia-diplo-and-labrinth-team-up-for-new-song-genius-listen-1202796730/ |date=16 June 2018 }}, ''Variety'', 3 May 2018; Rettig, James. [https://www.stereogum.com/1995583/lsd-sia-diplo-labrinth-audio-video/video \"LSD (Sia, Diplo, & Labrinth) \u2013 'Audio' Video\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616153713/https://www.stereogum.com/1995583/lsd-sia-diplo-labrinth-audio-video/video/ |date=16 June 2018 }}, [[Stereogum]], 10 May 2018; and Bein, Kat. [https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/8482791/lsd-mountains-new-song \"LSD Reaches New Heights on 'Mountains'\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181102165506/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/8482791/lsd-mountains-new-song |date=2 November 2018 }}, ''Billboard'', 1 November 2018</ref> which were then released as an EP called ''Mountains'' on Spotify.<ref name=\"Legaspi\">{{cite journal |last1=Legaspi |first1=Althea |title=Hear Diplo, Sia, Labrinth Move \u2018Mountains\u2019 on New Song |journal=Rolling Stone |date=1 November 2018 |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/diplo-sia-labrinth-mountains-new-lsd-song-750952/ |accessdate=3 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181102175747/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/diplo-sia-labrinth-mountains-new-lsd-song-750952/ |archive-date=2 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The group released an album, ''[[LSD (album)|Labrinth, Sia & Diplo Present... LSD]]'', in April 2019,<ref>Daw, Stephen. (11 March 2019). [https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/8501893/diplo-sia-labrinth-announce-debut-lsd-album-release-date \"Diplo, Sia & Labrinth Announce Debut LSD Album Release Date\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190315104320/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/8501893/diplo-sia-labrinth-announce-debut-lsd-album-release-date |date=15 March 2019 }}, ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''. Retrieved 11 March 2019</ref> containing the same four songs, five new songs, and a previously released remix of their track \"[[Genius (LSD song)|Genius]]\" with [[Lil Wayne]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/nz/album/labrinth-sia-diplo-present-lsd/1455271201|title=Labrinth, Sia & Diplo Present... LSD by LSD on iTunes|last=|first=|date=|website=iTunes Store|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328164726/https://itunes.apple.com/nz/album/labrinth-sia-diplo-present-lsd/1455271201|archive-date=28 March 2019|url-status=live|access-date=12 April 2019}}</ref> \n\nAlso in 2018, Sia was one of the narrators of Australian animal rights documentary [[Dominion (documentary)|''Dominion'']],<ref>Webber, Jemima. [https://www.livekindly.co/vegan-celebrity-sia-joins-cast-of-new-animal-rights-documentary-dominion \"Vegan Celebrity Sia Joins Cast of New Animal Rights Documentary Dominion\"], LiveKindly.co, 18 May 2018, accessed 14 February 2020</ref> and shared in a 2018 Award of Excellence from the Hollywood International Independent Documentary Awards.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://hiida.com/july-2018-winners.html|title=Hollywood International Independent Documentary Awards]]</ref> The next year, Sia collaborated with composer [[Hans Zimmer]] on the title song, \"Out There\", for the BBC [[David Attenborough]] documentary series ''[[Seven Worlds, One Planet]]''.<ref>Pearce, Tilly. [https://metro.co.uk/2019/10/28/seven-worlds-one-planet-sia-joined-forces-sir-david-attenborough-hans-zimmer-create-iconic-track-10995575 \"''Seven Worlds One Planet'': How Sia joined forces with Sir David Attenborough and Hans Zimmer to create epic track\"], Metro.co.uk, 28 October 2019</ref> In January 2020, Furler released her song \"[[Original (Sia song)|Original]]\", which featured on the ''[[Dolittle (film)|Dolittle]]'' film soundtrack.<ref>https://pitchfork.com/news/listen-to-sias-new-song-original</ref>\n\n==Artistry, musical style and accolades==\n{{further|List of awards and nominations received by Sia}}\n\nAt the start of her career, with the bands Crisp<ref name=AllmusicHealing>{{cite web|last1=O'Brien|first1=Jon|title=Sia: Healing is Difficult|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/healing-is-difficult-mw0000464188|website=AllMusic|accessdate=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180717024024/https://www.allmusic.com/album/healing-is-difficult-mw0000464188|archive-date=17 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Jamiroquai]], Sia performed \"acid jazz\" in Australia and later in London.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Prato|first1=Greg|title=Jamiroquai Overview|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/jamiroquai-mn0000176358|website=AllMusic|accessdate=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180201041752/https://www.allmusic.com/artist/jamiroquai-mn0000176358|archive-date=1 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> With her first solo single, \"Taken for Granted\", she experimented with [[trip hop]].<ref name=AllmusicHealing/> When she joined Zero 7, she sang [[downtempo]] numbers.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wesolowski|first1=David Peter|title=Zero 7 Overview|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/zero-7-mn0000696668|website=AllMusic|accessdate=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180413190527/https://www.allmusic.com/artist/zero-7-mn0000696668|archive-date=13 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nWith ''[[Colour the Small One]]'' (2004) and ''[[Some People Have Real Problems]]'' (2007) she moved into [[jazz]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sullivan|first1=Caroline|title=Sia, Colour the Small One|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2004/jan/02/popandrock.shopping|accessdate=13 April 2018|work=The Guardian|date=1 January 2004|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180718180149/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2004/jan/02/popandrock.shopping|archive-date=18 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[folktronica]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=O'Brien|first1=Jon|title=Sia: Colour the Small One|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/colour-the-small-one-mw0000463309|website=AllMusic|accessdate=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171104214544/https://www.allmusic.com/album/colour-the-small-one-mw0000463309|archive-date=4 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> although the album's biggest hit, \"[[Breathe Me]]\", is described as [[alternative rock]] and a [[power ballad]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Sia: Breathe Me|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/breathe-me-mw0001977876|website=AllMusic|accessdate=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201044614/https://www.allmusic.com/album/breathe-me-mw0001977876|archive-date=1 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Some People Have Real Problems'' expanded her connection with [[indie pop]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mason|first1=Stewart|title=Some People Have Real Problems|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/some-people-have-real-problems-mw0000492954|website=AllMusic|accessdate=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201131351/https://www.allmusic.com/album/some-people-have-real-problems-mw0000492954|archive-date=1 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Some People Have Real Problems / Sia| url=https://www.billboard.com/bbcom/content_display/reviews/albums/e3i5d4ee6c1f9636327deaa5402a021aa97| website=Billboard|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080925190851/http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/content_display/reviews/albums/e3i5d4ee6c1f9636327deaa5402a021aa97|archivedate=25 September 2008}}</ref> Sia stated, \"''Colour the Small One'' ... couldn't be more derivative of [[Kings of Convenience]] and [[James Taylor]] and the things that Zero 7 were playing on the [tour] bus. I'm very easily influenced.\"<ref name=\"Rolling Stone\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/sias-reject-opus-songwriter-on-reclaiming-adele-rihannas-unwanted-hits-20151203?page=4|title=Sia on Reclaiming Adele, Rihanna's Unwanted Hits|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=3 December 2015|access-date=11 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170913213312/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/sias-reject-opus-songwriter-on-reclaiming-adele-rihannas-unwanted-hits-20151203?page=4|archive-date=13 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, after leaving Zero 7, Sia dedicated herself entirely to her solo career.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Leahey|first1=Andrew|title=Sia Biography|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/sia-mn0000753742/biography|website=AllMusic|accessdate=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180717014836/https://www.allmusic.com/artist/sia-mn0000753742/biography|archive-date=17 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[We Are Born]]'' (2010), incorporated various pop styles, including [[synthpop]] and [[R&B]], with introspective themes accompanied by more insistent and livelier rhythms.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hoffman|first1=K. Ross|title=Sia: We Are Born|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/we-are-born-mw0001988460|website=AllMusic|accessdate=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180413190530/https://www.allmusic.com/album/we-are-born-mw0001988460|archive-date=13 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> ''1000 Forms of Fear'' (2014) consolidated her connection with pop (with traces of [[electropop]], reggae and hip-hop)<ref>{{cite web |last=Zaleski |first=Marah |url=https://www.avclub.com/review/accidental-pop-songwriter-sia-doesnt-quite-reclaim-206353 |title=Accidental pop songwriter Sia doesn't quite reclaim solo career momentum |work=[[The A.V. Club]] |date=8 July 2014 |accessdate=8 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140712061920/http://www.avclub.com/review/accidental-pop-songwriter-sia-doesnt-quite-reclaim-206353 |archive-date=12 July 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Fares|first1=Heather|title=Sia: 1000 Forms of Fear|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/1000-forms-of-fear-mw0002680594|website=AllMusic|accessdate=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627144311/https://www.allmusic.com/album/1000-forms-of-fear-mw0002680594|archive-date=27 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> ''This Is Acting'' is mostly composed of songs written by Sia with other female pop artists in mind, but the artists did not include the songs on their albums.<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite web | url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/jan/31/sia-this-is-acting-review-favourite-rejects-beyonce-rihanna-adele | title=Sia: This Is Acting review \u2013 mass-appeal pop with a manic edge | work=The Guardian | date=31 January 2016 | accessdate=2 October 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161003154023/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/jan/31/sia-this-is-acting-review-favourite-rejects-beyonce-rihanna-adele | archive-date=3 October 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> Sia described songwriting for others as \"play-acting.\"<ref name=\"Rolling Stone\"/> ''[[The Guardian]]''{{'}}s Kitty Empire commented that the latter album \"provides an obvious counterpoint to Sia's more personal album of 2014, ''1000 Forms of Fear'', whose stonking single, \"Chandelier\", tackled her intoxicated past. ''This Is Acting'' makes plain the fact of manufacture \u2013 a process akin to bespoke tailoring.\"<ref name=\"guardian\"/>\n\n''This Is Acting'' (2016) alternates more reggae and electropop with more introspective themes.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Chau|first1=Thomas|title=Sia Reveals that She Originally Wrote Her Next Single for Adele|url=http://popcrush.com/sia-new-single-alive-adele/|website=Popcrush|accessdate=13 April 2018|date=7 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150909205054/http://popcrush.com/sia-new-single-alive-adele/|archive-date=9 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Phares|first1=Heather|title=Sia: This Is Acting|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/this-is-acting-mw0002894912|website=AllMusic|accessdate=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709011409/https://www.allmusic.com/album/this-is-acting-mw0002894912|archive-date=9 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In her 2016 live performances, Sia's music is part of performance-art-like shows that involve dance and theatrical effects.<ref name=\"Harrington, Jim\"/><ref name=\"seattle times\">{{cite web | url=http://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/music/hitmaker-sia-kicks-off-nostalgia-for-the-present-tour-at-keyarena | title=Hitmaker Sia begins 'Nostalgic for the Present' tour at the Key | work=Seattle Times | date=1 October 2016 | accessdate=1 October 2016 | author=De Barros, Paul | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160925170836/http://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/music/hitmaker-sia-kicks-off-nostalgia-for-the-present-tour-at-keyarena/ | archive-date=25 September 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> For an [[MTV News]] writer \"Sia's throaty, slurred vocals are her norm\",<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2741713/rihanna-adele-and-what-happens-when-female-voices-show-their-pain/ | title=Rihanna, Adele, and What Happens When Female Voices Show Their Pain | work=MTV News | date=18 February 2016 | accessdate=2 October 2016 | author=Cills, Hazel | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161003194908/http://www.mtv.com/news/2741713/rihanna-adele-and-what-happens-when-female-voices-show-their-pain/ | archive-date=3 October 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> while a ''[[The Fader]]'' contributor noted \"In the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 landscape, Sia's songwriting voice, which deals with depression and addiction, is singular\u2014her actual voice even more so.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thefader.com/2016/01/21/sia-voice-this-is-acting-rihanna-beyonce | title=How Sia's Polarising Vocals Have Invaded The Pop Mainstream | work=The Fader | date=21 January 2016 | accessdate=2 October 2016 | author=Cliff, Aimee | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921170921/http://www.thefader.com/2016/01/21/sia-voice-this-is-acting-rihanna-beyonce | archive-date=21 September 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> ''Everyday Is Christmas'' (2017), Sia's first release of [[Christmas music]] is a pop album that gives old-fashioned holiday music \"some 21st century pop gloss\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Phares|first1=Heather|title=Sia: Everyday Is Christmas|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/everyday-is-christmas-mw0003118444|website=AllMusic|accessdate=13 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180717013042/https://www.allmusic.com/album/everyday-is-christmas-mw0003118444|archive-date=17 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> National Public Radio called Sia \"the 21st century's most resilient songwriter\".<ref>St. Asaph, Katherine. [https://wamu.org/story/18/11/06/sia-is-the-21st-centurys-most-resilient-songwriter \"Sia Is The 21st Century's Most Resilient Songwriter\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181107145333/https://wamu.org/story/18/11/06/sia-is-the-21st-centurys-most-resilient-songwriter/ |date=7 November 2018 }}, NPR, 6 November 2018</ref>\n\nSia has received an array of accolades, including [[ARIA Awards]], an [[MTV Video Music Award]]<ref name=ARIA2014/> and nine nominations for [[Grammy Award]]s.<ref name=GrammyNoms2015/><ref name=GrammyNoms2017/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2012/12/05/grammy-nominees-list/1749735|title=55th annual Grammy Awards nominees|work=[[USA Today]]|accessdate=17 March 2014|date=16 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140314035249/http://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2012/12/05/grammy-nominees-list/1749735/|archive-date=14 March 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>\n{{Cite web |url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/sia |title=GRAMMY Awards Results for Sia |work=Grammy.com |accessdate=28 January 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171117112351/https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/sia |archive-date=17 November 2017 |url-status=live }}\n</ref>\n\n==Other ventures==\nSia lent her voice to the show ''[[South Park]]'' in its [[South Park (season 18)|eighteenth season]]. In episode 3 entitled \"[[The Cissy]]\", she portrayed [[Lorde]] in a parody song in the episode entitled \"Push (Feeling Good on a Wednesday)\". The resemblance was so convincing that many viewers thought Lorde had provided the voice in the song.<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Kaye|first1=Ben|title=''South Park'' releases full version of Lorde spoofing \"Push (Feel Good on a Wednesday)\" \u2013 listen|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2014/10/south-park-releases-full-version-of-lorde-spoofing-push-feel-good-on-a-wednesday-listen/|accessdate=18 September 2015|magazine=Consequence of Sound|date=16 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150927093640/http://consequenceofsound.net/2014/10/south-park-releases-full-version-of-lorde-spoofing-push-feel-good-on-a-wednesday-listen/|archive-date=27 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Sia wrote and recorded \"Angel by the Wings\", the title song for the documentary film ''[[The Eagle Huntress]]'', which premiered in 2016 at the [[Sundance Film Festival]].<ref>Brandle, Lars. [https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6844265/sia-angel-by-the-wings-eagle-huntress \"Sia Records 'Angel by the Wings' for New Film ''The Eagle Huntress'': Exclusive\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161024130827/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6844265/sia-angel-by-the-wings-eagle-huntress |date=24 October 2016 }}, ''Billboard'', 20 January 2016, accessed 4 November 2016</ref><ref>Guerrasio, Jason. [http://www.businessinsider.com/the-eagle-huntress-daisy-ridley-sia-2016-9 \"How a movie about eagle hunting nabbed a ''Star Wars'' lead actor and a chart-topping singer\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161105033025/http://www.businessinsider.com/the-eagle-huntress-daisy-ridley-sia-2016-9 |date=5 November 2016 }}, ''[[Business Insider]]'', 24 September 2016, accessed 4 November 2016</ref> In 2016 Sia covered \"[[Blackbird (Beatles song)|Blackbird]]\" by [[The Beatles]] for the [[Netflix]] original series ''[[Beat Bugs]]''.<ref name=\"blackbirdsia\">{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/sia-pink-beat-bugs-beatles-covers_us_57a0d767e4b0693164c2db69|title=Listen To Sia And Pink Cover The Beatles For Netflix's Adorable 'Beat Bugs'|first=Julia|last=Brucculieri|date=2 August 2016|accessdate=11 March 2017|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312064411/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/sia-pink-beat-bugs-beatles-covers_us_57a0d767e4b0693164c2db69|archive-date=12 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> She appeared in the 2017 animated film ''[[My Little Pony: The Movie (2017 film)|My Little Pony: The Movie]]'' as the voice of \"pop star\" character Songbird Serenade. She also contributed an original song, \"[[Rainbow (Sia song)|Rainbow]]\", to [[My Little Pony: The Movie (soundtrack)|the film's soundtrack]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/comic-con-sia-joins-my-little-pony-movie-1201820722/|title=Sia Joins the Voice Cast of 'My Little Pony: The Movie\u2019|work=Variety|date=22 July 2016|accessdate=22 July 2016|first=Dave|last=McNary|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160723163849/http://variety.com/2016/film/news/comic-con-sia-joins-my-little-pony-movie-1201820722/|archive-date=23 July 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSia wrote a screenplay based on a one-page story that she had written in 2007.<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Anderson|first1=Ariston|title=Venice: Sia Explains Why She's Directing Her Maddie Ziegler Screenplay|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/venice-sia-says-film-starring-820853|accessdate=18 September 2015|magazine=The Hollywood Reporter|date=7 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150911054358/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/venice-sia-says-film-starring-820853|archive-date=11 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Maddie Ziegler]] stars in the project, along with [[Kate Hudson]] and [[Leslie Odom Jr.]]. The musical, titled ''[[Music (upcoming film)|Music]]'', is directed by Sia and is expected to feature a soundtrack performed by her. It is set for release in 2020.<ref>Chikhoune, Ryma. [https://wwd.com/fashion-news/fashion-scoops/kate-hudson-chats-happyxnature-sustainability-and-starring-in-sias-anticipated-film-music-1203400388 \"Kate Hudson Chats HappyxNature, Sustainability and Starring in Sia's Anticipated Film ''Music''\"], WWD, 13 December 2019</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/sia-face-songs-chandelier-maddie-ziegler-712691/|title=How Sia Saved Herself|last=Aron|first=Hillel|date=24 August 2018|website=Rolling Stone|access-date=15 February 2020}}</ref> Sia wrote the songs for the [[Vox Lux (soundtrack)|soundtrack]] to the 2018 musical film ''[[Vox Lux]]'', with a score by [[Scott Walker (singer)|Scott Walker]].<ref name=Barfield>{{cite web| url=https://theplaylist.net/sia-scott-walker-vox-lux-20180821| title=Sia & Scott Walker Providing The Music For Natalie Portman Musical Drama ''Vox Lux''| last=Barfield| first=Charles| date=21 August 2018| accessdate=23 August 2018| work=The Playlist| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823210559/https://theplaylist.net/sia-scott-walker-vox-lux-20180821/| archive-date=23 August 2018| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nFollowing the disbandment of Crisp in 1997, Sia decided to move to London to follow her relationship with boyfriend Dan Pontifex.<ref name=\"FT06072014\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fashiontimes.com/articles/8205/20140607/sia-furlers-mystery-fiance-revealed-singer-songwriter-engaged-american-documentary.htm |title=Sia Furler's Mystery Fiance Revealed! Singer Songwriter Is Engaged to American Documentary Maker Erik Anders Lang |date=7 June 2014 |work=Fashion Times |accessdate=24 November 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151125065234/http://www.fashiontimes.com/articles/8205/20140607/sia-furlers-mystery-fiance-revealed-singer-songwriter-engaged-american-documentary.htm |archivedate=25 November 2015 }}</ref> Several weeks later, while on a stopover in Thailand, she received the news that Pontifex had died after being in a car accident in London.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Dan Pontifex Award \u2013 win a scholarship to Australia|url = http://www.jancisrobinson.com/articles/dan-pontifex-award-win-a-scholarship-to-australia|website = www.jancisrobinson.com|accessdate = 24 November 2015|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151125084342/http://www.jancisrobinson.com/articles/dan-pontifex-award-win-a-scholarship-to-australia|archive-date = 25 November 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> She returned to Australia, but soon she received a call from one of Pontifex's former housemates, who invited her to stay in London.<ref name=\"SMHSia\"/> Her 2001 album ''Healing Is Difficult'' lyrically deals with Pontifex's death: \"I was pretty fucked up after Dan died. I couldn't really feel anything. I could intellectualise a lot of stuff; that I had a purpose, that I was loved, but I couldn't actually feel anything.\" Sia recalled the effect of his death in a 2007 interview for ''[[The Sunday Times]]'': \"We were all devastated, so we got shit-faced on drugs and [[Special Brew]]. Unfortunately, that bender lasted six years for me.\"<ref name=Age>{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/music/sia-reveals-hearbreaking-reason-she-wears-wigs-in-james-cordens-carpool-karaoke-20160218-gmxa3r.html|title=Sia reveals reason she wears wigs in James Corden's Carpool Karaoke|work=The Age|date=18 February 2016|access-date=22 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161231161605/http://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/music/sia-reveals-hearbreaking-reason-she-wears-wigs-in-james-cordens-carpool-karaoke-20160218-gmxa3r.html|archive-date=31 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Verrico\">{{Cite news | url = http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/culture/music/article77556.ece | title = A Woman on the Verge | last1 = Verrico | first1 = Lisa | newspaper = [[The Sunday Times]] | date = 30 December 2007 | accessdate = 7 July 2011 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150114174024/http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/culture/music/article77556.ece | archive-date = 14 January 2015 | url-status=live }}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Sia discussed her sexual orientation in interviews<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kregloe|first1=Karman|title=Sia's Coming Out|url=http://www.afterellen.com/people/29001-sias-coming-out|accessdate=18 January 2015|work=[[AfterEllen.com]]|date=10 February 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150118085457/http://www.afterellen.com/people/29001-sias-coming-out|archive-date=18 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> and revealed her relationship with [[JD Samson]];<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nymag.com/guides/summer/2010/66785/|title=Sia, the Power Balladist Who Wants to Party|last=Murphy|first=Tim|date=20 June 2010|website=NYMag.com|publisher=|access-date=22 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170315072214/http://nymag.com/guides/summer/2010/66785/|archive-date=15 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> they broke up in 2011.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jeffs|first1=Lotte|title=Hit girl Sia ... the singer who writes Rihanna and Jessie J's chart-toppers|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/esmagazine/hit-girl-sia--the-singer-who-writes-rihanna-and-jessie-js-charttoppers-8319507.html|accessdate=18 January 2015|work=[[London Evening Standard]]|date=16 November 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150119020133/http://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/esmagazine/hit-girl-sia--the-singer-who-writes-rihanna-and-jessie-js-charttoppers-8319507.html|archive-date=19 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Sia, J.D. Samson Confirm Split|url=http://www.advocate.com/news/daily-news/2011/06/13/sia-jd-samson-split|accessdate=18 January 2015|work=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]|date=13 June 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150104030344/http://www.advocate.com/news/daily-news/2011/06/13/sia-jd-samson-split|archive-date=4 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> When asked about her sexuality in 2009, she said, \"I've always dated boys and girls and anything in between. I don't care what gender you are, it's about people. ... I've always been... well, flexible is the word I would use.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.samesame.com.au/25/2009/SiaFurler |title=Sia Furler: The Same Same 25, the 25 Most Influential Gay and Lesbian Australians |work=samesame.com.au |year=2009 |accessdate=30 September 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170224055513/http://www.samesame.com.au/25/2009/SiaFurler |archivedate=24 February 2017 }}</ref>\n\nSia has suffered from depression, addictions to painkillers and alcohol, and had contemplated suicide, going as far as to write a suicide note.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Knopper|first1=Steve|title=Sia Furler, the Socially Phobic Pop Star|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/20/magazine/sia-furler-the-socially-phobic-pop-star.html?_r=0|accessdate=18 January 2015|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=18 April 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129165206/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/20/magazine/sia-furler-the-socially-phobic-pop-star.html?_r=0|archive-date=29 November 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2010, Sia cancelled various promotional events and shows due to her poor health.<ref name=\"SiaStop\">{{cite web| url=http://www.siamusic.net/news-blogs/important-sia-announcement|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100628081118/http://www.siamusic.net/news-blogs/important-sia-announcement|title=*** important sia announcement ***|archivedate=28 June 2010|work=siamusic.net}}</ref> She cited extreme lethargy and panic attacks and considered retiring permanently from performing and touring. She stated that she had been diagnosed with [[Graves' disease]]&nbsp;\u2013 an [[autoimmune]] disorder characterized by an over-active [[thyroid]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/music/sia-furler-fame-does-not-become-her-20100617-yjdr.html|title=Sia Furler: Fame does not become her|work=[[The Age]]|first=Andrew|last=Murfett|date=18 June 2010|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150108204138/http://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/music/sia-furler-fame-does-not-become-her-20100617-yjdr.html|archive-date=8 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Later that year, in an ARIA Awards interview, Sia said her health was improving after rest and thyroid hormone replacement therapy.<ref name=\"JJJInterview\">{{cite web| url=http://www.inertia-music.com/2010/10/stream-sia-chats-about-aria-awards-recovery-and-pop-stardom|title=Sia Chats About ARIA Awards|publisher=Inertia Music|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110311001119/http://www.inertia-music.com/2010/10/stream-sia-chats-about-aria-awards-recovery-and-pop-stardom/|archivedate=11 March 2011}}</ref> In 2019, Sia revealed that she suffers from [[Ehlers\u2013Danlos syndromes|Ehlers\u2013Danlos syndrome]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.medpagetoday.com/blogs/celebritydiagnosis/82650?eun=g1256810d0r|title=Pop Star Sia Opens Up About Her Chronic Pain|website=[[MedPage Today]]|last1=Berman|first1=Michele R.|last2=Boguski|first2=Mark S.|date=10 October 2019|accessdate=13 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nSia married documentary filmmaker Erik Anders Lang at her home in [[Palm Springs, California]], in August 2014.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sia Furler gets married in US|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/latest-news/sia-furler-gets-married-in-us/story-fn3dxix6-1227012334021|work=The Australian|date=4 August 2014|access-date=4 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150117154220/http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/latest-news/sia-furler-gets-married-in-us/story-fn3dxix6-1227012334021|archive-date=17 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The couple revealed their separation in December 2016.<ref>Mizoguchi, Karen and Jeff Nelson. [http://people.com/music/sia-separates-from-husband-erik-anders-lang \"Sia Separates from Husband Erik Anders Lang: 'We Are Dedicated to Remaining Friends'\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161209132452/http://people.com/music/sia-separates-from-husband-erik-anders-lang/ |date=9 December 2016 }}, ''People'' magazine, 7 December 2016</ref> During a 2014 appearance on ''[[The Howard Stern Show]]'', Sia was asked if she was religious, to which she responded, \"I believe in a [[Higher Power]] and it's called 'Whatever Dude' and he's a [[queer]], surfing [[Santa Claus|Santa]] that's a bit like my grandpa, so yes.\"<ref name=\"10 Things\">{{cite magazine |first=Greg |last=Moskovitch |url=http://musicfeeds.com.au/news/10-things-we-learned-from-sias-howard-stern-interview/ |title=10 Things We Learned From Sia's Howard Stern Interview |date=19 June 2014 |magazine=[[Music Feeds]] |accessdate=5 June 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150316065608/http://musicfeeds.com.au/news/10-things-we-learned-from-sias-howard-stern-interview/ |archive-date=16 March 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the same interview, she stated that she is a feminist and that Whatever Dude [[Divine inspiration|divinely inspired]] the lyrics she wrote for [[Rihanna]]'s song \"[[Diamonds (Rihanna song)|Diamonds]]\".<ref name=\"10 Things\" /> One of Sia's tattoos, on her hand, reads \"Whatever Dude\".<ref>Jung, E. Alex. [https://www.vulture.com/2014/05/maddie-ziegler-sia-chandelier-video-chat.html \"Maddie Ziegler on Sia\u2019s 'Chandelier' Video, ''Dance Moms'', and Drew Barrymore\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160928041025/http://www.vulture.com/2014/05/maddie-ziegler-sia-chandelier-video-chat.html |date=28 September 2016 }}, [[New York (magazine)|Vulture.com]], 21 May 2014, accessed 23 September 2016</ref> Sia is a cousin of Australian [[Christian rock]] musician [[Peter Furler]].<ref>{{cite web |URL=http://m.sunshinecoastdaily.com.au/news/beyonces-rave-review-aussie-songwriter-sia-furler/2119840/ |title=Beyonce's rave review for Aussie songwriter Sia Furler |date=19 December 2013 |publisher=Australian Regional Media |access-date=16 June 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150618174051/http://m.sunshinecoastdaily.com.au/news/beyonces-rave-review-aussie-songwriter-sia-furler/2119840/ |archive-date=18 June 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, Sia told Gabriella Paiella of ''[[GQ]]'' that she had recently adopted a son and has \"decided to be single for the rest of [her] life.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gq.com/story/diplo-profile-february-2020|title=14 Hours Inside the Relentless, Often-Shirtless World of Diplo|last=Paiella|first=Gabriella|website=GQ|language=en|access-date=2020-01-14}}</ref>\n\n==Activism==\nSia, who is [[vegan]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Sia/status/465781323089473536|title=sia on Twitter: '@HectorRochas I will! I'm fully vegan now!'|author=Sia|date=12 May 2014|work=[[Twitter]]|accessdate=21 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401214128/https://twitter.com/Sia/status/465781323089473536|archive-date=1 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> participated in an advertisement for [[People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals|PETA Asia-Pacific]], with her dog, Pantera, to encourage pet [[neutering]].<ref name=\"Baker\">{{cite web|url=http://blog.petaasiapacific.com/companion-animals/sia-wants-you-to-take-a-bite-out-of-animal-overpopulation |title=Sia Wants You to 'Take a Bite Out of Animal Overpopulation' |publisher=PETA |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100618012250/http://blog.petaasiapacific.com/companion-animals/sia-wants-you-to-take-a-bite-out-of-animal-overpopulation |archivedate=18 June 2010 }}</ref> Sia has also joined other publicly known figures for the \"Oscar's Law\" campaign, in protest against large-scale pet breeding. Other advocates include singers [[Jon Stevens]], [[Paul Dempsey]], [[Rachael Leahcar]] and [[Missy Higgins]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Home|url=http://www.oscarslaw.org/|work=Oscar's law|publisher=Oscar's Law|accessdate=13 October 2012|year=2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121031141139/http://www.oscarslaw.org/|archive-date=31 October 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\nShe is also a supporter of the Beagle Freedom Project, performing \"I'm in Here\" live at the Beagle Freedom Project Gala on 9 September 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=Meet the Hollywood Hounds! |url=http://www.beaglefreedomproject.org/meet_the_hollywood_hound |work=Beagle Freedom Project |publisher=Beagle Freedom Project |accessdate=9 February 2015 |year=2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150209135123/http://www.beaglefreedomproject.org/meet_the_hollywood_hound |archivedate=9 February 2015 }}</ref> For her 2016 [[Nostalgic for the Present Tour]], Sia partnered with various rescue organizations to conduct a dog adoption fair at each of her concerts.<ref>[http://www.peta.org.au/news/sia-dog-adoption-concerts/ \"Sia Sets Up Dog-Adoption Fairs at Her Concerts\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161123201629/http://www.peta.org.au/news/sia-dog-adoption-concerts/ |date=23 November 2016 }}, PETA Australia, 11 October 2016, Retrieved 22 November 2016.</ref> Sia was nominated for a 2016 Libby Award for \"Best Voice for Animals\".<ref>[http://features.peta2.com/libby-awards-2016/#voteRegistrationDiv \"11th Annual Libby Awards\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161123201110/http://features.peta2.com/libby-awards-2016/#voteRegistrationDiv |date=23 November 2016 }}, peta2.com. Retrieved 22 November 2016.</ref> The video for her 2016 single [[The Greatest (Sia song)|\"The Greatest\"]] was a pro-[[LGBT]] tribute to the 49 people killed in the [[Orlando nightclub shooting|Pulse Orlando Shooting]].<ref>Havens, Lyndsey. [https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7496119/sia-the-greatest-video-orlando-nightclub-shooting-tribute-49-dancers \"Sia's 'The Greatest' Video Features 49 Dancers in Tribute to Orlando Shooting Victims\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180901003803/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7496119/sia-the-greatest-video-orlando-nightclub-shooting-tribute-49-dancers |date=1 September 2018 }}, ''Billboard'', 6 September 2016, accessed 24 October 2018</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{main|Sia discography}}\n{{see also|LSD (group)#Discography}}\n* ''OnlySee'' (1997)\n* ''[[Healing Is Difficult]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[Colour the Small One]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Some People Have Real Problems]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[We Are Born]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[1000 Forms of Fear]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[This Is Acting]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Everyday Is Christmas (album)|Everyday Is Christmas]]'' (2017)\n\n==Tours==\n* [[We Meaning You Tour]] (2010\u20132011)\n* [[We Are Born Tour]] (2011)\n* [[Nostalgic for the Present Tour]] (2016\u20132017)\n\n==Filmography==\n{{further|Sia discography}}\n\nSia wrote and/or performed songs on the following film soundtracks:\n{{Div col}}\n* ''[[The Twilight Saga: Eclipse]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[Burlesque (2010 American film)|Burlesque]]'' (2010)\n* [[The Great Gatsby (2013 film)|''The Great Gatsby'']] (2013)\n* ''[[The Hunger Games: Catching Fire]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[Annie (2014 film)|Annie]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[Transparent (TV series)|Transparent]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[Racing Extinction]]'' (2015)\n* [[Fifty Shades of Grey (film)|''Fifty Shades of Grey'']] (2015)\n* ''[[Pitch Perfect 2]]'' (2015)\n* [[San Andreas (film)|''San Andreas'']] (2015)\n* ''[[Beat Bugs]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[The Eagle Huntress]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Zootopia]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Finding Dory]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[The Neon Demon]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Star Trek Beyond]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Lion (2016 film)|Lion]]'' (2016)<ref name=\"Spanos2\" />\n* ''[[Fifty Shades Darker (film)|Fifty Shades Darker]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Wonder Woman (2017 film)|Wonder Woman]]'' (2017)<ref name=\"Spanos2\" />\n* [[My Little Pony: The Movie (2017 film)|''My Little Pony: The Movie'']] (2017)\n* ''[[Fifty Shades Freed (film)|Fifty Shades Freed]]'' (2018)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Sia/status/950424054091173888|title=The final chapter is coming & Sia's song 'Deer In Headlights' is on the #FiftyShadesFreed soundtrack, out February 9th! Pre-order the album this Friday. - Team Siapic.twitter.com/enXPnFLNR4|last=sia|first=|date=8 January 2018|website=@Sia|language=en|accessdate=10 January 2018}}</ref>\n* ''[[A Wrinkle in Time (2018 film)|A Wrinkle in Time]]'' (2018)<ref>{{cite news|last=Snetiker|first=Marc|title=A Wrinkle in Time soundtrack taps Sade, Sia, Game of Thrones composer|url=https://ew.com/movies/2018/02/20/a-wrinkle-in-time-soundtrack-sade-game-of-thrones-composer/|accessdate=20 February 2018|work=[[Entertainment 