{"title_page": "Pok\u00e9mon Sun and Moon", "text_new": "{{For|the twentieth season of the ''Pok\u00e9mon'' animated series|List of Pok\u00e9mon: Sun & Moon episodes}}\n{{Redirect|SuMo|other uses|Sumo (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:''Pok\u00e9mon Sun'' and ''Moon''}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title        = {{ubl|''Pok\u00e9mon Sun''|''Pok\u00e9mon Moon''}}\n| italic title = no\n| image        = Pokemon Sun Boxart.jpg\n| caption      = North American box art for ''Pok\u00e9mon Sun'', depicting the [[legendary Pok\u00e9mon]] [[Solgaleo]]. The box art for ''Pok\u00e9mon Moon'' depicts the legendary Pok\u00e9mon [[Lunala]] (not pictured).\n| developer    = [[Game Freak]]\n| publisher    = {{ubl|[[The Pok\u00e9mon Company]]|[[Nintendo]]}}\n| director     = Shigeru Ohmori\n| producer     = {{ubl|[[Junichi Masuda]]|Shin Uwai|Takato Utsunomiya|Hitoshi Yamagami|[[Shinya Takahashi]]}}\n| designer     = Shigeru Ohmori\n| programmer   = Sosuke Tamada\n| artist       = Takao Unno\n| writer       = {{ubl|Toshinobu Matsumiya|Suguru Nakatsui|Kenji Matsushima|Masafumi Nukita}}\n| composer     = {{ubl|Minako Adachi|Go Ichinose|Junichi Masuda|Hitomi Sato|Tomoaki Oga|Hideaki Kuroda}}\n| series       = ''[[Pok\u00e9mon (video game series)|Pok\u00e9mon]]''\n| platforms    = [[Nintendo 3DS]]\n| released     = {{Video game release|WW|November 18, 2016|EU|November 23, 2016}}\n| genre        = [[Role-playing video game|Role-playing]]\n| modes        = [[Single-player]], [[multiplayer]]\n}}\n\n{{nihongo foot|'''''Pok\u00e9mon Sun''''' and '''''Pok\u00e9mon Moon'''''|\u30dd\u30b1\u30c3\u30c8\u30e2\u30f3\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u3000\u30b5\u30f3\u30fb\u30e0\u30fc\u30f3|Poketto Monsut\u0101 San\u30fbPoketto Monsut\u0101 M\u016bn|\"Pocket Monsters: Sun & Pocket Monsters: Moon\"|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} are 2016 [[role-playing video games]] developed by [[Game Freak]], published by [[The Pok\u00e9mon Company]] and [[Nintendo]] for the [[Nintendo 3DS]]. They are the first installments in the seventh generation of the [[Pok\u00e9mon (video game series)|''Pok\u00e9mon'' video game series]]. First announced in February 2016, ''Sun'' and ''Moon'' were released worldwide on November 18, 2016,<!-- Generalize the release dates in the lead, per WP:VG/DATE. --> commemorating [[Pok\u00e9mon|the franchise]]'s 20th anniversary. Two follow-up games, [[Pok\u00e9mon Ultra Sun and Ultra Moon|''Pok\u00e9mon Ultra Sun'' and ''Pok\u00e9mon Ultra Moon'']], were released for the same consoles on November 17, 2017.\n\nThe titles began development following completion of [[Pok\u00e9mon Omega Ruby and Alpha Sapphire|''Pok\u00e9mon Omega Ruby'' and ''Alpha Sapphire'']], with increased emphasis on Pok\u00e9mon interactions. Like previous installments, they follow the journey of a young Pok\u00e9mon trainer, taking place in the Alola region\u2014based on [[Hawaii]]\u2014with the objective of the games being to complete the island challenge and thwart the schemes of Team Skull, and later the Aether Foundation, all while attempting to challenge various Pok\u00e9mon trainers of gradually increasing difficulty. ''Sun'' and ''Moon'' introduced [[List of generation VII Pok\u00e9mon|81 new Pok\u00e9mon]] species, and new features such as Alolan forms of previous generation Pok\u00e9mon, powerful moves known as Z-Moves, alien creatures known as Ultra Beasts, updated battle and training mechanics, and improved [[Polygonal modeling|polygonal 3D graphics]]. While largely independent of one another, the two games follow a similar plot, and while each can be played separately, trading Pok\u00e9mon between the two games is necessary to complete the Pok\u00e9dex, just like in previous installments.\n\nThe games received generally favorable reviews from critics, who welcomed the change from the formula used by prior ''Pok\u00e9mon'' games and praised the gameplay of ''Sun'' and ''Moon'' while criticizing the lack of content beyond the primary plot. Upon release, the games became one of the fastest-selling games in Nintendo's history. To date, ''Sun'' and ''Moon'' have sold over 16 million copies worldwide, making them the third-best-selling Nintendo 3DS titles, after ''[[Mario Kart 7]]'' and their predecessors, [[Pok\u00e9mon X and Y|''Pok\u00e9mon X'' and ''Y'']].\n\n==Gameplay==\n{{see also|Gameplay of Pok\u00e9mon}}\n''Pok\u00e9mon Sun'' and ''Moon'' are [[role-playing video game]]s with [[adventure game|adventure]] elements, set in the fictional Alola region (loosely based on Hawaii),<ref name=\"weknow\">{{cite news |last1=Alexander |first1=Julia |title=Pok\u00e9mon Moon and Sun: Everything we know |url=https://www.polygon.com/2016/6/14/11936306/pokemon-moon-and-sun-everything-we-know |accessdate=5 July 2019 |work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |date=14 June 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190705212911/https://www.polygon.com/2016/6/14/11936306/pokemon-moon-and-sun-everything-we-know |archive-date=July 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> presented in a [[Grammatical person#Use of grammatical person in creative media|third-person]], [[overhead perspective]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Minotti |first1=Mike |title=Pok\u00e9mon Sun and Moon make a good first impression with their formula-shaking tweaks |url=https://venturebeat.com/2016/11/17/pokemon-sun-and-moon-make-a-good-first-impression-with-their-formula-shaking-tweaks/ |accessdate=5 July 2019 |work=[[VentureBeat]] |date=17 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190705212913/https://venturebeat.com/2016/11/17/pokemon-sun-and-moon-make-a-good-first-impression-with-their-formula-shaking-tweaks/ |archive-date=July 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The player controls a young trainer who goes on a quest to catch and train creatures known as Pok\u00e9mon, and win battles against other trainers.<ref name=\"weknow\"/> By defeating opposing Pok\u00e9mon in turn-based battles, the player's Pok\u00e9mon gains [[experience points|experience]], allowing them to level up and increase their battle statistics, learn new battle techniques, and in some cases, [[Pok\u00e9mon evolution|evolve]] into more powerful Pok\u00e9mon. Players can capture wild Pok\u00e9mon, found during [[random encounter]]s, by weakening them in battle and catching them with [[Pok\u00e9 Ball]]s, allowing them to be added to their [[Party (role-playing games)|party]]. Players are also able to battle and [[Pok\u00e9mon trading|trade]] Pok\u00e9mon with other human players using the Nintendo 3DS' connectivity features. As with previous games in the series, certain Pok\u00e9mon are only obtainable in either ''Sun'' or ''Moon'', with players encouraged to trade with others in order to obtain all Pok\u00e9mon from both versions.<ref>{{cite web |title=Pok\u00e9mon Black Version Instruction Booklet |url=https://www.nintendo.com/consumer/gameslist/manuals/DS_Pokemon_Black.pdf |publisher=[[Nintendo]] |accessdate=5 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180911142039/https://www.nintendo.com/consumer/gameslist/manuals/DS_Pokemon_Black.pdf |archive-date=September 11, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Pokemon Sun & Moon guide: version differences, plus where to find & catch exclusive Pokemon |url=https://www.vg247.com/2016/11/22/pokemon-sun-moon-guide-version-differences-plus-where-to-find-catch-exclusive-pokemon/ |accessdate=5 July 2019 |work=[[VG247]] |date=22 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190705212912/https://www.vg247.com/2016/11/22/pokemon-sun-moon-guide-version-differences-plus-where-to-find-catch-exclusive-pokemon/ |archive-date=July 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===New features===\n{{see also|List of generation VII Pok\u00e9mon}}\n[[File:Pokemon sm screenshot.png|thumb|The bottom screen in ''Sun'' and ''Moon'' is occupied by a [[Rotom]], showing a map of the player's location. The red flag indicates a story waypoint.]]\n''Pok\u00e9mon Sun'' and ''Moon'' are presented in fully [[3D computer graphics|three dimensional]] (3D) [[polygonal graphics]], like their predecessors, allowing for more interactivity with the overworld and more dynamic action during battles. However, the character models in ''Sun'' and ''Moon'' possess more realistic proportions compared to [[chibi (slang)|chibi]]-styled models used in [[Pok\u00e9mon X and Y|''Pokemon X'' and ''Y'']] or [[Pok\u00e9mon Omega Ruby and Alpha Sapphire|''Pok\u00e9mon Omega Ruby'' and ''Alpha Sapphire'']].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Garcia|first1=Edwin|title=POK\u00c9MON SUN and MOON's Subtle Changes Are Super Effective (Preview)|url=https://nerdist.com/pokemon-sun-and-moons-subtle-changes-are-super-effective-preview/|accessdate=10 February 2018|work=[[Nerdist]]|date=25 October 2016|language=en|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180211131337/https://nerdist.com/pokemon-sun-and-moons-subtle-changes-are-super-effective-preview/|archivedate=February 11, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Players are also able to customize their Pok\u00e9mon trainer's appearance, choosing gender, skin tone and hair color at the start of the game and can later acquire outfits and accessories to change their character's appearance. Joining the previous generations of Pok\u00e9mon are all new species, such as the new [[starter Pok\u00e9mon]]; [[Rowlet]], [[List of generation VII Pok\u00e9mon#Litten|Litten]] and [[Popplio]] and the Pok\u00e9mon that are, within the fictional Pok\u00e9mon world, described as legendary, namely [[Solgaleo]] and [[Lunala]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/finally-the-evolved-forms-of-pokemon-sun-moons-rowlet-litten-and-popplio-are-here/ |title=Finally, the evolved forms of Pokemon Sun & Moon's Rowlet, Popplio, and Litten are here |work=[[GamesRadar]] |accessdate=October 23, 2016 |date=October 4, 2016 |author=Prell, Sam |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161024104027/http://www.gamesradar.com/finally-the-evolved-forms-of-pokemon-sun-moons-rowlet-litten-and-popplio-are-here/ |archivedate=October 24, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Legendary Pok\u00e9mon unveiled for Pok\u00e9mon Sun and Pok\u00e9mon Moon |url=https://www.nintendo.co.uk/News/2016/June/Legendary-Pokemon-unveiled-for-Pokemon-Sun-and-Pokemon-Moon-1110956.html |publisher=[[Nintendo]] |accessdate=5 July 2019 |date=2 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n''Pok\u00e9mon Sun'' and ''Moon'' are the first entries in the series to be available in Chinese, both [[Simplified Chinese characters|Simplified]] and [[Traditional Chinese characters|Traditional]], along with English, French, Spanish, Italian, German, Japanese and Korean, for a total of nine available languages.<ref>\n{{cite web |url=http://www.mcvuk.com/news/read/pok-mon-targets-china-with-sun-and-moon/0163159 |title=Pok\u00e9mon targets China with Sun and Moon |first=Alex |last=Calvin |work=[[MCV (magazine)|MCV]] UK |date=February 26, 2016 |accessdate=May 1, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503194114/http://www.mcvuk.com/news/read/pok-mon-targets-china-with-sun-and-moon/0163159 |archivedate=May 3, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}\n</ref> The games introduce variants of Pok\u00e9mon introduced in older games with new typings and appearances, known as Alolan Forms. Alolan [[Vulpix and Ninetales]], which are Fire types in other regions, are respectively Ice and dual Ice and Fairy types. Alolan Sandshrew and Sandslash, which are Ground types in other regions, are Ice and Steel types. Alolan Meowth and Persian, which are Normal types in other regions, are Dark types. Some Pok\u00e9mon evolutions have gained dual typings as well, such as Alolan Marowak which is now a Fire and Ghost type and Alolan Raichu, an Electric and Psychic type.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2016/aug/02/pokemon-nintendo-alola-forms-exeggutor|title=Pok\u00e9mon introduces Alola forms \u2013 including a 36-foot Exeggutor|last=Hern|first=Alex|date=August 2, 2016|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|access-date=December 2, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161203064038/https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2016/aug/02/pokemon-nintendo-alola-forms-exeggutor|archivedate=December 3, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mic.com/articles/160225/pokemon-sun-and-moon-pokedex-how-many-new-pokemon-are-in-gen-7|title='Pok\u00e9mon Sun and Moon' Pok\u00e9dex: How many new Pok\u00e9mon are in Gen 7?|website=Mic|language=en|access-date=2019-12-15}}</ref> Throughout the game, players utilize a [[Rotom]]-possessed [[Pok\u00e9dex]] on the bottom [[touchscreen]], which displays a minimap containing markers for story objectives.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Phillips|first1=Tom|title=Pok\u00e9mon Sun and Moon's new Pok\u00e9dex is a Pok\u00e9mon|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-06-03-pokemon-sun-and-moons-new-pokedex-is-a-pokemon|accessdate=10 February 2018|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=3 June 2016|language=en-UK|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180211071642/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-06-03-pokemon-sun-and-moons-new-pokedex-is-a-pokemon|archivedate=February 11, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n''Pok\u00e9mon Sun'' and ''Moon'' introduce a powerful new type of move known as Z-Moves which can only be used once per battle.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nintendo.com/whatsnew/detail/z-moves-and-variants-in-pokemon-sun-and-pokemon-moon|title=Z-moves and Alolan Pok\u00e9mon variants announced for Pok\u00e9mon Sun and Pok\u00e9mon Moon|publisher=[[Nintendo]]|access-date=August 21, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822024329/http://www.nintendo.com/whatsnew/detail/z-moves-and-variants-in-pokemon-sun-and-pokemon-moon|archivedate=August 22, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Hidden Moves, which were used to navigate terrain in past games, have been replaced by specialized Pok\u00e9mon that can be summoned at will.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2016/10/19/13329864/pokemon-sun-and-moon-hms-removed-tms-ride-pokemon|title=Pok\u00e9mon Sun and Moon are changing one of the series' most frustrating mechanics|last=Frank|first=Allegra|date=19 October 2016|website=Polygon|language=en|access-date=7 November 2019}}</ref> The \"Pok\u00e9 Finder\" is a function of the Rotom Pok\u00e9dex which allows players to take photos of Pok\u00e9mon in the wild, similar to ''[[Pok\u00e9mon Snap]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/9/6/12814046/pokemon-sun-moon-photography-mode-pokemon-snap|title=Pok\u00e9mon Sun and Moon will let you take pictures Pok\u00e9mon Snap-style|last=Webster|first=Andrew|date=September 6, 2016|website=[[The Verge]]|access-date=September 7, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160906171905/http://www.theverge.com/2016/9/6/12814046/pokemon-sun-moon-photography-mode-pokemon-snap|archivedate=September 6, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2016/09/06/new-pokemon-sun-and-moon-details-new-pokemon-ultra-beasts-and-a-pokemon-snap-style-feature-revealed|title=New Pokemon Sun and Moon Details - New Pokemon, Ultra Beasts and a Pokemon Snap Style Feature Revealed|last=Skrebels|first=Joe|date=September 6, 2016|website=IGN|language=en-US|access-date=September 7, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160906205636/http://www.ign.com/articles/2016/09/06/new-pokemon-sun-and-moon-details-new-pokemon-ultra-beasts-and-a-pokemon-snap-style-feature-revealed|archivedate=September 6, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In addition, the two games' clocks are set 12 hours apart from each other, with ''Sun'' operating on the 3DS' time and ''Moon'' operating 12 hours ahead.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pokemon-sunmoon.com/en-us/sept-6-sunmoon-differences/|title=The Differences between Pok\u00e9mon Sun and Moon on Pok\u00e9mon Sun and Moon.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170402165835/http://www.pokemon-sunmoon.com/en-us/sept-6-sunmoon-differences/|publisher=[[The Pok\u00e9mon Company]]|archivedate=April 2, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Character customization as previously seen in ''X'' and ''Y'' returns in ''Sun'' and ''Moon''. A new \"Pok\u00e9mon Refresh\" feature enables players to care for and feed their Pok\u00e9mon.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/pokemon-sunmoon-new-creatures-revealed-bank-featur/1100-6443743/|title=Pokemon Sun/Moon: New Creatures Revealed, Bank Feature Delayed|access-date=September 21, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160924161211/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/pokemon-sunmoon-new-creatures-revealed-bank-featur/1100-6443743/|work=[[GameSpot]]|archivedate=September 24, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Mega Evolution]], a game mechanic first introduced in ''X'' and ''Y'', returns in ''Sun'' and ''Moon''.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/olliebarder/2016/10/05/pokemon-sun-and-moon-is-getting-a-demo-this-october/#61052abb4b5d|title='Pok\u00e9mon Sun And Moon' Is Getting A Demo This October|date=5 October 2016|last=Barder|first=Ollie|newspaper=[[Forbes.com]]|access-date=October 8, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161009035246/http://www.forbes.com/sites/olliebarder/2016/10/05/pokemon-sun-and-moon-is-getting-a-demo-this-october/#61052abb4b5d|archivedate=October 9, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The ''Battle Tree'' is a location which allows players to battle or team up with Pok\u00e9mon trainers, including Kanto region trainers Red and Blue.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nintendo-insider.com/2016/10/red-and-blue-return-in-pokemon-sun-and-moons-battle-tree/|title=Red And Blue Return In Pok\u00e9mon Sun And Moon's Battle Tree - Nintendo Insider|date=October 27, 2016|newspaper=Nintendo Insider|language=en-GB|access-date=December 2, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161129032823/http://www.nintendo-insider.com/2016/10/red-and-blue-return-in-pokemon-sun-and-moons-battle-tree/|archivedate=November 29, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Players can trade or battle with other players online.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pok\u00e9mon Sun & Moon's Festival Plaza Is A Very Giving Place|url=http://www.siliconera.com/2016/11/21/pokemon-sun-moons-festival-plaza-giving-place/|accessdate=2 January 2018|work=[[Siliconera]]|date=21 November 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180103072918/http://www.siliconera.com/2016/11/21/pokemon-sun-moons-festival-plaza-giving-place/|archivedate=January 3, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref> From a location called the Festival Plaza, players can participate in \"Global Missions\", where people from across the world work towards a set target \u2014 such as catching 100 million Pok\u00e9mon collectively.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Carden|first1=Dennis|title=The fourth Pokemon Sun and Moon Global Mission is already a resounding success|url=https://www.destructoid.com/the-fourth-pokemon-sun-and-moon-global-mission-is-already-a-resounding-success-421602.phtml|accessdate=2 January 2018|work=[[Destructoid]]|date=3 January 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170513071315/https://www.destructoid.com/the-fourth-pokemon-sun-and-moon-global-mission-is-already-a-resounding-success-421602.phtml|archivedate=May 13, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Connectivity===\nPok\u00e9mon caught in ''Pok\u00e9mon X'', ''Y'', ''Omega Ruby'' and ''Alpha Sapphire'' can be transferred to ''Sun'' and ''Moon''.<ref name=\"Pokemoncom\" /> The games are also compatible with ''[[Pok\u00e9mon Bank]]'', an online Pok\u00e9mon storage system introduced during the previous generation of ''Pok\u00e9mon'' games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pokemon-sunmoon.com/en-us/pokemon-bank/|title=Pok\u00e9mon Bank on Pok\u00e9mon Sun and Moon.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170403013334/http://www.pokemon-sunmoon.com/en-us/pokemon-bank/|archivedate=April 3, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In a special Pok\u00e9mon Direct on February 26, 2016, Tsunekazu Ishihara from The Pok\u00e9mon Company announced that Pok\u00e9mon caught in the [[Virtual Console]] versions of [[Pok\u00e9mon Red and Blue|''Red'', ''Blue'']], and ''[[Pok\u00e9mon Yellow|Yellow]]'' are transferable to ''Sun'' and ''Moon'' via ''Pok\u00e9mon Bank''. Compatibility with ''Pok\u00e9mon Bank'' was initially planned to be available at the games' launch but was delayed and later became available on January 24, 2017.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite web|last1=Macy|first1=Seth|title=Pokemon Bank Now Compatible With Sun and Moon|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2017/01/25/pokemon-bank-now-compatible-with-sun-and-moon|website=[[IGN]]|accessdate=January 25, 2017|date=January 24, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170125041407/http://www.ign.com/articles/2017/01/25/pokemon-bank-now-compatible-with-sun-and-moon|archivedate=January 25, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Tomy]] also released a peripheral interactive toy resembling a Z-Ring, which synchronizes with the use of Z-Moves in the games.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fahey|first1=Mike|title=Toy Time Plays With Pok\u00e9mon Sun And Moon's Z-Ring|url=https://kotaku.com/toy-time-plays-with-pokemon-sun-and-moons-z-ring-1789007852|accessdate=10 February 2018|work=[[Kotaku]]|date=18 November 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180211072228/https://kotaku.com/toy-time-plays-with-pokemon-sun-and-moons-z-ring-1789007852|archivedate=February 11, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n\n===Setting===\n[[File:Pok\u00e9mon Alola Region.jpg|thumb|right|The Alola region comprises several islands of varying sizes; from left to right: Exeggutor Island, Poni Island, Melemele Island, Akala Island, and Ula'ula Island. The white structure just south of Melemele is the [[very large floating structure]] Aether Paradise.]]\n[[File:Kauai (7635268890).jpg|right|thumb|The Alola region was heavily inspired by Hawaii, with Game Freak staff visiting the islands to conduct research for the games.]]\nThe games take place on a tropical archipelago, a group of islands known as the Alola region. Joe Skrebels of ''[[IGN]]'' describes it as \"''Pok\u00e9mon''{{'}}s take on [[Hawaii]]\".<ref>{{cite web|first=Joe|last=Skrebels|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=Ziff Davis|date=May 10, 2016|accessdate=May 10, 2016|title=Pokemon Sun and Moon: First Gameplay, New Starters, Region Revealed|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2016/05/10/pokemon-sun-and-moon-first-gameplay-new-starters-region-revealed|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160510183917/http://www.ign.com/articles/2016/05/10/pokemon-sun-and-moon-first-gameplay-new-starters-region-revealed|archivedate=May 10, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> During an interview at [[Electronic Entertainment Expo 2016|E3 2016]], Shigeru Ohmori noted that Game Freak staff took trips to Hawaii to conduct research for ''Sun'' and ''Moon''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UC-uLg_5RIA|title=Pok\u00e9mon Sun and Pok\u00e9mon Moon - Demonstration - Nintendo E3 2016|website=[[YouTube]]|publisher=[[Nintendo]]|at=33m 25s|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160616171938/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UC-uLg_5RIA|archivedate=June 16, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe leading scientist in the Alola region is Professor Kukui, whose name comes from the [[kukui]], also known as the [[candlenut]], the Hawaiian state tree, continuing the trend of ''Pok\u00e9mon'' professors being named after trees. Team Skull is the name of the villainous group in Alola.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/olliebarder/2016/08/12/team-skull-and-more-pokemon-join-pokemon-sun-and-moon/#43ea7156175c|title=Team Skull And More Pok\u00e9mon Join 'Pok\u00e9mon Sun And Moon'|last=Barder|first=Ollie|access-date=September 7, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921113848/http://www.forbes.com/sites/olliebarder/2016/08/12/team-skull-and-more-pokemon-join-pokemon-sun-and-moon/#43ea7156175c|archivedate=September 21, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.idigitaltimes.com/pokemon-sun-and-moon-new-pokemon-and-ultra-beasts-revealed-latest-trailer-554310|title='Pok\u00e9mon Sun And Moon': New Pok\u00e9mon And Ultra Beasts Revealed In Latest Trailer|date=September 6, 2016|access-date=September 9, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160909021550/http://www.idigitaltimes.com/pokemon-sun-and-moon-new-pokemon-and-ultra-beasts-revealed-latest-trailer-554310|archivedate=September 9, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The [[Aether Foundation]] is an organization which studies Ultra Beasts, mysterious creatures from another dimension.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/pokemon-sun-moon-new-trailer-new-pokemon-null-jangmo-o-alolan-raticate-ub-01-revealed-2412170|title='Pok\u00e9mon Sun And Moon' New Trailer: New Pok\u00e9mon Null, Jangmo-o, Alolan Raticate, UB-01 Revealed; Time Difference, Aether Foundation Announced|date=September 7, 2016|access-date=September 9, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160908213139/http://www.ibtimes.com/pokemon-sun-moon-new-trailer-new-pokemon-null-jangmo-o-alolan-raticate-ub-01-revealed-2412170|archivedate=September 8, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Though [[Professor Oak]] does not appear in ''Sun'' and ''Moon'', his cousin Samson Oak takes his place.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2016/9/8/12848132/pokemon-sun-and-moon-professor-oak|title=Professor Oak's not in Pok\u00e9mon Sun and Moon, but his chilled-out cousin is|last=Frank|first=Allegra|date=September 8, 2016|website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|language=en-US|access-date=September 8, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160909042729/http://www.polygon.com/2016/9/8/12848132/pokemon-sun-and-moon-professor-oak|archivedate=September 9, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Story===\nThe player starts off as a youngster moving from [[Kanto (Pok\u00e9mon)|Kanto]] to Alola's Melemele Island with their mother. After meeting Lillie and rescuing her special Pok\u00e9mon she calls Nebby, the player obtains a starter Pok\u00e9mon from local Professor, Kukui, and embark on the island challenge, a [[coming-of-age]] custom spanning trials across Alola, along with local youngster Hau. Unlike in previous games, trials involve battles with powered-up Pok\u00e9mon followed by battles with each island's Kahuna upon completion of an island's trials. Throughout this the player encounters Team Skull, a gang of people who quit the island trials whose members include their leader Guzma and enforcer Gladion. The player will also encounter the Aether Foundation, an organization aiming to shelter Pok\u00e9mon from various threats.\n\nDuring a visit to Aether Foundation's base, Aether Paradise\u2014a [[very large floating structure]]\u2014, a mysterious creature called an Ultra Beast emerges from a wormhole but retreats before it could be defeated or captured. Later, after the player has defeated Team Skull at their base, Gladion reveals that Team Skull had been working for Aether Foundation, kidnapping Nebby to use its powers in summoning Ultra Beasts. The player then proceeds to battle through Aether Paradise with Hau and Gladion's help, eventually defeating Aether president Lusamine, who is revealed to be Gladion and Lillie's mother. Despite this, Lusamine and Guzma manage to open an Ultra Wormhole, with the former overclocking Nebby's powers, transporting them to Ultra Space (the Ultra Beasts' dimension). This causes Nebby to evolve into a cocoon-like form while Ultra Beasts are unleashed on to Alola's islands, forcing the island Kahunas and [[guardian deity|guardian deities]] to fight them.\n\nProceeding to the final island, the player and Lillie perform a ritual to evolve Nebby into its final form \u2014 Solgaleo or Lunala depending on the version \u2014 at the island's Altar.{{efn|Nebby evolves into Solgaleo at the Altar of the Sunne in ''Sun''; in ''Moon'' it evolves into Lunala at the Altar of the Moone}} With Nebby's newfound power, the player and Lillie travel to Ultra Space and find Lusamine who, not wanting to be rescued, allows herself to be taken over by the Ultra Beast they encountered earlier, forcing the player to battle her in self-defense. After defeating the crazed Lusamine, the player returns to Alola and ascends Mount Lanakila to challenge the newly-formed Alola Pok\u00e9mon League Elite Four. In the last match, they defeat Kukui to become Alola's first Pok\u00e9mon League champion. In the credits, the player battles Melemele's guardian deity [[Tapu Koko]] after a celebration, with Lillie and Lusamine departing Alola for Kanto the following day.\n\nAfter becoming the champion, the player is contacted by two members of the International Police: Anabel (who was head of the Battle Tower in ''[[Pok\u00e9mon Emerald]]'') and Looker (a side character from Pok\u00e9mon Diamond, Pearl, and Platinum). The player assists the two with handling the wild Ultra Beasts that Lusamine let loose into Alola in a series of quests.{{efn|Ultra Beasts featured are Buzzwole and Kartana in ''Sun'', with Pheromosa and Celesteela in ''Moon''}} Following the final quest, Looker reveals that he saw another Ultra Beast, although Anabel dismisses this. If the player then travels to Ten Carat Hill, they will encounter [[Necrozma]].\n\n==Development==\nGame director Shigeru Ohmori stated that the choice of ''Sun'' and ''Moon'' as title was inspired by the two celestial bodies\u2019 metaphorical representation of human relationships.<ref name=\"timeint\"/> Hawaii was chosen as the basis for the game's region following the title's determination, due to its clear nights and plentiful sunshine.<ref name=\"noeint\">{{cite news|title=Learn all about Pok\u00e9mon Sun and Pok\u00e9mon Moon in our in-depth interview|url=https://www.nintendo.co.uk/News/2016/October/Learn-all-about-Pokemon-Sun-and-Pokemon-Moon-in-our-in-depth-interview-1149779.html|accessdate=December 27, 2017|work=Nintendo of Europe GmbH}}</ref> Development started immediately after ''Pok\u00e9mon Omega Ruby'' and ''Alpha Sapphire'' was completed and Ohmori kept his game director position. Since the games were to be released on the franchise's 20th anniversary, ''Sun'' and ''Moon'' were developed comparatively from scratch with the application of more radical changes than its predecessor.<ref name=\"timeint\">{{cite news|last1=Peckham|first1=Matt|title=Why the New Pok\u00e9mon are Called 'Sun and Moon'|url=http://time.com/4536438/pokemon-sun-moon-interview/|accessdate=December 27, 2017|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=October 29, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180103040644/http://time.com/4536438/pokemon-sun-moon-interview/|archivedate=January 3, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Separately, he also mentioned that the games' intended to place more emphasis on the Pok\u00e9mon and the nature of the games, in addition to the player's interactions with them.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bailey|first1=Kat|title=Interview: First-time Pok\u00e9mon Director Shigeru Ohmori Opens Up About Sun and Moon|url=http://www.usgamer.net/articles/interview-first-time-pokmon-director-shigeru-ohmori-opens-up-about-sun-and-moon|accessdate=December 27, 2017|work=USgamer|date=October 19, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171228112312/http://www.usgamer.net/articles/interview-first-time-pokmon-director-shigeru-ohmori-opens-up-about-sun-and-moon|archivedate=December 28, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe first Pok\u00e9mon of the seventh generation to be designed was [[Jangmo-o]]. Regarding the various other designs of the generation, Ohmori mentioned that \u201c[f]or the 20th anniversary, we wanted to have a lot of special surprises\u2026 we wanted a funny element\u201d.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hernandez|first1=Patricia|title=The Creators of Pok\u00e9mon Explain Why Sun and Moon Has Ridiculous Monster Designs|date=October 25, 2016|url=https://kotaku.com/the-creators-of-pokemon-explain-why-sun-and-moon-has-ri-1788191518|accessdate=December 27, 2017|work=[[Kotaku]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171228112317/https://kotaku.com/the-creators-of-pokemon-explain-why-sun-and-moon-has-ri-1788191518|archivedate=December 28, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Pok\u00e9mon from ''Red'' and ''Blue'' were the only ones to receive Alolan forms\u2014according to Ohmori, this was as a special surprise for long-time players and simply due to the older Pok\u00e9mon being more recognizable.<ref name=\"burn\">{{cite news|last1=Hillard|first1=Kyle|title=Burning Questions For Pok\u00e9mon Sun & Moon|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2016/10/19/burning-questions-for-pokemon-sun-and-moon.aspx|accessdate=December 27, 2017|work=[[Game Informer]]|date=October 19, 2016|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171228112238/http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2016/10/19/burning-questions-for-pokemon-sun-and-moon.aspx|archivedate=December 28, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Following the trend between newer generations of the main series, the designers of ''Sun'' and ''Moon'' focused on the motions on the full 3D models from ''X'' and ''Y'' in order to create livelier creatures.<ref name=\"noeint\"/>\n\nDespite the successes of ''[[Pok\u00e9mon Go]]'', the developers stated that it did not affect the development of ''Sun'' and ''Moon'', although it did improve public awareness of the franchise in general and that they were working to develop interactivity between the app and the main series.<ref name=\"burn\"/> Ohmori added that during the development of ''Sun'' and ''Moon'' they \"completely redesigned the system, and actually ended up pushing the 3DS even further to what [they] thought was the most [they] could draw out of it.\"<ref name=\"last\">{{cite news|url=http://ign.com/articles/2017/10/19/ultra-sun-and-ultra-moon-will-be-the-last-pokemon-rpgs-for-3ds|title=Ultra Sun and Ultra Moon will be the last Pok\u00e9mon RPGs for the 3DS|date=October 19, 2017|last1=Skrebels|first1=Joe|work=[[IGN]]|accessdate=December 27, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180201040246/http://www.ign.com/articles/2017/10/19/ultra-sun-and-ultra-moon-will-be-the-last-pokemon-rpgs-for-3ds|archivedate=February 1, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref> With a team of around 120, the games took about three years to develop, which is comparable with other new-generation games.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Haywald|first1=Justin|title=Pokemon Sun/Moon Devs on Legendaries, Pokemon Go, and the Origin of Pikachu|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/pokemon-sunmoon-devs-on-legendaries-pokemon-go-and/1100-6444620/|accessdate=December 27, 2017|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=October 19, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171228112232/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/pokemon-sunmoon-devs-on-legendaries-pokemon-go-and/1100-6444620/|archivedate=December 28, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Later on, Kazumasa Iwao, who was responsible for the battle systems in ''Sun'' and ''Moon'', was recruited as director for ''Ultra Sun'' and ''Ultra Moon''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Webster|first1=Andrew|title=How Pok\u00e9mon Go helped shape the upcoming Ultra Sun and Moon on Nintendo 3DS|url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/10/19/16466536/pokemon-ultra-sun-moon-interview-nintendo|accessdate=December 27, 2017|work=[[The Verge]]|date=October 19, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107013501/https://www.theverge.com/2017/10/19/16466536/pokemon-ultra-sun-moon-interview-nintendo|archivedate=November 7, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\nAccording to composer [[Junichi Masuda]], who co-produced the game, the soundtracks used in ''Sun'' and ''Moon'' were based off [[Music of Hawaii|traditional Hawaiian music]] styles. However, while it utilizes their core rhythms, Alola's music employs \"completely different\" melodies while still invoking a tropical island feel.<ref name=\"timeint\"/> On November 30, 2016 the {{nihongo foot|''Nintendo 3DS Pok\u00e9mon Sun and Moon Super Music Complete''|\u30cb\u30f3\u30c6\u30f3\u30c9\u30fc3DS \u30dd\u30b1\u30e2\u30f3 \u30b5\u30f3\u30fb\u30e0\u30fc\u30f3 \u30b9\u30fc\u30d1\u30fc\u30df\u30e5\u30fc\u30b8\u30c3\u30af\u30fb\u30b3\u30f3\u30d7\u30ea\u30fc\u30c8|Nintend\u014d 3 D\u012b Esu Pok\u00e9mon San \u00b7 M\u016bn S\u016bp\u0101 My\u016bjikku Konp\u016brito|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}}, a four-disk soundtrack containing 169 songs, 160 from the games and 9 special tracks, was released in Japan. The international release, known as ''Pok\u00e9mon Sun & Pok\u00e9mon Moon: Super Music Collection'', was released on [[iTunes]] on the same date.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rossignol|first1=Derrick|title=The POK\u00c9MON SUN and MOON Soundtrack Is Now Available on iTunes|url=https://nerdist.com/the-pokemon-sun-and-moon-soundtrack-is-now-available-on-itunes/|accessdate=December 27, 2017|work=[[Nerdist]]|date=December 1, 2016|language=en|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171228171535/https://nerdist.com/the-pokemon-sun-and-moon-soundtrack-is-now-available-on-itunes/|archivedate=December 28, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=\u30cb\u30f3\u30c6\u30f3\u30c9\u30fc3DS \u30dd\u30b1\u30e2\u30f3 \u30b5\u30f3\u30fb\u30e0\u30fc\u30f3 \u30b9\u30fc\u30d1\u30fc\u30df\u30e5\u30fc\u30b8\u30c3\u30af\u30fb\u30b3\u30f3\u30d7\u30ea\u30fc\u30c8|language=ja|url=http://over-lap.co.jp/cd/sm/|publisher=Over-Lap|accessdate=December 27, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171228054053/http://over-lap.co.jp/cd/sm/|archivedate=December 28, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Promotion and release==\nOn February 25, 2016, the existence of the two games was leaked when Nintendo's trademarks for them were found on the website of the [[European Union Intellectual Property Office]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ca.ign.com/articles/2016/02/25/the-next-pokemon-games-could-be-called-sun-and-moon |title=The Next Pokemon Games Could Be Called Sun And Moon |author=Matt Porter |publisher=IGN |accessdate=February 25, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20160227094942/http://ca.ign.com/articles/2016/02/25/the-next-pokemon-games-could-be-called-sun-and-moon |archivedate=February 27, 2016 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> ''IGN'' pointed towards the recent introduction of a new Pok\u00e9mon, [[Magearna]], as indication the two games would be revealed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2016/02/26/pokemon-sun-and-moon-officially-announced |title=Pokemon Sun and Moon Officially Announced |author=Seth G. Macy |date=February 26, 2016 |work=[[IGN]] |accessdate=February 27, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160226164409/http://www.ign.com/articles/2016/02/26/pokemon-sun-and-moon-officially-announced |archivedate=February 26, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The games were officially announced the following day in a [[Nintendo Direct]] presentation that also commemorated the franchise's 20th anniversary.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://comicbook.com/2016/02/26/nintendo-announces-pokemon-sun-and-moon-for-20th-anniversary/ |date=February 26, 2016 |title=Nintendo Announces Pokemon Sun And Moon For 20th Anniversary |author=James Viscardi |work=Comicbook.com |accessdate=February 26, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20160226163505/http://comicbook.com/2016/02/26/nintendo-announces-pokemon-sun-and-moon-for-20th-anniversary/ |archivedate=February 26, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The games launched with support for nine languages.<ref name=\"Pokemoncom\">{{cite web |url=http://www.pokemon.com/uk/pokemon-video-games/pokemon-sun-and-pokemon-moon/ |title=Pok\u00e9mon Sun and Pok\u00e9mon Moon |publisher=[[The Pok\u00e9mon Company]] |access-date=February 26, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160228120537/http://www.pokemon.com/uk/pokemon-video-games/pokemon-sun-and-pokemon-moon/ |archivedate=February 28, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> On May 10, more information on the games was released through a new trailer, including new Pok\u00e9mon, box art, and release dates. ''Pok\u00e9mon Sun'' and ''Moon'' released in Japan, North America, and Australia on November 18, 2016, and in Europe on November 23, 2016.<ref name=\"Junichi Masuda's Blog\">{{cite web |url=http://lineblog.me/masudajunichi/archives/3355017.html |title=Look for tomorrow |publisher=[[Junichi Masuda]] |access-date=May 9, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160512170241/http://lineblog.me/masudajunichi/archives/3355017.html |archivedate=May 12, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> A comic based on ''Pok\u00e9mon Sun'' and ''Moon'' launched alongside an edition of ''[[CoroCoro Comic]]'' on September 15, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Whitehead|first1=Thomas|title=A Pok\u00e9mon Sun And Moon Manga Series Is Coming To CoroCoro Comics|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2016/08/a_pokemon_sun_and_moon_manga_series_is_coming_to_corocoro_comics|website=[[Nintendo Life]]|accessdate=August 8, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160809145724/http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2016/08/a_pokemon_sun_and_moon_manga_series_is_coming_to_corocoro_comics|archivedate=August 9, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Early purchasers of the games received a special [[Munchlax]] holding Snorlium Z, enabling it to use an exclusive Z-Move unique to [[Snorlax]], Munchlax's evolution, via a wireless distribution event.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/09/01/sun-and-moons-early-purchase-bonus-is-a-pre-snorlax-pokemon/|title=Sun and Moon's early purchase bonus is a pre-Snorlax Pok\u00e9mon|last=Etherington|first=Darrell|website=[[TechCrunch]]|access-date=September 2, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160902143941/https://techcrunch.com/2016/09/01/sun-and-moons-early-purchase-bonus-is-a-pre-snorlax-pokemon/|archivedate=September 2, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> A Japanese trailer was unveiled on September 8, 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/olliebarder/2016/09/08/pokemon-sun-and-moon-shows-off-its-legendary-pokemon-in-latest-trailer/#3cf836ca2026|title='Pok\u00e9mon Sun And Moon' Shows Off Its Legendary Pok\u00e9mon In Latest Trailer|last=Barder|website=[[Forbes.com]]|first=Ollie|date=8 September 2016|access-date=September 9, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160909161309/http://www.forbes.com/sites/olliebarder/2016/09/08/pokemon-sun-and-moon-shows-off-its-legendary-pokemon-in-latest-trailer/#3cf836ca2026|archivedate=September 9, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> A ''Pok\u00e9mon Sun'' and ''Moon''-themed [[New Nintendo 3DS XL]] was released on October 28, 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2016/09/13/pokemon-sun-and-moon-new-nintendo-3ds-xl-special-edition-announced|title=Pokemon Sun and Moon New Nintendo 3DS XL Special Edition Announced|last=Dornbush|first=Jonathon|date=September 13, 2016|website=[[IGN]]|language=en-US|access-date=September 14, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160913200824/http://www.ign.com/articles/2016/09/13/pokemon-sun-and-moon-new-nintendo-3ds-xl-special-edition-announced|archivedate=September 13, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nSimilar to ''Pok\u00e9mon Omega Ruby'' and ''Alpha Sapphire'', a special demo was released on October 18, 2016.<ref name=\":1\"/> On October 27, 2016 during Nintendo's Financial Briefing, they stated the demo had been downloaded more than 3.5 million times, being the most popular and fastest \"selling\" demo in 3DS history.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Harp|first1=Justin|title=Pok\u00e9mon Sun and Moon demo racks up a record-breaking 3.5 million downloads|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/gaming/pokemon/news/a812416/pokemon-sun-and-moon-demo-racks-up-record-breaking-35-million-downloads/|website=[[Digital Spy]]|date=October 28, 2016|accessdate=October 28, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161028231954/http://www.digitalspy.com/gaming/pokemon/news/a812416/pokemon-sun-and-moon-demo-racks-up-record-breaking-35-million-downloads/|archivedate=October 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> ''Pok\u00e9mon Sun'' and ''Moon'' were the most pre-ordered games in Nintendo's history.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Frank|first1=Allegra|title=Pok\u00e9mon Sun and Moon are Nintendo's biggest pre-orders ever|url=http://www.polygon.com/2016/10/27/13446280/pokemon-sun-and-moon-pre-order-record/|website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|accessdate=October 28, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161028133430/http://www.polygon.com/2016/10/27/13446280/pokemon-sun-and-moon-pre-order-record|archivedate=October 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The games were also the most anticipated 3DS releases in 2016, according to [[Nielsen Holdings|Nielsen]] Game Rank.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tops of 2016: Video Games|url=http://www.nielsen.com/us/en/insights/news/2016/tops-of-2016-video-games.html|publisher=[[Nielsen Holdings|Nielsen]]|website=nielsen.com|accessdate=3 January 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180103193635/http://www.nielsen.com/us/en/insights/news/2016/tops-of-2016-video-games.html|archivedate=January 3, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nDays before their release, the games' files were leaked on to the Internet, giving [[software pirate]]s access to the full game, including online functions, before their release. Nintendo took action against those who used the Internet features, banning users involved from not only using the online features of the games\u2014even if later playing the genuine release\u2014, but also from accessing other 3DS online services, such as the eShop and Miiverse.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hernandez|first1=Patricia|title=Players Who Pirated Pokemon Sun and Moon Say Nintendo is Banning them|url=http://kotaku.com/players-who-pirated-pokemon-sun-and-moon-say-nintendo-i-1789039343|website=[[Kotaku]]|accessdate=November 16, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161116154915/http://kotaku.com/players-who-pirated-pokemon-sun-and-moon-say-nintendo-i-1789039343|archivedate=November 16, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Video game reviews\n<!-- Aggregators-->\n| MC = 87/100<ref name=\"MetaSun\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/3ds/pokemon-sun |title=Pokemon Sun for 3DS Reviews&nbsp;\u2014 Metacritic |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=July 12, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170701001917/http://www.metacritic.com/game/3ds/pokemon-sun |archivedate=July 1, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"MetaMoon\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/3ds/pokemon-moon |title=Pokemon Moon for 3DS Reviews&nbsp;\u2014 Metacritic |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=July 12, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170714071006/http://www.metacritic.com/game/3ds/pokemon-moon |archivedate=July 14, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n| state = plain\n| Destruct= 9/10 <ref name=\"Destruct\">{{cite web|url=https://www.destructoid.com/review-pokemon-sun-399628.phtml|title=Review: Pokemon Sun|last=Devore|first=Jordan|publisher=Destructoid|date=November 11, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170305003818/https://www.destructoid.com/review-pokemon-sun-399628.phtml|archivedate=March 5, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| Fam = 38/40<ref name=\"famitsu\">{{cite news |last1=Romano |first1=Sal |title=Famitsu Review Scores: Issue 1459 |date=15 November 2016 |url=https://gematsu.com/2016/11/famitsu-review-scores-issue-1459 |accessdate=5 July 2019 |work=Gematsu |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190420144855/https://gematsu.com/2016/11/famitsu-review-scores-issue-1459 |archive-date=April 20, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| GI = 8.5/10 (''Moon'')<ref name=\"GI\">{{cite magazine|magazine=Game Informer|publisher=[[GameStop]]|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/themes/blogs/generic/post.aspx?WeblogApp=3ds&y=2016&m=11&d=15&WeblogPostName=game-informer-pokemon-sun-moon-review-3ds&GroupKeys=games/pokemon_moon/|title=Pokemon Moon: Destination Vacation|last=Hilliard|first=Kyle|date=November 15, 2016|accessdate=July 12, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170803091602/http://www.gameinformer.com/themes/blogs/generic/post.aspx?WeblogApp=3ds&y=2016&m=11&d=15&WeblogPostName=game-informer-pokemon-sun-moon-review-3ds&GroupKeys=games%2Fpokemon_moon%2F|archivedate=August 3, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| GSpot = 8/10<ref name=GameSpot>{{cite web|last1=Justin|first1=Haywald|title=Pok\u00e9mon Sun/Moon Review|url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/pokemon-sun-and-moon-review/1900-6416574/|publisher=[[GameSpot]]|accessdate=July 12, 2017|date=November 18, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170705010933/https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/pokemon-sun-and-moon-review/1900-6416574/|archivedate=July 5, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| GameZone = 9.5/10<ref name=\"GameZone\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamezone.com/reviews/review-pokemon-sun-moon-is-a-proper-evolution-k2rs|title=Pokemon Sun & Moon is a proper evolution|last=Splechta|first=Mike|publisher=Game Zone|date=November 16, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171020033015/http://www.gamezone.com/reviews/review-pokemon-sun-moon-is-a-proper-evolution-k2rs|archivedate=October 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| IGN = 9/10<ref name=\"IGN_Review\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2016/11/15/pokemon-sun-and-moon-review|title=Pokemon Sun and Moon review|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161116155217/http://www.ign.com/articles/2016/11/15/pokemon-sun-and-moon-review|archivedate=November 16, 2016|df=mdy-all|last=Plagge|first=Kalle|work=[[IGN]]|date=15 November 2016}}</ref>\n| NLife = 10/10<ref name=\"NLife\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nintendolife.com/reviews/3ds/pokemon_sun_and_moon |title=Review: Pok\u00e9mon Sun and Moon (3DS) |last=Olney |first=Alex |work=[[Nintendo Life]] |date=November 15, 2016 |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170926170259/http://www.nintendolife.com/reviews/3ds/pokemon_sun_and_moon |archivedate=September 26, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n| NWR = 8/10 (''Moon'')<ref name=\"NWR\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/review/43671/pokemon-moon-3ds-review |title=Pokemon Moon (3DS) Review |last=Koopman |first=Dan |publisher=Nintendo World Report |date=November 15, 2016 |accessdate=July 12, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170622064406/http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/review/43671/pokemon-moon-3ds-review |archivedate=June 22, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n| Poly = 8.5/10<ref name=\"Poly\">{{cite web|first=Allegra|last=Frank|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|date=November 15, 2016|accessdate=July 12, 2017|title=Pokemon Sun and Moon Review|url=https://www.polygon.com/2016/11/15/13637246/pokemon-sun-and-moon-review-nintendo-3ds|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170624113259/https://www.polygon.com/2016/11/15/13637246/pokemon-sun-and-moon-review-nintendo-3ds|archivedate=June 24, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| USG = 4.5/5<ref name=\"USG\">{{cite web |last1=Parish |first1=Jeremy |title=Aloha, Alola |url=https://www.usgamer.net/articles/pokmon-sunmoon-versions-3ds-review-finally-pokemon-feels-modern-2 |website=[[USgamer]] |accessdate=January 2, 2020 |language=en |date=November 18, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191008032447/https://www.usgamer.net/articles/pokmon-sunmoon-versions-3ds-review-finally-pokemon-feels-modern-2 |archive-date=8 October 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n}}\n\n===Critical response===\n''Pok\u00e9mon Sun'' and ''Moon'' received a score of 87/100 on [[Metacritic]] based on 84 reviews, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref name=\"MetaSun\"/><ref name=\"MetaMoon\"/> This placed ''Sun'' and ''Moon'' as the 5th and 6th highest-rated 3DS games in 2016, and the 19th and 20th on the console of all time.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Best Video Games of 2016|url=http://www.metacritic.com/feature/best-videogames-of-2016|publisher=Metacritic|accessdate=3 February 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161222041129/http://www.metacritic.com/feature/best-videogames-of-2016|archivedate=December 22, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=All Nintendo 3DS Video Game Releases|url=http://www.metacritic.com/browse/games/release-date/available/3ds/metascore|publisher=Metacritic|accessdate=3 February 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6eDHRvuoJ?url=http://www.metacritic.com/browse/games/release-date/available/3ds/metascore|archivedate=January 1, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The move from the gym system received widespread praise from critics, some of whom saw the change as a major step towards future developments of the franchise.<ref name=\"Destruct\"/><ref name=\"NWR\"/>\n\nJapanese magazine ''[[Famitsu]]'' gave the pair a 38/40 rating.<ref name=\"famitsu\"/> Writing for video game review site ''[[IGN]]'', Kallie Plagge gave the games a 9/10, and said that they \"switch up the formula to create an engaging adventure that improves on its predecessors\", in addition to praising the streamlined battle interface and other mechanics.<ref name=\"IGN_Review\"/> Many critics praised the story as one of the best in the franchise, Ollie Barder from ''[[Forbes]]'' highlighted how the story and characters were nicely done,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Barder |first1=Ollie |title='Pok\u00e9mon Sun' And 'Pok\u00e9mon Moon' Review: Say Alola To A Wonderful New World Of Pok\u00e9mon |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/games/2016/11/28/pokemon-sun-and-moon-review-say-alola-to-a-wonderful-new-world-of-pokemon/#abd28f53c48f |website=[[Forbes]] |accessdate=January 2, 2020 |date=November 28, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191202132240/https://www.forbes.com/sites/games/2016/11/28/pokemon-sun-and-moon-review-say-alola-to-a-wonderful-new-world-of-pokemon/ |archive-date=December 2, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> while Alex Donaldson of ''[[VG247]]'' remarked that the story drew him in deeper, saying \"I remain more engaged in this story than in any other ''Pok\u00e9mon'' tale yet\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Donaldson |first1=Alex |title=Pokemon Sun & Moon review: the best Pokemon game in years |url=https://www.vg247.com/2016/11/23/pokemon-sun-moon-review-the-best-pokemon-game-in-years/ |website=[[VG247]] |accessdate=January 2, 2020 |date=November 23, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190605111258/https://www.vg247.com/2016/11/23/pokemon-sun-moon-review-the-best-pokemon-game-in-years/ |archive-date=December 2, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Alex Olney of ''[[Nintendo Life]]'' said that \"the plot in Sun & Moon is the deepest and most ambitious Game Freak has dared attempt\", he also called them the best ''Pok\u00e9mon'' games ever produced, commenting that Alola's design felt natural and organic, praising Game Freak for successfully balancing additional mechanics without alienating existing fans.<ref name=\"NLife\"/> Chris Tapsell of ''Eurogamer'' said the games were \"the best generation in more than a decade\". They earned an \"essential\" ranking from the site.<ref name=\"eurorev\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-11-15-pokemon-sun-and-moon-review|title=Pok\u00e9mon Sun and Moon review|first=Chris|last=Tapsell|date=November 23, 2016|website=[[Eurogamer]]|accessdate=January 3, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171228112311/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-11-15-pokemon-sun-and-moon-review|archivedate=December 28, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn the other hand, Tapsell also remarked that the first few hours of the games included too many tutorials and protected gameplay.<ref name=\"eurorev\"/> Jeremy Parish of ''[[USGamer]]'' assessed that \"Z-Moves feel underwhelming\" taking \"way too long\" despite being the most engaging campaign the series has offered in a long time,<ref name=\"USG\"/> while ''[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]''{{'}}s Allegra Frank criticized their linear gameplay and lack of content beyond the primary storyline although the games had \"the most memorable ''Pok\u00e9mon'' journey in years\".<ref name=\"Poly\"/>\n\n===Sales===\nAccording to Nintendo of America, ''Sun'' and ''Moon'' were the fastest-selling titles in Nintendo's history at the time.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=NintendoAmerica|author=Nintendo of America|number=804052396259282948|date=November 30, 2016|title=It\u2019s official: #PokemonSunMoon are the fastest-selling games in Nintendo history in the Americas! Which version are\u2026|accessdate=January 3, 2018}}</ref> As of December 31, 2019, ''Sun'' and ''Moon'' have sold 16.18 million copies, ranking them as the [[List of best-selling Nintendo 3DS video games|third-best-selling Nintendo 3DS titles]] behind both ''[[Mario Kart 7]]'' and ''Pok\u00e9mon X'' and ''Y''.<ref name=\"third\">{{cite web|title=Top Selling Title Sales Units|url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/en/finance/software/3ds.html|publisher=[[Nintendo]]|accessdate=30 January 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all |date=December 31, 2019}}</ref> During a [[GameStop]] Q3 earnings conference call, ''Pok\u00e9mon Sun'' and ''Moon'' were said to have had the most pre-orders for any video game in the last five years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thisgengaming.com/2016/11/23/pokemon-sun-moon-most-pre-ordered-game-in-5-years-call-of-duty-infinite-warfare-underpreformed-says-gamestop/|title=Pokemon Sun & Moon \"Most Pre-Ordered Game In 5 Years\", Call Of Duty Infinite Warfare Underpreformed Says Gamestop|website=thisgengaming.com|accessdate=January 3, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107011200/http://thisgengaming.com/2016/11/23/pokemon-sun-moon-most-pre-ordered-game-in-5-years-call-of-duty-infinite-warfare-underpreformed-says-gamestop/|archivedate=November 7, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> It is GameStop's best-selling game of 2016, outselling ''[[Call of Duty: Infinite Warfare]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/gamestop-sales-hurting-as-new-call-of-duty-underpe/1100-6445664/|title=GameStop Sales Hurting, as New Call of Duty Underperforms; Pokemon Sun/Moon Biggest of 2016|first=Eddie|last=Makuch|date=November 22, 2016|accessdate=January 3, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171213135355/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/gamestop-sales-hurting-as-new-call-of-duty-underpe/1100-6445664/|archivedate=December 13, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On its first day of release, ''Pok\u00e9mon Sun'' and ''Moon'' shipped 10 million units worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2016/11/18/pokemon-sun-and-moon-break-nintendo-3ds-record-with-10-million-copies-shipped/|title=Pok\u00e9mon Sun and Moon break Nintendo 3DS record with 10 million copies shipped - GamesBeat|website=[[VentureBeat]]|accessdate=January 3, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107031247/https://venturebeat.com/2016/11/18/pokemon-sun-and-moon-break-nintendo-3ds-record-with-10-million-copies-shipped/|archivedate=November 7, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The games sold over 1.9 million copies in Japan in its first three days on the market and are Nintendo's biggest game launch of all time in Europe, with the [[United Kingdom]] and [[France]] launches selling 368,000 and 450,000 copies respectively within a week out of the continent's 1.5 million sales.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kerr|first1=Chris|title=Pokemon Sun and Moon first week sales top 1.9 million in Japan|url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/286065/Pokemon_Sun_and_Moon_first_week_sales_top_19_million_in_Japan.php|website=[[Gamasutra]]|publisher=[[UBM TechWeb]]|accessdate=November 22, 2016|date=November 22, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161123133738/http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/286065/Pokemon_Sun_and_Moon_first_week_sales_top_19_million_in_Japan.php|archivedate=November 23, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Phillips|first1=Tom|title=Pok\u00e9mon Sun and Moon are Nintendo's biggest UK launch of all time|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-11-28-pokemon-sun-and-moon-are-nintendos-biggest-uk-launch|website=[[Eurogamer]]|publisher=Gamer Network|accessdate=November 28, 2016|date=November 28, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161128231728/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-11-28-pokemon-sun-and-moon-are-nintendos-biggest-uk-launch|archivedate=November 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Casey|title=Pok\u00e9mon Sun & Moon Sell Over 425,000 Copies In First Week In France, Set New Record|url=http://www.siliconera.com/2016/12/04/pokmon-sun-moon-sell-425000-copies-first-week-france-set-new-record/|website=[[Siliconera]]|accessdate=December 4, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161205131747/http://www.siliconera.com/2016/12/04/pokmon-sun-moon-sell-425000-copies-first-week-france-set-new-record/|archivedate=December 5, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The European sales rose past the 2 million mark within the following week.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Forde|first1=Matthew|title=Pok\u00e9mon Sun & Moon Sales Pass 2 Million in Europe|url=https://www.nintendolife.com/news/2016/12/pokemon_sun_and_moon_sales_pass_2_million_in_europe|website=[[Nintendo Life]]|accessdate=December 8, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161209153835/http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2016/12/pokemon_sun_and_moon_sales_pass_2_million_in_europe|archivedate=December 9, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In North America, the games sold over 3.7 million units in less than two weeks after initial release, climbing to 4.5 million by mid-January.<ref>{{cite web|last=Nunneley|first=Stephany|website=[[VG247]]|url=http://www.vg247.com/2016/11/30/pokemon-sun-and-moon-sold-3-7-million-units-in-north-america-in-less-than-two-weeks/|title=Pokemon Sun and Moon sold 3.7 million units in North America in less than two weeks|accessdate=January 3, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180105205853/https://www.vg247.com/2016/11/30/pokemon-sun-and-moon-sold-3-7-million-units-in-north-america-in-less-than-two-weeks/|archivedate=January 5, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Macy|first1=Seth|title=Pokemon Sun And Moon Pass Huge Sales Milestone|url=http://ign.com/articles/2017/01/19/pokemon-sun-and-moon-pass-huge-sales-milestone|website=[[IGN]]|accessdate=January 19, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170119233458/http://www.ign.com/articles/2017/01/19/pokemon-sun-and-moon-pass-huge-sales-milestone|archivedate=January 19, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Follow-up versions==\n{{main|Pok\u00e9mon Ultra Sun and Ultra Moon}}\n'''''Pok\u00e9mon Ultra Sun''''' and '''''Pok\u00e9mon Ultra Moon''''' are enhanced versions of ''Pok\u00e9mon Sun'' and ''Moon'', developed by Game Freak, published by The Pok\u00e9mon Company and Nintendo for the Nintendo 3DS. They were announced on June 6, 2017, during a Nintendo Direct presentation<ref name=hernandez>{{cite news|first=Patricia|last=Hernandez|work=[[Kotaku]]|publisher=[[Gawker Media]]|date=June 6, 2017|accessdate=June 6, 2017|title=''Pok\u00e9mon Ultra Sun and Moon'' Only Announced For 3DS Later This Year [Update]|url=http://kotaku.com/pokemon-ultra-sun-and-moon-coming-only-to-3ds-later-thi-1795847363|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606152234/http://kotaku.com/pokemon-ultra-sun-and-moon-coming-only-to-3ds-later-thi-1795847363|archivedate=June 6, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and were released worldwide on November 17, 2017.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Humphries |first1=Matthew |title=Ultra Sun and Moon Are the Last 3DS Pokemon Games |url=https://uk.pcmag.com/news-analysis/91647/ultra-sun-and-moon-are-the-last-3ds-pokemon-games |accessdate=May 15, 2019 |work=[[PC Magazine|PCMag UK]] |date=October 19, 2017 |language=en}}</ref> They feature an alternate storyline set in ''Sun'' and ''Moon''{{'}}s world, and include Pok\u00e9mon and locations not available in the original games.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pokemon-sunmoon.com/ultra/en-us/alola-region.html|title=Alola Region {{!}} Pok\u00e9mon Ultra Sun and Pok\u00e9mon Ultra Moon|website=pokemon-sunmoon.com|language=en-us|access-date=2019-02-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190216091516/https://www.pokemon-sunmoon.com/ultra/en-us/alola-region.html|archive-date=February 16, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.pokemon.com/us/pokemon-video-games/pokemon-sun-and-pokemon-moon/}}\n\n{{Pok\u00e9mon video games|state=collapsed}}\n{{Portal bar|Video games}}\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pok\u00e9mon Sun and Moon}}\n[[Category:2016 video games]]\n[[Category:Game Freak games]]\n[[Category:Japanese role-playing video games]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer and single-player video games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo 3DS eShop games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo 3DS games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo 3DS-only games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo Network games]]\n[[Category:Pok\u00e9mon video games|Sun and Moon]]\n[[Category:Role-playing video games]]\n[[Category:Video games adapted into comics]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Japan]]\n[[Category:Video games featuring female antagonists]]\n[[Category:Video games featuring protagonists of selectable gender]]\n[[Category:Video games with alternate versions]]\n[[Category:Wormholes in fiction]]\n[[Category:Video games scored by Junichi Masuda]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the twentieth season of the ''Pok\u00e9mon'' animated series|List of Pok\u00e9mon: Sun & Moon episodes}}\n{{Redirect|SuMo|other uses|Sumo (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:''Pok\u00e9mon Sun'' and ''Moon''}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title        = {{ubl|''Pok\u00e9mon Sun''|''Pok\u00e9mon Moon''}}\n| italic title = no\n| image        = Pokemon Sun Boxart.jpg\n| caption      = North American box art for ''Pok\u00e9mon Sun'', depicting the [[legendary Pok\u00e9mon]] [[Solgaleo]]. The box art for ''Pok\u00e9mon Moon'' depicts the legendary Pok\u00e9mon [[Lunala]] (not pictured).\n| developer    = [[Game Freak]]\n| publisher    = {{ubl|[[The Pok\u00e9mon Company]]|[[Nintendo]]}}\n| director     = Shigeru Ohmori\n| producer     = {{ubl|[[Junichi Masuda]]|Shin Uwai|Takato Utsunomiya|Hitoshi Yamagami|[[Shinya Takahashi]]}}\n| designer     = Shigeru Ohmori\n| programmer   = Sosuke Tamada\n| artist       = Takao Unno\n| writer       = {{ubl|Toshinobu Matsumiya|Suguru Nakatsui|Kenji Matsushima|Masafumi Nukita}}\n| composer     = {{ubl|Minako Adachi|Go Ichinose|Junichi Masuda|Hitomi Sato|Tomoaki Oga|Hideaki Kuroda}}\n| series       = ''[[Pok\u00e9mon (video game series)|Pok\u00e9mon]]''\n| platforms    = [[Nintendo 3DS]]\n| released     = {{Video game release|WW|November 18, 2016|EU|November 23, 2016}}\n| genre        = [[Role-playing video game|Role-playing]]\n| modes        = [[Single-player]], [[multiplayer]]\n}}\n\n{{nihongo foot|'''''Pok\u00e9mon Sun''''' and '''''Pok\u00e9mon Moon'''''|\u30dd\u30b1\u30c3\u30c8\u30e2\u30f3\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u3000\u30b5\u30f3\u30fb\u30e0\u30fc\u30f3|Poketto Monsut\u0101 San\u30fbPoketto Monsut\u0101 M\u016bn|\"Pocket Monsters: Sun & Pocket Monsters: Moon\"|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} are 2016 [[role-playing video games]] developed by [[Game Freak]], published by [[The Pok\u00e9mon Company]] and [[Nintendo]] for the [[Nintendo 3DS]]. They are the first installments in the seventh generation of the [[Pok\u00e9mon (video game series)|''Pok\u00e9mon'' video game series]]. First announced in February 2016, ''Sun'' and ''Moon'' were released worldwide on November 18, 2016,<!-- Generalize the release dates in the lead, per WP:VG/DATE. --> commemorating [[Pok\u00e9mon|the franchise]]'s 20th anniversary. Two follow-up games, [[Pok\u00e9mon Ultra Sun and Ultra Moon|''Pok\u00e9mon Ultra Sun'' and ''Pok\u00e9mon Ultra Moon'']], were released for the same consoles on November 17, 2017.\n\nThe titles began development following completion of [[Pok\u00e9mon Omega Ruby and Alpha Sapphire|''Pok\u00e9mon Omega Ruby'' and ''Alpha Sapphire'']], with increased emphasis on Pok\u00e9mon interactions. Like previous installments, they follow the journey of a young Pok\u00e9mon trainer, taking place in the Alola region\u2014based on [[Hawaii]]\u2014with the objective of the games being to complete the island challenge and thwart the schemes of Team Skull, and later the Aether Foundation, all while attempting to challenge various Pok\u00e9mon trainers of gradually increasing difficulty. ''Sun'' and ''Moon'' introduced [[List of generation VII Pok\u00e9mon|81 new Pok\u00e9mon]] species, and new features such as Alolan forms of previous generation Pok\u00e9mon, powerful moves known as Z-Moves, alien creatures known as Ultra Beasts, updated battle and training mechanics, and improved [[Polygonal modeling|polygonal 3D graphics]]. While largely independent of one another, the two games follow a similar plot, and while each can be played separately, trading Pok\u00e9mon between the two games is necessary to complete the Pok\u00e9dex, just like in previous installments.\n\nThe games received generally favorable reviews from critics, who welcomed the change from the formula used by prior ''Pok\u00e9mon'' games and praised the gameplay of ''Sun'' and ''Moon'' while criticizing the lack of content beyond the primary plot. Upon release, the games became one of the fastest-selling games in Nintendo's history. To date, ''Sun'' and ''Moon'' have sold over 16 million copies worldwide, making them the third-best-selling Nintendo 3DS titles, after ''[[Mario Kart 7]]'' and their predecessors, [[Pok\u00e9mon X and Y|''Pok\u00e9mon X'' and ''Y'']].\n\n==Gameplay==\n{{see also|Gameplay of Pok\u00e9mon}}\n''Pok\u00e9mon Sun'' and ''Moon'' are [[role-playing video game]]s with [[adventure game|adventure]] elements, set in the fictional Alola region (loosely based on Hawaii),<ref name=\"weknow\">{{cite news |last1=Alexander |first1=Julia |title=Pok\u00e9mon Moon and Sun: Everything we know |url=https://www.polygon.com/2016/6/14/11936306/pokemon-moon-and-sun-everything-we-know |accessdate=5 July 2019 |work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |date=14 June 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190705212911/https://www.polygon.com/2016/6/14/11936306/pokemon-moon-and-sun-everything-we-know |archive-date=July 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> presented in a [[Grammatical person#Use of grammatical person in creative media|third-person]], [[overhead perspective]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Minotti |first1=Mike |title=Pok\u00e9mon Sun and Moon make a good first impression with their formula-shaking tweaks |url=https://venturebeat.com/2016/11/17/pokemon-sun-and-moon-make-a-good-first-impression-with-their-formula-shaking-tweaks/ |accessdate=5 July 2019 |work=[[VentureBeat]] |date=17 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190705212913/https://venturebeat.com/2016/11/17/pokemon-sun-and-moon-make-a-good-first-impression-with-their-formula-shaking-tweaks/ |archive-date=July 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The player controls a young trainer who goes on a quest to catch and train creatures known as Pok\u00e9mon, and win battles against other trainers.<ref name=\"weknow\"/> By defeating opposing Pok\u00e9mon in turn-based battles, the player's Pok\u00e9mon gains [[experience points|experience]], allowing them to level up and increase their battle statistics, learn new battle techniques, and in some cases, [[Pok\u00e9mon evolution|evolve]] into more powerful Pok\u00e9mon. Players can capture wild Pok\u00e9mon, found during [[random encounter]]s, by weakening them in battle and catching them with [[Pok\u00e9 Ball]]s, allowing them to be added to their [[Party (role-playing games)|party]]. Players are also able to battle and [[Pok\u00e9mon trading|trade]] Pok\u00e9mon with other human players using the Nintendo 3DS' connectivity features. As with previous games in the series, certain Pok\u00e9mon are only obtainable in either ''Sun'' or ''Moon'', with players encouraged to trade with others in order to obtain all Pok\u00e9mon from both versions.<ref>{{cite web |title=Pok\u00e9mon Black Version Instruction Booklet |url=https://www.nintendo.com/consumer/gameslist/manuals/DS_Pokemon_Black.pdf |publisher=[[Nintendo]] |accessdate=5 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180911142039/https://www.nintendo.com/consumer/gameslist/manuals/DS_Pokemon_Black.pdf |archive-date=September 11, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Pokemon Sun & Moon guide: version differences, plus where to find & catch exclusive Pokemon |url=https://www.vg247.com/2016/11/22/pokemon-sun-moon-guide-version-differences-plus-where-to-find-catch-exclusive-pokemon/ |accessdate=5 July 2019 |work=[[VG247]] |date=22 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190705212912/https://www.vg247.com/2016/11/22/pokemon-sun-moon-guide-version-differences-plus-where-to-find-catch-exclusive-pokemon/ |archive-date=July 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===New features===\n{{see also|List of generation VII Pok\u00e9mon}}\n[[File:Pokemon sm screenshot.png|thumb|The bottom screen in ''Sun'' and ''Moon'' is occupied by a [[List of generation IV Pok\u00e9mon#Rotom|Rotom]], showing a map of the player's location. The red flag indicates a story waypoint.]]\n''Pok\u00e9mon Sun'' and ''Moon'' are presented in fully [[3D computer graphics|three dimensional]] (3D) [[polygonal graphics]], like their predecessors, allowing for more interactivity with the overworld and more dynamic action during battles. However, the character models in ''Sun'' and ''Moon'' possess more realistic proportions compared to [[chibi (slang)|chibi]]-styled models used in [[Pok\u00e9mon X and Y|''Pokemon X'' and ''Y'']] or [[Pok\u00e9mon Omega Ruby and Alpha Sapphire|''Pok\u00e9mon Omega Ruby'' and ''Alpha Sapphire'']].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Garcia|first1=Edwin|title=POK\u00c9MON SUN and MOON's Subtle Changes Are Super Effective (Preview)|url=https://nerdist.com/pokemon-sun-and-moons-subtle-changes-are-super-effective-preview/|accessdate=10 February 2018|work=[[Nerdist]]|date=25 October 2016|language=en|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180211131337/https://nerdist.com/pokemon-sun-and-moons-subtle-changes-are-super-effective-preview/|archivedate=February 11, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Players are also able to customize their Pok\u00e9mon trainer's appearance, choosing gender, skin tone and hair color at the start of the game and can later acquire outfits and accessories to change their character's appearance. Joining the previous generations of Pok\u00e9mon are all new species, such as the new [[starter Pok\u00e9mon]]; [[List of generation VII Pok\u00e9mon#Rowlet|Rowlet]], [[List of generation VII Pok\u00e9mon#Litten|Litten]] and [[List of generation VII Pok\u00e9mon#Popplio|Popplio]] and the Pok\u00e9mon that are, within the fictional Pok\u00e9mon world, described as legendary, namely [[Solgaleo]] and [[Lunala]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/finally-the-evolved-forms-of-pokemon-sun-moons-rowlet-litten-and-popplio-are-here/ |title=Finally, the evolved forms of Pokemon Sun & Moon's Rowlet, Popplio, and Litten are here |work=[[GamesRadar]] |accessdate=October 23, 2016 |date=October 4, 2016 |author=Prell, Sam |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161024104027/http://www.gamesradar.com/finally-the-evolved-forms-of-pokemon-sun-moons-rowlet-litten-and-popplio-are-here/ |archivedate=October 24, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Legendary Pok\u00e9mon unveiled for Pok\u00e9mon Sun and Pok\u00e9mon Moon |url=https://www.nintendo.co.uk/News/2016/June/Legendary-Pokemon-unveiled-for-Pokemon-Sun-and-Pokemon-Moon-1110956.html |publisher=[[Nintendo]] |accessdate=5 July 2019 |date=2 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n''Pok\u00e9mon Sun'' and ''Moon'' are the first entries in the series to be available in Chinese, both [[Simplified Chinese characters|Simplified]] and [[Traditional Chinese characters|Traditional]], along with English, French, Spanish, Italian, German, Japanese and Korean, for a total of nine available languages.<ref>\n{{cite web |url=http://www.mcvuk.com/news/read/pok-mon-targets-china-with-sun-and-moon/0163159 |title=Pok\u00e9mon targets China with Sun and Moon |first=Alex |last=Calvin |work=[[MCV (magazine)|MCV]] UK |date=February 26, 2016 |accessdate=May 1, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503194114/http://www.mcvuk.com/news/read/pok-mon-targets-china-with-sun-and-moon/0163159 |archivedate=May 3, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}\n</ref> The games introduce variants of Pok\u00e9mon introduced in older games with new typings and appearances, known as Alolan Forms. Alolan [[Vulpix and Ninetales]], which are Fire types in other regions, are respectively Ice and dual Ice and Fairy types. Alolan Sandshrew and Sandslash, which are Ground types in other regions, are Ice and Steel types. Alolan Meowth and Persian, which are Normal types in other regions, are Dark types. Some Pok\u00e9mon evolutions have gained dual typings as well, such as Alolan Marowak which is now a Fire and Ghost type and Alolan Raichu, an Electric and Psychic type.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2016/aug/02/pokemon-nintendo-alola-forms-exeggutor|title=Pok\u00e9mon introduces Alola forms \u2013 including a 36-foot Exeggutor|last=Hern|first=Alex|date=August 2, 2016|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|access-date=December 2, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161203064038/https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2016/aug/02/pokemon-nintendo-alola-forms-exeggutor|archivedate=December 3, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mic.com/articles/160225/pokemon-sun-and-moon-pokedex-how-many-new-pokemon-are-in-gen-7|title='Pok\u00e9mon Sun and Moon' Pok\u00e9dex: How many new Pok\u00e9mon are in Gen 7?|website=Mic|language=en|access-date=2019-12-15}}</ref> Throughout the game, players utilize a [[List of generation IV Pok\u00e9mon#Rotom|Rotom]]-possessed [[Pok\u00e9dex]] on the bottom [[touchscreen]], which displays a minimap containing markers for story objectives.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Phillips|first1=Tom|title=Pok\u00e9mon Sun and Moon's new Pok\u00e9dex is a Pok\u00e9mon|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-06-03-pokemon-sun-and-moons-new-pokedex-is-a-pokemon|accessdate=10 February 2018|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=3 June 2016|language=en-UK|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180211071642/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-06-03-pokemon-sun-and-moons-new-pokedex-is-a-pokemon|archivedate=February 11, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n''Pok\u00e9mon Sun'' and ''Moon'' introduce a powerful new type of move known as Z-Moves which can only be used once per battle.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nintendo.com/whatsnew/detail/z-moves-and-variants-in-pokemon-sun-and-pokemon-moon|title=Z-moves and Alolan Pok\u00e9mon variants announced for Pok\u00e9mon Sun and Pok\u00e9mon Moon|publisher=[[Nintendo]]|access-date=August 21, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822024329/http://www.nintendo.com/whatsnew/detail/z-moves-and-variants-in-pokemon-sun-and-pokemon-moon|archivedate=August 22, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Hidden Moves, which were used to navigate terrain in past games, have been replaced by specialized Pok\u00e9mon that can be summoned at will.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2016/10/19/13329864/pokemon-sun-and-moon-hms-removed-tms-ride-pokemon|title=Pok\u00e9mon Sun and Moon are changing one of the series' most frustrating mechanics|last=Frank|first=Allegra|date=19 October 2016|website=Polygon|language=en|access-date=7 November 2019}}</ref> The \"Pok\u00e9 Finder\" is a function of the Rotom Pok\u00e9dex which allows players to take photos of Pok\u00e9mon in the wild, similar to ''[[Pok\u00e9mon Snap]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/9/6/12814046/pokemon-sun-moon-photography-mode-pokemon-snap|title=Pok\u00e9mon Sun and Moon will let you take pictures Pok\u00e9mon Snap-style|last=Webster|first=Andrew|date=September 6, 2016|website=[[The Verge]]|access-date=September 7, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160906171905/http://www.theverge.com/2016/9/6/12814046/pokemon-sun-moon-photography-mode-pokemon-snap|archivedate=September 6, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2016/09/06/new-pokemon-sun-and-moon-details-new-pokemon-ultra-beasts-and-a-pokemon-snap-style-feature-revealed|title=New Pokemon Sun and Moon Details - New Pokemon, Ultra Beasts and a Pokemon Snap Style Feature Revealed|last=Skrebels|first=Joe|date=September 6, 2016|website=IGN|language=en-US|access-date=September 7, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160906205636/http://www.ign.com/articles/2016/09/06/new-pokemon-sun-and-moon-details-new-pokemon-ultra-beasts-and-a-pokemon-snap-style-feature-revealed|archivedate=September 6, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In addition, the two games' clocks are set 12 hours apart from each other, with ''Sun'' operating on the 3DS' time and ''Moon'' operating 12 hours ahead.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pokemon-sunmoon.com/en-us/sept-6-sunmoon-differences/|title=The Differences between Pok\u00e9mon Sun and Moon on Pok\u00e9mon Sun and Moon.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170402165835/http://www.pokemon-sunmoon.com/en-us/sept-6-sunmoon-differences/|publisher=[[The Pok\u00e9mon Company]]|archivedate=April 2, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Character customization as previously seen in ''X'' and ''Y'' returns in ''Sun'' and ''Moon''. A new \"Pok\u00e9mon Refresh\" feature enables players to care for and feed their Pok\u00e9mon.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/pokemon-sunmoon-new-creatures-revealed-bank-featur/1100-6443743/|title=Pokemon Sun/Moon: New Creatures Revealed, Bank Feature Delayed|access-date=September 21, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160924161211/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/pokemon-sunmoon-new-creatures-revealed-bank-featur/1100-6443743/|work=[[GameSpot]]|archivedate=September 24, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Mega Evolution]], a game mechanic first introduced in ''X'' and ''Y'', returns in ''Sun'' and ''Moon''.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/olliebarder/2016/10/05/pokemon-sun-and-moon-is-getting-a-demo-this-october/#61052abb4b5d|title='Pok\u00e9mon Sun And Moon' Is Getting A Demo This October|date=5 October 2016|last=Barder|first=Ollie|newspaper=[[Forbes.com]]|access-date=October 8, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161009035246/http://www.forbes.com/sites/olliebarder/2016/10/05/pokemon-sun-and-moon-is-getting-a-demo-this-october/#61052abb4b5d|archivedate=October 9, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The ''Battle Tree'' is a location which allows players to battle or team up with Pok\u00e9mon trainers, including Kanto region trainers Red and Blue.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nintendo-insider.com/2016/10/red-and-blue-return-in-pokemon-sun-and-moons-battle-tree/|title=Red And Blue Return In Pok\u00e9mon Sun And Moon's Battle Tree - Nintendo Insider|date=October 27, 2016|newspaper=Nintendo Insider|language=en-GB|access-date=December 2, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161129032823/http://www.nintendo-insider.com/2016/10/red-and-blue-return-in-pokemon-sun-and-moons-battle-tree/|archivedate=November 29, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Players can trade or battle with other players online.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pok\u00e9mon Sun & Moon's Festival Plaza Is A Very Giving Place|url=http://www.siliconera.com/2016/11/21/pokemon-sun-moons-festival-plaza-giving-place/|accessdate=2 January 2018|work=[[Siliconera]]|date=21 November 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180103072918/http://www.siliconera.com/2016/11/21/pokemon-sun-moons-festival-plaza-giving-place/|archivedate=January 3, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref> From a location called the Festival Plaza, players can participate in \"Global Missions\", where people from across the world work towards a set target \u2014 such as catching 100 million Pok\u00e9mon collectively.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Carden|first1=Dennis|title=The fourth Pokemon Sun and Moon Global Mission is already a resounding success|url=https://www.destructoid.com/the-fourth-pokemon-sun-and-moon-global-mission-is-already-a-resounding-success-421602.phtml|accessdate=2 January 2018|work=[[Destructoid]]|date=3 January 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170513071315/https://www.destructoid.com/the-fourth-pokemon-sun-and-moon-global-mission-is-already-a-resounding-success-421602.phtml|archivedate=May 13, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Connectivity===\nPok\u00e9mon caught in ''Pok\u00e9mon X'', ''Y'', ''Omega Ruby'' and ''Alpha Sapphire'' can be transferred to ''Sun'' and ''Moon''.<ref name=\"Pokemoncom\" /> The games are also compatible with ''[[Pok\u00e9mon Bank]]'', an online Pok\u00e9mon storage system introduced during the previous generation of ''Pok\u00e9mon'' games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pokemon-sunmoon.com/en-us/pokemon-bank/|title=Pok\u00e9mon Bank on Pok\u00e9mon Sun and Moon.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170403013334/http://www.pokemon-sunmoon.com/en-us/pokemon-bank/|archivedate=April 3, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In a special Pok\u00e9mon Direct on February 26, 2016, Tsunekazu Ishihara from The Pok\u00e9mon Company announced that Pok\u00e9mon caught in the [[Virtual Console]] versions of [[Pok\u00e9mon Red and Blue|''Red'', ''Blue'']], and ''[[Pok\u00e9mon Yellow|Yellow]]'' are transferable to ''Sun'' and ''Moon'' via ''Pok\u00e9mon Bank''. Compatibility with ''Pok\u00e9mon Bank'' was initially planned to be available at the games' launch but was delayed and later became available on January 24, 2017.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite web|last1=Macy|first1=Seth|title=Pokemon Bank Now Compatible With Sun and Moon|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2017/01/25/pokemon-bank-now-compatible-with-sun-and-moon|website=[[IGN]]|accessdate=January 25, 2017|date=January 24, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170125041407/http://www.ign.com/articles/2017/01/25/pokemon-bank-now-compatible-with-sun-and-moon|archivedate=January 25, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Tomy]] also released a peripheral interactive toy resembling a Z-Ring, which synchronizes with the use of Z-Moves in the games.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fahey|first1=Mike|title=Toy Time Plays With Pok\u00e9mon Sun And Moon's Z-Ring|url=https://kotaku.com/toy-time-plays-with-pokemon-sun-and-moons-z-ring-1789007852|accessdate=10 February 2018|work=[[Kotaku]]|date=18 November 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180211072228/https://kotaku.com/toy-time-plays-with-pokemon-sun-and-moons-z-ring-1789007852|archivedate=February 11, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n\n===Setting===\n[[File:Pok\u00e9mon Alola Region.jpg|thumb|right|The Alola region comprises several islands of varying sizes; from left to right: Exeggutor Island, Poni Island, Melemele Island, Akala Island, and Ula'ula Island. The white structure just south of Melemele is the [[very large floating structure]] Aether Paradise.]]\n[[File:Kauai (7635268890).jpg|right|thumb|The Alola region was heavily inspired by Hawaii, with Game Freak staff visiting the islands to conduct research for the games.]]\nThe games take place on a tropical archipelago, a group of islands known as the Alola region. Joe Skrebels of ''[[IGN]]'' describes it as \"''Pok\u00e9mon''{{'}}s take on [[Hawaii]]\".<ref>{{cite web|first=Joe|last=Skrebels|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=Ziff Davis|date=May 10, 2016|accessdate=May 10, 2016|title=Pokemon Sun and Moon: First Gameplay, New Starters, Region Revealed|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2016/05/10/pokemon-sun-and-moon-first-gameplay-new-starters-region-revealed|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160510183917/http://www.ign.com/articles/2016/05/10/pokemon-sun-and-moon-first-gameplay-new-starters-region-revealed|archivedate=May 10, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> During an interview at [[Electronic Entertainment Expo 2016|E3 2016]], Shigeru Ohmori noted that Game Freak staff took trips to Hawaii to conduct research for ''Sun'' and ''Moon''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UC-uLg_5RIA|title=Pok\u00e9mon Sun and Pok\u00e9mon Moon - Demonstration - Nintendo E3 2016|website=[[YouTube]]|publisher=[[Nintendo]]|at=33m 25s|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160616171938/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UC-uLg_5RIA|archivedate=June 16, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe leading scientist in the Alola region is Professor Kukui, whose name comes from the [[kukui]], also known as the [[candlenut]], the Hawaiian state tree, continuing the trend of ''Pok\u00e9mon'' professors being named after trees. Team Skull is the name of the villainous group in Alola.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/olliebarder/2016/08/12/team-skull-and-more-pokemon-join-pokemon-sun-and-moon/#43ea7156175c|title=Team Skull And More Pok\u00e9mon Join 'Pok\u00e9mon Sun And Moon'|last=Barder|first=Ollie|access-date=September 7, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921113848/http://www.forbes.com/sites/olliebarder/2016/08/12/team-skull-and-more-pokemon-join-pokemon-sun-and-moon/#43ea7156175c|archivedate=September 21, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.idigitaltimes.com/pokemon-sun-and-moon-new-pokemon-and-ultra-beasts-revealed-latest-trailer-554310|title='Pok\u00e9mon Sun And Moon': New Pok\u00e9mon And Ultra Beasts Revealed In Latest Trailer|date=September 6, 2016|access-date=September 9, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160909021550/http://www.idigitaltimes.com/pokemon-sun-and-moon-new-pokemon-and-ultra-beasts-revealed-latest-trailer-554310|archivedate=September 9, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The [[Aether Foundation]] is an organization which studies Ultra Beasts, mysterious creatures from another dimension.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/pokemon-sun-moon-new-trailer-new-pokemon-null-jangmo-o-alolan-raticate-ub-01-revealed-2412170|title='Pok\u00e9mon Sun And Moon' New Trailer: New Pok\u00e9mon Null, Jangmo-o, Alolan Raticate, UB-01 Revealed; Time Difference, Aether Foundation Announced|date=September 7, 2016|access-date=September 9, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160908213139/http://www.ibtimes.com/pokemon-sun-moon-new-trailer-new-pokemon-null-jangmo-o-alolan-raticate-ub-01-revealed-2412170|archivedate=September 8, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Though [[Professor Oak]] does not appear in ''Sun'' and ''Moon'', his cousin Samson Oak takes his place.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2016/9/8/12848132/pokemon-sun-and-moon-professor-oak|title=Professor Oak's not in Pok\u00e9mon Sun and Moon, but his chilled-out cousin is|last=Frank|first=Allegra|date=September 8, 2016|website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|language=en-US|access-date=September 8, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160909042729/http://www.polygon.com/2016/9/8/12848132/pokemon-sun-and-moon-professor-oak|archivedate=September 9, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Story===\nThe player starts off as a youngster moving from [[Kanto (Pok\u00e9mon)|Kanto]] to Alola's Melemele Island with their mother. After meeting Lillie and rescuing her special Pok\u00e9mon she calls Nebby, the player obtains a starter Pok\u00e9mon from local Professor, Kukui, and embark on the island challenge, a [[coming-of-age]] custom spanning trials across Alola, along with local youngster Hau. Unlike in previous games, trials involve battles with powered-up Pok\u00e9mon followed by battles with each island's Kahuna upon completion of an island's trials. Throughout this the player encounters Team Skull, a gang of people who quit the island trials whose members include their leader Guzma and enforcer Gladion. The player will also encounter the Aether Foundation, an organization aiming to shelter Pok\u00e9mon from various threats.\n\nDuring a visit to Aether Foundation's base, Aether Paradise\u2014a [[very large floating structure]]\u2014, a mysterious creature called an Ultra Beast emerges from a wormhole but retreats before it could be defeated or captured. Later, after the player has defeated Team Skull at their base, Gladion reveals that Team Skull had been working for Aether Foundation, kidnapping Nebby to use its powers in summoning Ultra Beasts. The player then proceeds to battle through Aether Paradise with Hau and Gladion's help, eventually defeating Aether president Lusamine, who is revealed to be Gladion and Lillie's mother. Despite this, Lusamine and Guzma manage to open an Ultra Wormhole, with the former overclocking Nebby's powers, transporting them to Ultra Space (the Ultra Beasts' dimension). This causes Nebby to evolve into a cocoon-like form while Ultra Beasts are unleashed on to Alola's islands, forcing the island Kahunas and [[guardian deity|guardian deities]] to fight them.\n\nProceeding to the final island, the player and Lillie perform a ritual to evolve Nebby into its final form \u2014 Solgaleo or Lunala depending on the version \u2014 at the island's Altar.{{efn|Nebby evolves into Solgaleo at the Altar of the Sunne in ''Sun''; in ''Moon'' it evolves into Lunala at the Altar of the Moone}} With Nebby's newfound power, the player and Lillie travel to Ultra Space and find Lusamine who, not wanting to be rescued, allows herself to be taken over by the Ultra Beast they encountered earlier, forcing the player to battle her in self-defense. After defeating the crazed Lusamine, the player returns to Alola and ascends Mount Lanakila to challenge the newly-formed Alola Pok\u00e9mon League Elite Four. In the last match, they defeat Kukui to become Alola's first Pok\u00e9mon League champion. In the credits, the player battles Melemele's guardian deity [[Tapu Koko]] after a celebration, with Lillie and Lusamine departing Alola for Kanto the following day.\n\nAfter becoming the champion, the player is contacted by two members of the International Police: Anabel (who was head of the Battle Tower in ''[[Pok\u00e9mon Emerald]]'') and Looker (a side character from Pok\u00e9mon Diamond, Pearl, and Platinum). The player assists the two with handling the wild Ultra Beasts that Lusamine let loose into Alola in a series of quests.{{efn|Ultra Beasts featured are Buzzwole and Kartana in ''Sun'', with Pheromosa and Celesteela in ''Moon''}} Following the final quest, Looker reveals that he saw another Ultra Beast, although Anabel dismisses this. If the player then travels to Ten Carat Hill, they will encounter [[Necrozma]].\n\n==Development==\nGame director Shigeru Ohmori stated that the choice of ''Sun'' and ''Moon'' as title was inspired by the two celestial bodies\u2019 metaphorical representation of human relationships.<ref name=\"timeint\"/> Hawaii was chosen as the basis for the game's region following the title's determination, due to its clear nights and plentiful sunshine.<ref name=\"noeint\">{{cite news|title=Learn all about Pok\u00e9mon Sun and Pok\u00e9mon Moon in our in-depth interview|url=https://www.nintendo.co.uk/News/2016/October/Learn-all-about-Pokemon-Sun-and-Pokemon-Moon-in-our-in-depth-interview-1149779.html|accessdate=December 27, 2017|work=Nintendo of Europe GmbH}}</ref> Development started immediately after ''Pok\u00e9mon Omega Ruby'' and ''Alpha Sapphire'' was completed and Ohmori kept his game director position. Since the games were to be released on the franchise's 20th anniversary, ''Sun'' and ''Moon'' were developed comparatively from scratch with the application of more radical changes than its predecessor.<ref name=\"timeint\">{{cite news|last1=Peckham|first1=Matt|title=Why the New Pok\u00e9mon are Called 'Sun and Moon'|url=http://time.com/4536438/pokemon-sun-moon-interview/|accessdate=December 27, 2017|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=October 29, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180103040644/http://time.com/4536438/pokemon-sun-moon-interview/|archivedate=January 3, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Separately, he also mentioned that the games' intended to place more emphasis on the Pok\u00e9mon and the nature of the games, in addition to the player's interactions with them.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bailey|first1=Kat|title=Interview: First-time Pok\u00e9mon Director Shigeru Ohmori Opens Up About Sun and Moon|url=http://www.usgamer.net/articles/interview-first-time-pokmon-director-shigeru-ohmori-opens-up-about-sun-and-moon|accessdate=December 27, 2017|work=USgamer|date=October 19, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171228112312/http://www.usgamer.net/articles/interview-first-time-pokmon-director-shigeru-ohmori-opens-up-about-sun-and-moon|archivedate=December 28, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe first Pok\u00e9mon of the seventh generation to be designed was [[Jangmo-o]]. Regarding the various other designs of the generation, Ohmori mentioned that \u201c[f]or the 20th anniversary, we wanted to have a lot of special surprises\u2026 we wanted a funny element\u201d.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hernandez|first1=Patricia|title=The Creators of Pok\u00e9mon Explain Why Sun and Moon Has Ridiculous Monster Designs|date=October 25, 2016|url=https://kotaku.com/the-creators-of-pokemon-explain-why-sun-and-moon-has-ri-1788191518|accessdate=December 27, 2017|work=[[Kotaku]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171228112317/https://kotaku.com/the-creators-of-pokemon-explain-why-sun-and-moon-has-ri-1788191518|archivedate=December 28, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Pok\u00e9mon from ''Red'' and ''Blue'' were the only ones to receive Alolan forms\u2014according to Ohmori, this was as a special surprise for long-time players and simply due to the older Pok\u00e9mon being more recognizable.<ref name=\"burn\">{{cite news|last1=Hillard|first1=Kyle|title=Burning Questions For Pok\u00e9mon Sun & Moon|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2016/10/19/burning-questions-for-pokemon-sun-and-moon.aspx|accessdate=December 27, 2017|work=[[Game Informer]]|date=October 19, 2016|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171228112238/http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2016/10/19/burning-questions-for-pokemon-sun-and-moon.aspx|archivedate=December 28, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Following the trend between newer generations of the main series, the designers of ''Sun'' and ''Moon'' focused on the motions on the full 3D models from ''X'' and ''Y'' in order to create livelier creatures.<ref name=\"noeint\"/>\n\nDespite the successes of ''[[Pok\u00e9mon Go]]'', the developers stated that it did not affect the development of ''Sun'' and ''Moon'', although it did improve public awareness of the franchise in general and that they were working to develop interactivity between the app and the main series.<ref name=\"burn\"/> Ohmori added that during the development of ''Sun'' and ''Moon'' they \"completely redesigned the system, and actually ended up pushing the 3DS even further to what [they] thought was the most [they] could draw out of it.\"<ref name=\"last\">{{cite news|url=http://ign.com/articles/2017/10/19/ultra-sun-and-ultra-moon-will-be-the-last-pokemon-rpgs-for-3ds|title=Ultra Sun and Ultra Moon will be the last Pok\u00e9mon RPGs for the 3DS|date=October 19, 2017|last1=Skrebels|first1=Joe|work=[[IGN]]|accessdate=December 27, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180201040246/http://www.ign.com/articles/2017/10/19/ultra-sun-and-ultra-moon-will-be-the-last-pokemon-rpgs-for-3ds|archivedate=February 1, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref> With a team of around 120, the games took about three years to develop, which is comparable with other new-generation games.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Haywald|first1=Justin|title=Pokemon Sun/Moon Devs on Legendaries, Pokemon Go, and the Origin of Pikachu|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/pokemon-sunmoon-devs-on-legendaries-pokemon-go-and/1100-6444620/|accessdate=December 27, 2017|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=October 19, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171228112232/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/pokemon-sunmoon-devs-on-legendaries-pokemon-go-and/1100-6444620/|archivedate=December 28, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Later on, Kazumasa Iwao, who was responsible for the battle systems in ''Sun'' and ''Moon'', was recruited as director for ''Ultra Sun'' and ''Ultra Moon''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Webster|first1=Andrew|title=How Pok\u00e9mon Go helped shape the upcoming Ultra Sun and Moon on Nintendo 3DS|url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/10/19/16466536/pokemon-ultra-sun-moon-interview-nintendo|accessdate=December 27, 2017|work=[[The Verge]]|date=October 19, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107013501/https://www.theverge.com/2017/10/19/16466536/pokemon-ultra-sun-moon-interview-nintendo|archivedate=November 7, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\nAccording to composer [[Junichi Masuda]], who co-produced the game, the soundtracks used in ''Sun'' and ''Moon'' were based off [[Music of Hawaii|traditional Hawaiian music]] styles. However, while it utilizes their core rhythms, Alola's music employs \"completely different\" melodies while still invoking a tropical island feel.<ref name=\"timeint\"/> On November 30, 2016 the {{nihongo foot|''Nintendo 3DS Pok\u00e9mon Sun and Moon Super Music Complete''|\u30cb\u30f3\u30c6\u30f3\u30c9\u30fc3DS \u30dd\u30b1\u30e2\u30f3 \u30b5\u30f3\u30fb\u30e0\u30fc\u30f3 \u30b9\u30fc\u30d1\u30fc\u30df\u30e5\u30fc\u30b8\u30c3\u30af\u30fb\u30b3\u30f3\u30d7\u30ea\u30fc\u30c8|Nintend\u014d 3 D\u012b Esu Pok\u00e9mon San \u00b7 M\u016bn S\u016bp\u0101 My\u016bjikku Konp\u016brito|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}}, a four-disk soundtrack containing 169 songs, 160 from the games and 9 special tracks, was released in Japan. The international release, known as ''Pok\u00e9mon Sun & Pok\u00e9mon Moon: Super Music Collection'', was released on [[iTunes]] on the same date.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rossignol|first1=Derrick|title=The POK\u00c9MON SUN and MOON Soundtrack Is Now Available on iTunes|url=https://nerdist.com/the-pokemon-sun-and-moon-soundtrack-is-now-available-on-itunes/|accessdate=December 27, 2017|work=[[Nerdist]]|date=December 1, 2016|language=en|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171228171535/https://nerdist.com/the-pokemon-sun-and-moon-soundtrack-is-now-available-on-itunes/|archivedate=December 28, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=\u30cb\u30f3\u30c6\u30f3\u30c9\u30fc3DS \u30dd\u30b1\u30e2\u30f3 \u30b5\u30f3\u30fb\u30e0\u30fc\u30f3 \u30b9\u30fc\u30d1\u30fc\u30df\u30e5\u30fc\u30b8\u30c3\u30af\u30fb\u30b3\u30f3\u30d7\u30ea\u30fc\u30c8|language=ja|url=http://over-lap.co.jp/cd/sm/|publisher=Over-Lap|accessdate=December 27, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171228054053/http://over-lap.co.jp/cd/sm/|archivedate=December 28, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Promotion and release==\nOn February 25, 2016, the existence of the two games was leaked when Nintendo's trademarks for them were found on the website of the [[European Union Intellectual Property Office]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ca.ign.com/articles/2016/02/25/the-next-pokemon-games-could-be-called-sun-and-moon |title=The Next Pokemon Games Could Be Called Sun And Moon |author=Matt Porter |publisher=IGN |accessdate=February 25, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20160227094942/http://ca.ign.com/articles/2016/02/25/the-next-pokemon-games-could-be-called-sun-and-moon |archivedate=February 27, 2016 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> ''IGN'' pointed towards the recent introduction of a new Pok\u00e9mon, [[Magearna]], as indication the two games would be revealed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2016/02/26/pokemon-sun-and-moon-officially-announced |title=Pokemon Sun and Moon Officially Announced |author=Seth G. Macy |date=February 26, 2016 |work=[[IGN]] |accessdate=February 27, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160226164409/http://www.ign.com/articles/2016/02/26/pokemon-sun-and-moon-officially-announced |archivedate=February 26, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The games were officially announced the following day in a [[Nintendo Direct]] presentation that also commemorated the franchise's 20th anniversary.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://comicbook.com/2016/02/26/nintendo-announces-pokemon-sun-and-moon-for-20th-anniversary/ |date=February 26, 2016 |title=Nintendo Announces Pokemon Sun And Moon For 20th Anniversary |author=James Viscardi |work=Comicbook.com |accessdate=February 26, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20160226163505/http://comicbook.com/2016/02/26/nintendo-announces-pokemon-sun-and-moon-for-20th-anniversary/ |archivedate=February 26, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The games launched with support for nine languages.<ref name=\"Pokemoncom\">{{cite web |url=http://www.pokemon.com/uk/pokemon-video-games/pokemon-sun-and-pokemon-moon/ |title=Pok\u00e9mon Sun and Pok\u00e9mon Moon |publisher=[[The Pok\u00e9mon Company]] |access-date=February 26, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160228120537/http://www.pokemon.com/uk/pokemon-video-games/pokemon-sun-and-pokemon-moon/ |archivedate=February 28, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> On May 10, more information on the games was released through a new trailer, including new Pok\u00e9mon, box art, and release dates. ''Pok\u00e9mon Sun'' and ''Moon'' released in Japan, North America, and Australia on November 18, 2016, and in Europe on November 23, 2016.<ref name=\"Junichi Masuda's Blog\">{{cite web |url=http://lineblog.me/masudajunichi/archives/3355017.html |title=Look for tomorrow |publisher=[[Junichi Masuda]] |access-date=May 9, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160512170241/http://lineblog.me/masudajunichi/archives/3355017.html |archivedate=May 12, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> A comic based on ''Pok\u00e9mon Sun'' and ''Moon'' launched alongside an edition of ''[[CoroCoro Comic]]'' on September 15, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Whitehead|first1=Thomas|title=A Pok\u00e9mon Sun And Moon Manga Series Is Coming To CoroCoro Comics|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2016/08/a_pokemon_sun_and_moon_manga_series_is_coming_to_corocoro_comics|website=[[Nintendo Life]]|accessdate=August 8, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160809145724/http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2016/08/a_pokemon_sun_and_moon_manga_series_is_coming_to_corocoro_comics|archivedate=August 9, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Early purchasers of the games received a special [[Munchlax]] holding Snorlium Z, enabling it to use an exclusive Z-Move unique to [[Snorlax]], Munchlax's evolution, via a wireless distribution event.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/09/01/sun-and-moons-early-purchase-bonus-is-a-pre-snorlax-pokemon/|title=Sun and Moon's early purchase bonus is a pre-Snorlax Pok\u00e9mon|last=Etherington|first=Darrell|website=[[TechCrunch]]|access-date=September 2, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160902143941/https://techcrunch.com/2016/09/01/sun-and-moons-early-purchase-bonus-is-a-pre-snorlax-pokemon/|archivedate=September 2, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> A Japanese trailer was unveiled on September 8, 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/olliebarder/2016/09/08/pokemon-sun-and-moon-shows-off-its-legendary-pokemon-in-latest-trailer/#3cf836ca2026|title='Pok\u00e9mon Sun And Moon' Shows Off Its Legendary Pok\u00e9mon In Latest Trailer|last=Barder|website=[[Forbes.com]]|first=Ollie|date=8 September 2016|access-date=September 9, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160909161309/http://www.forbes.com/sites/olliebarder/2016/09/08/pokemon-sun-and-moon-shows-off-its-legendary-pokemon-in-latest-trailer/#3cf836ca2026|archivedate=September 9, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> A ''Pok\u00e9mon Sun'' and ''Moon''-themed [[New Nintendo 3DS XL]] was released on October 28, 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2016/09/13/pokemon-sun-and-moon-new-nintendo-3ds-xl-special-edition-announced|title=Pokemon Sun and Moon New Nintendo 3DS XL Special Edition Announced|last=Dornbush|first=Jonathon|date=September 13, 2016|website=[[IGN]]|language=en-US|access-date=September 14, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160913200824/http://www.ign.com/articles/2016/09/13/pokemon-sun-and-moon-new-nintendo-3ds-xl-special-edition-announced|archivedate=September 13, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nSimilar to ''Pok\u00e9mon Omega Ruby'' and ''Alpha Sapphire'', a special demo was released on October 18, 2016.<ref name=\":1\"/> On October 27, 2016 during Nintendo's Financial Briefing, they stated the demo had been downloaded more than 3.5 million times, being the most popular and fastest \"selling\" demo in 3DS history.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Harp|first1=Justin|title=Pok\u00e9mon Sun and Moon demo racks up a record-breaking 3.5 million downloads|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/gaming/pokemon/news/a812416/pokemon-sun-and-moon-demo-racks-up-record-breaking-35-million-downloads/|website=[[Digital Spy]]|date=October 28, 2016|accessdate=October 28, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161028231954/http://www.digitalspy.com/gaming/pokemon/news/a812416/pokemon-sun-and-moon-demo-racks-up-record-breaking-35-million-downloads/|archivedate=October 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> ''Pok\u00e9mon Sun'' and ''Moon'' were the most pre-ordered games in Nintendo's history.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Frank|first1=Allegra|title=Pok\u00e9mon Sun and Moon are Nintendo's biggest pre-orders ever|url=http://www.polygon.com/2016/10/27/13446280/pokemon-sun-and-moon-pre-order-record/|website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|accessdate=October 28, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161028133430/http://www.polygon.com/2016/10/27/13446280/pokemon-sun-and-moon-pre-order-record|archivedate=October 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The games were also the most anticipated 3DS releases in 2016, according to [[Nielsen Holdings|Nielsen]] Game Rank.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tops of 2016: Video Games|url=http://www.nielsen.com/us/en/insights/news/2016/tops-of-2016-video-games.html|publisher=[[Nielsen Holdings|Nielsen]]|website=nielsen.com|accessdate=3 January 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180103193635/http://www.nielsen.com/us/en/insights/news/2016/tops-of-2016-video-games.html|archivedate=January 3, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nDays before their release, the games' files were leaked on to the Internet, giving [[software pirate]]s access to the full game, including online functions, before their release. Nintendo took action against those who used the Internet features, banning users involved from not only using the online features of the games\u2014even if later playing the genuine release\u2014, but also from accessing other 3DS online services, such as the eShop and Miiverse.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hernandez|first1=Patricia|title=Players Who Pirated Pokemon Sun and Moon Say Nintendo is Banning them|url=http://kotaku.com/players-who-pirated-pokemon-sun-and-moon-say-nintendo-i-1789039343|website=[[Kotaku]]|accessdate=November 16, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161116154915/http://kotaku.com/players-who-pirated-pokemon-sun-and-moon-say-nintendo-i-1789039343|archivedate=November 16, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Video game reviews\n<!-- Aggregators-->\n| MC = 87/100<ref name=\"MetaSun\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/3ds/pokemon-sun |title=Pokemon Sun for 3DS Reviews&nbsp;\u2014 Metacritic |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=July 12, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170701001917/http://www.metacritic.com/game/3ds/pokemon-sun |archivedate=July 1, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"MetaMoon\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/3ds/pokemon-moon |title=Pokemon Moon for 3DS Reviews&nbsp;\u2014 Metacritic |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=July 12, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170714071006/http://www.metacritic.com/game/3ds/pokemon-moon |archivedate=July 14, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n| state = plain\n| Destruct= 9/10 <ref name=\"Destruct\">{{cite web|url=https://www.destructoid.com/review-pokemon-sun-399628.phtml|title=Review: Pokemon Sun|last=Devore|first=Jordan|publisher=Destructoid|date=November 11, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170305003818/https://www.destructoid.com/review-pokemon-sun-399628.phtml|archivedate=March 5, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| Fam = 38/40<ref name=\"famitsu\">{{cite news |last1=Romano |first1=Sal |title=Famitsu Review Scores: Issue 1459 |date=15 November 2016 |url=https://gematsu.com/2016/11/famitsu-review-scores-issue-1459 |accessdate=5 July 2019 |work=Gematsu |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190420144855/https://gematsu.com/2016/11/famitsu-review-scores-issue-1459 |archive-date=April 20, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| GI = 8.5/10 (''Moon'')<ref name=\"GI\">{{cite magazine|magazine=Game Informer|publisher=[[GameStop]]|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/themes/blogs/generic/post.aspx?WeblogApp=3ds&y=2016&m=11&d=15&WeblogPostName=game-informer-pokemon-sun-moon-review-3ds&GroupKeys=games/pokemon_moon/|title=Pokemon Moon: Destination Vacation|last=Hilliard|first=Kyle|date=November 15, 2016|accessdate=July 12, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170803091602/http://www.gameinformer.com/themes/blogs/generic/post.aspx?WeblogApp=3ds&y=2016&m=11&d=15&WeblogPostName=game-informer-pokemon-sun-moon-review-3ds&GroupKeys=games%2Fpokemon_moon%2F|archivedate=August 3, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| GSpot = 8/10<ref name=GameSpot>{{cite web|last1=Justin|first1=Haywald|title=Pok\u00e9mon Sun/Moon Review|url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/pokemon-sun-and-moon-review/1900-6416574/|publisher=[[GameSpot]]|accessdate=July 12, 2017|date=November 18, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170705010933/https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/pokemon-sun-and-moon-review/1900-6416574/|archivedate=July 5, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| GameZone = 9.5/10<ref name=\"GameZone\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamezone.com/reviews/review-pokemon-sun-moon-is-a-proper-evolution-k2rs|title=Pokemon Sun & Moon is a proper evolution|last=Splechta|first=Mike|publisher=Game Zone|date=November 16, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171020033015/http://www.gamezone.com/reviews/review-pokemon-sun-moon-is-a-proper-evolution-k2rs|archivedate=October 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| IGN = 9/10<ref name=\"IGN_Review\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2016/11/15/pokemon-sun-and-moon-review|title=Pokemon Sun and Moon review|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161116155217/http://www.ign.com/articles/2016/11/15/pokemon-sun-and-moon-review|archivedate=November 16, 2016|df=mdy-all|last=Plagge|first=Kalle|work=[[IGN]]|date=15 November 2016}}</ref>\n| NLife = 10/10<ref name=\"NLife\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nintendolife.com/reviews/3ds/pokemon_sun_and_moon |title=Review: Pok\u00e9mon Sun and Moon (3DS) |last=Olney |first=Alex |work=[[Nintendo Life]] |date=November 15, 2016 |accessdate=October 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170926170259/http://www.nintendolife.com/reviews/3ds/pokemon_sun_and_moon |archivedate=September 26, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n| NWR = 8/10 (''Moon'')<ref name=\"NWR\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/review/43671/pokemon-moon-3ds-review |title=Pokemon Moon (3DS) Review |last=Koopman |first=Dan |publisher=Nintendo World Report |date=November 15, 2016 |accessdate=July 12, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170622064406/http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/review/43671/pokemon-moon-3ds-review |archivedate=June 22, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n| Poly = 8.5/10<ref name=\"Poly\">{{cite web|first=Allegra|last=Frank|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|date=November 15, 2016|accessdate=July 12, 2017|title=Pokemon Sun and Moon Review|url=https://www.polygon.com/2016/11/15/13637246/pokemon-sun-and-moon-review-nintendo-3ds|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170624113259/https://www.polygon.com/2016/11/15/13637246/pokemon-sun-and-moon-review-nintendo-3ds|archivedate=June 24, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| USG = 4.5/5<ref name=\"USG\">{{cite web |last1=Parish |first1=Jeremy |title=Aloha, Alola |url=https://www.usgamer.net/articles/pokmon-sunmoon-versions-3ds-review-finally-pokemon-feels-modern-2 |website=[[USgamer]] |accessdate=January 2, 2020 |language=en |date=November 18, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191008032447/https://www.usgamer.net/articles/pokmon-sunmoon-versions-3ds-review-finally-pokemon-feels-modern-2 |archive-date=8 October 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n}}\n\n===Critical response===\n''Pok\u00e9mon Sun'' and ''Moon'' received a score of 87/100 on [[Metacritic]] based on 84 reviews, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref name=\"MetaSun\"/><ref name=\"MetaMoon\"/> This placed ''Sun'' and ''Moon'' as the 5th and 6th highest-rated 3DS games in 2016, and the 19th and 20th on the console of all time.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Best Video Games of 2016|url=http://www.metacritic.com/feature/best-videogames-of-2016|publisher=Metacritic|accessdate=3 February 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161222041129/http://www.metacritic.com/feature/best-videogames-of-2016|archivedate=December 22, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=All Nintendo 3DS Video Game Releases|url=http://www.metacritic.com/browse/games/release-date/available/3ds/metascore|publisher=Metacritic|accessdate=3 February 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6eDHRvuoJ?url=http://www.metacritic.com/browse/games/release-date/available/3ds/metascore|archivedate=January 1, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The move from the gym system received widespread praise from critics, some of whom saw the change as a major step towards future developments of the franchise.<ref name=\"Destruct\"/><ref name=\"NWR\"/>\n\nJapanese magazine ''[[Famitsu]]'' gave the pair a 38/40 rating.<ref name=\"famitsu\"/> Writing for video game review site ''[[IGN]]'', Kallie Plagge gave the games a 9/10, and said that they \"switch up the formula to create an engaging adventure that improves on its predecessors\", in addition to praising the streamlined battle interface and other mechanics.<ref name=\"IGN_Review\"/> Many critics praised the story as one of the best in the franchise, Ollie Barder from ''[[Forbes]]'' highlighted how the story and characters were nicely done,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Barder |first1=Ollie |title='Pok\u00e9mon Sun' And 'Pok\u00e9mon Moon' Review: Say Alola To A Wonderful New World Of Pok\u00e9mon |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/games/2016/11/28/pokemon-sun-and-moon-review-say-alola-to-a-wonderful-new-world-of-pokemon/#abd28f53c48f |website=[[Forbes]] |accessdate=January 2, 2020 |date=November 28, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191202132240/https://www.forbes.com/sites/games/2016/11/28/pokemon-sun-and-moon-review-say-alola-to-a-wonderful-new-world-of-pokemon/ |archive-date=December 2, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> while Alex Donaldson of ''[[VG247]]'' remarked that the story drew him in deeper, saying \"I remain more engaged in this story than in any other ''Pok\u00e9mon'' tale yet\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Donaldson |first1=Alex |title=Pokemon Sun & Moon review: the best Pokemon game in years |url=https://www.vg247.com/2016/11/23/pokemon-sun-moon-review-the-best-pokemon-game-in-years/ |website=[[VG247]] |accessdate=January 2, 2020 |date=November 23, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190605111258/https://www.vg247.com/2016/11/23/pokemon-sun-moon-review-the-best-pokemon-game-in-years/ |archive-date=December 2, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Alex Olney of ''[[Nintendo Life]]'' said that \"the plot in Sun & Moon is the deepest and most ambitious Game Freak has dared attempt\", he also called them the best ''Pok\u00e9mon'' games ever produced, commenting that Alola's design felt natural and organic, praising Game Freak for successfully balancing additional mechanics without alienating existing fans.<ref name=\"NLife\"/> Chris Tapsell of ''Eurogamer'' said the games were \"the best generation in more than a decade\". They earned an \"essential\" ranking from the site.<ref name=\"eurorev\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-11-15-pokemon-sun-and-moon-review|title=Pok\u00e9mon Sun and Moon review|first=Chris|last=Tapsell|date=November 23, 2016|website=[[Eurogamer]]|accessdate=January 3, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171228112311/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-11-15-pokemon-sun-and-moon-review|archivedate=December 28, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn the other hand, Tapsell also remarked that the first few hours of the games included too many tutorials and protected gameplay.<ref name=\"eurorev\"/> Jeremy Parish of ''[[USGamer]]'' assessed that \"Z-Moves feel underwhelming\" taking \"way too long\" despite being the most engaging campaign the series has offered in a long time,<ref name=\"USG\"/> while ''[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]''{{'}}s Allegra Frank criticized their linear gameplay and lack of content beyond the primary storyline although the games had \"the most memorable ''Pok\u00e9mon'' journey in years\".<ref name=\"Poly\"/>\n\n===Sales===\nAccording to Nintendo of America, ''Sun'' and ''Moon'' were the fastest-selling titles in Nintendo's history at the time.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=NintendoAmerica|author=Nintendo of America|number=804052396259282948|date=November 30, 2016|title=It\u2019s official: #PokemonSunMoon are the fastest-selling games in Nintendo history in the Americas! Which version are\u2026|accessdate=January 3, 2018}}</ref> As of December 31, 2019, ''Sun'' and ''Moon'' have sold 16.18 million copies, ranking them as the [[List of best-selling Nintendo 3DS video games|third-best-selling Nintendo 3DS titles]] behind both ''[[Mario Kart 7]]'' and ''Pok\u00e9mon X'' and ''Y''.<ref name=\"third\">{{cite web|title=Top Selling Title Sales Units|url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/en/finance/software/3ds.html|publisher=[[Nintendo]]|accessdate=30 January 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all |date=December 31, 2019}}</ref> During a [[GameStop]] Q3 earnings conference call, ''Pok\u00e9mon Sun'' and ''Moon'' were said to have had the most pre-orders for any video game in the last five years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thisgengaming.com/2016/11/23/pokemon-sun-moon-most-pre-ordered-game-in-5-years-call-of-duty-infinite-warfare-underpreformed-says-gamestop/|title=Pokemon Sun & Moon \"Most Pre-Ordered Game In 5 Years\", Call Of Duty Infinite Warfare Underpreformed Says Gamestop|website=thisgengaming.com|accessdate=January 3, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107011200/http://thisgengaming.com/2016/11/23/pokemon-sun-moon-most-pre-ordered-game-in-5-years-call-of-duty-infinite-warfare-underpreformed-says-gamestop/|archivedate=November 7, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> It is GameStop's best-selling game of 2016, outselling ''[[Call of Duty: Infinite Warfare]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/gamestop-sales-hurting-as-new-call-of-duty-underpe/1100-6445664/|title=GameStop Sales Hurting, as New Call of Duty Underperforms; Pokemon Sun/Moon Biggest of 2016|first=Eddie|last=Makuch|date=November 22, 2016|accessdate=January 3, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171213135355/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/gamestop-sales-hurting-as-new-call-of-duty-underpe/1100-6445664/|archivedate=December 13, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On its first day of release, ''Pok\u00e9mon Sun'' and ''Moon'' shipped 10 million units worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2016/11/18/pokemon-sun-and-moon-break-nintendo-3ds-record-with-10-million-copies-shipped/|title=Pok\u00e9mon Sun and Moon break Nintendo 3DS record with 10 million copies shipped - GamesBeat|website=[[VentureBeat]]|accessdate=January 3, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107031247/https://venturebeat.com/2016/11/18/pokemon-sun-and-moon-break-nintendo-3ds-record-with-10-million-copies-shipped/|archivedate=November 7, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The games sold over 1.9 million copies in Japan in its first three days on the market and are Nintendo's biggest game launch of all time in Europe, with the [[United Kingdom]] and [[France]] launches selling 368,000 and 450,000 copies respectively within a week out of the continent's 1.5 million sales.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kerr|first1=Chris|title=Pokemon Sun and Moon first week sales top 1.9 million in Japan|url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/286065/Pokemon_Sun_and_Moon_first_week_sales_top_19_million_in_Japan.php|website=[[Gamasutra]]|publisher=[[UBM TechWeb]]|accessdate=November 22, 2016|date=November 22, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161123133738/http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/286065/Pokemon_Sun_and_Moon_first_week_sales_top_19_million_in_Japan.php|archivedate=November 23, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Phillips|first1=Tom|title=Pok\u00e9mon Sun and Moon are Nintendo's biggest UK launch of all time|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-11-28-pokemon-sun-and-moon-are-nintendos-biggest-uk-launch|website=[[Eurogamer]]|publisher=Gamer Network|accessdate=November 28, 2016|date=November 28, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161128231728/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-11-28-pokemon-sun-and-moon-are-nintendos-biggest-uk-launch|archivedate=November 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Casey|title=Pok\u00e9mon Sun & Moon Sell Over 425,000 Copies In First Week In France, Set New Record|url=http://www.siliconera.com/2016/12/04/pokmon-sun-moon-sell-425000-copies-first-week-france-set-new-record/|website=[[Siliconera]]|accessdate=December 4, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161205131747/http://www.siliconera.com/2016/12/04/pokmon-sun-moon-sell-425000-copies-first-week-france-set-new-record/|archivedate=December 5, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The European sales rose past the 2 million mark within the following week.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Forde|first1=Matthew|title=Pok\u00e9mon Sun & Moon Sales Pass 2 Million in Europe|url=https://www.nintendolife.com/news/2016/12/pokemon_sun_and_moon_sales_pass_2_million_in_europe|website=[[Nintendo Life]]|accessdate=December 8, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161209153835/http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2016/12/pokemon_sun_and_moon_sales_pass_2_million_in_europe|archivedate=December 9, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In North America, the games sold over 3.7 million units in less than two weeks after initial release, climbing to 4.5 million by mid-January.<ref>{{cite web|last=Nunneley|first=Stephany|website=[[VG247]]|url=http://www.vg247.com/2016/11/30/pokemon-sun-and-moon-sold-3-7-million-units-in-north-america-in-less-than-two-weeks/|title=Pokemon Sun and Moon sold 3.7 million units in North America in less than two weeks|accessdate=January 3, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180105205853/https://www.vg247.com/2016/11/30/pokemon-sun-and-moon-sold-3-7-million-units-in-north-america-in-less-than-two-weeks/|archivedate=January 5, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Macy|first1=Seth|title=Pokemon Sun And Moon Pass Huge Sales Milestone|url=http://ign.com/articles/2017/01/19/pokemon-sun-and-moon-pass-huge-sales-milestone|website=[[IGN]]|accessdate=January 19, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170119233458/http://www.ign.com/articles/2017/01/19/pokemon-sun-and-moon-pass-huge-sales-milestone|archivedate=January 19, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Follow-up versions==\n{{main|Pok\u00e9mon Ultra Sun and Ultra Moon}}\n'''''Pok\u00e9mon Ultra Sun''''' and '''''Pok\u00e9mon Ultra Moon''''' are enhanced versions of ''Pok\u00e9mon Sun'' and ''Moon'', developed by Game Freak, published by The Pok\u00e9mon Company and Nintendo for the Nintendo 3DS. They were announced on June 6, 2017, during a Nintendo Direct presentation<ref name=hernandez>{{cite news|first=Patricia|last=Hernandez|work=[[Kotaku]]|publisher=[[Gawker Media]]|date=June 6, 2017|accessdate=June 6, 2017|title=''Pok\u00e9mon Ultra Sun and Moon'' Only Announced For 3DS Later This Year [Update]|url=http://kotaku.com/pokemon-ultra-sun-and-moon-coming-only-to-3ds-later-thi-1795847363|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606152234/http://kotaku.com/pokemon-ultra-sun-and-moon-coming-only-to-3ds-later-thi-1795847363|archivedate=June 6, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and were released worldwide on November 17, 2017.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Humphries |first1=Matthew |title=Ultra Sun and Moon Are the Last 3DS Pokemon Games |url=https://uk.pcmag.com/news-analysis/91647/ultra-sun-and-moon-are-the-last-3ds-pokemon-games |accessdate=May 15, 2019 |work=[[PC Magazine|PCMag UK]] |date=October 19, 2017 |language=en}}</ref> They feature an alternate storyline set in ''Sun'' and ''Moon''{{'}}s world, and include Pok\u00e9mon and locations not available in the original games.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pokemon-sunmoon.com/ultra/en-us/alola-region.html|title=Alola Region {{!}} Pok\u00e9mon Ultra Sun and Pok\u00e9mon Ultra Moon|website=pokemon-sunmoon.com|language=en-us|access-date=2019-02-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190216091516/https://www.pokemon-sunmoon.com/ultra/en-us/alola-region.html|archive-date=February 16, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.pokemon.com/us/pokemon-video-games/pokemon-sun-and-pokemon-moon/}}\n\n{{Pok\u00e9mon video games|state=collapsed}}\n{{Portal bar|Video games}}\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pok\u00e9mon Sun and Moon}}\n[[Category:2016 video games]]\n[[Category:Game Freak games]]\n[[Category:Japanese role-playing video games]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer and single-player video games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo 3DS eShop games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo 3DS games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo 3DS-only games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo Network games]]\n[[Category:Pok\u00e9mon video games|Sun and Moon]]\n[[Category:Role-playing video games]]\n[[Category:Video games adapted into comics]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Japan]]\n[[Category:Video games featuring female antagonists]]\n[[Category:Video games featuring protagonists of selectable gender]]\n[[Category:Video games with alternate versions]]\n[[Category:Wormholes in fiction]]\n[[Category:Video games scored by Junichi Masuda]]\n", "name_user": "Stefvanschie", "label": "safe", "comment": "Remove unnecessary pipes as perMOS:NOPIPE", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pok%C3%A9mon_Sun_and_Moon"}
{"title_page": "Opinion polling for the next Austrian legislative election", "text_new": "In the run-up to the [[Next Austrian legislative election]], various organisations carry out [[opinion polling]] to gauge voting intentions in [[Austria]]. Results of such polls are displayed in this list.\n\nThe date range for these opinion polls are from the [[2019 Austrian legislative election|previous legislative election]], held on 29 September 2019, to the present day. The next election will likely be held in 2024.\n\n== VDMI quality criteria ==\nIn 2017 the Association of Market and Opinion Research Institutes of Austria (VDMI) published quality standards for polls, which are available to look at [http://vdmi.at/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/Richtlinie_Wahlforschung_01-2017.pdf here]. Although parts of these guidelines are still broken by most polling firms, there has been a significant increase of poll quality since publification, especially in sample size. \n\n== Graphical summary ==\n[[File:Austrian Opinion Polling, 30 Day Moving Average, 2019-2024.png]]\n\n== Poll results ==\n{{For|the events during those years|2019 in Austria|2020 in Austria}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:90%;line-height:14px;\"\n|- style=\"height:40px;\"\n! style=\"width:200px;\" rowspan=\"2\"| Polling firm\n! style=\"width:120px;\" rowspan=\"2\"| Fieldwork date\n! style=\"width:80px;\" rowspan=\"2\"| Sample<br>size\n! style=\"width:35px;\" rowspan=\"2\"| Method\n! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width:60px;\"| [[Austrian People's Party|\u00d6VP]]\n! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width:60px;\"| [[Social Democratic Party of Austria|SP\u00d6]]\n! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width:60px;\"| [[Freedom Party of Austria|FP\u00d6]]\n! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width:60px;\"| [[The Greens \u2013 The Green Alternative|Gr\u00fcne]]\n! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width:60px;\"| [[NEOS \u2013 The New Austria and Liberal Forum|NEOS]]\n! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width:60p